<HEADLINE>
PACK OF FRIENDS EXPECTED FOR WOLF'S START
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Randy Wolf makes his first start at Dodger Stadium
as a member of the Philadelphia Phillies today, but the second-year
pitcher has a history with the ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf pitched his final high school game at Dodger Stadium in
1994, when he threw a complete game in the L.A. City championship
game for El Camino Real of Woodland Hills. Wolf, who also pitched
at Pepperdine for three seasons, expects to have a cheering section
in the stands today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's about 30 people on the pass list, and I'm sure
a few more will show up,'' said Wolf, who was drafted by the
Dodgers out of high school but didn't sign. ``I got to go home
(Friday) night and see a bunch of friends, and it's really pretty
special to play in your hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone to all the stadiums, and they're all cool, but to
come here and sit in the dugout and hear the organ, when you grew
up sitting in the stands, that's pretty cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf missed playing in Dodger Stadium last year by one game - he
started the last game of a series in San Diego - and said he feels
more comfortable this year after losing eight consecutive starts in
1999. Wolf is 3-3 with a 4.26 ERA this year and has won two of his
past three starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience is just so important,'' Wolf said. ``It doesn't
matter if it's good or bad, what's important is just to learn. Even
when things are bad, it teaches you how to handle the tough times,
and it makes you stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeling fine: Todd Hundley hit two home runs in Friday's victory
over the Phillies, and the Dodgers catcher has a lot to celebrate
these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything feels good,'' Hundley said. ``The elbow feels good,
the arm feels good, the leg feels good. I'm really pleased right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley hit safely in 20 of the past 26 games and homered in
eight of the past 13 going into Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   His 13 home runs are tied for second best on the team with Eric
Karros, one behind Gary Sheffield, but Hundley, who hit a
career-high 41 home runs in 1996, can't pinpoint a specific reason
for his power resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just about solid hitting, seeing the ball well and
getting a good swing,'' Hundley said. ``There's nothing special
about it, it's just a matter of getting solid contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's confidence has reached a high point. Last season was
filled with questions about his surgically repaired elbow and his
inability to throw out runners. But now that his throwing has
improved, just about the only question is whether he will return to
the Dodgers after he becomes an unrestricted free agent this
winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not even thinking about that right now,'' Hundley said.
``I just want to play well, win some games, and the contract will
take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a game for me now, the way it should be,
especially compared to last year. Last year it was work, and it
wasn't a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   What a welcome: It's been quite a first week for Dodgers
reliever Trever Miller, who joined the team Monday, two days before
the mass suspensions were handed down in the Wrigley Field
incident.
</P>
<P>
   Miller made his Dodgers debut that night, retired just one of
the five batters he faced and was charged with two runs in a 10-3
loss to Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just eager to get back out there,'' Miller said. ``I threw
in the bullpen (Friday) and felt good, so I'm looking forward to
the next chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller's new team faced his old team Saturday, but the pitcher
said it didn't seem strange to watch the Phillies from the opposing
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't there long enough for it to feel weird,'' said
Miller, who spent just two months with Philadelphia after three
seasons in Houston. ``It was weird when we opened the new park in
Houston, because I was there for a lot longer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
