<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPTV-ARIZONA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC TV NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FUQUAY  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALTOM CITY, Texas _ When Hispanic Television Network needed
money last fall, it decided to sell 10 million shares for $1 each.
</P>
<P>
   For that sum, investors got a piece of a company with the
financial track record of an Internet start-up, including the
obligatory red ink that flows when expenses dwarf revenues. Looking
at it another way, investors had a chance to pay $1 for shares that
traded for as little as 16 cents as recently as Oct. 12.
</P>
<P>
   To sweeten the deal, the company gave its backers a warrant. A
warrant is the right to buy another share of the company for $2. It
could be worth some real money, assuming the stock price went up.
</P>
<P>
   Good assumption.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic Television Network, less than a year old and still
putting together a network of local stations, has seen its shares
climb as high as $20 this year. Working out of a modest building in
Haltom City, the fledgling broadcaster has hired a number of
experienced managers, announced a deal to buy 12 television
stations and is pursuing more.
</P>
<P>
   HTVN has two low-power UHF stations in Phoenix, but only one of
them, Channel 28, is on the air. The network plans to begin
broadcasting on Channel 30 in about a month, said Rod Rodriguez,
sales director for HTVN.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured that two lower-power stations would give us the
same amount of coverage as two full-power stations,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   The network plans to open an office at 30th Avenue and Thomas
Road, and hopes to launch some local programing next fall, he said.
</P>
<P>
   HTVN also has purchased stations in Tucson and Globe, but
neither has begun broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   HTVN will challenge two existing Spanish-language networks _
Telemundo, controlled by Sony, and Univision, whose publicly traded
stock has been soaring _ for the growing Hispanic audience in the
United States. There are an estimated 32 million U.S. Hispanics _
more than the population of Canada. And their numbers are growing
about five times as fast as the general U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our intention to be an international media company,''
said Jim Ryffel, chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Ryffel runs Woodcrest Enterprises, a Fort Worth real estate
company, and previously backed FlashNet Communications, which is
being acquired by Prodigy Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic Television Network might plan to go international, but
it will do it by staying closer to home. Mexico, specifically.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at Univision's lineup, few are Mexican,'' HTVN
President Marco Camacho says. ``They're Cuban, or from Puerto Rico
or Peru.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Telemundo executive sees Mexico as HTVN's niche,
because most Hispanics living in Texas, Southern California, even
Chicago, came from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   So that's the plan: Air more Mexican-focused programs, and if
they're not available, produce them. &QL; 
Republic reporter Hal Mattern contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
