<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAST CHAMPIONS HAVE EDGE ON CURRENT LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Lakers are six wins away from
``fulfilling their destiny'' as NBA Champions, a phrase that
carries the dead weight of expectations. Imagine James Earl Jones
saying it, as he did as Darth Vader, to get a true feel for its
density.
</P>
<P>
   But before we get too far ahead of ourselves, the Lakers won't
have it easy winning those last six games, two more from the game
Portland Trail Blazers and then four more from either Indiana or
New York.
</P>
<P>
   And this team, by any measure, doesn't stack up very well with
the six L.A. Laker teams that won titles, or any of the other teams
that won titles in the last two decades.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't said as a rip on Shaquille O'Neal or any of his
teammates, or at architect Jerry West or construction chief Phil
Jackson. It's just a fact: The NBA at the dawn of a new century
mitigates against the development of great teams, like those Magic
Johnson-led Lakers and Larry Bird-led Celtics teams that fought
each other to the death and took home eight of ten titles in the
1980s, or the oppressive Celtics of the '60s.
</P>
<P>
   This may be the biggest cultural change in the league's history.
Thanks to expansion to 29 teams, the blanding of the draft, the
salary cap and the raiding of college programs for immature talent,
it is increasingly difficult to mold a great team.
</P>
<P>
   The '00 Lakers have MVP O'Neal and a fast-maturing Bryant, but
this team didn't grow up together. O'Neal is an import, the biggest
free agent signing in the team's history, and Jerry West bamboozled
Charlotte into trading Bryant to the Lakers on draft day.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the team are role players, three of whom were new to
the team this season -- Ron Harper, redux A.C. Green and Brian
Shaw. Glen Rice hasn't been the third star of the Laker
constellation nearly as much as anyone expected, and Harper and
Green are 36-year-old dinosaurs around for one last dance.
</P>
<P>
   The case can be made, in fact, that the Lakers had better
personnel 15 months ago, before the Eddie Jones-Glen Rice trade,
than they do now.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the late '70s, a time of too-rapid expansion and
off-court ailments that saw the title change hands annually between
teams with maybe one star player -- from Rick Barry's Warriors, to
Dave Cowens' Celts, to Bill Walton's Trail Blazers, to Elvin Hayes'
Bullets, to Gus Williams' SuperSonics -- the league's calling card
has always been its great teams.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Celtic epoch of the late '50s and '60s, when they won
11 titles between 1957 and 1969. The 1959-60-61 Celtics roster
featured seven future basketball Hall of Famers -- Bob Cousy, Tom
Heinsohn, K.C. Jones, Sam Jones, Frank Ramsey, Bill Russell and
Bill Sharman -- as well as Hall of Fame coach Red Auerbach.
</P>
<P>
   The teams that alternated titles in the early '70s were pretty
sensational, too. The 1970 and 1973 Knicks had Walt Frazier, Willis
Reed, Bill Bradley, Dave DeBusschere, Dick Barnett and Jackson. In
1973, it added Earl Monroe and Jerry Lucas to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   The 1971 Milwaukee Bucks featured Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Oscar
Robertson, and the 1972 Lakers had West, Wilt Chamberlain and Gail
Goodrich.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem and Magic were the constants of the Lakers' five titles
in the '80s, but they had considerable help. Jamaal Wilkes was the
outside shooter in 1980 and 1982, Byron Scott in 1985-87-88. James
Worthy has as much to do with the three latter titles as anyone,
and there were always plenty of solid-to-superb forwards to help --
Bob McAdoo (1982, 1985), Kurt Rambis, Mitch Kupchak, A.C. Green,
Mychal Thompson. They also had defensive specialist Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   If those Laker starting fives weren't the best since Russell's
Celtics, then it was Bird's Celtics of the same era. Two titles
were won with Bird, Dennis Johnson, and inside forces Robert Parish
and Kevin McHale. The 1981 team had Tiny Archibald and Cedric
Maxwell instead of Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to lose the 1989 and 1990 Detroit Pistons between the
Celtics, Lakers and Bulls, but those two teams were also great,
with Isiah Thomas and Joe Dumars outside and a lineup of
heavyweights inside, Bill Laimbeer, James Edwards, Rodman and Rick
Mahorn.
</P>
<P>
   And as dominant a figure as Jordan was, he wasn't playing by
himself during the '90s. The second Bulls title trilogy starred
Jordan, Scottie Pippen, Toni Kukoc at the three, a younger Harper
and Dennis Rodman before his self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The first Bulls trilogy had more muscle inside with Horace
Grant, Bill Cartwright and Scott Williams. By today's standard of
centers, Cartwright now looks pretty studly, and Jackson always had
a handful of gunners available in B.J. Armstrong, John Paxson and
Craig Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   If the league is to overcome the retirement of Jordan and stop
the bleeding in the TV ratings and box office, it is going to have
to develop teams with dynasty-like qualities. Contrary to the
expansion nature of sports, success and interest comes when there's
something shiny to watch at its center -- the Yankees, the Lakers
and Celtics, the 49ers and Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Shaq and Kobe have first crack at it. But the truth may be that
they'll need more help than they have right now if it's going to
happen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999-2000 LOS ANGELES LAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Regular season record: 67-15. Playoff record (to date): 9-4.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, center: One vote shy of becoming the NBA's
first unanimous MVP. Averages of 29.8 (points) and 16.7 (rebounds)
and an all-defense honoree.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, guard: Fulfilling all phases of his promise as an
impact player, who can make the 20-footer at the buzzer as well as
a clean block of a shot by 7-3 Arvydas Sabonis.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper, guard: A 36-year-old 14-year veteran who Phil
Jackson hired for his knowledge of the Triangle offense and work
ethic.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green, forward: Lakers never expected the 36-year-old to
play as much as he has.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, forward: Hasn't come close to being the consistent
outside threat the Lakers expected when they traded Eddie Jones.
Spotty on defense, too.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Forward Robert Horry, who won two titles in Houston, is
having his best playoff series since becoming a Laker. Rick Fox,
Derek Fisher and Brian Shaw play at the whim of the coach. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1995-96 CHICAGO BULLS
</P>
<P>
   Regular season record: 72-10. Playoff record: 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, guard: Averaged 30.4 enroute to ring number four
(of six).
</P>
<P>
   Ron Harper, guard: Stats belie his contributions to the success
of the Triangle Offense.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen, forward: Averages of 19.4 points and 5.8
rebounds as Jordan's second in command.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Kukoc, forward: Filled important outside shooting role
(13.1 points per) that separates the second Bulls' trilogy from the
first.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Rodman, center: Averaged a stunning 14.8 rebounds a game
before becoming increasingly insufferable.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Luc Longley, James Edwards and Bill Wennington added
inside depth, and Steve Kerr the outside gun. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1986-87 LOS ANGELES LAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Regular season record: 65-17. Playoff record: 15-4.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, center: Hall of Famer. Averaged 17.5 points
and 6.7 rebounds as hub of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, guard: Hall of Famer. A great season with 23.9
points, 6.3 rebounds and 12.2 assists a game.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Scott, guard: Shooter extraordinaire who filled his role
beautifully. Averaged 17.0 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   James Worthy, forward: Future Hall of Famer. Big Game James
averaged 19.4 and 5.6.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green, forward: Worker bee in the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Mychal Thompson and Kurt Rambis gave the Lakers great
inside depth. Michael Cooper was the league's best defender. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1985-86 BOSTON CELTICS
</P>
<P>
   Regular season record: 67-15. Playoff record: 15-3.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird, forward: Hall of Famer. Averaged 25.8 season, a
career high, to go with 9.8 boards per.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Parish, center: A quiet, efficient inside killer, he
averaged 16.1 points and 9.5 rebounds a night.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin McHale, forward: Mad man inside who gave no ground. Swears
he never committed a foul in his career. Averages of 21.3 and 8.1.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Johnson, guard: Still underrated. Boston's version of
James Worthy.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Ainge, guard: Pest.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Playing on two bad feet, Hall of Famer Bill Walton gave
the Celtics 7.6 points and 6.8 rebounds a game. Scott Wedman and
Jerry Sichting also contributed. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1981-82 LOS ANGELES LAKERS
</P>
<P>
   Regular season record: 57-25. Playoff record: 12-2.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, center: Hall of Famer. Not at his best, but
still averaged 23.9 and 8.6.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, guard: Hall of Famer. It's hard comparing years,
but he averaged 18.6 points, 9.6 rebounds and 9.5 assists a game.
</P>
<P>
   Jamaal Wilkes, forward: Lakers sharpshooter from early years,
averaging 21.1 points per.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Nixon, guard: We've all kind of forgotten how good Nixon
was. Averaged 17.6 points and 7.9 assists a game.
</P>
<P>
   Bob McAdoo, forward: Hall of Famer. Day before Christmas trade
gave Lakers the inside force they needed.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Mitch Kupchak and Rambis lent muscle inside. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
