<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7984 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS     05-28 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros make empty threat, bow to Braves
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Perhaps there were some among the Astros' fan base who missed the
point at the beginning of this homestand when Jeff Bagwell made the
astute assessment that it is not easy to lose games the way he and
his teammates have this season.
</P>
<P>
   We offer Saturday's 6-5 loss to the Atlanta Braves as exhibit
No. well, pick a number.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by a run in the bottom of the ninth inning, the Astros
loaded the bases against Braves closer John Rocker with nobody out.
Further tipping the scales in the Astros' favor, Daryle Ward was at
the plate against Kerry Ligtenberg with an extremely advantageous
3-0 count.
</P>
<P>
   In golf, this would be the equivalent of a gimmie putt. Somehow,
the Astros turned it into a triple-bogey, stranding all three
runners to lose for the 13th time in 14 one-run games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tough one to stomach,'' Astros third baseman Ken
Caminiti said. ``That's obviously a great situation to be in when
you're trying to pick up a run, but unfortunately, we weren't able
to get it done. It's just one of those things. We're battling right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Astros' biggest battle might have been with
themselves. Shane Reynolds had his worst outing of the season,
losing for the first time since Sept. 1, and the Astros didn't play
one of their better defensive games behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Astros banged out 10 hits, but they also
stranded 10 runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a really poor game,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``Our own mistakes cost us the game. If you make too many
mistakes against a team like the Braves, you're not going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing before the largest crowd (42,632) to watch at game at
Enron Field and for the first time during the regular season with
the retractable roof closed, the Astros failed in their fifth
attempt at extending a winning streak beyond two games. They have
lost nine of their last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good feeling,'' Astros shortstop Bill Spiers said.
``We put two wins together, have the bases loaded with no outs in
the ninth, and we don't win. It's frustrating. I really thought we
were going to win this game. Unfortunately, things aren't going our
way. It's definitely not for a lack of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiers was the subject of the most talked-about play of the
game. He was on third base in the ninth when Ward scorched a line
drive, which was caught by Braves center fielder Andruw Jones.
Instead of staying on the bag and preparing to tag up, Spiers
cautiously made his way down the third-base line. By the time he
retreated to the bag, it was too late to attempt to score.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions differed regarding whether Spiers could have scored had
he remained on the bag until the ball was caught, but considering
the shallow depth at which Jones plays _ not to mention the
strength and accuracy of his arm _ the potential tying run was
hardly a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been close,'' Spiers said. ``I would have tried
if I had done the right thing and stayed on the bag. Daryle hit a
rocket, and I assumed it was going to fall in (for a hit). The
cardinal rule is that you can't ever assume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake, and it cost us. If the ball has any air
under it all, you have to go back to the base. It was a bad read on
my part, and I feel bad about. (Third base coach Mike) Cubbage said
he would have sent me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker thought the ball was deep enough to allow Spiers to
score had he stayed on the bag, but the former big-league pitcher
also added: ``It's hard for me to criticize baserunning. I didn't
do a lot of it myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves opened the scoring in the first on Chipper Jones'
sacrifice fly, which brought home leadoff man Quilvio Veras, who
reached on a double.
</P>
<P>
   The run might have been prevented if Astros outfielder Moises
Alou had been able to hold Veras to a single, but Alou injured his
left quadriceps muscle on the play and wasn't able to get to the
ball quickly enough. He left the game in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them a run in the first,'' Dierker said. ``They held
Billy (Spiers) to a single on that same ball in the (bottom of the)
first. I'm not saying it's a play that should have been made, but
it was a play that could have been made.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta took a 3-0 lead on Andruw Jones' two-run homer in the
third, but the Astros narrowed the lead, scoring two in the bottom
of the third on Richard Hidalgo's single up the middle and a
fielder's-choice grounder by Lance Berkman. Hidalgo, who was
2-for-5, leads the club with 16 multi-hit games, and he's hitting
.500 (10-for-20) on the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Jordan's sixth-inning solo homer increased the Braves'
lead to 4-2, and Chipper Jones' two-run shot ended Reynolds' outing
with one out in the eighth inning _ the deepest Reynolds has
pitched into a game this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do my job as far as keeping the game close,'' said
Reynolds, who allowed three homers Saturday after giving up just
one in his first 20 innings at Enron Field. ``The offense had to do
a lot every inning just to get us back in the game. It was just one
of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Braves starter John Burkett, who is 4-0 with a 3.50 earned run
average over his last four starts, held the Astros to two runs in
six innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros pulled within a run on Caminiti's solo homer in the
seventh and a two-run shot in the eighth by Berkman, who tied a
career high with three RBIs. The Astros have hit at least one home
run in 14 consecutive games, tying a club record established last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Berkman's homer would be the Astros' last hit despite their
ninth-inning rally, which consisted of three walks issued by
Rocker, including an intentional pass to Caminiti. After Ligtenberg
got Ward to line out to center, he coaxed a game-ending double-play
ball to third from Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for a fastball,'' Hidalgo said. ``I just hit it
right at somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
