</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN--STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stars hold off Avalanche
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By SCOTT KAISER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ Before the start of the NHL Western Conference finals,
Dallas Stars goaltender Eddie Belfour said he was ``as good, if not
better'' than Avalanche counterpart Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   If the last two years mean anything, Belfour's right.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting for a second straight year in the conference finals,
Belfour outdueled Roy by turning away 31 shots as the Stars
dominated early and then held on for a 3-2 win in Game 7 on
Saturday night before a sellout crowd of 17,001 at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   With the win, Belfour and the Stars earned a chance to defend
their Stanley Cup championship against New Jersey in the finals,
which begin Tuesday in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to think about the next series,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   A second straight championship would allow Belfour to match Roy
in Stanley Cup rings, which Roy won previously in Montreal (1993)
and Colorado (1996).
</P>
<P>
   ``Patrick's a great goaltender and I always love competing
against him,'' Belfour said. ``I'm not a cocky guy, but I'm
confident in my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Avalanche rallied with a pair of third-period goals,
the game wasn't decided until a shot by Ray Bourque from the point
deflected off Adam Deadmarsh's arm and bounced off the right post
with 12 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a little lucky at the end, but fortunately we were able
to hang on,'' Stars right wing Brett Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   The teams came into Game 7 having scored 11 goals apiece, but
the Stars' special teams basically won the game in the first 20
minutes. They scored two power-play goals and killed off two while
not allowing a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That cost us the game,'' Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said.
``It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Zubov made it 1-0 at 6:36 when he one-timed a pass from
Mike Modano through a crowd just past Roy's left skate. Then, after
the Stars twice neutralized the Avalanche's power play, Modano
scored with 5.5 seconds left. Modano had a great look at an open
net off a pass from Richard Matvichuk, but his weak shot off the
heel of his stick somehow slipped past Roy and barely got inside
the post.
</P>
<P>
   ``The puck deflected off a D's stick (on the pass), but I still
tried to keep my eye on it,'' Modano said. ``At that point it seems
like it's all going in slow motion, but it somehow got by Roy's
shoulder. It was a little bit lucky, but it gave us a big boost
going into the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   For the series, the Stars' penalty-killing unit held the
Avalanche scoreless the final 17 times and allowed only three goals
in 33 opportunities. The two power-play goals in Game 7 gave them
six in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our special teams really got us going, especially tonight,''
Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who outshot the Avalanche 18-6 in the opening period,
kept the pressure on to open the second and scored again at 5:31.
This one was a bit of a gift as Derian Hatcher's wrist shot from
the point bounced off the back of Mike Keane and then off the leg
of a fallen Roman Lyashenko past Roy to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all along that both teams were evenly matched and that
breaks would decide the series,'' Hartley said. ``We couldn't buy a
break tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche outshot the Stars 15-2 the remainder of the
period, but Belfour robbed Deadmarsh on a short-handed breakaway,
then came up big three times while the Stars were short-handed late
in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first 30 minutes we were pretty dominant, but then we
started looking at the clock and hoping it would go by quicker,''
Modano said. ``When you do that, you start turning over the puck
and getting caught more in your zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg scored a short-handed goal at 5:25 and Milan
Hejduk followed with a deflection goal at 8:26 to give the
Avalanche new life, but Colorado could not finish off the rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't start behind three goals,'' Deadmarsh said. ``We made
a game out of it, but it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock credited his team's playoff experience over the past
five years for pulling the Stars through this Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our passion and enthusiasm to compete tonight was the
difference,'' Hitchcock said. ``We weren't afraid to lose and we
beat a hell of hockey team.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
