<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7986 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN--KNICKS-HNS &LR;      05-28 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--KNICKS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sprewell lifts Knicks to win
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ Lost and found.
</P>
<P>
   That pretty much sums up the New York Knicks in Game 3 of the
Eastern Conference finals against the Indiana Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks not only had lost the first two games in the
best-of-seven series, but they also had lost starting center
Patrick Ewing to injury.
</P>
<P>
   But just when it looked like another loss was inevitable,
Latrell Sprewell found his long-lost fourth-quarter touch and as a
result, the Knicks again find themselves in this series after a
98-95 victory before 19,763 at Madison Square Garden. The win pulls
the Knicks to within 2-1 in the best-of-seven series that resumes
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And they can thank Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   Just one game removed from what he called the worst playoff game
of his career, Sprewell scored nine of his 32 points in the fourth
quarter to lead the Knicks to the much-needed win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had to keep attacking them,'' Sprewell said. ``I had to
stay confident because I knew how big this game was. We didn't want
to go down 3-0 to them (the Pacers). The big thing was that Larry
(Johnson), Allan (Houston) and I stepped up and made the plays
today when we needed them.''
</P>
<P>
   And did the Knicks ever need them.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Ewing find himself sitting on the sidelines, unable
to play in this important game, but the Knicks also lost backup
center Marcus Camby with just under nine minutes left in the first
half after he sprained his right knee. An MRI revealed no ligament
tears, and the Knicks hope Camby and Ewing will be available for
Monday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing suffered the injury in the first quarter of Game 2 and has
not played since that game-starting seven-minute stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But just as they did last year, the Knicks took advantage by
opening up the offense, using Sprewell and Houston (28 points) to
slash to the basket or post up the Indiana guards.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Ward took advantage of the shifting Pacers defense,
finishing with 14 points and nine assists, outplaying Indiana's
Mark Jackson (three points, six assists and three turnovers).
</P>
<P>
   ``I do believe our team has exceptional pride. I do,'' said New
York coach Jeff Van Gundy. ``We could have, subconsciously anyway,
had a little give-in after halftime (when the Pacers were up by a
point), but I thought we hung in there very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, Pacers coach Larry Bird was frustrated by his
team's inability to put away a short-handed opponent. Frustrated,
but not surprised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (the Pacers' lack of focus in key games) has worried me for
the last 2{ years, to tell you the truth,'' Bird said. ``I have
seen it happen before. I have seen them focus, come in and beat a
team when they have to, but this is a strange team. When their
backs are to the wall they seem to play better. They never make it
easy on themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Indiana center Rik Smits, who was a huge
waste _ literally and figuratively _ in the second half. Minus
Ewing and Camby to deal with, The 7-4 center dominated in the first
half, scoring 21 points on 10-of-15 shooting, staking the Pacers to
a 42-41 lead. But he barely touched the ball in the second half,
getting only five shots to finish with 25 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt we should have went to him, especially at the start of
the third quarter,'' Reggie Miller said. ``I don't think we did a
good job of that, especially in the first six or seven minutes. We
should have rode him to the end, but we kind of went away from
him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Smits was hardly the only topic of postgame discussion in
the Pacers' locker room. Perhaps just as baffling was Bird benching
Dale Davis (16 rebounds Saturday, 48 in the series) and Miller down
the stretch. The benching of Davis (for the final 9:03) might have
been understandable given the Pacers needed outside shooting to
come back, but Miller has been known to knock down an outside shot
or two, especially in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Reggie was a little bit too involved with (talking
to) the referees,'' said Bird of his decision to bench Miller for
the final 1:49. ``One time I thought he was going to get a
(technical foul), and I didn't want to end up with him getting
thrown out of the game like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who finished with 19 points, was as abrupt when asked
about the benching.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coach's call,'' he said. ``I'm not going to check
myself in.''
</P>
<P>
   Had he done that it would have amounted to perhaps the best
decision the Pacers made in the second half. In addition to
ignoring Smits, the Pacers turned the ball over nine times in the
second half, including a stretch of five turnovers in seven
possessions, allowing the Knicks to open a 71-64 lead.
</P>
<P>
   While it might seem the Pacers mounted a comeback, that was
hardly the case. Jalen Rose scored 22 of his 26 points in the final
period, but only because the Knicks were playing token defense on
him while swarming Miller and Smits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sprewell and Houston (eight fourth-quarter points)
were keeping the Knicks out of trouble _ and out of a 3-0 hole in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we really shouldn't have been in that position (down
2-0), but we were,'' Houston said. ``We dug ourselves a hole, and
the only way to get out of it was to win a game. You can't worry
about who's out. You have to do whatever you can to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 0037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
