<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7987 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR &LR;      05-28 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TIME SURE FLIES FOR VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J.MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Fifteen years ago, I was bucking for a better job and figured one
way to get it was to write about some kids whose dad was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The dead man was Robert James Lugiewicz, about whom I knew
nothing. I hadn't seen news reports about his death and didn't read
articles describing his killer's trial until just before the
sentencing _ after I'd decided one way to get a better job was to
write about a murdered man's kids.
</P>
<P>
   Lugiewicz was shot to death by William Norman Zingsheim, a
former police officer. Lugiewicz had been dating Zingsheim's
ex-wife, Lisa Steiner. On Feb. 4, 1985, Zingsheim broke into
Steiner's apartment and shot Steiner and Lugiewicz. She lived and
testified against her ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   By the time of the murder, Robert Lugiewicz had been divorced
from wife Sandi for three years.
</P>
<P>
   He was a good father, though, and had remained close to his
family. Sandi gave him a key to her home, and he spent a lot of
time there with their children _ Mike, Robert and Sabrina.
</P>
<P>
   I showed up one evening not long after Zingsheim, who was then
40, had been sentenced to 30 years in prison. Sandi thought it
would be good for her children to have their say with the press.
</P>
<P>
   The kids were 10, 11 and 12 at the time. Sabrina was the oldest.
She held a letter she'd written to the judge. Because she was
nervous and sad, her hands trembled. She couldn't stop them. The
paper shook in her hands like the mythical butterfly flapping its
wings in South America, sending a shudder in the air that
eventually becomes a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   ``That man has not only killed my dad,'' Sabrina read,
haltingly, ``but some of my future and a lot of my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   I was an idiot looking for a story who'd stumbled into a
tragedy. Waves from that quivering piece of paper have resonated in
me ever since.
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Zingsheim (who changed his last name to
Johnson) managed to get his case reopened. Rather than go through
another trial, Sandi and her children agreed to a plea bargain that
reduced his sentence to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after all this time, Sandi Lugiewicz received a form letter
from the state Department of Corrections asking if she would like
to prevent Zingsheim/Johnson from writing to her at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to put it behind us,'' she says. ``But you can't.
Something always comes up. Some terrible reminder. I told the state
the only letter I want to receive about him is one saying he's
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, chances are the next official letter she receives, in
roughly four years, will inform her the killer is free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine it,'' she says. ``Just the other day Sabrina
(who's getting married) talked about how she wished her dad were
around. That'll never happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like a long time to be in prison _ 20 years. Maybe it
is, if you're the one behind bars. But to the family of the victim,
it flies by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because the pain never leaves,'' Sandi says. ``The
reminders are constant. The wounds never heal.''
</P>
<P>
   They can't. Not for me. Not for Sandi.
</P>
<P>
   Not for the children of Robert James Lugiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   When the guy who killed their father walks out of prison a free
man, all three of them will be in their 30s, the age their dad was
when he was shot to death. &QL; 
Reach Montini at Ed.Montini(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or (602)
444-8978. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
