<HEADER>
A7989 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PROBLEMS-H     05-28 1610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PROBLEMS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
What's gone wrong with the Astros?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was a three-year run of success unparalleled in the brief
history of the National League Central Division and a wondrous
collection of glory days that suddenly seem as distant a memory as
bell bottoms and eight-track tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the good-old days of 1997, 1998 and 1999 have given way
to these troubled times when the Astros find themselves trying to
shake the reality that they are among the worst teams in Major
League Baseball's 30-member fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   What happened?
</P>
<P>
   How did the Astros go from the euphoria of hanging division
banners year after year to the increasingly difficult exercise of
hanging onto their sanity night after night?
</P>
<P>
   A total collapse of a baseball team _ and yes, that is what has
happened to the Astros _ does not begin with a particular player or
a specific area of the team. It starts at the top, just as winning
does, filtering its way down the chain and ultimately manifesting
itself on the playing field.
</P>
<P>
   This is not an attack on the Astros' braintrust of owner Drayton
McLane Jr., president Tal Smith, general manager Gerry Hunsicker
and manager Larry Dierker. Lest we forget, these are the same men
who helped transform the Astros from a mediocre team to one of the
elite franchises in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   But management has to bear its share of responsibility for what
this team has become. While the Astros have never been among the
biggest spenders in baseball, they have managed to be successful in
an era when dollars often translate into victories.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps a drop-off was to be expected when the Astros trimmed
their payroll in the offseason. McLane and Co. aren't stupid; they
had to know the 2000 Astros were not as talented as the clubs they
have put on the field over the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But the hope was that they could remain competitive while
reducing payroll and that Hunsicker _ the 1998 Major League
Executive of the Year _ could catch lightning in a bottle with a
few of his acquisitions, as he has done so many times in the past.
</P>
<P>
   So far, that hasn't happened, leading many to wonder if the
Astros would have been better off keeping free-agents-to-be Mike
Hampton, Carl Everett and Derek Bell, all of whom were traded
during the offseason because the Astros didn't want to risk the
possibility of losing them without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   However, keeping the 1999 club intact would have cost at least
$65 million, which is out of the question for a club that still
considers itself a mid-market franchise, even with a new
revenue-producing park.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there are no guarantees in the go-for-it approach.
Remember, the Astros tried that in 1998 when they traded three
quality prospects to Seattle for ace pitcher Randy Johnson and
still didn't get past the first round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't Freddy Garcia, John Halama and Carlos Guillen look good
in the Astros' new brick, black and sand colors?
</P>
<P>
   While the Astros might still be struggling had they not decided
to begin their transition period this season, it's doubtful they
would have sunk this low. Hampton was their best pitcher in 1999.
Everett was arguably the best overall player on the team, and while
last season was a down year for Bell, he always has been a
dangerous hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss those guys big-time,'' Astros righthander Jose Lima
said. ``Those guys were a big part of this team and a big reason we
won the division for three years in a row. You can't help but miss
them. But we still have enough talent on this team to be doing
better than we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to another factor in the collapse. The Astros
have been fortunate to have key players have career years, from
Darryl Kile winning 19 games in 1997 to Moises Alou having a Most
Valuable Player-caliber season in 1998 to Lima winning a
career-high 21 games in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some of the key players are on pace for career-worst years.
</P>
<P>
   Who could have guessed that Lima, who won 37 games in 1998 and
1999, would drop seven of his first eight decisions in 2000? Or how
about Billy Wagner blowing six of his first 10 save opportunities
after converting 39 of 42 chances in 1999 en route to the NL
Fireman of the Year award?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of crazy,'' Lima said. ``I can't explain what's
going on with this ballclub. Last year, when I pitched well, we
won. I'm not saying the team is struggling because I'm not pitching
well, but it's a big difference. I have to do better, and we have
to do better as a team. I believe we will.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how realistic that expectation is remains a subject of
debate. Three of the Astros' five starting pitchers entered the
season with less than two full seasons in the majors. Two of three
starting outfielders had less than two years' experience as
every-day players, and the primary shortstop and catcher became
every-day players for the first time in their careers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with players such as Jeff Bagwell, Craig Biggio, Moises
Alou, Ken Caminiti and Shane Reynolds, the Astros didn't foresee
the hard times that awaited them in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm past being disappointed,'' Hunsicker said. ``I'm angry.
I'm puzzled more than anything else, because this is a good
baseball team. Yeah, we've got some weaknesses. But we've got a
good team, and for whatever reason, these guys haven't clicked
together.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros could benefit from another proven starting pitcher _
someone along the lines of Mike Mussina or Brad Radke, although
neither is likely to be available in a deal until the July 31
trading deadline nears.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen also is in need of at least one more arm, but the
alternatives at Class AAA New Orleans don't figure to be an
improvement over what the Astros already have.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop is a question mark, and the outfield defense has left
something to be desired. While the offense has been better lately,
it still tends to run hot-and-cold, and that's an inconsistency
this team can ill afford. But for now, what you see is what you
get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when you have multiple leaks, it's a bigger
challenge,'' Hunsicker said. ``It's not just one area, it's the
entire club. We just need to start playing up to our capabilities,
and the rest of it will take care of itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club does not need a major overhaul. A lot of these
players are the same players who have won championships the last
three years. There are a lot of reasons for why we are where we
are, but it's not because we don't have talent. We just need to go
out and play our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the only measure of improvement that matters is
victories, and if they don't start to occur with more frequency,
then what? Although the season is only two months old, it's not
totally premature to consider the possibility of breaking up the
team.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros are still struggling when the trading deadline
approaches, there will be many contending teams inquiring about the
availability of their playoff-tested veterans.
</P>
<P>
   One of those players almost certainly would be Bagwell, who is
under contract through 2001 and will be the Astros' top priority
this offseason, assuming he's still on the club.
</P>
<P>
   It may become crucial that the Astros determine their intentions
regarding Bagwell between now and the trading deadline. If they
believe they will be able to re-sign him, perhaps it's in the
club's best interest to trade Daryle Ward.
</P>
<P>
   If they come to the conclusion they can't sign Bagwell, the
Astros might be best served to trade the four-time All-Star and
begin to rebuild around their young nucleus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all speculation,'' Bagwell said. ``I'm sure that's not
going to happen real soon, but if it does, that's the
organization's decision. I'm almost 100 percent positive that's not
on their agenda at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play a lot better. That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best sign of how poorly the Astros have played is
their 1-13 record in one-run games. Simply put, good teams find a
way to win the close ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could very easily be 14-0 in those one-run games, and no
one would be saying a thing about anything,'' shortstop Tim Bogar
said. ``I don't know if there's an answer to it. You can't just
look at one aspect of a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of talent in this clubhouse. If you look at this
team, we shouldn't be losing. I don't know if there's an answer.
Losing is just as contagious as winning. When you're losing and
going through a funk, it's easy to say, `What's going to happen
next?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think that's what we have here. I think guys are
playing their hearts out. Everyone here knows we're a good team.
It's just a matter of getting some confidence, and the only way you
get confidence is to start winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning has a way of masking problems, just as losing has a way
of shining a magnifying glass on things. There is a certain amount
of tension in every big-league clubhouse, and the Astros' is no
different.
</P>
<P>
   But the problems have been low-keyed over the past few years
because the team was busy winning division titles. If the losing
continues, it will be interesting to see if the Astros remain a
harmonious bunch, from the manager to the coaches to the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we stick together, it's going to be fine,'' Lima said.
``But I hope we don't hate each other by the end of the year,
because it's getting to a point where it's kind of scary. It can't
get worse. The good thing is that we're not 20 games out. We're not
out of this thing, but if we keep losing, we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
