<SLUG> BC-RAC-CART-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Victory by de Ferran gives Penske No. 100
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NAZARETH, Pa. _ Three years without a victory and nine months of
tragedy and change are all behind Roger Penske now.
</P>
<P>
   The long elusive 100th victory for the winningest team owner in
CART history came at his home track Saturday when Gil de Ferran won
the Bosch Grand Prix at the Nazareth Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first oval-track victory for de Ferran, who joined
Marlboro Team Penske this season, replacing Al Unser Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have no idea how happy I am,'' said de Ferran, who was
choking back tears in Victory Lane. ``It has so much meaning to me
that it's hard to put into words. This is a great day in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauricio Gugelmin was second in the Nextel Mercedes/Reynard,
.815 seconds behind de Ferran in the Marlboro Honda/Reynard. Kenny
Brack, the 1999 Indianapolis 500 winner, finished third in the
Shell Ford/Reynard.
</P>
<P>
   But the day belonged to the Penske team, which finally got to
pull out and wear the caps that had ``100'' on the front. The team
was ecstatic with the win after going through so much
disappointment in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very important win for us,'' Penske said. ``There
have been a lot of great victories, but this is the greatest one at
the moment. It's great to see that we can be competitive again and
get back in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was the first victory for Penske since May 24, 1997,
when Paul Tracy took the checkered flag at Gateway International
Raceway outside of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1999 season was a disaster for the Marlboro cars. The
team was hopelessly noncompetitive and it was obvious that Unser
and Penske's long relationship was ending.
</P>
<P>
   But two deaths also marred the 1999 season for the team. Rookie
driver Gonzalo Rodriguez was killed in an accident in practice at
Monterey, Calif. in September.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Moore, who signed with Penske along with de Ferran last
July as the new drivers for 2000, was killed in California in the
final race of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was a year I want to forget,'' Penske said. ``I knew
what I had to do. It was time to level the playing field.''
</P>
<P>
   Penske hired Helio Castroneves to replace Moore, but Penske also
knew it would take major changes to the cars if his team was going
to regain it's past glory.
</P>
<P>
   The team switched from its own chassis to a Reynard chassis,
switched engines from Mercedes to Honda, and changed from Goodyear
to Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had our ups and downs,'' Penske said. ``But we've been
able to put the right combination together.''
</P>
<P>
   De Ferran, 32, has been the key component. The Brazilian had
three top-10 finishes this season before his victory Saturday, and
he also put his car on the pole at Miami and Long Beach. The Bosch
Grand Prix was the fourth victory of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Signing with Roger was very big deal for me,'' said de Ferran,
who received a three-year deal worth $10 million. ``That was the
first step and today we took another one. A lot of great drivers
have worn the same overalls I have on right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser, Bobby Unser, Mario Andretti, Rick Mears, Danny
Sullivan, Emerson Fittipaldi and Mark Donohue are some of the
winning drivers who have been with Penske over the years. The first
victory came in 1971 at Pocono, Pa., by Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   The 100 victories include a record 10 wins at the Indy 500, a
place where Marlboro Team Penske has not competed since the split
with the Indy Racing League in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
