<SLUG> BC-RAC-INDY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Indianapolis 500 field bolstered with CART additions
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Everyone who should be here isn't here, which is
the way it has been for the last five years at the Indianapolis
500.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the most important people in racing have put the
feuding behind them and are back to compete in the historic event
for the first time in half a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Al Unser Jr., whose family accomplishments of nine victories at
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway is part of racing lore, is back to
continue a storied tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Walker, one of the most respected team owners in
Indy-car racing, has returned with a splash _ a 19-year-old driver
named Sarah Fisher, who has the talent to be winner.
</P>
<P>
   With Lyn St. James also in the field, the starting grid will
have two women for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   And the pride organization of the Championship Auto Racing Teams
circuit _ the league that has boycotted the Brickyard in a bitter
civil war with the Indy Racing League _ has returned.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Ganassi and Team Target, with the last four CART
championships in tow, are back at Indy with drivers Juan Montoya
and Jimmy Vasser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not being here has been a bit of an absence in my racing
life,'' said Vasser, who competed in four Indy 500s before the
split. ``This is still the biggest race in the world and I'm happy
to be back. This race is the reason I wanted to become a race
driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganassi has spent close to $2 million to purchase the cars, the
engines and the crew he needed to take part in the 84th running of
the race.
</P>
<P>
   With the rescheduled CART race at Nazareth, Pa., Saturday coming
on the heels of a race in Japan last week, it turned out to be even
more of an undertaking than the Target team expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've put a lot of effort into this and we've asked a lot of
our people,'' Ganassi said. ``I really appreciate their hard work.
I don't think anybody can imagine the logistics of racing in Japan,
then back here, over to Pennsylvania and back to Indy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people on opposite sides of the CART-IRL squabble will view
this race as a chance to compare the best drivers of the two
open-wheel leagues. But Ganassi and his drivers have refused to get
into that type of debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy and I aren't here to show whether CART is better,''
Montoya said. ``We just came here to have fun and try to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya, the defending CART champion, is a rookie at Indy, but
he will start on the front row today, right next to defending IRL
champion and pole-winner Greg Ray.
</P>
<P>
   That will add even more drama to the start of the race, but
Vasser said all the differences won't matter once the green flag
drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just racing,'' Vasser said. ``CART opened a window on the
schedule this year and Chip asked us if we wanted to run Indy. We
all said yes. We had the resources to do it and we wanted to race.
It's that simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as flying any CART flags or making a political
statement, it's not like that for me. I don't feel like I'm
representing the CART guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The reasons for the split are long and complex, but the divide
started in 1996 when Indianapolis Motor Speedway president Tony
George founded the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   George believed costs needed to be controlled, oval-track racing
needed to be emphasized and something needed to be done to give
up-and-coming drivers a chance to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Worthy goals, but George infuriated CART owners in 1996 when he
insisted that the first 25 spots on the Indy 500 grid would be
guaranteed to IRL drivers. That rule has long since been abolished,
but the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   The two leagues, which now use different chassis and engines,
came close to a reconciliation last fall, but George broke off the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Any type of merger seems unlikely now, but the hope is that both
leagues eventually will run together at Indy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be back because there's magic in this place,''
Walker said. ``But it doesn't seem quite as dramatic as it once
was. The atmosphere is not quite as intense.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
