<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-TRIATHLON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT, EARLY PACE COMBINE TO PRODUCE OLYMPIC HEARTBREAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The day was hot. The stakes were cherished.
</P>
<P>
   The early pace, as America's best triathlete came to realize,
was enough to break a woman's heart.
</P>
<P>
   By all rights, Barb Lindquist of Jackson Hole, Wyo., was
supposed to race to the finish line yesterday with her spot on the
U.S. Olympic team secured and her head held high. The latest world
rankings listed Lindquist as fifth _ first among the U.S. female
triathletes.
</P>
<P>
   At the most recent world championships in Perth, Australia, the
30-year-old Lindquist had finished a highly respectable fourth.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone was expected to be on the victory stand at the U.S.
Olympic triathlon trials, it was Lindquist _ the national champion
and one-time almost-Olympian swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in the long minutes after yesterday's race, Lindquist
remained on her back in the event's first-aid tent, while medics
pumped fluids into her limp, exhausted body.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the race, which determined the remaining two women's
triathlon spots on the U.S. Olympic team, Lindquist sat quietly and
tried to reflect on what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really hot and also humid,'' she began. ``It became
kind of hard to breathe. I wasn't feeling stellar or anything
today.''
</P>
<P>
   No one seemed surprised, though, when Lindquist and eventual
winner Sheila Taormina emerged from the opening event, the
1,500-meter (nine-tenths of a mile) swim, with nearly a full
minute's lead. Lindquist, a Stanford teammate of Janet Evans, had
reached the finals in three events at the 1988 U.S. Olympic
swimming trials.
</P>
<P>
   But in yesterday's 40-kilometer (24.8 miles) bike ride,
Lindquist and Taormina had boldly stretched their lead, expanding
the anxiety behind them.
</P>
<P>
   The margin became three minutes _ and growing _ and former SMU
swimmer Laura Reback recalled, ``We were saying, `So, guys, are we
just going to give this race to those two girls? What on earth is
this _ three minutes?'''
</P>
<P>
   Lindquist explained later, ``I've been in plenty of races where
I've gone out as hard, so I know I didn't work the bike too hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't have done anything differently. That's way I race.
I work from the front.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Lindquist concluded the first of three laps of the
10-kilometer (6.2 miles) run course, it was clear that something
was wrong. The temperature was rising. Lindquist had dramatically
fallen 50 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
   Her second lap became a blur. ``I knew my body just wasn't
there,'' she said. ``My core was too hot. My legs got the
wobbles.''
</P>
<P>
   On the steep downhill at Goodson Drive, Joanna Zeiger passed an
obviously struggling Lindquist and moved into second place.
Lindquist mumbled a few words of encouragement _ she doesn't
remember _ to Zeiger, ran a few more steps and heard her husband
Loren shout, ``It's not worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   She stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a race like this,'' she said, ``third is last.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the leaders ran on in this first-ever U.S. Olympic
triathlon trials for women. For Taormina, it would be a stunning
affirmation of her decision to take up the sport after winning a
swimming relay gold medal at the 1996 Olympics. On a whim, she had
first tried a triathlon in her native Michigan in the summer of
1998. The race director, Lew Kidder, saw her obvious talent and
offered to be her personal coach.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of '99, she overcame a crippling bout with
rhabdomyolysis, a rare muscle disorder that can affect the liver.
Taormina doesn't know how she got it. Emergency room personnel more
commonly see the condition in burn victims and people who've been
crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Zeiger's story, on the other hand, was her quest. Three times
previously she had tried to make a U.S. Olympic team. She had come
up short at both the 1988 and 1992 swimming trials, and at the
Olympic marathon trials this past February, she had finished 30th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whole life everybody talks about the Olympics,'' her
mother, Karen, said, fighting back tears. ``It seems like such an
unrealistic dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were wondering, `How many Olympic trials can you go to and
not make it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Down the final stretch, Taormina smiled and slapped hands with
spectators that lined O'Connor Road. The only thing that broke her
smile later was when someone mentioned her partner for most of the
day, Lindquist.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything makes me cry, that will,'' Taormina said through
moistening eyes. ``It's because I almost feel like I don't deserve
to make this. I just hope her and Karen Smyers know how admired
they are.''
</P>
<P>
   In a quiet room of the event's headquarters hotel, Lindquist,
too, tried to search for the day's consolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing that I have a strong faith,'' she said.
``Otherwise, I'd be extremely devastated now. I have trust that he
has a bigger plan for me.''
</P>
<P>
   No, Barb Lindquist said, she has no plans yet to try for the
2004 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   {Gil LeBreton is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
