<HEADLINE>
FORCE-COIL BOND IS TITLE-RUN TOUGH IN NHRA FUNNY CARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Texas _ John Force admits there are few things that he
can teach Austin Coil.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing Force can teach his crew chief of 15 years has
nothing to do with racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always told him he made it big time when I saw the big house
with the swimming pool and saw matching Dobermans sitting there at
the pool,'' Force said. ``I said `Coil, let's go swimming.' That is
when he told me he couldn't swim. I said, `You are the smartest man
on the face of the earth and you can't swim.' It might be the only
thing in the world I could ever teach you.''
</P>
<P>
   Coil, 54, may not know how to swim, but when it comes to setting
up Funny Cars for Force, there is no better. And the numbers prove
it.
</P>
<P>
   Coil, always with a toothpick in his mouth, has been with Force
through all nine of his National Hot Rod Association Funny Car
championships and 84 national event victories.
</P>
<P>
   Force, who drives the Castrol GTX Ford Mustang, can tie Bob
Glidden's record for national event victories with a victory during
today's final eliminations at the Castrol Nationals at the Texas
Motorplex.
</P>
<P>
   It looks as though Coil has given Force a good chance. Force
earned the No. 1 qualifying position for the 95th time in his
career, with a time of 4.872 seconds for a top speed of 319.71 mph
on the all-concrete quarter-mile drag strip.
</P>
<P>
   While Force's electric personality and success continues to draw
media attention and more fans, Coil continues to ply his trade as
co-crew chief for drag racing's top star in relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   And it seems to be all right with Coil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never been one to stand up and smile, and I guess what
I work for is the respect of my peers,'' said Coil, who is a native
of Chicago but lives in California. ``I think I have gotten that,
and it makes me feel good. The old saying is I'm as famous as I
want to be, now I just want to be rich.''
</P>
<P>
   When Force called Coil in 1985 to offer him a job, Coil already
had winning credentials and more than 20 years in the drag-racing
business. He was part of the ``Chi-Town Huster'' Funny Car team
driven by Frank Hawley that won NHRA Funny Car titles in 1982 and
1983.
</P>
<P>
   But at the end of 1984, the major sponsor on the team left and
Hawley went on to start his drag-racing school. That is when Force
called.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess you could say he made me a deal I couldn't refuse,''
Coil said.
</P>
<P>
   There were some lean times in the early years at John Force
Racing, both admit. But once things started rolling, they did not
seem to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Force won his first Funny Car title in 1990, and 1992 is the
only year in the '90s that he did not win a title. Coil said
winning is just as much fun today as it was when Force won his
first national event in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Force and Coil have seen John Force Racing grow into a company
of more than 30 employees, along with Force's hiring Bernie
Fedderly and John Medlen to help with tuning duties on Force's car
and Tony Pedregon's machine.
</P>
<P>
   Force said there have been some arguments between the two
through the years, but they've always been resolved. Force talks
with reverence about Coil's intelligence and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to use a word I don't use often ... the man is
brilliant,'' Force said. ``As good as he is, he always listens and
comes to us and says `I'm in trouble. Help me.' That takes a lot. A
lot of guys would stay lost and would not let anybody know they are
in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Coil has seen Force win races and survive crunching wrecks, and
he wonders how Force continues to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Like in 1992 at Memphis, when Force's car hit the wall and
disintegrated and Force said he saw ``Elvis at 1,000 feet.'' After
that wreck, Coil was wondering if he would be working next week on
the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took John to the hospital, and I thought this is getting
out of hand here and I would not blame him if he came back and said
we can't try this hard because I don't want to die,'' Coil said.
``Instead, he said I will find the money to build more cars. I'll
wear two fire suits if I need to. It's been pretty good ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   The two will probably be together as long as Force continues to
thrill crowds with his trademark long burnouts and his ability to
win races.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten into such a ritual that we don't have to talk a
lot,'' Force said. ``He was the turning point, along with Castrol's
money. I've always said when Coil's had enough, I've had enough. In
the heat of battle, who is your life about? Your crew chief and
your money. I could not have what I have without \RCoil\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Force can repay him with that long-awaited swimming
lesson.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
