<HEADER>
A7996 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX     05-28 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TWINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' COOL-DOWN CONTINUES IN LOSS TO TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ An impressive streak came to an end for the
Rangers last night. For the first time in May, the Rangers are
going to lose a series.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Twins assured the Rangers of that when they
pounded Mark Clark for seven runs in 4 1/3 innings and went on to a
10-5 victory at the Metrodome last night. Ruben Mateo's two-run
homer in the third had given the Rangers a 4-1 lead before the
Twins scored four in the fourth and two in the fifth off Clark.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the second consecutive for the Twins in the
three-game series, which ends this afternoon. The Rangers had won
six consecutive three-game series and split a four-game series with
the Anaheim Angels since losing two of three to the Baltimore
Orioles on April 28-30.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, at 16-8, still have the best record in baseball for
the month of May, but they have lost three of four since their
seven-game winning streak and, more curiously, they've lost four of
five to the Twins this season. The Rangers were 12-0 against the
Twins last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at how we've played lately, it's disappointing,''
Rangers shortstop Royce Clayton said. ``But as hot as we were,
sometimes you hit a cool spell. If we win tomorrow, though, we can
get back to our winning ways, then go to Detroit and still salvage
a pretty good road trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the Rangers' sometimes fifth starter, is trying to
salvage his spot in the rotation but admitted last night's
performance didn't help much.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying too hard,'' said Clark after making his first
start since May 16. ``I want to be perfect and get back in the
rotation, but I've got to throw better than I did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark did nothing to change manager Johnny Oates' mind about
using Thursday's day off to skip him in his next start. The Rangers
don't need a fifth starter until June 5 against the Los Angeles
Dodgers. Oates said Clark is still likely to make that start, but
he didn't rule out other options, such as trying Matt Perisho or
bringing back Doug Davis from the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to visit with a couple of people in the next few
days,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Clark, Oates said, ``I just wish he'd get deeper in the
ballgame. He has his good innings, but it just seems like he runs
into trouble in the fourth or fifth inning for whatever reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark was fine through three innings, allowing only a
second-inning home run to Midre Cummings. But he fell apart in the
fourth, and much of it was his own doing.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Coomer started the inning with a single to left, then Clark
proceeded to load the bases by walking Cummings and Butch Huskey.
That didn't thrill the manager, especially considering Clark was
ahead 1-2 on Cummings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to make him swing the bat, in my mind,'' Oates
said. ``You've got to make him hit the ball. We pitched ourselves
in a hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey Koskie followed with a three-run triple to right-center,
and Matt LeCroy singled to left, giving the Twins a 5-4 lead. Clark
got out of that inning without further damage, but Huskey ended his
night with a two-run double with one out in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from the first two innings where I throwing the ball
good and everything was working to struggling to throw the ball
down the middle,'' Clark said. ``I started trying to make pitches
they couldn't hit instead of keeping the ball down and let them hit
ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Twins pitcher Joe Mays hung around for 62/3 innings to get the
victory, but he was fortunate he didn't get knocked out faster than
Clark. He escaped a one-out bases loaded jam in the first by
allowing just one run and kept the Rangers from scoring in the
second after giving up a leadoff triple to Clayton.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
