r s BC-BBC-BAYLOR-FLORIDA-TE     05-28 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-BAYLOR-FLORIDA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SORE-ARMED GATORS PITCHER HELPS SENDS BAYLOR TO EARLY EXIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ In the seventh inning, Florida coach Andy Lopez
began the trip out to the mound to retrieve his pitcher, Jeff
Cardozo. The Gators had the lead, and Cardozo had a sore arm. Time
for a little relief, Lopez figured.
</P>
<P>
   He was met by a team revolt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the position players gathered around Jeff, and told me to
let him finish it,'' Lopez said. ``I was kind of outvoted. When I
got back to the dugout, the guys on the bench told me the same
thing. So I guess it was 25-1.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, with a No. 5 national ranking, Baylor's season ended at
the hands of a young man who has pitched the season with the
knowledge that he probably has a torn rotator cuff. Cardozo (6-2)
threw 138 pitches, finishing the game and the top-seeded Bears
(45-17), who were eliminated from the NCAA regional tournament in a
10-1 loss.
</P>
<P>
   The elimination game between Florida and Southwest Texas,
scheduled for last night, was postponed after a 2-hour, 35-minute
rain delay. The Gators and Bobcats are scheduled to play at 1 p.m.
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest disappointment,'' said Baylor coach Steve Smith,
``is that I know we're a better club than we've shown here. And I
know our players wish they could have gone out leaving their best
game on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Smith expressed satisfaction with a season in
which the Bears won a Big 12 title despite having to replace the
``heart and soul'' of last year's 50-win team, including national
player of the year Jason Jennings. Of this season's 25-man team, 17
are freshmen and sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may have performed a miracle this year,'' Smith said. ``But
pitching and defense got us here, not hitting, and we didn't have
it today. They got a gutty performance from their pitcher, who has
had arm problems, and you just have to say, hats off to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gators (42-22-1) also recovered their hitting stroke,
driving Baylor's Kyle Evans (11-2) from the mound in the seventh
and finishing it with four runs against reliever Kyle Edens. First
baseman Kurt Keene had a two-run homer, and catcher Tony Socarras
hit his 19th home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the big lift came from Cardozo, who came to Lopez with an
offer after the team lost its closer and top two starters to Tommy
John surgery early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``His shoulder was hurt, but he said, `I can pitch for you every
Saturday, but I can't do bullpen or anything in between,''' Lopez
said. ``His shoulder was aching, but he wanted to help the team. So
he pitches on the weekends and doesn't pick up a ball in between.
I've never had anyone like him, not even on the national
championship team (1992) at Pepperdine.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his injury, Cardozo said, ``It's in my shoulder and
I'm pretty sure it's torn ... but I don't understand all the
technical stuff. It hurts the most when I'm warming up, then it
doesn't bother me for a while. It comes back about the fifth or
sixth inning \Rwhich is usually when he goes out\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always there, and it's something I have to deal with ...
but it doesn't hurt on every pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the Bears, who were shut out Friday by Blake Williams of
Southwest Texas State and managed only one run off Cardozo
yesterday, this was a tournament in which every pitch hurt.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
