<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUCE ALLEN BARELY MAKES FIELD IN PRO STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Texas _ Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen felt as though he
and his Reher-Morrison team were behind for most of this weekend at
the NHRA Castrol Nationals at the Texas Motorplex.
</P>
<P>
   But despite feeling as though they were behind, Allen's run of
7.049 seconds in yesterday's first qualifying session was enough to
get him into the 16-car Pro Stock field at the National Hot Rod
Association event.
</P>
<P>
   His time dropped from No. 13 to No. 16 by the end of yesterday's
final session, but the time withstood several challenges and was
good enough to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, of Arlington, will face No. 1 qualifier Kurt Johnson in
the first round of today's final eliminations in his Reher-Morrison
Pontiac Firebird.
</P>
<P>
   The final day of the four-day event at the all-concrete
quarter-mile drag strip concludes today, with eliminations
scheduled to start at 10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got out of the groove a little bit \Ron the last run of the
day\S, and we just knew we did not make a very good run,'' Allen
said. ``We were just lucky to stay in. The time we had \Rin the
first session yesterday\S was pretty good _ it was just slow _ and
we were in the process of trying to do some things to make it go
faster \Rin the second run\S.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen said the team got behind when he was not able to complete
his first qualifying run Friday. He said he noticed a miss in the
engine and was forced to shut it down, and the team was not able to
receive any data.
Important spot Gary Scelzi made one clean run during two rounds of
qualifying for this weekend's event, and that came Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But his time of 4.577 seconds and a top speed of 322.81 mph
stood through two qualifying sessions yesterday, even though Scelzi
lost traction in both runs. The two-time Top Fuel champion said
that conditions during the second qualifying session yesterday
could be similar to today's final eliminations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tricky,'' said Scelzi, who drives the Winston
Dragster tuned by Alan Johnson. ``The first round starts at 10
a.m., and that may be the best the track is going to be all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Scelzi's first-round matchup with Dallas resident Don Lampus
could be his most important run of the day. If he wins, he will
earn 60 points, 20 for advancing past the first round and 40 for
receiving the bye into the semifinals. Quick field Today's 16-car
Funny Car field is the quickest in NHRA history. John Force had the
quickest elapsed time of 4.872, with No. 16 qualifier Al Hofmann
running a 5.050 to barely get in the field. The longtime rivals
will square off in today's first round.
</P>
<P>
   Whit Bazemore also ran a 4.872 in yesterday's first session, but
Force's speed of 319.71 mph was close to 9 mph faster than
Bazemore's run of 310.34. Hammonds misses Tom Hammonds, a power
forward for the Minnesota Timberwolves, did not qualify for today's
Pro Stock final eliminations. Hammonds improved on each of his
qualifying runs, coming up with a time of 7.094 seconds, his best
of the day.
</P>
<P>
   But to get into the field, Hammonds would have had to run 7.060
or better to get in.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second race of the season for Hammonds, who
attempted to qualify for last weekend's event in his
Winnebago/Itasca Camaro Z28. He will run in 13 NHRA national events
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hammonds has run in the NHRA Pro Stock class for 41/2 years and
said when he retires he plans to run the series full time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
