<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-AVS-TEX     05-28 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEVENTH WONDER: STARS OUTLAST AVALANCHE FOR CUP BERTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Fear swept through Stars captain Derian Hatcher's body.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe 20 seconds separated the Stars from a second consecutive
trip to the Stanley Cup Finals and a chance to defend last season's
championship. Only Colorado wouldn't go away. The Avalanche kept
coming and coming while Dallas clung to a one-goal lead with 12
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado defenseman Ray Bourque attempted to erase 59 minutes
and 48 seconds of Dallas dominance with a single shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew there was a shot coming from the point so I tried to
position my body,'' Stars goalie Ed Belfour said. ``I think it hit
me in the hip and ricocheted to the post. It was like slow motion
watching it go toward the post.''
</P>
<P>
   The shot dinged off the post and into the corner, preserving the
Stars' 3-2 victory in Game 7 of the Western Conference Finals. The
victory sends the Stars to New Jersey, needing to beat the Devils
for back-to-back Cups. They need four more victories and get their
first chance in Game 1 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Which isn't to say the Stars don't know how close they came to
not having the chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary,'' Hatcher said of the final 80 seconds. ``You
don't want to be in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars nearly coughed up a 3-0 lead. The Avs had pulled their
goalie. The desperation was palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with this season's Stars, you wouldn't expect
anything less than a down-to-the-last-second affair. Certainly not
between these teams. For the second consecutive season, the Avs and
Stars required seven games to decide on a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the best team in the league for beer sales,'' Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We make you stay right to the end. We
are unbelievable. Our season has been about surviving and about
finding a way, maneuvering to wins.''
</P>
<P>
   After Avs forward Milan Hejduk scored at 8:26 of the third
period to slice Dallas' lead to 3-2, the game became maneuvering
like mad. The final 11 minutes and 34 seconds of Game 7 were one
really long penalty kill for the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was ever going to end,'' said Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk, who played despite suffering a mild
concussion in Game 6. ``I looked at the clock, there was 11 minutes
left, and what is it now, 3 a.m. I think? That's how it felt. I
didn't think it was ever going to end. Unfortunately, all playoffs
and all regular season we've had to make it interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Interesting? The game looked like it was going to be a
suspenseless, put-it-in-the-books affair after the first period.
The Stars didn't just beat the Avs in the first 20 minutes. They
embarrassed them.
</P>
<P>
   They buried them with offense, including a 18-6 shot
differential. When the opening 20 minutes were complete, the Stars
had a 2-0 lead with both goals coming on power plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our special teams tonight really got us going,'' Stars center
Mike Modano said. ``It was a big goal by Zubie, and, our second
goal, I think really settled us into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Sergei Zubov simply finished what had been a
better-than-anything-they-could've-hoped-for first power play. The
Stars had six shots, the last by Zubov beating Avs goalie Patrick
Roy at 6:36 of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The second shot Modano spoke of was his own, a power-play blast
with 5.5 seconds remaining in the first period that bounced off
Roy's glove, hit the post and gave the Stars a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars also smothered them defensively. Not only couldn't the
Avs generate anything five-on-five, they struggled with a man
advantage, too. They not only didn't score on either of their
first-period power plays, they didn't get a shot on either.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to leave the game out there,'' Hatcher said.
``Game 6 was left out there, and they got the win. We didn't want
that to happen. We wanted to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy everybody in Dallas wanted suspended for his Game 6
elbow that left Matvichuk and what turned out to be winning goal,
hit his stick.
</P>
<P>
   The shot had an even-more-indirect path than one that went off
Avs forward Chris Drury's knee to win Game 6. Hatcher took a shot
from the point that hit Andreychuk's stick, bounced off Mike
Keane's butt onto Roman Lyashenko's calf and finally over Roy's
shoulder at 5:31 of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went of my butt and then Roman's butt, I believe,'' Keane
said. ``I don't think it gets any more uglier unless it goes off
his face.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal gave the Stars a 3-0 lead which they held until 5:25 of
the third period. The Avs had finally started to generate some
offense, but their first goal came as they were killing a penalty.
With his goal, Avs forward Peter Forsberg seemed to be saying
``we're not going down easy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When two teams are evenly matched, it's never easy,'' Stars
general manager Bob Gainey said.
</P>
<P>
   From 8:26 of the third period on, there certainly was nothing
easy about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who outshot the Avs for most of the game, were caught
and subsequently passed in the third period. The difference once
again was Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't mean to antagonize Roy with his statement that
he was ``as good as Patrick or better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Patrick is a great goaltender, and I always enjoy
playing against him,'' Belfour said. ``I'm not a cocky guy, but I'm
confident in my ability.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are, too. He stopped 31 of 33 Colorado shots and 191
of 204 in this seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   His Game 7 performance was simply the icing on the cake. He's
4-0 now when a series goes to a seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience in Game 7 really showed,'' Hitchcock said. ``We
lost to Edmonton \Rin 1997\S, and we learned some lessons. We were
nervous, and we played afraid to lose. We vowed as a team and an
organization if we ever got in those things again we would just
throw everything we could, passion and emotion and everything, at
it to win, and if we got beat we got beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was playing with not afraid to win and that's what we
played tonight. We weren't afraid to win.''
</P>
<P>
   No, exactly what they did. The West has been won. The Cup
awaits. The Stars say they aren't satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more important than winning the Cup for this
team,'' Keane said. ``If we didn't get here, the whole year would
be a washout. ... You want to win the Cup. They want to win it. We
don't want to give it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
