<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY'S GODS WINKED AT STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The puck hit the post, and the Cup doesn't hit the
road. Not yet anyway. Maybe not ever.
</P>
<P>
   To see was to believe last night. Believe that the Stars' 3-2,
Game 7 survival against Colorado had to be a sign from the hockey
gods that the Stanley Cup is extending its local lease for another
year, if not beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Those final frantic seconds at Reunion Arena left no doubt that,
as advertised, almost nothing separated the two combatants in the
NHL's Western Conference Finals. But in the end, there was
something.
</P>
<P>
   Almost nothing became the post that stands on the right side of
Eddie Belfour. Quick, before the New Jersey Devils get to town _
somebody better bronze that thing. Better yet, get Tom Hicks to
spring for a gold-plating.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fun Game 7 for a while. The ``Ed-die's Better'' chant
aimed at Patty Roy was a nice twist. The Reunion house can be
excused for celebrating prematurely as the Stars did indeed appear
to be traveling Easy Street to the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   But just as everyone was absolutely certain the Avalanche could
never recover from a 3-0, third-period burial, this series suddenly
reverted to form and substance. Game 7, like the rest of the
series, became too close to call.
</P>
<P>
   The ``wall of noise'' created by 17,001 throats never lost
velocity, but in the final 30 seconds of uncertainty, lungs were
drained of air and hearts tumbled into stomachs. About that time,
Ray Bourque took his shot from the point. This one will be
remembered for a while in both Denver and North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There were strange goals scored in the series _ the game-winner
for the Avs in Game 6 off Chris Drury's knee. What turned out to be
the game-winner in this Game 7 was a deflection off the butt of
Mike Keane to the leg of Roman Lyashenko to the back of the net
behind a stunned Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's shot, with 12 seconds to play, found a body part of
Adam Deadmarsh (he thought it was his arm), who was trying to hold
his ice in that battleground known as the slot. The puck shot off
Deadmarsh, headed toward net, except it caught Belfour's hip, then
took an agonizing turn toward the corner of the Avs' promised land.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour could do nothing except watch. Watching was the hard
part. ``Everything became slow motion,'' he said. ``I knew it was
gonna be tight. And then it hit the post.''
</P>
<P>
   And from there, the puck took a crazy Stars' bounce, and was
cleared, allowing a return trip to the Stanley Cup Finals, where
beating the Devils will be expected by everyone, including Las
Vegas. Hockey-wise, the Stars will be heavily favored to repeat as
champions and build the foundation of a dynasty in the
Chicken-fried Kingdom. And not even the emotional drain of this
series with the Avalanche will be allowed as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you lucky?'' came a media interview question aimed at Ken
Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as hard as we work,'' shot back Hitch, not appreciating
the question. ``We've been lucky for three years \Rthree Western
Conference Finals appearances\S and we've got rings to prove it.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, in the end last night, luck was involved. The puck hitting
the post is the same as a smile and a wink from the hockey gods.
But no matter which team won this series, it would take luck. The
Avs had it in Game 6 with that puck off Drury's knee.
</P>
<P>
   Luck is not a factor, however, in the Avalanche never scoring
more than two goals in any of the seven games. That's all about
Belfour, all about supreme penalty killing, all about the defensive
commitment Hitchcock beats daily into his players. They cuss him
for it, sometimes out loud. But they win with it, and they survived
this series with it.
</P>
<P>
   And that was not luck in the first period last night, when as
Colorado coach Bob Hartley, stating the obvious, said, ``the game
was won.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars scored twice on power plays. The Avs didn't come close
to scoring on two power plays of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also an emotional fury from the Stars in that
first period like nothing ever witnessed, hockey-wise, in these
parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly the best since I've been here,'' Hitchcock said.
``We've never played a period like that. We wanted to create a
sense of urgency and passion _ we wanted to throw so much at them,
they couldn't handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars did. The Avs couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   And then Hitchcock added something else. The coach, and his
staff, deserved no credit for it. ``What was seen in the first
period, that came from our team leaders, and we have nine players
who form the leadership for us,'' Hitchcock said. ``The coaches
asked those nine players to make this pre-game point to the entire
team. What was seen was the team's response to the team leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such an impressive opening display, the Avs would not go
away without a pride-surge of their own. A puck hitting the post
had to finally decide Game 7. And maybe decide that the Cup stays
put.
</P>
<P>
   {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
