<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-DEFENSEMEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENSEMEN LEAD STARS BACK TO FINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk was feeling a little
dizzy last night. It had nothing to do with the concussion he had
in Game 6. It had everything to do with a return to the Stanley Cup
Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights after seeing stars, Matvichuk had helped the Stars
win the Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The headaches were there, but it's a Game 7, and I wasn't
going to miss it,'' said Matvichuk, who had an assist in the Stars'
3-2 victory. ``You'd have to take out my heart and cut off one of
my legs for me to miss that.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of year, everybody's bumped up and injured. You
see one guy on either side of the ice that doesn't have an ice bag
on, there's something wrong. That's playoff hockey. It's the
healthiest survive, and defense wins championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk was knocked out on a hit by Dave Andreychuk in the
first period Thursday, and the Avalanche scored two goals after
that for a 2-1 victory. Matvichuk showed up for Game 7, and the
Avalanche disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Before the series began, Matvichuk and his defensive partner,
Derian Hatcher, had talked about containing Peter Forsberg.
Instead, they stopped him.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg had two goals, three assists and 24 shots in the
series. Second-line center Joe Sakic had even less impact, with no
goals, three assists and 24 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a key to our success this series,'' Matvichuk said.
``... Peter and Joe are probably two of the best players in the
league, and they're playing with guys like Adam Deadmarsh and
\RMilan\S Hejduk and guys like that who are very skilled. We know
where they want to go, which is the front of our net. Fortunately,
we did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' defensemen have Dallas playing for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk, Hatcher, Darryl Sydor, Dave Manson, Sergei Zubov and
Sylvain Cote were the Stars' sixth sense. Besides helping limit the
Avs to 13 goals on 204 shots in the series, the defensemen had the
Stars' special teams make a special delivery: the Campbell Bowl for
winning the West.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 6-for-29 on the power play in the series,
including 2-for-4 last night.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov scored a power-play goal and had an assist on center Mike
Modano's power-play goal. Sydor had an assist, and Hatcher had an
assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our power play really came through when we needed it,'' Sydor
said. ``We had two big goals. We just wanted to get pucks to the
net and some traffic, and they went in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' penalty killers held the Avs to 3-for-33 on the power
play for the series, including 0-for-3 with only four shots last
night. Colorado did not score on the power play in its last 18
chances. (The Avs did score a short-handed goal last night.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Our special teams did a great job,'' Hatcher said. ``Our power
play outdid their power play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' defensemen outdid the Avalanche defensemen, which is
why Matvichuk, despite a headache and stitches above his left eye,
was feeling pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This means a lot,'' Matvichuk said. ``This is something guys
always dream about.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
