<SLUG> BC-HKN-BOURQUE-AVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISAPPOINTED BOURQUE HOPES FOR ANOTHER CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TRACEY MYERS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the past 21 years, Ray Bourque has seen only
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   He came to Colorado looking for a chance to win his first
Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   With seconds remaining in last night's Western Conference Final,
he had his chance.
</P>
<P>
   With about 12 seconds remaining, Bourque sent a shot from the
point that teammate Adam Deadmarsh deflected. The puck slipped past
Eddie Belfour and rebounded off the post.
</P>
<P>
   The team was different. The frustration the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see it. But I heard it hit the post,'' Bourque said.
``I was trying to get closer to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Bourque's chance was gone for another year.
</P>
<P>
   But his night was not all frustrating. The veteran assisted on
Chris Drury's goal in the third period that pulled the Avs to
within striking distance, at 3-2. He posted just two shots, but
both were good scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got an opportunity to play in seven games in the
semifinals,'' Bourque said. ``It was a great experience, a great
ride. We had a good run but we came out short of what we wanted to
accomplish. Anything less than the Cup is not good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disappointment, Bourque said he plans to play again
next year and continue his quest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed Denver and I am definitely interested in coming
back,'' he said. ``I'm pretty sure I am coming back somewhere next
year. It was a joy to play in Denver, so we'll wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque's missed chance may have hurt his teammates even more,
especially Dave Andreychuk, who came to Colorado with Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel real bad for \RRay\S, but he'll get another chance,''
Andreychuk said. ``We all know him, and he deserves better.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the disappointment, Bourque said he loved the experience
of playing with the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to do over, I'd do it in a heartbeat,'' Bourque said.
``I am very happy with the decision I made. When I got traded I
wanted to make the playoffs. I really thought we had a good enough
team to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Bourque will have to look for his next chance.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
