<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CUP-MATCHUPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS, DEVILS LOOKING TO ERASE `BORING' TAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The purists will go to their graves swearing both teams
long ago sold their souls to hockey's devil: Neutral zone traps,
smothering defenses, grinding, mucking, grabbing, clutching.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL instituted the mandatory helmet rule two decades ago in
anticipation for the 2000 Stanley Cup Finals between the Stars and
the New Jersey Devils, two of the toughest, hardest hitting teams
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jersey is a lot similar to our hockey team,'' said Stars
winger Kirk Muller, who spent seven seasons with the Devils. ``They
are going to plug along and grind it out. It's going to be two
similar teams plugging along and waiting for an opportunity. We
have to play well defensively again, and it's going to be a tough
series.''
</P>
<P>
   The puck drops Tuesday night at Continental Arena in East
Rutherford, N.J., where the Devils are 5-3 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, be wary of the experts and pundits who will surely
label the styles of both teams and the ensuing series as boring or
tedious or as much of an eyesore as watching the NBA's New York
Knicks battle the Miami Heat series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they told us last year, too, that Dallas and
Buffalo was a boring series,'' Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk
said. ``We played in it, and you can ask us, ask our fans, ask
Buffalo and their fans. If that's boring, I'd hate to see
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils and Stars do play the similar, tight-checking style.
They do clog the neutral zone. They do put a premium on defense
first, scoring second. It is a battle of big, bad defensemen.
Richard Matvichuk and Derian Hatcher patrol the Stars' zone.
Hard-nosed Devils defenseman Scott Stevens, as Eric Lindros found
out Friday night, will attack and do it with unforgiving force from
anywhere on the rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what it is,'' Matvichuk said. ``You don't want
to be coming down the middle with your head down.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams also feature two of the league's top goaltenders.
Eddie Belfour dispatched Colorado's Patrick Roy for a second
consecutive season. Now, he faces New Jersey's Martin Brodeur, who
owns the playoffs' best goals-against average of 1.77 and held the
Flyers to one goal in Games 5, 6 and 7 as the Devils rallied from a
3-1 deficit. Belfour is right behind at 1.80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie's solid, and he gets better and better as it goes on
here,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``He's a real focused
goalie right now. He has another tough challenge ahead of him in
Brodeur, so it will be interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this series gets bogged down as an ugly defensive series,
a few offensive facts are pertinent. Entering the series, the
Devils and Stars have combined for 89 playoff goals in 17 games.
The Devils have scored more goals in the playoffs than anyone with
46. The Stars have scored 43 and lead all playoff teams with 16
different players contributing goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars roll out Mike Modano and Brett Hull on their top line.
The Devils match with 24-year-old sensation Patrick Elias, who had
two goals in their Game 7 victory against Philadelphia, and Jason
Arnott. The Stars have playmakers like Nieuwendyk and Jamie
Langenbrunner. The Devils have Petr Sykora and Claude Lemieux. The
Stars have rookie Brenden Morrow. The Devils have
rookie-of-the-year Scott Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks New Jersey has a real tight defensive team,
but they have an awful lot of skill up front, too, and they can zip
that puck around,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``They are a very good team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
