<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8007 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-BELFOUR-ROY-TEX     05-28 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BELFOUR-ROY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' BELFOUR BACKS UP CLAIMS WITH SUPERIOR PLAY AGAINST ROY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS_ Reunion Arena crowds don't often agree on cheers for
anything other than goals or dot races.
</P>
<P>
   But when a few fans began chanting ``Eddie's Better,'' the the
rest of the 17,001 fans quickly agreed and thunderously roared in
unison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I definitely could hear that,'' Stars goalie Ed Belfour
said. ``It might be better until they wait till the last minute,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, especially after Ray Bourque's shot bounced off Adam
Deadmarsh and hit the post with 12 seconds remaining, ensuring the
Stars' 3-2 Game 7 victory in the Western Conference Finals at
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Close shots aside, for the second consecutive season Belfour
proved that he is as good, if not better, than Colorado goalie
Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was far from Eddie to come off sounding cocky,'' Stars
winger Mike Keane said. ``He just wanted the same status as
Patrick. Patrick is a world-class goalie. For Eddie to be not in
the same breath as Patrick ... maybe people might start talking
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   There is little choice now.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, who improved his record in Game 7s to 4-0, outplayed
his celebrated counterpart during the game and throughout the
series. By defeating Roy for the second consecutive season, Belfour
also evened his personal playoff record against Roy to 10-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Patrick is a great goaltender, and I always enjoy
playing against him,'' Belfour said. ``I think we're both great
goaltenders. I am not a cocky guy, but I am confident in my
ability.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, Belfour stopped 31 of 33 shots. Roy stopped 26 of 29
attempts. For the series, however, Belfour stopped 191 of 204 shots
and Roy stopped 156 of 170 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie made great saves one after the other and allowed us to
be in every single game,'' Stars center Mike Modano said.
``Everyone talked about him and Roy coming into this series, and it
was going to be who played better was going to be the team that was
going to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, Eddie was the better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite allowing two third-period goals in a span of 3 minutes
and 1 second, including Milan Hejduk's redirect shot that bounced
through his legs, Belfour's play last night encapsulated his effort
in the series: dominant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were putting it in, and he was putting it right back out
and killing the momentum,'' Colorado forward Dave Reid said.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour killed Colorado's momentum all series. He never allowed
more than two goals in any of the seven games and hasn't in eight
consecutive games dating back to Game 4 of the series against San
Jose.
</P>
<P>
   In his past 31 postseason games, Belfour has allowed three or
more goals six times.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Avs, Belfour was 3-1 in one-goal games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This series, there is no seventh game without Eddie Belfour,''
ESPN analyst Bill Clement said. ``Two times, maybe three, Dallas
doesn't win without Belfour.''
</P>
<P>
   So, this finally proves that Belfour is as good as, if not
better, than Roy?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' Clement said, ``if the Stars win the Stanley
Cup. If he does, it puts an exclamation point on it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
