<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY SETTLES FOR TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- With more than a third of the season gone, and more
than a third of its original starters sent elsewhere, the dominant
Galaxy team that left preseason camp and cruised through March and
April with a 5-0-2 mark -- is looking more and more average each
passing day.
</P>
<P>
   Against San Jose, the second worst team in the MLS, the Galaxy
could only manage a 1-1 draw in front of 17,831 at the Rose Bowl on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's record moved to 6-1-6, but they are 1-1-4 in their
last six matches. San Jose is now 2-6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid warned this could happen, and has
mentioned countless times that the Galaxy may as well start the
season over again with so many recent changes.
</P>
<P>
   With the allocation of newly acquired Mexican striker Luis
Hernandez, the Galaxy is feeling the loss of departed starters
Clint Mathis, Roy Myers and Joey Franchino -- all lost in the
Hernandez fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   The problems are spread:
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Rookie central defender Danny Califf is getting
baptized while Robin Fraser recovers from a strained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Striker Cobi Jones hasn't scored since April 1, and the
Galaxy has only six goals in their last six games after scoring 15
goals in their first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   (Bullet) Hernandez, touted as MLS' franchise player, is without
a goal in two games and may need two or three more weeks untill he
is finally in sync with the offense.
</P>
<P>
   What else, or does there need to be anything else? Oh, the U.S.
Cup begins next week. The Galaxy loses Fraser, Jones and Greg
Vanney to the U.S. team while Hernandez joins Mexico for the next
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   At least Schmid has until September to sort this out.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy struck first.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching the penalty arc, Simon Elliott picked up an errant
clear by San Jose defender Mauricio Solis. Elliott didn't waste any
time, firing a return shot to the upper-right netting to give the
Galaxy a 1-0 lead in the 22nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   The play started down the left-side as Vanney sent a pass across
the field for Jones. Jones picked the ball out of the air, cutting
inside to lose Earthquakes defender Wade Barrett. Jones attempted a
cross in the middle, but Solis cleared it away straight to Elliott,
who notched his second goal of the season from 20-yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, thin in the back with the loss of Fraser and Ezra
Hendrickson (yellow-card accumulation), looked confused on a
set-play that evened the match, 1-1, in the 30th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Off an innocent looking pass from the right side, Iranian
striker Khodadad Azizi sent a looping cross over the middle for
Ronald Cerritos -- with no Galaxy defender in sight. Cerritos had
his choice of spots, finishing with a header to the right of
Hartman for his fifth goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Elliott bursted down the left-side, sending a cross to
Hernandez, who was sneaking near the back post. Hernandez timed his
shot, but his one-touch shot off a bounce sailed high over the goal
in the 11th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Earthquakes nearly scored on an ensuing counter. Cerritos
took a through pass from Azizi. He was all alone to the right of
the goal, but Hartman protected the near post as Cerritos' shot
sailed off Hartman's leg and out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   (Notes) The Galaxy signed midfield Ivan Polic, a native of
Kraljevo, Yugoslavia, as a discovery player.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old midfielder trained with the Galaxy during
preseason. After losing Clint Mathis, Joey Franchino and Roy Myers
to acquire Hernandez, the Galaxy had a roster spot available.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited to add Ivan because he is a player that already
has experience overseas and is technically a very confident
player,'' said Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid. ``With the number of
players we lost in the Hernandez acquisition, one of our needs is
another central midfielder and that's something Ivan can rectify
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Polic was naturalized in 1995, meaning he does not count as a
foreign player. He last played for Radnicki Nis of the Yugoslavian
first division and was a four-year letterman at Southern Methodist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
