<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8015 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a COYOTES-GRETZKY-AZR     05-28 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS FLOCK ING TO COYOTES 
</HEADLINE>
 COYOTES-GRETZKY-AZR  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHIP SCUTARI 
 and BOB MCMANAMA 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just minutes after developer Steve Ellman announced that hockey
superstar Wayne Gretzky would join the new Phoenix Coyotes
ownership team, the phone started ringing with $1 million offers.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a dozen investors, local and out of state, called late
Friday night and expressed interest in a possible financial share
in the franchise, Ellman told The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   The late-night calls came after Ellman corralled Gretzky with an
all-day sales pitch at Gretzky's Southern California home. If
Gretzky had turned down Ellman's eleventh-hour overture, the
Phoenix Coyotes likely would be taking their sticks and pucks to
Portland where Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen was waiting with his
billions.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the very beginning, all we were focused on was keeping
hockey in Arizona,'' said Ellman, who would not disclose names of
the potential investors. ``That's what it came down to. Truly, I
have slept less than 24 hours in the last seven days.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cox Communications spokesman said Gretzky's involvement could
spark renewed interest from Valley companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, we're very excited that the Coyotes will be
staying in Phoenix,'' Cox spokesman Alex Horwitz said. ``Cox has
always had a solid relationship with the Coyotes. We hope to
continue that relationship down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Gretzky, Ellman would not have put down a
non-refundable, $10 million payment as the crucial first
installment of an $87 million purchase of the Coyotes. Ellman
enticed Gretzky to help save hockey in the Valley, outwitting a
half-dozen other teams who were trying to woo the hockey legend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ellman secured a deal with the NHL that will give him
more time to raise cash and complete the purchase. Ellman will have
to pay $6.5 million instead of $17 million to former Coyotes owner
Richard Burke by June 30. The NHL will give Ellman until Dec. 31 to
pay off Burke and complete his $100 million fund-raising efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And Ellman is banking on his business savvy and financial acumen
to whittle down operating losses at America West Arena while he
builds an 18,000-seat arena at Los Arcos Mall in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   By raising $100 million, Ellman says, he can wipe out Burke's
interest payments on a $60 million loan, limit red ink and save
money. Ellman is predicting that his cost-cutting measures will
limit annual losses to $8 million a year. The team now loses about
$13 million to $15 million a year because 23 percent of the seats
at America West Arena have obstructed views for hockey, Burke has
said.
</P>
<P>
   The future of professional hockey in the Valley was hanging by a
thread Friday. Recurring rumors swarmed talk radio with word of the
Coyotes' exodus.
</P>
<P>
   Ellman didn't hear the blather. On Friday, he hopped an early
flight to Los Angeles. Then, he spent all day at Gretzky's Thousand
Oaks home before he persuaded him to come to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne and I have believed all along that keeping hockey in the
Valley was the right thing to do for Arizona, our community and our
children,'' Ellman told The Republic. ``This is a pledge to
Scottsdale voters that we're go ing to build Los Arcos and com mit
to the revitalization plan for south Scottsdale.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8016 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-B     05-28 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAY OF HOPE EXTINGUISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Ray Bourque followed his heart, left Boston on a quest,
and Saturday &UR;  &LR; night his lifelong passion sifted ever lower in the
hourglass.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas Stars, taking advantage of a lackluster early effort
by Colorado, rolled up a 3-0 lead by the second period and hung on,
surviving a Bourque shot that rang off the left post with 12
seconds to go, for a 3-2 victory in Game 7 of the Western Confernce
finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, defending NHL champs, will face the New Jersey Devils
in the best-of-seven Stanley Cup finals, which begin Tuesday night
in East Rutherford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought we had a good enough team to get there,''
said Bourque, after his 21st NHL season ended like all the others,
without his name etched into hockey's holy chalice. ``It was a
great experience, a great ride. I only wish it had turned out
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old Bourque, who will take advantage of unrestricted
free agency for the first time in his career July 1, reiterated his
desire to play at least one more season. He said, as he has for
weeks, that Denver would be high on the list of clubs he would like
to play for, but he's wise enough to know handicapping contract
negotiations is pure folly.
</P>
<P>
   All he knew when he left Reunion Arena Saturday &UR;  &LR; night was that
he wants to play again, somewhere, and that he was happy for the
11-week odyssey that led him from a dying vine in Boston to a vista
of endless possibilities in the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do it again, in a heartbeat,'' said Bourque, swapped to
the Avalanche at the March trading deadline, a deal he prompted by
asking Boston management to send him to a potential Cup winner.
``I'm happy with the decision,'' he said. ``I was looking for an
opportunity _ to make the playoffs, to have a good run. We had that
here, but it just wasn't good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Bourque's steady hand behind their blue line, the
Avalanche couldn't suppress the stronger, faster Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado was down by three goals when Peter Forsberg, set up by
Chris Drury, finally broke Ed Belfour's shutout bid with 5:25 gone
in the third. Just over three minutes later, Drury sent a pass up
to Bourque at the blue line and the former Bruins captain belted a
slapper that was deflected in by Milan Hejduk to cut the deficit to
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it was a game, a microcosm of that last chance Bourque
was seeking when he bolted Boston. The Avalanche were within a goal
with 11:34 remaining in regulation, plenty of time to get even and
perhaps use overtime as a springboard to a date with the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't to be. Time whittled away. With 1:20 to go, the
Avalanche pulled Patrick Roy for an extra man. Over the course of
four faceoffs in the final 80 seconds, the Avalanche generated two
great chances to tie it, both delivered by Bourque.
</P>
<P>
   First, with 21.2 seconds to go, Bourque fired in a 45-footer
from the high slot. The shot was deflected on the way in, and the
puck was still live when the referees blew it down. Nine seconds
after the draw, with 12 seconds to go, Bourque's long-range wrister
was deflected in the slot by Adam Deadmarsh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it,'' said Belfour, a top candidate for playoff MVP.
``It was all happening in slow motion. It got by me and hit the
post.''
</P>
<P>
   It hit the left post, about a foot above the ice, and caromed
out. The building went into a frenzy. The Stars were on their way
to the finals, a round that Bourque has reached only twice (1988
and '90).
</P>
<P>
   The lasting image for the Avalanche had to be their poor start.
They gave up a pair of power-play goals in the first period, to
Sergei Zubov and Mike Modano, the latter with six seconds to go.
Former Bruin Dave Andreychuk cost his team dearly by taking a dumb
penalty with 16 seconds left in the period with an elbow to Darryl
Sydor's head. It took the Stars but 10 seconds to knock one in for
the 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche were still flat when they came out for the second.
Only 5:31 in, Roman Lyashenko got the last deflection of a Derian
Hatcher shot from up high. It was 3-0. All but over.
</P>
<P>
   One more time. The seasons come. The seasons go. And Ray Bourque
goes on, a constant. He dared himself to leave, to try something
new, and he said it was all worth it. No matter how it ended.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 0145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0029 </DOCNO>
