<HEADLINE>
USC'S OFFENSE COMES TO LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS COCOLES  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULLERTON - USC got to the winner's bracket of the NCAA baseball
regionals with pitching and defense, the team's strengths
throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
   But the Trojans are one win away from a berth in the Super
Regionals because of offense. Eighteen hits and 13 runs worth.
</P>
<P>
   Just about everyone in the lineup contributed in top-seeded
USC's 13-5 win over Loyola Marymount at Cal State Fullerton on
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (40-18) would have to lose twice today to be
deprived of winning the four-team regional. LMU and Cal State
Fullerton met in an elimination game late Saturday night to
determine USC's opponent in the 1 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans aren't offensively challenged, hitting .302 as a
team and hitting 82 home runs entering Saturday's game. But coach
Mike Gillespie's concern has been fielding a quality batting order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough outs 1-through-9 that have been an issue,''
Gillespie said. ``If you look at our team's stats, we have four
guys with pretty good numbers, some guys with horrible numbers and
some in between.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 7-8-9 batters in the USC order _ Alberto Concepcion,
Brian Barre and Abel Montanez _ went a combined 7 for 10 with two
RBI and eight runs scored. Only Montanez was hitting more than .300
and that was in 29 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Montanez, a senior left fielder, was cut from the team three
years ago, served as team manager and rarely played until the final
three weeks of the season. But he went 3 for 3 with three runs
scored and an RBI from the ninth spot.
</P>
<P>
   Everything went right for the Trojans. Barre had one of the
game's biggest hits, an RBI triple in the eighth that broke a 5-5
tie. But it happened against Gillespie's orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually pretty funny because skip gave me the take
(sign) and I missed it,'' Barre said. ``And (LMU pitcher Michael
Schultz) ended up throwing a fastball down the middle, I hit it
good and the rest is history.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillespie's reaction to the sign: ``I was just kidding.''
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of giddy attitude a coach can have when his team
gets that kind of contribution from everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, USC's most consistent hitters in the middle of the
lineup were held down. Justin Gemoll, Beau Craig, Anthony Lunetta
and Josh Persell managed just three hits between them.
</P>
<P>
   But leadoff batter Seth Davidson went 5 for 6 and Rob Garibaldi
was 3 for 5 with four RBI in the No. 2 spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to step up tonight was really key because it helps out
the whole rest of our lineup,'' Davidson said. ``We're on base for
our top hitters, so I think just in general that's really key.''
</P>
<P>
   Schultz (9-6), who attended Cleveland High of Reseda, has been
the big-game pitcher for the Lions (40-18). But the 6-foot-8 junior
right-hander allowed 15 hits and seven earned runs in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans led 8-5 entering the ninth and sealed it with five
more runs, four off Chaminade High of West Hills graduate Chris
Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Prior (9-6) earned the win for the Trojans, giving up five
earned runs on eight hits in 7 innings.
</P>
<P>
   USC freshman Anthony Reyes (5-6, 4.29 ERA) will start today's
championship round game against either LMU or Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   Cal State Fullerton 8, Virginia Tech 6: Chris Beck, a senior
who's been bothered by wrist and back injuries all season, went 4
for 5 and hit a tiebreaking two-run homer in the top of the ninth
to keep the host Titans (37-20) alive.
</P>
<P>
   Beck hit .408 with 75 RBI as a junior but was limited to just
117 at-bats and 17 RBI this season. His homer eliminated the
fourth- seeded Hokies (34-25-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any more pain in my wrist or my back,'' Beck
said. ``The (home run) pitch was slow ... I reached out and didn't
think I got all of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
