<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREIFORT CAN'T STOP PHILLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's been two steps forward, one step back for
Dodgers pitcher Darren Dreifort for much of this young season, and
Saturday night brought another halt to what had been Dreifort's
steady progress.
</P>
<P>
   The Philadelphia Phillies, led by light-hitting shortstop Desi
Relaford, blasted Dreifort for six runs in three innings and
survived a late rally to beat the Dodgers 7-6 in front of 33,967 at
Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The loss hurt the Dodgers on multiple levels. They lost third
baseman Adrian Beltre, who strained his right hamstring running out
a ground ball in the sixth and will be evaluated again today.
</P>
<P>
   There were also plenty of missed opportunities in the late
innings. The Dodgers loaded the bases in the seventh but scored
just once to cut the lead to 6-5. Kevin Elster singled to lead off
the eighth and reached third with two outs, but Philadelphia right
fielder Bobby Abreu made a sliding, snow-cone catch on a Mark
Grudzielanek liner to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' Mike Lieberthal and the Dodgers' Gary Sheffield
exchanged home runs in the ninth, and with Shawn Green on second
with one out, Phillies closer Jeff Brantley struck out Todd Hundley
and pinch-hitter Geronimo Berroa to earn the save.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most painful part of the game, however, was the
performance of Dreifort (3-2), just three starts removed from a
two-hit shutout May 12 against St. Louis. Dreifort offered few
positives against the Phillies, one of baseball's weakest-hitting
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Relaford, the Phillies' No. 8 hitter who entered the game with
12 RBI in 37 games, hit a three-run home run in the second and a
two-run single in the third. Dreifort struck out five but left the
game after the third, having allowed six runs on six hits and three
walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreifort just didn't have it; he struggled pretty much from
the get-go,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The performance was all the more disappointing considering
Dreifort has displayed flashes of dominance this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort allowed two runs in eight innings in a no-decision
Monday against Cincinnati and had not lost since his first start of
the season, when he walked eight in a 2-1 loss to the New York
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander had control problems again Saturday and
frequently fell behind batters. Relaford's home run came on a 3-2
pitch that was left over the middle of the plate, but by that point
Dreifort was already in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros hit a two-run double off the top of the left-field
wall in the first for a short-lived 2-0 Dodgers lead against
Philadelphia starter Robert Person (5-2). It was the second
consecutive night Karros hit a ball off the wall, after Friday's
disputed call.
</P>
<P>
   Karros would hit another two-run double in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Burrell led off the second with a home run. Rob Ducey walked
on five pitches and Kevin Jordan blooped a single into right field
to set up Relaford's blast to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort was finished off in the third, when Relaford, with two
outs, lined the first pitch he faced up the middle to score Burrell
and Ducey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you beat the devil, sometimes you don't,'' Dreifort
said.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges relieved Dreifort to begin the fourth and fared
better, although not without some anxious moments. Herges threw
three shutout innings but allowed six baserunners (two hits, three
walks, one error) and twice needed double plays to escape jams.
</P>
</TEXT>
