<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8045 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-WOMEN-ADS-COX     05-28 1798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Aesthetics or athletics: Teams tread carefully in ads
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Clarke
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami Sol forward Yolanda Moore was driving home from the mall a
few months ago, heading south on Interstate 95 in Miami-Dade
County, when she passed a yellow billboard featuring someone she
recognized.
</P>
<P>
   It was her _ wearing baggy athletic clothes, holding a
basketball on her hip and staring unsmiling at the South Florida
landscape. The sign read ``I will sacrifice my body to preserve my
Sol,'' and it was promoting the WNBA team that begins its first
season Thursday at AmericanAirlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got off at the next exit and drove back around to see it
again and make sure it really was me,'' Moore said, laughing. ``I
was just creeping. I probably could have gotten a ticket for going
so slow.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an overwhelming experience for Moore, who was a single
mother when she joined the WNBA three years ago as a free agent.
Moore struggled with knee problems this pre-season, had surgery on
both knees Saturday and was waived.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sol's pre-season campaign featuring her was a sign of
the times for women _ a 14-by-48-foot sign that they can be
promoted as athletes who will run, sweat, throw themselves on the
ground and still get fans to buy tickets and passionately cheer
them on.
</P>
<P>
   It's a recent change, however. Although girls have joined boys
on athletic fields regularly for 20 years, Madison Avenue spent
most of that time selling women athletes primarily for their
perkiness (Mary Lou Retton), looks (tennis player Chris Evert) or
glamour (golfer Laura Baugh). That they played sports was a small
part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the ice skaters: Dorothy Hamill with her haircut
and Peggy Fleming,'' said 35-year-old Dawn Riley, a member of the
Women's Sports Foundation's board of trustees. ``The first images I
remember are, 'Wow. They're pretty.' That they were athletes too
was kind of secondary. I think that's definitely changed.''
</P>
<P>
   WTA has `Glamour Calendar'
</P>
<P>
   But how much?
</P>
<P>
   In tennis, the WTA Web site teases a link to the 2001 ``Glamour
Calendar'' with this line: ``Keep up with your busy schedule while
keeping up with this beautiful tour calendar.'' The calendar has
been published for years and players seem to enjoy showing how they
look off the court, vice president for communications Chris De
Maria said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that's a really great way for the fans to see the
players in another way, to show them for their glamour,'' De Maria
said. ``In some of the pictures, you know who it is, but it's
amazing how different they can look when you take off the tennis
whites and you dress the way you want to and get photographed by a
professional photographer.''
</P>
<P>
   The calendar is just part of one of the broadest marketing
campaigns in women's sports. The WTA wants its athletes seen in as
many media outlets as make sense _ and even some that don't, De
Maria said. Examples include Serena Williams' recent visit to MTV's
House of Style and Monica Seles' trip to meet CART racers during
the Ericsson Open.
</P>
<P>
   But that approach means the WTA rarely discourages players from
anything _ even if it means 15th-ranked Anna Kournikova, who hasn't
won a tournament, earns millions more in endorsements than
second-ranked Lindsay Davenport, who has won three Grand Slams.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh-ranked veteran Nathalie Tauziat recently published a
book criticizing the tour for letting glamour overshadow
performance, but she doesn't expect anything to change until the
world marketplace changes. And she knows that's a long time away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just think it's very important for the fans to know what
these players do besides tennis,'' De Maria said. ``Sex appeal
certainly is part of it, but mostly we're looking at each player
individually and saying, 'Where can we go with her?'''
</P>
<P>
   Soccer becomes `babe city'
</P>
<P>
   WNBA, Women's World Cup soccer and LGPA officials all stated
similar marketing goals: showing the public their best stories and
athletes so fans have good images of their sports and want to watch
them. Soccer, more than basketball and golf, admits sex appeal is
just part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   The Late Show host David Letterman, for example, nicknamed the
Women's World Cup team ``babe city'' last year and few but the
staunchest feminists got upset.
</P>
<P>
   Brandi Chastain stirred controversy by ripping off her shirt
after scoring the game-winning goal in last year's final. She
earlier had done the same by posing nude in Gear magazine. But if
fans remember one name besides Mia Hamm, it's Chastain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a bit uncomfortable with Brandi's deal,'' teammate
Michelle Akers said. ``Everybody has to make their own decisions on
how they want to be portrayed. Regardless of that, it has a
reflection on us as a team and women's sports as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   Marla Messing, president of the 1999 Women's World Cup
organizing committee, doesn't think the Gear photograph reflected
badly on the team, although it wasn't a function of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cornerstone in almost everything we did was first and
foremost, they have to be great athletes,'' Messing said. ``Whether
they're mothers or beautiful or funny or whatever, there are a lot
of other women out there that are all those things. What makes
these women different is that they are great athletes.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Durkin, vice president of marketing for the LPGA,
considers the job of selling women's golf more difficult because it
has little national television exposure and an older, slightly more
male audience.
</P>
<P>
   The LPGA has only recently started selling its players on and
off the course, but it doesn't have the money for its own large
television media campaign so it instead relies largely on sponsors
using its athletes and on its own public service announcements,
which run during tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Famer Juli Inkster is featured in a new PSA, Durkin
said, that lists her many golf credentials but shows another side
of her by poking fun at her unique ``celebratory dance maneuvers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence is Juli certainly can play golf, but she sure
can't dance,'' Durkin said. ``It captures Juli's sense of humor and
who she is and isn't just Juli Inkster as a golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the days of the LPGA's Fairway magazine glamour
shots, one of which showed Jan Stephenson in a Marilyn Monroe pose,
and cashing in on Baugh's individual promotion as the
``Ultra-Brite'' girl are over. Durkin thinks that's a good thing,
for golf and the rest of women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that is anything particular to the LGPA,'' she
said. ``It's just a different time. Women's sports had a different
place in corporate America.''
</P>
<P>
   Marketers change approach
</P>
<P>
   That can't be denied. Opportunities for women to play sports and
earn endorsements and make money from the industry have grown
exponentially, particularly since the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think marketers are realizing that there's an audience,''
said Sue Rodin, owner of Stars &AMP; Stripes, an agency representing
primarily female athletes. ``They're seeing that lots of women and
girls and soccer moms follow these sports and have fun playing
them. It's not, 'Oh, let's get Joe Montana' automatically
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Rodin said one of her clients, World Cup soccer's
Julie Foudy, is close to signing a deal to become a national
spokeswoman for Dunkin' Donuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're her favorite food, and so (the company) thought, 'Why
not affiliate with women's soccer in this way?' Think of all the
moms who bring Munchkins to soccer games.''
</P>
<P>
   Moms have started earning a greater presence in sports recently,
too. They're fans, mothers of fans, mothers of athletes and even
athletes themselves. The Sol were one of a few WNBA teams promoting
that they have players with kids.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who has two daughters, is pictured on one billboard
reading ``Mother of Two. Queen of the Three.'' Another shows her
holding a 2-year-old girl on her hip beside the words ``Hoops.
Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   The intended messages are different, said Michael McCullough,
Sol executive vice president and chief marketing officer. The first
simply is that Moore is a mom and a professional athlete, something
most Americans recognize as a difficult task. The second ad shows a
woman who plays professional basketball and a girl who can dream
about doing that, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a mom who's playing professional sports,'' McCullough
said. ``We definitely wanted to play up that angle when we could.''
</P>
<P>
   A touchy issue
</P>
<P>
   But that offends a few and makes some, including veteran
basketball player Ann Meyers, wary, because promoting women
athletes as moms could be seen as demeaning their athletic
abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, it's a positive,'' said Meyers, a WNBA commentator
for NBC. ``But we cannot overextend that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough said he has received only positive feedback to the
billboards and feels he's promoting women as both mothers and
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only a few players who are moms in the WNBA. We have
one of them,'' McCullough said Thursday. ``To be a mom and primary
caregiver and knowing the toll on the body just to have children, I
think most women really appreciate that. We're not going to
overstate that point, but to ignore it would have been a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Sol players agree _ both about marketing Moore as a mom
and about how that extends to using a little sex appeal when
appropriate. WNBA President Val Ackerman has tried to promote her
players first ``as basketball players and as professionals,'' she
said. That means tasteful, but the league tries to set as few rules
as possible and what players do individually isn't the WNBA's
business.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Debbie Black wouldn't mind seeing a harder push from
the WNBA _ regardless of taste.
</P>
<P>
   She howled, for example, at Chastain's post-World Cup Nike ad in
which Chastain plays foosball with NBA star Kevin Garnett and
friends. She scores a goal, then notices Garnett staring intently
at her _ apparently hoping for another World Cup stripping.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Black said. ``I know it's sexist but I thought it
was cute. Maybe I'm old school, but it's exposure and we need
exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   She wants people to truly consider women athletes to be athletes
and thinks anything could help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they realize we actually do the same kind of
pounding in the gym that a guy does,'' she said. ``I say promote us
and market us and any exposure we can get _ as long as we're not in
jail and beating someone up _ anything else is terrific. Get them
here and they'll see what kind of athletes we are.''
</P>
<P>
   elizabethclarke(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
