<P>
   &UR; FOR MONDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, May 29:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-REFUGEES (Yanji, China) _ The Chinese police have
dramatically increased their efforts to expel North Koreans living
undercover in China in recent months, creating a potentially
explosive international refugee crisis. The Chinese government has
also stepped up raids on the hundreds of tiny shelters and
factories where the illegal migrants live and work, generally run
by local churches, South Korean aid groups or Chinese of Korean
descent. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECTION (Lima, Peru) _ Peruvians are scheduled to vote in
a presidential election in which the main challenger has pulled
out. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SCANDAL (Jerusalem) _ President Ezer Weizman, threatened
with impeachment over a gift-taking scandal, will resign from his
ceremonial job on July 10, an adviser confirmed on Sunday. By
William A. Orme Jr.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON (Dateline TK) _ Developments. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ETHIOPIA-ERITREA (Asmara, Eritrea) _ On Monday, senior officials
from Ethiopia and Eritrea are to meet in Algeria, to talk about
ending a two-year war that has killed tens of thousands of young
men and, here in Eritrea, women serving as soldiers too. But this
war has become only more complex in recent days. Despite Eritrea's
retreat, Ethiopia shows no signs of stopping the fight. By Ian
Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRALIA-CIVIL-RIGHTS (Sydney, Australia) _ More than 200,000
people, a crowd larger than any expected at the Olympics here in
September, marched Sunday to support campaigns for social justice
for Australia's black minority. By John Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   EXPO-2000 (Hanover, Germany) _ Something is afoot in Hanover.
This country has built itself a 400-foot-long glass structure,
called it ``Germany: Workshop of Ideas,'' and adorned it with 47
giant busts of great Germans that include one Jurgen Sparwasser, a
soccer player, but not Goethe. The structure in question is
Germany's pavillion at Expo 2000, the World's Fair that opens on
June 1. The absence of Goethe, eased out by the likes of Marlene
Dietrich, is suggestive of an insistent national quest: to get
people to think differently about Germany. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-DROP-REACT (Chicago) _ With the historic drop in violent
crime beginning to take hold in even the most blighted urban areas,
cities across the country are being transformed as neighborhoods
that had become frightening wastelands are showing glimmers of
renaissance. New homes are being built, stores are opening and, for
the first time in years, people are sitting on their front porches.
By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-OIL-FALLOUT (Midland, Texas) _ For nearly a century, the
compact between ranchers and oilmen created the huge wealth that
built modern Texas. The ranchers owned the land, the wildcatters
found the oil, and everyone got rich together. But oil is no longer
king in Texas, and the state is grappling with a less glamorous
legacy of the high-flying days. Tens of thousands of oil wells
could be leaking and threatening underground aquifers at a time
when drought has made water the state's most precious natural
resource. Now, the ranchers and the oil producers are fighting over
cleaning up the mess. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT-TECHNO (Detroit) _ Carl Craig is an international music
star. Every weekend he is somewhere in the world performing before
sold-out crowds. But here in his hometown, the place that spawned
the sound known around the world as Detroit techno, Craig remains
an unknown. For nearly two decades the city that set the '60s to
music with the Motown sound, has largely closed its ears to its
other musical offspring, the techno sound. By Nichole M. Christian.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENCEMENT-ADDRESSES (Undated) _ Every spring, they parade to
the podiums of colleges and universities across the country,
offering sage words of advice _ or at least a few one-liners. Poets
and politicians. Athletes and artists. Diplomats and do-gooders.
(Features excerpts from 19 commencement addresses from across the
country.) By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WILLS (Undated) _ Although millions of Americans have
signed living wills and power-of-attorney forms, thinking the
documents would help them avoid unwanted treatment and prolonged
deaths, in many cases those measures turn out to be useless. First
of two articles. A special report. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Coded w)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-BIRTH-CERTIFICATES (Washington) _ After making it safely
to the United States, Hans Peter Bieri faced the problem that
millions of illegal immigrants have faced over the years. He had to
convince employers, government agencies, and others that he was
here legally. It was not long before Bieri discovered a little
secret: In some states, it is possible to adopt the identity of an
American citizen by simply walking into the right government office
and paying a few dollars for someone's birth certificate. By
Renwick McLean.
</P>
<P>
   ENTREPRENEUR-PROFILE (Washington) _ Profile of Robert Johnson,
the head of Black Entertainment and prospective airline chief.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILES-COHEN (Washington) _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen
responds to George W. Bush's statements on missile defense on
``Meet the Press.'' By Steven Lee Myers.
