<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8057 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-REAL-DEVELOP-GINSBURG     05-28 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REAL-DEVELOP-GINSBURG-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: A WESTCHESTER BUILDER EXPANDS INTO CONNECTICUT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., N.Y.)  By ELEANOR CHARLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Ginsburg Development Corp., a 36-year-old home builder known
for the quality of its houses and condominiums in Westchester
County, has opened its first project in Connecticut, a condominium
community of detached single-family homes in the Georgetown section
of Redding.
</P>
<P>
   Called Redding Woods, the Victorian cottage-style development at
62 Redding Road (Route 107) sits on a wooded knoll with views of
forested hills receding into the distance. Of the 23 homes to be
built by the end of the year, six have been sold since sales began
a month ago. The four models, with square footage of 2,500 to
3,600, are priced from $489,000 to $589,000.
</P>
<P>
   Condos are the exception, not the rule in Redding, and
Georgetown is the only section where they are allowed. Only one
other condominium complex exists, with four apartments in a single
building.
</P>
<P>
   The Ginsburg company, which has filed plans for almost 400 homes
in two projects elsewhere in Fairfield County, in Danbury and
Newtown, has been known in Westchester for its focus on the
high-end town-house niche, often on challenging sites.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph A. Novella Jr., the president of Ginsburg Development CT
in Danbury, the new Connecticut division set up by the company,
said, ``Our charge is to become the premier multifamily community
developer in Connecticut: to deliver what there is a dire lack of _
a variety of luxury town homes for empty nesters, aging baby
boomers, singles, people who may not have children, people in
nontraditional family situations, and do it at a reasonable
price.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Shew, the village manager of Ossining, N.Y., spoke highly
of the Ginsburg company. ``GDC did a substantial project here known
as Mystic Pointe _ high-end condos up to the $600,000 range,'' he
said. ``Our building department was impressed with the fact that
everything was done according to the book. No corners cut. The
development is regarded as one of our better ones _ attractive,
well built, exceptionally marketable.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Feiner, the supervisor of the Town of Greenburgh, N.Y.,
where the Ginsburg company has built three projects, has a fourth
under construction and is planning a fifth, owns a Ginsburg home.
``Five years ago when my wife and I were looking for a house, the
only three we liked were Ginsburg's. We bought one in Boulder Ridge
from the original owner, and we love it. Ginsburg buys property
nobody would think is buildable _ on a steep slope, or covered with
rocks and boulders, and builds on it. The projects are very
pleasing aesthetically and very well built.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Gissen, Ginsburg's director of development, described its
business philosophy like this: ``We have tried to develop a niche
in the very upscale town home or clustered single-family home
development, with heavy investment in architectural detail and
landscaping. We look closely at the site, and the character of the
local community. We don't try to jam a square peg into a round
hole. Redding, for example, is very dissimilar from Yonkers. We try
to work within that.''
</P>
<P>
   By making Redding the site of its first foray into Connecticut,
the company is moving into an active market. Amy Pardee, the
Redding's zoning enforcement officer, said: ``We're having a little
building boom here. We're the next town up from lower Fairfield
County, ripe for development, so we might as well brace
ourselves.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Incorporated in 1764, Redding has preserved much of its early
rural atmosphere. It contains two districts listed on the National
Register of Historic Places. Its large village green is the site of
summer concerts, and its library, founded in 1908 by Mark Twain
with a collection from his own library, holds one of the largest
book sales in the state each August. Twain moved to Redding in 1908
and died there in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   Only 9,000 people inhabit Redding's 32.3 square miles, almost
all of it zoned for two-acre, single-family lots. More than 4,000
acres are protected in permanent open space. Georgetown is the only
section of Redding with municipal sewers and water. Other parts of
Georgetown belong to Ridgefield, Weston and Wilton.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Ginsburg, the president and chief operating officer of
the development company, and his brother, Sam, the other principal,
are both architects, and their developments are known for their
architectural integrity. Since 1964 the company, which is based in
Hawthorne, N.Y., has built more than 1,650 houses and condominiums
and 2,300 rental apartments in 20 projects along the East Coast,
from Florida to Westchester. The brothers made a decision two years
ago, Martin Ginsburg said, ``to go into new territories,''
specifically Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months ago, the Ginsburgs bought the 10-acre Redding
tract for $1.5 million from Adam Lebarski, owner of the Georgetown
Saloon on Main Street, and began reworking Lebarski's previously
approved subdivision.
</P>
<P>
   William Delsner, the designer of the Redding Woods homes, was
brought into the project by Novella, whose family-owned
construction company, the Novella Development Corp. in Danbury,
merged with Ginsburg two years ago. Delsner, the Ginsburgs and Jane
Didona, a landscape architect, scrapped the subdivision's original
cookie-cutter layout and the identical designs for the houses, but
the footprints of the houses could not be changed without going
through a new approval process.
</P>
<P>
   Delsner's designs incorporate a contemporary reinterpretation of
turn-of-the-century details like bay windows, covered porches and
trellises. The roof lines have several levels, the lower levels of
the houses have stone facing, and the garage doors, with their
arches and crisscrossed moldings, are reminiscent of carriage
houses. Rather than being positioned in a straight line going up
the hill, the houses are scattered informally along a single
dead-end road.
</P>
<P>
   Delsner is not a licensed architect, but a structural engineer
on his staff and an architect sign off on the blueprints. On this
project he worked closely with Didona to make the new houses look
as if they had been there for years. Period street lights further
that effect.
</P>
<P>
   The site posed some challenges: one side drops to the road below
at a 30-degree angle. ``Very often you get much more interesting
results with a difficult site,'' Martin Ginsburg said. ``We've been
dealing with difficult sites in Westchester for a long time, so
we've developed a lot of expertise over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   The land was too steep for lawns, and the designers rejected a
covering of loosely laid stone. Their solution? Huge sheets of
green fabric installed against the hill, impregnated with
wildflower seeds. With luck, each spring there will be little
bluestem, switch grass, partridge pea, nodding bur marigold, showy
tick trefoil and green-headed coneflower growing through the
fabric, securing the soil, blooming and dying back naturally in the
fall.
</P>
<P>
   Of the four models of houses, three have three bedrooms and one
has two. All have two and a half baths, two-car garages, nine-foot
first-floor ceilings (eight feet upstairs) and solid-core interior
doors. A large attic loft can be finished in one model for use as
another bedroom or office. The space above the garage in another
model can be finished as an all-purpose room with a pyramid ceiling
18 feet high at its point.
</P>
<P>
   Basements will be finished, waterproofed and carpeted. Some will
be completed as guest suites with living rooms, bedrooms and full
baths. Basements in the houses with the steep backyards open onto
patios.
</P>
<P>
   The Ginsburg company has proposed two other developments that
are now going through the approval process in Connecticut: 280 town
homes in Danbury and 110 condominiums for people 55 and older in
Newtown.
</P>
<P>
   Gissen, Ginsburg's director of development, said, ``We are
hoping for another `active adult' community of 70 luxury units in
Farmington, 150 town homes in a lower Litchfield County town that I
am not at liberty to name, and we are looking at properties in the
New London and New Haven areas.''
</P>
<P>
   When about two-thirds of the homes at Redding Woods are sold, a
homeowners' association will be formed to maintain the road, lawns,
landscaping and the exteriors of the houses. Common charges are
expected to run about $2,000 a year. Property taxes, which will be
set in July, may range from $5,500 to $6,500, said Diane Eppoliti,
the sales agent for Redding Woods at Raveis Real Estate in
Georgetown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
