<SLUG> BC-IPO-MARKETPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUBLIC OFFERINGS FROM '99 FALTER IN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the list of 1999's best initial public offerings, Ditech
Communications and FreeMarkets Inc. came close to being bookends.
Both were among the best performers of last year, with Ditech's
stock ending the year up 611 percent from its offering price and
FreeMarkets' ending with a gain of 750 percent. Each could show
rapidly growing sales over the previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this is now. So far in 2000, their fates
have diverged as much as any two stocks could. Ditech's share price
is up nearly 90 percent this year, while FreeMarkets' is down by
nearly the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the companies and their stories were never very
similar. Ditech, a maker of echo cancellation equipment for
telephone companies, was profitable but uninteresting to many
investors when it went public last June. It got off to a dull
start, rising 14 percent the first day it traded, and even that
modest lift was possible only because the company placed its shares
at the bottom of the price range it mentioned when it filed to go
public.
</P>
<P>
   FreeMarkets, on the other hand, was a phenomenon. A
business-to-business Internet auction company, it went public in
December at the height of Internet speculation, when its losses did
not faze investors. It sold shares for three times as much as it
had sought when it first filed to go public, and found that even
this was not nearly enough to meet the demand. The shares leaped
483 percent the first day of trading.
</P>
<P>
   So what has happened since the beginning of this year? Ditech
has grown faster than anyone expected, and is in a business that
has not worn out its welcome on Wall Street. Its share price is up
88 percent this year. It did, however, drop 5 percent on Friday,
closing at $87.8125, despite posting quarterly results that were
well in excess of published forecasts. That could be an indication
that investors are beginning to look around for technology stocks
where there are still profits to be taken, and taking them.
</P>
<P>
   As for FreeMarkets, it has reported growing sales, but the bloom
is off the rose when it comes to money-losing Internet companies.
Its stock price is down 89 percent in 2000, closing Friday at
$37.25. Those who got in at the offering price in December, and
held on, have seen a massive paper profit completely evaporate, and
have lost 22 percent of their money. Anyone who bought on the first
day is down 87 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, FreeMarkets is more representative of what has
happened to last year's hot new offerings than is Ditech. Of the 50
best-performing new offerings of 1999, as calculated by CommScan,
46 have declined in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   That performance is a testimony to just how far stocks can fall
when market sentiment changes. A few of the companies have plunged
because their operations have not lived up to expectations. But the
decline of many of the companies cannot be explained by their
business performance _ any more than the original soaring prices
could be explained.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of those stocks in 1999, from initial offering
price through the end of the year, ranged from a gain of 2,723
percent for Internet Capital Group, the best performing offering,
to 540 percent for Software.com, which ranked 50th. That so many
new offerings went up so far was a testimony to just how hot the
market was.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the market has cooled, and the air has come out of many of
the stocks long before their results have shown whether or not last
year's optimism was justified. The average performance of those 50
stocks is a loss of 52 percent. Since March 10, when the Nasdaq
stock market peaked, the Nasdaq composite is down 37 percent, while
the average performance of the once-hot 50 is a drop of 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are plenty of profits that have been made in the
stocks. All but 15 of the stocks are trading higher than they did
the day they went public, and only two _ FreeMarkets and Bluestone
Software, a maker of software for Internet companies _ are trading
below their original offering prices. A third, Ventro, trades for
its original offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Ventro, which went public last July as Chemdex, an Internet
seller of chemical equipment, renamed itself in March as it
announced plans to broaden into other areas of business-to-business
Internet service. It is down 92 percent since March 10, the worst
performer over that period.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Capital, No. 1 in 1999, is down 85 percent so far in
2000, as the attraction of a company that owns stakes in many other
Internet companies has faded. Even so, it is still trading at twice
the price at which it ended the first day of trading, and for more
than four times its original offering price.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Capital doubled the first day of trading, a performance
that once would have seemed extraordinary, yet for much of last
year was almost routine.
</P>
<P>
   But the stocks that had the biggest first-day gains have, in
general, proved to be disappointments thereafter. Seven of the 50
stocks quadrupled on the first day of trading. Six of those seven
are trading below where they ended that first day, with the only
exception being Sycamore Networks, which markets optical networking
products. It is still up 24 percent since that first day, but it is
trading for less than half its peak price reached in early March.
</P>
<P>
   The other big movers the first day, all of which are trading for
less than they fetched that day, are Ask Jeeves, an Internet search
service; Akamai Technologies, an Internet content delivery service;
Foundry Networks, an Internet switching service; Chinadotcom, an
Internet company that provides Asian news and services to other
Internet companies; VA Linux Systems, a distributor of software and
computers using the Linux operating system, and FreeMarkets.
</P>
<P>
   There is one final measure of just how far some of the hottest
issues have fallen. Brocade Communications is now up 2,111 percent
from its offering price, making it the best performing of 1999's
initial offerings to date. But it has plenty of unhappy
shareholders. It is down 43 percent from its peak in March.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
