<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: DASHBOARD MICROWAVE; FAST-FOOD CHOICES; CEREAL WITH ITS
OWN MILK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone planning a road trip this summer might be interested in
recent inventions for eating on the go. A long trip with children
in the car, for example, could be eased by a video monitor attached
to the back of the driver's seat _ or perhaps a dashboard
microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Perlman and Jane Katims, both of Arlington, Mass., have
won a patent for a microwave oven built into the area now used for
glove compartments in most cars. It is big enough to hold a coffee
cup or a fast-food container. A hinged door opens downward like
traditional glove-compartment doors, creating a shelf for holding
containers or serving food. An additional cup holder slides into
the oven to prevent beverages placed inside from tipping and
spilling.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say they decided to replace the glove compartment
with a microwave because ``many items which were formerly stored in
the dashboard area, in particular, the dashboard glove compartment,
are now stored in new, more accessible door pockets, seat pockets
and a centrally located storage console located between the two
front seats.''
</P>
<P>
   The microwave would draw power from the car's battery or
alternator, and the inventors write in their patent application
that ``a high voltage transformer and the power inverter can be
placed behind the engine firewall.''
</P>
<P>
   People who still need the glove compartment for gloves, maps and
other papers could store them in a container designed to fit inside
the microwave. When someone wanted to use the microwave, the
container and the objects it held could be removed. The microwave
would work only when the insert was pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors suggest several other safety features, such as
blocking the oven from working at all when the car is in motion;
allowing it to operate but preventing the door from opening until
the car is stopped; and keeping the oven from operating during
acceleration, braking or sharp turns. When the oven door is opened,
the patent application says, an alarm warns the driver ``to avoid
any sudden start-up acceleration of the vehicle which could result
in a food spill.''
</P>
<P>
   The inventors added recessed areas to the inside of the
microwave and its door, so any spilled liquid or food would collect
there. Controls for the microwave, including a timer, power setting
and on-off switch, would be placed on the dashboard within reach of
a driver or a front-seat passenger.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors received patent 6,060,700.
</P>
<P>
   New Choices for Fast Food
</P>
<P>
   Travelers who prefer fast-food restaurants could soon face new
choices at the cash register. Jay Walker, the founder of
Priceline.com, and two other inventors, Andrew Van Luchene and
Joshua Rogers, have won a patent for a system of offering fast-food
diners a choice of fresh food or food that is a few minutes old.
The aim is to reduce waste in restaurants where food is prepared in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   With the patented system, restaurants would use a microprocessor
to record the time when foods like hamburgers and french fries are
prepared, and to track how long the food sits in food warmers
before being sold.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when a customer orders a plain hamburger, for example, the
system would know what similar foods are available that were
prepared earlier than the burger. If cheeseburgers or chicken
sandwiches were prepared before the hamburgers, the system would
indicate that those foods were already close to the end of their
shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   It would offer to substitute one of them, either at no
additional charge or for a discounted price. The customer might be
offered a cheeseburger instead of the hamburger, for example, or a
double cheeseburger instead of a regular one. Thus, the restaurant
would sell a double cheeseburger at a reduced price that it
otherwise might eventually have to throw away, and the customer
would get a deal on his meal.
</P>
<P>
   The inventors believe that as the burgers under the heat lamps
age, their value decreases and they can be substituted for cheaper
menu items. For example, the customer's original order for a plain
hamburger might be replaced with a cheeseburger that is six or
seven minutes old, or with a double cheeseburger that is 10 or 12
minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-food restaurants do not regularly announce that they
prepare some food minutes before it is sold, and this system would
draw more attention to that practice.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestions for replacement orders would be drawn from
categories set up in a database that tracks the turnover of food.
Any food ordered from one category, such as chicken, might be
replaced with another item from that same category, the inventors
say. The offer of such substitutions could either appear on a
monitor at the cash register or be explained to the customer by a
cashier.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, Van Luchene and Rogers won patent 6,052,667.
</P>
<P>
   Cereal With Its Own Milk
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast on the road, at a camp site or in a hotel room often
means breakfast far from a refrigerator. Those who still want a
bowl of cereal might soon choose a brand that comes with its own
milk. Many breakfast cereals are coated with sweeteners, flavorings
and colorings, but two inventors say none has thought to coat
cereal with powdered milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so, Arthur A. Krause and Walter K. Lim, men of great
genius apt to invent and discover ingenious things, come now with
an invention they have discovered,'' the two men from California
write in their own patent application. ``By applying a special
coating onto the surface of cereal pieces, a food product is
created where one may just add water to the product and the result
is a delicious cereal and milk combination.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonfat dry milk powder is bound to cereal by slightly
rehydrating the dried milk so it becomes sticky, by misting the
cereal so the powdered milk sticks to the surface, or by coating
the cereal first with sugar or a sugar substitute. Later, a hungry
traveler has only to add water and watch as ``the milk coating
dissolves and separates from the cereal and combines with the added
water.''
</P>
<P>
   The inventors say cereal coated with dry milk can be packaged
and transported without any special storage measures. They received
patent 6,051,262.
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the Patent
and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
