u f BC-GUY-MAGS-MEDIA-ART-2T     05-28 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUY-MAGS-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEN'S MAGAZINES BATTLE FOR BIGGER SHARE OF AD DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: 2 graphics are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, advertisers and agencies seeking to reach the elusive
male consumer had an inside joke: The only magazine most men read
regularly was TV Guide.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there were many publications aimed at men _ among them,
Esquire, GQ and Playboy. But Madison Avenue considered television,
particularly sports programming, the more efficient way to peddle
products like cars, beer, fast food and sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   Men, especially in the category of free-spenders ages 18 to 34,
were perceived to have a predilection for video over print. And the
fabled limited male attention span was deemed ill suited to
magazine advertising, which takes more time to accumulate those
all-important ``impressions,'' compared with the immediacy of TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marketplace didn't indicate a broad interest in men's
magazines,'' said Ellen Oppenheim, media director at the New York
office of FCB Worldwide, an agency owned by True North
Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the sheer size of the male audience watching televised
coverage of golf, tennis and professional team sports made it
simpler to reach men by buying commercial time on those shows. For
instance, the average male viewership of one ``Monday Night
Football'' game on ABC last season was about 12.8 million. That is
only 400,000 less than the combined circulations of nine leading
magazines with predominantly male readerships, including Sports
Illustrated.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, magazine publishers are battling back. They are
aggressively trying to entice the agency executives who decide
where to spend billions of advertising dollars to divert more money
to print from television, or to at least earmark additional dollars
for magazine ads.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from major sporting events, ``you don't see a lot of men
at home sitting in front of the tube,'' said Valerie Salembier,
vice president and publisher at Esquire in New York, part of Hearst
Magazines. ``I asked a 26-year-old if he watches `The Practice,'''
she added, ``and he said, `When is it on?'''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers like Salembier are trying to persuade Madison Avenue
that men's magazines offer real alternatives to programs aimed at
men on broadcast and cable television _ particularly as the cost of
TV commercials climbs to record levels for the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With television, there's more demand than supply, so you go to
them,'' said Steve Sturm, vice president for marketing at the
Toyota division of Toyota Motor Sales USA in Torrance, Calif.
``With print, we can choose from 300 publications, so they come to
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the newer choices are magazines like FHM and Maxim, with
the personalities of fraternity brothers; Gear and Stuff, offering
advice on buying gizmos and gadgets; Cigar Aficionado, Dads and
Men's Health, with lifestyle focuses; and ESPN, Maximum Golf and
Men's Journal, for men who are armchair (or actual) athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see men embracing magazines more,'' said Melissa Pordy,
senior vice president and print services director at Zenith Media
in New York, a joint venture of the Cordiant Communications Group
and Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi that buys ad space and commercial time for
major marketers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants TV because of its reach,'' Pordy said. ``But
print has a strong story to tell.''
</P>
<P>
   That story is amplified when the newcomers are considered
alongside established magazines with large male readerships. Among
those are special-interest publications covering subjects like
business, cars, fishing, hunting, music and sports; the mainstays
like Esquire, GQ, Outside, Penthouse and Playboy; and even
magazines read by gay men like The Advocate, Genre and Out.
</P>
<P>
   Also of potential appeal to advertisers is a spate of magazines
intended for teen-age boys, a coveted demographic group because
they are typically still forming their brand preferences. The
magazines are meant to provide articles on lifestyle,
entertainment, fashion and service topics the same way that
Seventeen and YM do for teen-age girls. One, already introduced, is
Transworld Stance, a joint venture of Transworld Media, the
publisher of Skateboarding, and Times Mirror Magazines. A second,
due in September from Rodale, the publisher of Men's Health, is
called MH-18.
</P>
<P>
   With all those options, magazines seem to be mounting a battle
against television bellicose enough for that male TV favorite,
``WWF Smackdown.'' But in competing for ad dollars, print still
faces a struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not give up wrestling so fast,'' Alan Jurmain said with
a chuckle. Jurmain is executive vice president and managing
director for U.S. media services at Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners
Worldwide in New York, part of the Lowe Group unit of the
Interpublic Group of Cos.
</P>
<P>
   He and his media decision-making counterparts at other agencies
described some doubts that magazines must overcome to turn the tide
against TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to question how broad an interest men's fashion
is,'' Jurmain said, noting the subject that predominates among the
articles in many men's magazines.
</P>
<P>
   More troubling, he added, are worries about the ``environment''
of some popular publications. He was using a shorthand term for
editorial formulas that deliver large doses of articles celebrating
hedonistic behavior and photographs of scantily clad women.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one client who has been uncomfortable with at least
one men's magazine'' because of problematic content, said Dan
Binder, vice president and director for print investment at Starcom
Worldwide in Chicago, a media services agency owned by the B Com3
Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we've taken special steps with the publication to ensure
our ads are as far away from certain types of editorial as they can
be,'' Binder said, ``with the option to move out of issues if
there's no way to separate us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes even those precautions are not sufficient. Fragrance
brands carrying the Ralph Lauren name, for instance, are not being
advertised in Maxim or Playboy magazines, said Jack Wiswall, senior
vice president and general manager for the designer fragrance
division of Cosmair in New York, the unit of L'Oreal responsible
for those scents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't get settled on that particular pictorial,''
Wiswall said. ``It's not a venue we choose.'' Maxim is, however, on
the media schedule for two of his other fragrance brands, Acqua di
Gio and Emporio Armani for Him.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lance Ford, group publisher for Maxim and Stuff magazines at
Dennis Maxim Inc. in New York, concedes that some advertisers
remain reluctant. ``I think we can carry the bulk of categories
that advertise in men's lifestyle magazines, but some will take
longer than others to come in,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was resistance in the beginning, no doubt about it,'' he
added, particularly among marketers of products aimed at more
affluent men, ``and I would think there is still some work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Content, of course, is also an issue when agencies buy
commercial time on TV. But the widespread availability of sports
programming ameliorates those difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Another challenge for magazines is the mortality rate among
newer publications that were promoted to advertisers as guaranteed
to attract younger male consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to proceed with some caution,'' said Bobbi Silten,
president for the Dockers and Slates U.S. unit of Levi Strauss &AMP;
Co. in San Francisco. ``Not every magazine being launched will be a
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is a lengthening list of titles being closed.
Among them are Bikini, Blaze, Icon and P.O.V. And in March, Advance
Publications suddenly stopped publishing Details, which is to
return in October after a revamping.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about a new magazine that advertisers find
exciting,'' said Roberta Garfinkle, senior vice president and print
media director at McCann-Erickson Worldwide Advertising in New
York. ``But you want the magazine to last for more than the
launch.'' Her agency is part of the McCann-Erickson World Group
unit of the Interpublic Group.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``There is going to be some shakeout,'' predicted Thomas A.
Florio, vice president and publisher of a venerable men's magazine,
GQ, part of the Conde Nast Publications unit of Advance. ``I liken
it to the Nasdaq,'' he added, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, turning serious, Florio continued: ``Think about how
successful the Internet is with men. They're getting information
and entertainment by reading. That's good for men's magazines.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, according to Sturm of Toyota, pitting magazines and
television against each other is so 20th-century _ such an
old-media way to look at things.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   These days, Toyota spends about a quarter of its print ad budget
on magazines read by men and about a third of its TV ad budget on
programs watched by men. But online media have also become an
increasingly important factor. ``You actually have a bridge now
between television and print: the Internet,'' Sturm said. ``Fifty
percent of my interactive plan is targeted to men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Web,'' he said, ``you can get the two-dimensional
detail of print and the three-dimensional feel of television
without having to spend three-dimensional dollars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
