<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-LATAM-STARMEDIA-ART-2     05-28 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-STARMEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARMEDIA FACES NEW CHALLENGES IN LATIN AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JENNIFER L. RICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ When rumors circulated last month that the
American company StarMedia Network might be acquired by Terra
Networks, the Internet industry found the story plausible.
</P>
<P>
   After all, StarMedia, based in New York, had one of last year's
hot Internet stock offerings but had seen its shares fall from the
firmament. And its Web portal, which since 1996 had been the
premier gateway to material on the Internet in Spanish and
Portuguese, was facing increased competition in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure has come from both local and international
multimedia giants _ like Terra, which is owned by Spain's largest
telecommunications company, Telefonica. Terra, in fact, had already
bought up a handful of Internet service providers in Latin America
to challenge StarMedia as the region's biggest player.
</P>
<P>
   But Terra was weak on content _ the news, information and
entertainment that is StarMedia's specialty. So on the face of it,
a deal made sense even if StarMedia continued to insist that it was
holding no talks with Terra.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, StarMedia's denials were genuine. Two weeks
ago, Terra did make a content play _ a $12.5 billion deal to buy
Lycos, an American Web portal with international reach. So now,
rather than having a partner, StarMedia must contemplate an even
bigger, more powerful rival in the Latin American Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia's charismatic 33-year-old founder and chief executive,
Fernando J. Espuelas, is not one to voice anxiety, though. In Sao
Paulo recently for the introduction of the company's redesigned
portal, StarMedia 6.0, he brushed off worries of growing
competition in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our leadership to lose, and we are not going to lose
it,'' said Espuelas, a native of Uruguay who speaks English like an
unusually articulate American. ``Not because we are preordained to
win, because nobody is. But we move very fast. We know this
business very well. It is the only thing that we do, and we did our
homework. We built a brand when those companies didn't believe in
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite its early leadership in the Latin American market,
the uncertainties are mounting for StarMedia. In the last year,
huge international players like Terra and America Online have made
Latin America's growing Internet market a major priority. And many
of the region's dominant media and telecommunication companies are
also devoting huge resources to building up Internet businesses.
Some analysts say StarMedia no longer has what it takes to compete
alone in the new highly competitive Latin American Internet market.
</P>
<P>
   ``What looks on the basis of 1999 numbers as a commanding lead,
will, on 2000 numbers, look like StarMedia is one of many rather
than a clear leader,'' said Lars Schonander, a media analyst for
the investment bank ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   And investors are hardly sanguine about StarMedia's stance.
After Espuelas announced in March that the company would confront
its growing competition by increasing its marketing spending by $12
million in the first half of the year, the stock plummeted 33
percent in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Even before that announcement, StarMedia was well off its high
of $70, reached last July, six weeks after its public offering.
Recently, with the oscillations in the Nasdaq market, the stock has
fallen even more, closing at $15.0625 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, StarMedia had seemed to lead a charmed
existence. Espuelas met the company's co-founder, Jack Chen, in the
sixth grade. Both of their families had recently immigrated to
Greenwich, Conn.; Espuelas' was from Uruguay, and Chen's was from
China. As children, they took English classes together. As
teen-agers, they jointly won a high school debate championship.
</P>
<P>
   While still in his 20s, Espuelas took a vacation in the Nepalese
Himalayas. It was there that he visualized what would become the
underlying goal of StarMedia: to knock down cultural barriers in
Latin America through universal Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole cliche about why would an Argentine care about a
Chilean is just not true,'' he said. ``It is part of the same type
of propaganda that has been fed to us for 200 years about why there
should be separate countries. Now, we are faced with a generation
in Latin America in which 60 or 65 percent of the people are
younger than 24 years of age. This is truly the Internet generation
and this generation will grow with a completely different set of
experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Espuelas quit his job as managing director for
marketing for AT&AMP;T's Latin American operations. Along with Chen,
who was by then a Wall Street investment banker, he moved back to
Connecticut to start StarMedia out of the Chen family's house.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the success of Yahoo in the United States, the two men
designed StarMedia as a so-called content aggregator. StarMedia
would build a gateway to various Spanish- and Portuguese-language
Web sites rather than go through the costly process of creating its
own sites. At the time, Latin America was barely on the Internet
radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia used a storm of local television commercials to make
itself a household name in the region. And while Latin America's
nascent Internet service providers struggled to build the network
capacity to meet the budding demand for Internet access, StarMedia
was busy gathering Spanish- and Portuguese-language content sites
to give the new Web surfers places to surf.
</P>
<P>
   Multinational advertisers gravitated toward StarMedia on the
strength of its brand and the conviction of its chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Espuelas' leadership is considered one of the driving forces
behind the company's early success, and a reason why its stock was
initially so popular with investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you meet Fernando, it is kind of love at first sight,''
said Susan Segal, general partner at Chase Capital Partners, who,
along with Fred Wilson, managing partner at Flatiron Partners, put
up the initial $3.5 million in seed financing for StarMedia in
1997. ``He and Jack are a very charismatic management team.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, StarMedia captured $80 million in its third
round of financing, the largest equity investment in a private
Internet company up to that time. The celebrity from that
investment, in turn, helped the company raise $110 million in its
May 1999 initial public offering. All told, StarMedia has raised
almost half a billion dollars in the public and private markets.
</P>
<P>
   The company has put some of the money to use by buying Brazil's
leading Internet search services, Zeek and Cade, and a handful of
other Internet properties around the region to add to StarMedia's
basic chat rooms and free e-mail service. New wireless and
broadband-network units have been started to enable StarMedia to
expand its audience to users of cell phones and high-speed cable
modems.
</P>
<P>
   And the company's hefty marketing budget has helped it to become
the Latin American leader in Internet advertising revenue _ $10
million in this year's first quarter. That outpaced Terra and the
region's other publicly traded Web company, El Sitio.
</P>
<P>
   But StarMedia's first-starter advantages are quickly fading. In
Mexico, StarMedia's strongest market, local competition is heating
up. Telefonos de Mexico, the country's largest telecommunications
company, has teamed up with Microsoft to start a portal and
Internet access service called T1MSN.com. And two big Mexican media
companies, Grupo Televisa (EsMas.com) and Televisa Azteca
(todito.com), have also recently started Web portals.
</P>
<P>
   So far, though, StarMedia has preferred to remain independent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 200 strategic relationships with content providers
across the globe, which we think adds infinitely more value that
having one big-name relationship,'' Espuelas said. ``I think that
is something that is not really understood in Latin America, which
has such an historic bias toward these big media monopolies.''
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts expect Latin America to mirror Internet
development in Europe, where big telecommunications and media
companies dominate the Web scene.
</P>
<P>
   StarMedia's experience in Brazil, Latin America's most promising
Internet market, provides a telling example of the challenges it
faces.
</P>
<P>
   Here, where fewer than 7 million people out of a population of
165 million are online, and forecasts call for perhaps an
additional 2 million people to get Internet access this year,
StarMedia had a weak start. The company's underlying concept of a
borderless pan-Latin community did not play well with the
Portuguese-speaking Brazilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem with StarMedia is that it always tried to head the
Latin American market, but Brazilians don't think that they are
Latin,'' said Alvaro de Castro, new business director at the
Internet consulting company Visualcom and author of books on
e-commerce and e-marketing in Brazil. ``When Brazilians entered the
StarMedia.com Web site and were asked to select what country they
were from off of a list, they would say: What are we doing among
all those other countries?''
</P>
<P>
   While StarMedia was busy rethinking its Brazilian strategy,
local companies were making inroads into the market. Universo
Online, or UOL, a joint venture of two Sao Paulo newspaper and
magazine publishing giants, the Folha Group and Editora Abril,
began providing Internet access and set up a comprehensive portal
with content supplied by its parent companies. More important, UOL
mounted a formidable advertising campaign using its parents' own
media outlets, which include Sao Paulo's leading newspaper, Folha
de Sao Paulo, and Brazil's leading weekly news magazine, Veja.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's first quarter, UOL said it logged 2.9 billion
page views. Compared with StarMedia's 2.1 billion views, that would
place UOL firmly in the lead among the region's Internet companies.
But StarMedia contends that UOL's figures, which are audited by
Ernst &AMP; Young in Sao Paulo, would not hold up under the scrutiny of
the Internet traffic auditor ABC Interactive, an American company
that StarMedia says is the measurement standard.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, StarMedia had some success in giving its Brazilian
site a more authentically local feel. The redesigned portal,
StarMedia 6.0, takes Brazilian Web surfers directly to local news
and issues. The company also introduced a new television and print
advertising campaign that featured a local soap opera star.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the first mover, StarMedia still occupies a lot of space in
the market,'' said Marcos Moraes, founder of Zip.net in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In Brazil, where a dozen portals vie for a limited audience,
consolidation is soon expected to reduce the number of players to
perhaps three or four. In competing to be one of the survivors,
StarMedia's main rivals will be UOL, the Brazilian media power
Globo, Terra/Lycos, Zip.net/PT Multimedia and AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the pressures, a group of Internet access providers
shocked the market last December by offering free dial-up service
in Brazil. Independent service providers, which used to feed
traffic to StarMedia because they lacked content of their own, may
now be forced to join with portals to compensate for their lost
revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the portals has any idea what will be at the end of
this race,'' said Jack London, a Brazilian who founded Booknet, an
online bookseller, and other Internet properties.
</P>
<P>
   But Espuelas contends that the strength of StarMedia's content
will draw new users to its site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The explosion of free ISPs in Brazil is a wonderful thing,''
Espuelas said, referring to Internet service providers. ``It is
lowering costs, bringing more people online. We want to create the
same dynamic in all of the major markets by essentially demolishing
the paid ISP model.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
