<HEADLINE>
MEDIA NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Plot Twist for Two Giuliani Biographies
</P>
<P>
   At first, the furor over Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's personal life
might have seemed like the ultimate publicity blitz for two New
York journalists rushing to complete biographies of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Both books were scheduled for publication by late summer, just
as the mayor's Senate campaign against Hillary Rodham Clinton would
be gathering steam. But now that Giuliani has announced his
withdrawal from the race, publishing experts wonder if the books
have lost their urgency and are doomed to being ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The writers are two New York journalists who have covered the
mayor for years, Wayne Barrett, an investigative reporter for The
Village Voice, and Andrew Kirtzman, a political reporter for New
York One, a local cable TV news station.
</P>
<P>
   Kirtzman said that he was working on the final chapters of his
book, ``Rudy Giuliani: Emperor of the City,'' the day Giuliani
announced his withdrawal from the Senate race. Upon hearing the
news, he immediately called the publishers, William Morrow Press,
an imprint of the News Corp.'s HarperCollins unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were mesmerized by the events at City Hall,'' he said.
``If anything, they were even more excited about the book. National
awareness and curiosity about Giuliani has been enhanced by his
operatic departure.''
</P>
<P>
   Kirtzman said he would revise his introduction, and in his final
chapter track the mayor as he agonized over his final decision.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Leonard, a spokeswoman for Morrow, said the company had
not yet decided how many copies of the book would be printed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we're disappointed he dropped out of the race, but
he is still a national news figure,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett said he has added chapters to include this month's
roller coaster ride for his biography, ``Rudy: Gotham's Goliath,''
for Basic Books, an imprint of the Perseus Books Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudy certainly has a much larger national profile now than
when I originally signed the book, much larger even than a month
ago,'' he said. ``But he's no longer running against the first
lady, and that's got to have some effect on the interest in the
book in other parts of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   _ COREY KILGANNON
</P>
<P>
   CBS Braces for Complaints on `Early Show'
</P>
<P>
   This week, the managers of the more than 200 television stations
that are affiliated with CBS will attend their annual meeting with
the network's top executives. It is to take place at the luxurious
Bellagio Hotel in Las Vegas, but for the top CBS executives, this
will be no holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Many CBS station managers are becoming impatient with the
network's new morning program, ``Early Show,'' with Bryant Gumbel.
At last year's meeting, they were told the program would prove to
be a great ratings boon for them.
</P>
<P>
   But the show has actually done worse than the show that it
replaced, ``This Morning,'' which was widely considered to be a
half-hearted effort and did not have a star of Gumbel's caliber.
``Early Show,'' which is watched in an average 1.9 million homes,
is down 22 percent from its predecessor's ratings.
</P>
<P>
   That has made for some unhappy CBS station managers, who will
make their feelings known when the meeting begins on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a high level of disenchantment among stations with
the progress of the program,'' said Robert G. Lee, president and
general manager of WDBJ, the CBS affiliate in Roanoke, Va., who is
also the treasury secretary of the affiliates advisory board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be fair to say that patience is becoming thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said that he is so unhappy with the show's performance, he
would like to replace it with a local news program. But, he said,
he is contractually obliged to continue carrying ``Early Show''
until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other station managers, while also displeased, were more
temperate.
</P>
<P>
   Alan M. Bell, president of Freedom Broadcasting, which owns five
CBS affiliated stations, said that while he has no plans to pull
the show, he thinks the network has to do something, before viewers
completely tune it out. ``What we have to do is get the show to
work,'' he said. ``They know it and we know it: It doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Still, even executives at CBS admit that they would not force a
station to hold onto the show if it is absolutely hurting its
business. They say, however, that no one has formally discussed
dropping the show.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that is something that they want to avoid. So they
are preparing to work hard at the conference to persuade the
station managers to stand by ``Early Show'' and give it more time.
</P>
<P>
   Executives said they would argue that the program, which
features Jane Clayson and Gumbel, is at least far better,
qualitatively, than the one that it replaced and that its audience
is bound to grow eventually. They also plan to announce some minor
initiatives that they say will help it catch on with viewers.
</P>
<P>
   They said that they know there will probably be some serious
hecklers in the crowd. That, however, is to be expected. As one TV
executive who has spent plenty of time at affiliate conferences put
it, ``At these events, it's like being tied to a tree and having
the vulture come and pluck at your liver _ and that's in the best
of times.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
<P>
   Fox Hopes to Turn Lurid TV into Web Gold
</P>
<P>
   Fox executives are hoping that the Internet can do for junk TV
what eBay did for junk: make it a hot commodity.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, the network disavowed programs like ``When Good
Pets Go Bad and ``World's Scariest Police Chases'' after the mother
of the genre, ``Who Wants to Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' became a
considerable embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   But reality programming will again emerge under the Fox banner
this fall, when the network begins TooHotForFox.com, a Web site
displaying clips from the specials now banned from the TV network.
</P>
<P>
   They will be listed under different subject headings, like
``Pets Gone Bad'' and ``Police Chases,'' said Jon Richmond,
president of Fox's digital media division. The site will also
include some newly produced segments.
</P>
<P>
   TooHotForFox will represent one of the bolder uses of the
Internet by a major broadcast network. Ever since cable became
nearly ubiquitous, broadcast executives have complained that they
are at a disadvantage because they are so heavily scrutinized and,
thus, restricted in what they can show.
</P>
<P>
   With the Web site, Fox, is in essence creating a new kind of
channel where its popular reality programming can live beyond the
scrutiny reserved for the networks, lost in the clutter of lurid
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized it would be a great testing ground for things like
viewer choice, where you can program your own reality experience,''
Richmond said. ``We felt TooHotForFox would be a great test tube
for what the future of narrowband and broadband content might look
like.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JIM RUTENBERG
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
