<HEADLINE>
THERE IS SOMETHING SO FAMILIAR ABOUT SUMMER MOVIE WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: Matthew Mirapaul writes the arts(at)large column, published
each Thursday in CyberTimes on The New York Times on the Web.) 
 By MATTHEW MIRAPAUL   
 C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The film industry loves the familiarity of sequels, so it won't
spoil the ending of this column to reveal that the Web sites for
this year's roster of potential summer box-office blockbusters are
mostly formulaic rehashes of past sites.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the site for ``The Blair Witch Project'' seemed to
signal a turning point. By supplementing the movie's
faux-documentary footage with additional online ``evidence,'' the
filmmakers simultaneously built an audience for their low-budget
flick and showed Hollywood's new-media mavens that a successful
site didn't have to be a bland bouillabaisse of canned production
notes, fuzzy video clips and simple games.
</P>
<P>
   But a tour of the promotional sites for some recently released
or soon-to-open movies often felt like ``Nightmare on HTML Street
5'' _ it might have been horrifying if we hadn't seen it all
before.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if memory serves, the sites for ``Mission: Impossible
2'' (www.missionimpossible.com) and ``Nutty Professor II: The
Klumps'' (www.nuttyprofessor.com) are remarkably similar to _ and
just as routine as _ the ones developed for their cinematic
antecedents in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Producers who say their budgets are ``all on the screen'' don't
mean the computer monitor. Given that Hollywood spends millions of
dollars on spectacular computer-generated special effects to
attract summer crowds, some of that digital creativity might be
expected to trickle down to the Internet. But except for the
widespread use of animated pages requiring the Flash software
plug-in, the multimedia possibilities of the Internet seem to be
lost on the industry's high-technology wizards.
</P>
<P>
   Only one site, for ``The Cell'' (www.thecell.com), a movie set
for release in August, provides a compelling online experience.
Instead of relying on film stills and video clips, the site conveys
the grim thriller's sick but stylish sensibility through a series
of elaborate, effectively creepy animations. These are augmented by
a database of information on serial killers and an interactive
psychology test that seeks to draw visitors into the film's story _
the tale of a psychologically disturbed killer who drowns his
female victims before mutilating the bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere among movie sites, this kind of immersed content is
hard to find. In the past, sites for films like ``Twister'' and
``Contact'' supplied all sorts of topical information and
scientific background designed to support their cinematic version
of reality.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few current sites that take such pains is the one for
``The Perfect Storm,'' (www.perfectstorm.com) which provides enough
context that it might actually encourage online visitors to shut
off their computers and head for the movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   The site is easy to navigate and overflowing with multimedia
features, including home video clips of the northeaster that
walloped Gloucester, Mass., in 1991 and supplies the drama for the
film's story. There also is a 14-minute documentary on residents
who survived the real storm, as well as a series of video clips
about the film's special effects.
</P>
<P>
   So the site for Disney's ``Dinosaur''
(http://disney.go.com/disneypictures/dinosaur) should be swamped
with Mesozoic material, right? Strangely, no. The skimpy site
highlights the digital cartoon's scaly characters and supplies a
few rudimentary examples of animation, but it stomps on an
opportunity to educate young visitors about the pleasures of
paleontology.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for ``The Patriot'' (www.thepatriot.com) is all too
typical of the genre, with biographies of the cast and crew, a copy
of the trailer and a bunch of photos and drawings.
</P>
<P>
   A Revolutionary War chronology is short on historical detail and
pointlessly interactive. And the loopiest element is a discussion
area that implies that Internet taxation might be a revolutionary
cause, though it is unlikely that people will start tossing their
personal computers into Boston Harbor anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even more meandering is the ``Gladiator''
(http://gladiator-thefilm.com) site. Its circular interface _ meant
no doubt to resemble the Coliseum in Rome _ was a constant battle
to navigate. And to access special areas of the site, visitors must
first traverse it and collect 40 different ``virtues,'' including
``changability'' and ``deceipt'' (but not ``spelling'').
</P>
<P>
   One final note: The ``Mission: Impossible 2'' site requires
visitors to submit e-mail addresses to enter certain areas, but
registrants then receive unsolicited promotional messages. Perhaps
the plot of ``Mission: Impossible 3'' will be about the worldwide
effort to end spam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
