<SLUG> BC-GERM-BOOK-REVIEW-865&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BIOGRAPHY OF A GERM': LYME DISEASE MICROBE HAS ITS OWN STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gaia'' is a term invented around 1950 by an English theorist,
James Lovelock, suggesting a kind of ultimate ecological
connectedness, the idea that living things are so interlocked in
function that all of them, from microbes to elephants, are part of
a single immense organism.
</P>
<P>
   In his informative and clever little book, ``Biography of a
Germ,'' Arno Karlen, a psychoanalyst who has written other books on
biology and medical history, rejects the more fuzzily spiritual
concepts of gaia. He does not see the entire biosphere as ``one big
pulsating organism.''
</P>
<P>
   Still his description of the life of a single microscopic
organism does bring into focus the interrelatedness of living
things, in this instance of white mice, deer, ticks, the microbe
Borrelia burgdorferi and the man-made condition of various flora.
</P>
<P>
   The germ in question, which is at the center of Karlen's book,
causes Lyme disease, and that has made it an object of considerable
interest in the last couple of decades. Borrelia burgdorferi, known
as Bb, was discovered only in 1982, not long after Lyme disease was
identified, but it has been on the planet, living in nonhuman
organisms, since before there were human organisms, and it will
probably still be here after the humans are gone.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason, Karlen says, that this germ is a good
subject for a ``biography,'' as good in its way as a conventional
biography of some influential human figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life stories of animals and insects, like biographies of
people, have a purpose,'' Karlen writes. ``They illuminate the
community of life, showing what makes species different and what
unites them. They show that by knowing any creature, one better
understands the living web in which it, and we, are threads.''
</P>
<P>
   Karlen almost overdoes this point, prefacing his plunge into the
germ itself with a good deal of throat-clearing, edging over from
the clever to the adorable here and there and straining a bit too
much for both literary effect and ecological enlightenment. The
interrelatedness of things has been drummed into us enough these
days, and Karlen's reiteration belabors the principle.
</P>
<P>
   But when he gets to Bb itself, Karlen's book becomes informative
and entertaining at the same time, a fine piece of popular-science
writing that covers the biological basics for those who do not know
them but covers them stylishly enough for the more informed to gain
insight, too.
</P>
<P>
   The stress is on the biological diversity of microbes _ such
that ``Bb and the bacilli in sour milk differ from each other more
than hummingbirds and eagles do'' _ and the slyness of genetic
adaptation. Along the way Karlen summarizes matters like the
Linnaean system of classification, the 17th-century discovery of
microbes, and the various types and sizes of microscopic creatures.
</P>
<P>
   Bb is a spirochete, one of the three main shapes of bacteria; it
is a long, slender spiral similar in some ways to the organism that
causes syphilis. It takes what Karlen calls a fantastic voyage to
get into the human bloodstream, a voyage that provokes a fair
degree of wonderment about the complexity of things and about their
unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   Karlen clearly enjoys the irony that Bb in recent years invaded
human beings, not as the result of our doing ``bad'' things like
despoiling the environment or pushing other species into extinction
but because we did such ``good'' things as protecting the natural
world.
</P>
<P>
   The peregrinations of Bb take it from ticks to white-footed
mice, which are warm-blooded, and back into the gut of a tick,
which is, as Karlen graphically puts it, like being cast ``in one
moment from a hot tub to a meat locker.''
</P>
<P>
   He explains succinctly how the microbe manages to survive this
shock and also to survive the intense invisible battle that all
microbes must fight with the varied arsenals of their hosts' immune
systems, the attacks of white blood cells, T cells and antibodies.
</P>
<P>
   Bb fights this battle continuously as it moves from its second
tick to another warm-blooded animal, possibly a raccoon or a
rabbit, and back to a tick, which then must pass a critical stage
of its life cycle on a deer before infecting a human being.
</P>
<P>
   As he recounts Bb's life history, Karlen along the way addresses
interesting questions like whether ticks themselves get sick from
Bb, and if not, why not. He gives a brief history of the emergence
of Lyme disease in Lyme, Conn., in the late 1970s, which is itself
a fascinating story, and then the discovery of Bb by a Swiss
biologist named Willy Burgdorfer, working in a lab in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   A critical part of the story was the long-term transformation of
the landscape of the American Northeast, from forest to farm, and
then in furtherance of the conservation movement, back to
semiforest again. The invasion of human beings by Bb, which
depended on the reintroduction of deer to the habitat without the
introduction of the deer's erstwhile natural enemies, was the
unintended consequence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyme disease could not have become epidemic until a changing
ecosystem revived Bb and its hosts, and suburbanization thrust
people into their midst,'' Karlen writes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He adds that the case of Lyme disease is not the only one in
which humans have unwittingly placed themselves at the intersection
of microbes and other animals. He provides the additional example
of Bolivian hemorrhagic fever, which became epidemic when
insecticides ingested by lizards ended up killing the cats (which
ate the lizards) that were the only natural enemy of the mice that
bore the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Karlen closes with some facts and questions concerning Lyme
disease itself, reassuring us that most people's immune systems
take care of Bb's invasion without outside intervention, which is
most commonly antibiotics. Indeed, there is a sharp debate among
specialists about the usefulness of antibiotics, which some doctors
feel are unnecessary and are likely to lead to more resistant Bb
strains.
</P>
<P>
   Karlen handles his subject with wit and comprehensiveness. His
book will help you know where you are going the next time you take
a little walk in some pleasant meadow.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `BIOGRAPHY OF A GERM'
</P>
<P>
   By Arno Karlen
</P>
<P>
   178 pages. Pantheon. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
