<HEADLINE>
DON'T EXPECT RAPID CONVERGENCE OF INTERNET, PHONE, VIDEO 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANA POINT, Calif. _ For all of the buzzwords in the technology
industry, perhaps none is invoked as blindly, reflexively and
totemically as ``convergence.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk to a senior technology executive these days and you will
probably hear about how television, the telephone system and the
Internet are converging to create an interactive world of
information and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   But, in fact, convergence is not really happening, at least not
yet. And when it does, it will probably take forms much different
than those generally envisioned today.
</P>
<P>
   That is not a conclusion a visitor might have expected to bring
away from the annual Vortex conference that ended on Friday here on
the Pacific Coast. Vortex is about convergence, and it may be North
America's most concentrated gathering of top communications
investors and executives. But according to an automated polling
service at the conference, Vortex attendees gave convergence an
overall letter grade of D-plus for now.
</P>
<P>
   They recognize that even though billions of dollars are being
spent on convergence, immense obstacles remain. And in the end,
convergence will be far less than universal.
</P>
<P>
   At the first Vortex conference two years ago, the mood about
convergence was positively giddy. ``Two years ago here I remember
people looking at the new carriers, the Qwests and Level 3's, and
thinking that they were just going to make convergence happen,''
said a senior technical executive for a regional communications
carrier. ``I think what's impressing me this year is a new sense of
maturity _ sobriety even.''
</P>
<P>
   A 21-percent drop in the Nasdaq will sober up just about anyone
in the technology business. And it has. But beyond the financial
picture, the emerging sense of realism about convergence seems
based on a simple and renewed appreciation of the mundane technical
obstacles that stand in its way, and on some newly creative
thinking about what sorts of services will best embody it.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, convergence is the last mile. That sounds obvious,
but the last few years, at least some technology pundits,
executives and investors have drooled over the exponential
increases in bandwidth capacity in the nation's long-distance fiber
optic networks and mistaken that for convergence.
</P>
<P>
   But for all of the leaps in long-haul capacity, no more than 2
percent of the nation's 100 million or so homes currently log on
the Internet with anything more powerful than an analog modem. The
last mile of the nation's communications networks _ or the first
mile, depending on who's holding the mouse _ is the part that
actually touches homes. But this crucial link has not kept pace
with the rest of the network.
</P>
<P>
   The digital subscriber line technology that local phone
companies want to use to deliver torrents of Internet data over
traditional copper phone lines has had a particularly tough time
living up to expectations. DSL is far more difficult to put in
place than was originally thought. And the bandwidth, or speed, it
delivers is far less than was first contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, when many of the nation's leading computer,
software and local communications companies formed an alliance to
support DSL, they thought it would generally deliver 1.5 million
digital bits per second to consumers' homes. Today, it is unlikely
that more than a quarter of the few hundred thousand residences
with working DSL are consistently receiving more than a million
bits, or a megabit, per second. Industry experts say that most DSL
users probably receive only about 500,000 bits per second, at best.
Cable modems, the main alternative to DSL, more frequently deliver
megabit-plus speeds, but in some ways those communications pathways
are less reliable than DSL.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even 500,000 bits per second is still an order of
magnitude faster than the 53,000 or so bits per second that can be
delivered by today's fastest analog modems. But consider that a
single channel of TV-quality video, using compression technology,
requires at least 2 million bits per second and often requires more
than 5 million bits per second; it becomes quite clear that for the
majority of consumers, television as they know it is not going to
be converging with the Internet soon.
</P>
<P>
   But then, merging TV with the Internet is probably the wrong
goal, anyway. Television is a one-way, centrally created and
distributed medium. It is not the killer application for the
Internet because the Internet does not operate like TV.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, most demonstrations of converged applications that
include video, including those at Vortex, are essentially
television with some interactive buttons, like ``buy now,'' or
``chat about this program,'' tacked on the side of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trap is when people think about this new media strictly in
the context of the old,'' said Michael O'Dell, chief scientist for
Worldcom's Uunet division, the No. 1 Internet carrier. ``I have a
problem believing that the future of the Internet is a bad version
of cable TV.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, Pushpendra Mohta, until recently one of
AT&AMP;T's top Internet engineers and now entrepreneur-in-residence at
the venture capital firm Benchmark Capital, shared an analogy he
picked up at a conference on wireless data services: ``If you are
used to shipping stuff by boat and all of a sudden you get access
to an airplane,'' he said, ``you don't put the boat on the airplane
and fly the boat to your destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than take the form of merely repackaged traditional
media, the most successful converged services will probably be cut
wholly from new cloth to take advantage of the specific
characteristics of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Napster, the service that allows users to swap digital music
files, is a perfect example. And some technology experts believe
that Napster is already consuming more of the Internet's bandwidth
than the leading Web portal, Yahoo! Rather than simply selling
compact discs online or streaming radio stations _ the audio
equivalent of adding a ``chat now'' button to a TV program _ the
nature of Napster's service emerged from the Internet. In fact,
Vinod Khosla, the venture capitalist from Kleiner Perkins Caufield
&AMP; Byers, said trying to repackage traditional media online was
actually hindering the deployment of broadband communications and
converged services in general.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're trying to migrate old services to a new medium,
the barriers are high and the payoffs aren't that great,'' Khosla
said. ``But when you have a new service, maybe the barrier is high
but I'll climb over it because the payoff is higher.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
