<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALANCHINE-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY BALLET CELEBRATES BALANCHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York City Ballet honored its founding
choreographer on Friday night with a program at the New York State
Theater that celebrated George Balanchine's extraordinary creative
versatility.
</P>
<P>
   There were many exhilarating moments. Nevertheless the evening
was dominated by ``Robert Schumann's `Davidsbuendlertaenze,'''
Balanchine's melancholy masterpiece of 1980. The title, which
refers to the accompanying piano score and its composer, reveals no
hint of the work's emotional content. As a result the changing
choreographic moods come as surprises.
</P>
<P>
   At first the ballet seems to be a suite for some ardent young
people dancing in an unaccountably gloomy ballroom designed by
Rouben Ter-Arutunian. The dancers on this occasion were Helene
Alexopoulos, Maria Kowroski, Kyra Nichols, Wendy Whelan, Charles
Askegard, Nikolaj Hubbe, Nilas Martins and Jock Soto, and all but
Nichols and Hubbe were making debuts in their roles.
</P>
<P>
   At times the dancers looked blithely innocent, and at other
times passionate. But it soon became apparent that Nichols and
Askegard were an unusual couple, for he appeared to be wandering
off into a dream world all his own while Nichols tried to steady
him.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years some balletgoers have interpreted the character
Askegard portrayed as a symbol of Schumann himself, who had mental
illness. But this role could represent any emotionally disturbed or
physically ill person who finds himself divorced from reality and
unable to cope with life.
</P>
<P>
   As the entire cast's dancing grew increasingly intense, as if in
response to the troubles of Askegard and the ever solicitous
Nichols, one could understand the reason for the gloomy scenery,
and the sense of drama was enhanced by Richard Moredock's
introspective performance of Schumann's score.
</P>
<P>
   Balanchine turned courtly and convivial in ``Le Tombeau de
Couperin.'' In this intricately patterned work to Ravel, two groups
of dancers move as if they were mirror images of each other, and on
Friday they moved with considerable charm.
</P>
<P>
   Charm was also one of the virtues of ``Tchaikovsky Pas de
Deux.'' This virtuosic duet can be danced with extroverted flair.
But Margaret Tracey and Robert Tewsley, a guest artist from the
Stuttgart Ballet, emphasized the choreography's graciousness, and
Tewsley's control, ease and sense of quiet joy were especially
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The program, conducted by Maurice Kaplow, also included a repeat
performance of ``Symphony in Three Movements,'' an exciting ballet
to Stravinsky in which Balanchine appears to be trying to turn
dancers into lightning bolts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
