<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8111 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-MIDDLEWARE-     05-28 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MIDDLEWARE-(1250)2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHALLENGE FOR MICROSOFT IS IN MIDDLEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The government's antitrust suit against Microsoft has provided
plenty of surprises the last two years. But surely one of its most
remarkable byproducts is that a nerdish bit of computer plumbing
called middleware has emerged as the star of the case and a focus
of public-policy debate in the Internet age.
</P>
<P>
   In his legal ruling last month, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
had no doubts about what so frightened Microsoft that it repeatedly
violated the nation's antitrust laws. ``Middleware,'' he wrote,
``threatened to demolish Microsoft's coveted monopoly power.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the Justice Department and states suing Microsoft
called earlier this month for the company to be split in two, the
rationale for such a harsh remedy was largely to make the world
safe for middleware _ a layer of software that acts as a technology
translator between the basic computer operating system and the
various applications programs that people use to carry out tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft,'' the government declared, ``has repeatedly, and in
a variety of ways, used the monopoly power of its operating systems
to prevent the development, distribution and success of middleware
products.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson may well issue his remedies order later this week _
probably approving the government's call for a breakup, antitrust
experts say. Anticipating that, Microsoft on Friday postponed a
gathering of news media and industry analysts that had been
scheduled for this Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At the event, rescheduled for June 22, the company was to detail
its technology plans for the next few years, including an
initiative called ``Next Generation Windows Services.'' To its
critics, the Microsoft effort appears to be intended to fold more
Internet software into its industry-standard Windows operating
system. And such a move, they say, would be a rerun of the tactics
the government cited in asking for a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft,'' the government said, ``has combined the software
code of separate middleware products with the code of its monopoly
operating system _ again with the purpose and effect of foreclosing
customer choice and excluding competition.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Microsoft, the middleware declarations of Judge Jackson
and the government reflect a puzzling inability of those in
Washington to comprehend the software business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government,'' Microsoft wrote in reply, ``seeks to
regulate Microsoft's inclusion of any `middleware' in Windows _ a
term the government defines so broadly as to include virtually
 &UR; any &LR;  feature Microsoft might add to its operating systems.''
</P>
<P>
   So what is' all the fuss about anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Middleware, a layer of software residing above the operating
system that applications can run on, has been around since the
mainframe days. But it has taken on a far more significant role in
recent years because of the Internet and the rise of electronic
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike desktop computing, which Microsoft dominates through its
Windows operating system, Internet computing is based on open
communications standards that are not owned or controlled by any
single software maker.
</P>
<P>
   As electronic commerce spreads, more and more companies are
writing Internet applications _ for sharing data, handling
transactions and so on _ that are written to run on top of a layer
of middleware. Because middleware runs on a variety of operating
systems, programmers can write a single version of an application,
rather than having to write various versions for different
operating systems, like Windows and Unix.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is a diverse, global network, and middleware can
serve as the translator that enables the different dialects of
computing to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   ``As these distributed Internet applications increase, so does
the use of middleware,'' said Dan Kusnetzky, an analyst at the
International Data Corp., a research firm. ``And that makes
operating systems less and less important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Raduchel, the chief technology officer of America Online,
observed, ``Almost all the new applications in computing are being
written above the operating system. The challenge in software now
is to write for the middleware.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet middleware business is growing fast, but still in
its infancy. There are perhaps 200 suppliers. International Data
estimated middleware sales at $2.77 billion last year, up 66
percent from two years earlier. Both growth and consolidation are
predicted for the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big battle of this decade is going to be in middleware,
not operating systems,'' said John Swainson, a general manager in
IBM's software group.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, not surprisingly, views things quite differently.
``We focus on the platform _ the set of technologies and services
that software developers need to write programs,'' said Tod
Nielsen, vice president of Microsoft's platform group. ``Drawing a
distinction between the operating system and middleware isn't
something we necessarily do.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's platform group is creating the so-called Next
Generation Windows Services. Many of the details are not known, but
generally it is an effort to have software developers write the new
wave of Internet applications to run on Microsoft's layer of
software instead of on middleware provided by other companies.
</P>
<P>
   One Microsoft executive explained, ``Think of these new Windows
services as API's for the Internet.'' API's, or application program
interfaces, are the software hooks to which programmers must tailor
their applications if they are to run smoothly. In the government's
antitrust suit, the Windows API's were portrayed as a key
instrument of the company's control of the industry _ enabling
Microsoft to withhold or delay rivals' access to that technology.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet middleware could allow software developers to write
for the middleware API's instead of Windows API's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's monopoly is particularly threatened by the
development of `cross-platform middleware' _ software that exposes
API's that are not controlled by Microsoft and that could be
accessed using a wide range of operating systems,'' Rebecca
Henderson, a professor at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Sloan School of Management, wrote in a brief on behalf
of the government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft views its Internet initiative as repeating its past
behavior, but in a very different light than its critics. Just as
Windows took care of the innards of personal computing, Microsoft
executives say they want to perform a similar role with Internet
software. ``Software developers want a solid foundation, so they
can write value-added products, not plumbing,'' Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   To Microsoft, the Next Generation Windows Services program could
supply that ``solid foundation'' for the Internet. And the project,
Microsoft protested in a court filing last week, ``will be doomed
to failure at the outset if Microsoft is split along the arbitrary
lines proposed by the government.''
</P>
<P>
   In the more closed environment of the personal computer
business, of course, no company benefited as much as Microsoft,
since it owned the industry-standard technology. With the open
technology standards of the Internet, however, Microsoft will face
a very different business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Next Generation Windows Services is part of the
repositioning of the company to compete in this evolving Internet
world,'' said Ted Schadler, an analyst at Forrester Research Inc.
``But it's not the PC model. No one can own the standards, and
Microsoft knows that. If they're not open, they're toast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
