<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-28 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE REAL ROCKET, THE ONLY ROCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other athletes are known today as The Rocket, notably pitcher
Roger Clemens, the tennis legend Rod Laver and wide receiver Raghib
Ismael, but they plagiarized the nickname. To anyone who saw
Maurice Richard play hockey, he was not only the original Rocket,
he also deserved to be remembered as the real Rocket, the only
Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Babe defined George Herman Ruth, Rocket defined the
Montreal Canadiens' folk hero who set all the National Hockey
League goal-scoring records that Gordie Howe and Wayne Gretzky
eventually shattered.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Richard scored in the hockey cathedral that was the
Montreal Forum, hats, programs, galoshes and newspapers were tossed
onto the ice in celebration as the public-address announcer boomed
formally, first in French and then in English, ``Goal by Maur-eees
Reee-chard.''
</P>
<P>
   But his coach and former linemate at left wing, Hector (Toe)
Blake, usually referred to him as ``Rocket.'' So did his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat beside Rocket in the dressing room for the seven years I
played with him,'' the center Jean Beliveau once said. ``He was an
inspiration and the idol of my generation. On the team we all knew
he was kind of an introvert and not the greatest talker.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in his own way, he was a leader and, as players and as a
team, we followed him because we were inspired by his desire to
win. When we lost, Rocket did not need to say anything to show how
hard he accepted defeat. You could see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, those blazing eyes, which finally closed Saturday when he
died at 78 after a two-year struggle with abdominal cancer.
</P>
<P>
   When he had the puck and swooped toward them, goaltenders
compared those eyes to headlights and searchlights. Chuck Rayner,
once a Rangers goaltender, said that Rocket's hand-eye coordination
as a right wing with a lefthanded shot put every puck ``an inch
inside'' the goal post. He made the No. 9 on his bleu-blanc-rouge
uniform hockey's most fashionable number, worn later by Gordie
Howe, Bobby Hull and Andy Bathgate among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are better hockey players,'' Richard once said, ``but
they don't work as hard. I like to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 18 seasons, the Canadiens won the Stanley Cup eight
times, including a record five in a row when he was their captain.
He still holds the career record for most overtime playoff goals,
six, including three in 1951, and shares the record for most goals
in a playoff game, five.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 82 goals in 133 playoff games, 18 were game-winners.
Gretzky is the record-holder with 24, in 221 games. The Devils'
Claude Lemieux is next with 19 in 215 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocket always enjoyed scoring goals,'' Beliveau added. ``I'll
always remember that he scored four goals in the scrimmage that
morning in the fall of 1960, then announced his retirement. He was
39 and had had a couple of injuries, including a torn Achilles'
tendon.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard once spent a day helping to move furniture into a new
home for his wife, Lucille, then scored five goals that night. He
set 17 records, such as 544 regular-season goals and 50 goals in
the 50-game season of 1944-45 during the final months of World War
II, prompting some observers to wonder if he was merely a wartime
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   But when many quality players returned to the NHL from military
service, Richard was even more dynamic, more famous. Of all his
contemporaries, only the younger Howe would eventually be rated
better all-around in that six-team league, long before Gretzky and
Mario Lemieux thrived in an NHL diluted by expansion.
</P>
<P>
   With his slick black hair and sturdy 5-foot-10{-inch frame,
Richard was an eight-time first-team All-Star, the sociological
pride of the French-speaking province of Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Richard was not only the best of the French-Canadian players
that stocked the Montreal team in those years long before the
integration of the American and European players, he was also the
best of all the players from the other Canadian provinces where
English is the primary language.
</P>
<P>
   Often fined for flareups, his internal flame sometimes exploded.
When cut by Hal Laycoe's stick late in the 1954-55 season at the
Boston Garden, he attacked the Bruins defenseman with his stick.
When linesman Cliff Thompson tried to stop the assault, Richard
punched him twice in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Campbell, then the NHL president, suspended Richard for
the three remaining games of the season and the entire playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   When Campbell, whose office was in Montreal, took his seat at
the Forum for the Canadiens' next game, he was pelted with trash
and someone threw a tear-gas cannister on the ice. The fumes sent a
sellout crowd hurrying onto Ste. Catherine Street, where store
windows were broken and merchandise looted in what was called ``the
Richard Riot.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day Richard was persuaded to go on the radio to calm
the city, but the Montreal fans never forgave Campbell for the
suspension that cost him the NHL scoring title (which he never won)
as well as the Canadiens' bid that year for the Stanley Cup, which
they lost to Detroit in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Campbell appreciated Richard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' Campbell once said, ``have I met a man with such
singleness of purpose and so completely dedicated to his
profession.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL created a new award a year ago, the Maurice Richard
trophy for the regular-season's goal-scoring leader. And as well as
his youngest brother by 15 years, Henri, naturally nicknamed the
Pocket Rocket, played as a member of a record 11 Stanley Cup
champions in Montreal, Maurice remains the original Rocket, the
only Rocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still tell me,'' Henri has often said in recent years,
``that I'm Maurice's little brother.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
