<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IN A TALE OF TWO OFFERINGS, BEST OF TIMES ENDS FOR ONE
</P>
<P>
   On the list of 1999's best initial public offerings, Ditech
Communications and FreeMarkets were among the best performers, with
Ditech's stock ending the year up 611 percent from its offering
price and FreeMarkets' ending with a gain of 750 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But that was then, and this is now. So far in 2000, their fates
have diverged as much as any two stocks' could. Ditech's share
price is up nearly 90 percent this year, while FreeMarkets' is down
by nearly the same amount. Unfortunately, FreeMarkets is more
representative of what has happened to last year's hot new
offerings than is Ditech, showing how far stocks can fall when
market sentiment shifts.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT SEEN IN DEAL FOR CHROMATIS
</P>
<P>
   Moving to expand its presence in the fast-changing
optical-networking sector, Lucent Technologies, North America's No.
1 maker of communications equipment, is in advanced negotiations to
acquire Chromatis Networks, a small private company, for as much as
$5.5 billion in stock, people close to the companies said over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   `CONVERGENCE' STILL A BLANK SLATE
</P>
<P>
   Of all of the buzzwords in the technology industry, perhaps none
is invoked as reflexively as ``convergence,'' the melding of
television, the telephone system and the Internet into an
interactive world of information and entertainment. But convergence
is not really happening, at least not yet. And when it does, it
will probably take forms very different from those generally
envisioned today.
</P>
<P>
   E-DARWINISM MAY NOT SPARE FITTEST
</P>
<P>
   The recent closings of Toysmart, CraftShop.com, Brandwise.com
and Boo.com have been the most visible e-commerce casualties to
date, and the consensus within the Internet industry is that more
closings will follow quickly. But analysts disagree about the
meaning of the recent closings. Some say the shakeout represents a
healthy dose of digital Darwinism. But others suggest that as
investors continue their wholesale rejection of consumer e-commerce
companies, they may be condemning some companies that deserve a
better fate.
</P>
<P>
   FILM WEB SITES BREAKING OLD GROUND
</P>
<P>
   The film industry loves the familiarity of sequels, so it comes
as no surprise that the Web sites for this year's roster of
potential summer box-office blockbusters are mostly formulaic
rehashes of past sites.
</P>
<P>
   SALON CHANGES PROMPT COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   Salon introduced a redesigned site last week, and it did not
take long before critiques started pouring in by e-mail: The site
had technical bugs; it was too cluttered; its new, smaller type
font was too hard to read.
</P>
<P>
   Salon's editor, David Talbot, said Salon was tinkering with the
site to fix the bugs and to address concerns about the font size.
But Salon's readers are not the only audience that matters. Talbot
also said that the redesign gave more prominent placement to
advertisers and made it easier to find room for continuous breaking
news.
</P>
<P>
   PLOT TWIST FOR GIULIANI BIOGRAPHIES
</P>
<P>
   At first, the furor over the personal life of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani of New York might have seemed like the ultimate publicity
blitz for two New York journalists _ Wayne Barrett, an
investigative reporter for The Village Voice, and Andrew Kirtzman,
a political reporter for New York One, the cable TV news station _
who are rushing to complete biographies of the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   But now that Giuliani has withdrawn from the Senate race,
publishing experts wonder whether the books have lost their
urgency. Kirtzman said he would revise his introduction, and in his
final chapter would track the mayor as he agonized over his final
decision. Barrett said he had added chapters to include this
month's roller-coaster ride for his book.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRIES BEGUN INTO AIRLINE DEAL
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys general of New York and Pennsylvania have begun
inquiries into the effect that the proposed United Airlines
acquisition of US Airways would have on competition.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED FOR HOLIDAY
</P>
<P>
   U.S. financial markets, banks and government offices are closed
Monday in observance of Memorial Day. In addition, markets,
government offices and most businesses are closed in Britain for
the spring bank holiday. Markets in most other countries are open.
</P>
</TEXT>
