<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, May 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Inclement conditions will linger in the southern Middle Atlantic
States as weakening low pressure moves off the Carolina coast. The
heaviest showers will be in southeastern Virginia and northeastern
North Carolina as cooler air arrives on northeasterly winds. Clouds
and lighter showers will linger near the southern and central
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, sunshine will be mixed with clouds. Clouds will
thicken over the mountains of northern New York and New England,
where a few afternoon sprinkles will occur.
</P>
<P>
   Unusually hot weather for late May will cover a large area from
the southwestern states to the central Plains. Late Monday, strong
thunderstorms will develop across Nebraska and Iowa as a cold front
lifts the increasingly humid air mass. Meanwhile, the Northwest
will be seasonably cool with a few mountain showers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WHEN SUMMER BEGINS
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of summer can be defined in many ways. The
Memorial Day weekend is the traditional start of the summer season.
Nevertheless, for ease of record keeping, climatologists consider
summer to be the months of June, July and August. However, the
warmest 90-day period in most of the contiguous United States
begins around June 6. The season will begin officially on June 20,
when the summer solstice occurs. The solstice, an astronomical
event, is when the noontime sun is directly overhead at the Tropic
of Cancer, 23.5 degrees of latitude north of the equator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8121 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-MILITARY-0529-CO     05-28 1630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-MILITARY-0529-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S VIETNAM DAYS LOOM LARGE IN FOREIGN POLICY VIEWS
 &HT;    (875&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    Moving in both (p) Politics and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ ``Brother Buck'' believes the Vietnam
Syndrome _ that is, the reluctance of American leaders to send U.S.
soldiers to far-away trouble spots of the world _ has just about
run its course in the making of this country's foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, and with the passing of nearly three decades, ``Brother
Buck'' still views issues of war and peace through the prism of his
experience in Vietnam _ a habit that is unlikely to change if he is
elected president of the United States this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brother Buck'' is Vice President Al Gore. And as the
Democratic Party's presumptive presidential nominee, Gore is closer
to becoming the nation's commander-in-chief than any other veteran
of America's longest war and one of the most divisive wars.
</P>
<P>
   It is instructive, then, to measure the degree to which Gore's
military experience has shaped his policy views, especially as
America's national security interests and military planning begin
to shift away from Europe and the Cold War toward Asia as the most
likely arena for future military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Gore discussed those views during an interview with Cox
Newspapers on the campus of the U.S. Military Academy following his
commencement address to the graduating cadets Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always think about Vietnam when considering issues of war
and peace,'' Gore said. ``Certainly, it was on my mind when I voted
for the Gulf War, or understood the necessity of sending NATO
troops to Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   The interview was conducted in the private study of Lt. Gen.
Daniel William Christman, the West Point superintendent,
overlooking the parade ground from which came the likes of Lee,
Grant, MacArthur, Eisenhower and Patton.
</P>
<P>
   The ground rules for the interview were simple _ no discussion
of his presidential campaign or his Republican rival, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush. ``Not here at West Point,'' he insisted.
</P>
<P>
   But the contrast between Gore and Bush in terms of military
experience is inevitable. While Bush rarely mentions his stateside
service in the Texas Air National Guard during the Vietnam War,
Gore rarely misses an opportunity to remind his audiences of his
service in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, during the interview, acknowledged that military
experience is not a prerequisite for policymakers, not even
presidents. And he suggested that it is time to stop judging ``baby
boomers'' who did not serve in the military during Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some distinguished leaders in the past have not had military
experience, so you can't say it's essential,'' Gore said. ``But I
can only speak to my own experience in life. I would find it hard
to relate to these cadets today or to the soldiers I meet on duty
in the same way that I do if I had not had the experience of
serving in uniform and serving my country overseas myself. It gives
an extra dimension about what you think and feel when you're
talking about the issues that face them.''
</P>
<P>
   Few Americans of Gore's generation made the decision he did _ to
enlist in the military rather than avoid the draft. He did so as
his father, Al Gore Sr., an opponent of the war in the U.S. Senate,
was facing a tough re-election campaign. The senior Gore lost, and
shortly thereafter, on Dec. 26, 1970, his father's birthday, the
younger Gore was shipped off to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not pass judgement on anyone who made a decision
different from mine in the 1960s or '70s about military service,''
Gore said. ``Everybody faced a different personal situation. The
country made a big mistake in its policy. A lot of time has passed
and as far as I'm concerned, we just ought to cut everybody some
slack.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back over his own experience, Gore said, ``The
consequences of peace fading into war are not abstract for me.
Anyone who has been part of an expeditionary force of Americans
sent to another country to defend our interests has seen firsthand
what it means for tens of thousands of young soldiers to travel
from here half-way around the world to deploy in war zones and what
it means to their families and what it means to their home towns
and to the country as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not theory,'' he added. ``That's not just words. That's
something that I lived. And that has an impact on you.''
</P>
<P>
   The trauma of Vietnam affected not only those who served there,
but also policymakers and military planners. For nearly three
decades, military analysts have spoken of a Vietnam Syndrome, a
psychological barrier to initiate military action for fear of heavy
casualties of an open-ended commitment of troops.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, when asked if this barrier exists today, replied, ``I
actually think that what we used to talk about all the time as the
Vietnam Syndrome has pretty much run its course.''
</P>
<P>
   He said U.S. military actions, beginning with Grenada, the
Persian Gulf War and, most recently, the conflicts in Yugoslavia _
Bosnia and Kosovo _ have demonstrated that ``our military is
well-trained and the lessons of Vietnam so well integrated to our
strategy and tactics that the specific fears that Vietnam aroused
have dissipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, ``there is an enduring isolationist streak in the
way many Americans think about foreign policy _ and a natural and
healthy reluctance to get involved overseas,'' he added. ``That
existed before Vietnam and it exists after the Vietnam Syndrome, as
a specific phenomenon, as faded.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Other Vietnam veterans have run for president, most notably,
Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska, a former Navy S.E.A.L. who was awarded
the Medal of Honor, the nation's highest military decoration. But
none have been as politically successful as Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was not a ``grunt'' in Vietnam, a foot soldier who sloshed
through rice paddies in pursuit of elusive Viet Cong. He was an
``information specialist,'' essentially, an Army journalist,
writing for the Castle Courier, the newspaper of the 20th Engineer
Brigade, based at Bien Hoa, a large Army and Air Force base about
40 miles north of Saigon.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore experienced the military conflict in the jungles of
Indochina in ways few Americans of his generation did, especially
those, like him, of America's privileged class.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of only two graduates of his Harvard class who
enlisted in the military and chose to go to Vietnam. And during his
five months ``in country,'' he ``never tried to get out of
anything,'' said Michael O'Hara, a sportswriter for the Detroit
News who served with Gore in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   That included guard duty at Ben Hoa and helicopter trips around
the country to report on the various projects of the engineering
brigade _ sometimes south to the Mekong Delta, sometimes north to
the DMZ, the Demilitarized Zone that theoretically separated North
and South Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara is the one who tagged Gore with the nickname, ``Brother
Buck.'' Its origin is forgotten by both men. ``It may have had
something to do with Tennessee or Davy Crockett or some nonsense
like that, I just don't remember,'' said O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   O'Hara recalled how the two of them once spent a couple of days
in a deserted foxhole in Khe Sanh where the engineers were building
an airstrip to support the incursion into Laos in 1971. Gore kept
piling large pieces of abandoned sheet metal over the foxhole _
just in case. ``I needled him with `I thought you were building a
high-rise','' O''Hara said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's experiences in Vietnam have colored every foreign policy
decision of his political career, from his early years in Congress
trying to understand the threat of nuclear proliferation to, most
dramatically, his vote in the Senate, against political party
pressures, to support ``Operation Desert Storm'' against Iraqi
leader Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam is very much a part of his campaign for president as
well. Some of the campaign television ads prepared for his
``reintroduction'' to the American voters this summer feature
photos of the young Gore in Vietnam jungle fatigues, carrying an
M-16 rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his presidential campaign, Gore has paraded his
Vietnam experience, often sprinkling references to his military
services throughout a speech, sometimes in a grave manner,
sometimes jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   This Memorial Day weekend, for example, in his speech to the
graduating cadets at West Point, Gore got the soon-to-be second
lieutenants to laugh heartily when he mockingly bragged of ``rising
all the way to the rank of Spec-Five,'' the rank equivalent of a
buck sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   Later, during a luncheon in the garden of the academy
superintendent's home, Christman, Gore recovered from a military
protocol mistake _ he called the officers to attention for an
awards ceremony _ with another joke: ``Did I mention that I was a
Spec-Five?''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a deadly serious decision for Gore to enlist in the
military _ one that many friends at Harvard and in Washington urged
him not to do. But his draft board was in the Gore family's
hometown of Carthage, Tenn., and he reasoned that if he didn't go,
somebody else would, possibly a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``And ... if, a few years later that young man was killed over
there, and I was walking down the sidewalk through the heart of
Carthage and his family was walking on the sidewalk in the opposite
direction, what in the hell would I do? Hang my head?,'' Gore said.
``I wasn't about to test that proposition. I didn't want anyone to
go in my place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's E-mail address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
