<HEADER>
A8124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AUBURN-THEATER-INTERV     05-28 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUBURN-THEATER-INTERVIEW-ART-715(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING MATH, A PLAYWRIGHT EXPLORES A FAMILY IN STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Auburn's ``Proof'' at the Manhattan Theater
Club is a family play of ideas. With intricate twists and turns, it
takes a dramatic and comic ride through the lives of a brilliant,
deranged mathematician and his two daughters, one of whom has
devoted herself to taking care of her father.
</P>
<P>
   Although this is not Auburn's first play, it is his first major
production and it has been a heady experience for the 30-year-old
playwright. ``Proof'' opened last week starring Mary-Louise Parker
and directed by Daniel Sullivan. For the author, the sequence of
events was quick and stunning: from page to stage in less than two
years, and then surrounded by praise from critics and theatergoers.
</P>
<P>
   In his first extended interview, Auburn spoke modestly about his
accomplishment. He said that he had written the first draft of the
play very quickly and, accepting suggestions from his agent and
friends, he painstakingly revised it. Then he submitted it to the
Manhattan Theater Club. Last April the company had a reading with
Parker playing the central role.
</P>
<P>
   ``She nailed it,'' he said. ``With no prompting and no
direction, she surpassed all my expectations and was unafraid to be
scary'' and to stress the critical edginess of her character.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately the play was scheduled for this season. With
a year to wait _ a year in which his play was still his secret _
Auburn took a job writing scripts for television documentaries and
wrote a new play. He also got married: He and his wife, who is a
historian, live in Brooklyn. Before ``Proof'' opened, he won a
Guggenheim Foundation fellowship and a Helen Merrill Playwriting
Award.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the genesis of the play, he said he began with two
ideas: ``One was to write about two sisters who are quarreling over
the legacy of something left behind by their father. The other was
about someone who knew that her parent had had problems of mental
illness,'' and when she reached the age of the onset of his
madness, was beginning to worry that ``she might be going through
the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   There were many possibilities for that legacy, or, as he said,
``any number of Maguffins.'' He decided to use mathematics, and,
for plot, the question of the authorship of a brilliant
mathematical proof. Explaining that choice, he said: ``The great
thing about math is that it's a kind of scientific activity that's
still done in a solitary way. Most science is now with big teams on
big projects. In math, someone could have done something major
working alone in an attic.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the play is filled with mathematical references and
amusing asides about scholarship and rivalry in the field, it is
not, he said, a play about math. More important, it deals with the
family under stress, especially with the daughter ``and her desire
to follow in her father's footsteps and also her fear of doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Auburn is not a math scholar, but he studied calculus at the
University of Chicago and has a great interest in popular science.
``I knew a lot of science and math guys in school,'' he said.
``You'd go to the gym and you'd hear them talking pure math talk,
locker room talk, University of Chicago style.''
</P>
<P>
   For research, he read many books, beginning with ``A
Mathematician's Apology'' by G.H. Hardy: ``It's a classic work
about doing math and science and their aesthetic appeal. It
communicates the passion and excitement'' _ as does the play.
</P>
<P>
   When Auburn began the play, Sylvia Nasar's book ``A Beautiful
Mind'' had not been published; but he was aware of the subject,
John Forbes Nash Jr., a Nobel Prize-winning mathematician who had
paranoid schizophrenia. In some ways, Nash could have been a model
for the father in the play (played by Larry Bryggman). Along the
way the playwright talked to mathematicians, partly to decide on
his use of language. He was told that some of it was so arcane that
even those in the field did not always understand it.
</P>
<P>
   One major decision was how much technical information to
include. In contrast to Michael Frayn's ``Copenhagen,'' he chose
``to err on the side of less information.'' It is not until the
closing minutes that theatergoers have more than an inkling of the
nature of the proof. The title came early, and intentionally has
metaphorical intimations.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The academic context of the play comes from the playwright's own
experience. He was born in Chicago and grew up in Arkansas, where
his father was an English professor (he is now a college dean), an
expert on Richard Brinsley Sheridan. The first play his son saw was
``The School for Scandal,'' eventually many times in many
productions.
</P>
<P>
   His days at the University of Chicago were transforming. He
joined a theater troupe called Off Off Campus and acted and wrote
comedy sketches, very much in the Chicago tradition of Second City.
Writing sketches, he said, ``you develop a rough toolbox of
techniques,'' and with that as a base he moved to one-acts.
</P>
<P>
   As a critic on his university newspaper, he immersed himself in
Chicago theater, seeing a diversity of plays at Steppenwolf,
Goodman and other theaters. He especially liked Steppenwolf, where
he was excited by ``that immediate roughhouse style.'' Although
Auburn has great admiration for David Mamet, Tom Stoppard would
seem to be more of an influence, for his ``playfulness and the
rigor of his construction.''
</P>
<P>
   Following up an interest in political science, he had an offer
to work for then-Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois during the summer of
his sophomore year but turned it down to join his theater company
at the Edinburgh Festival. After a Stephen Spielberg fellowship
writing screenplays in Los Angeles, he came to New York to continue
his writing.
</P>
<P>
   Accepted into the Juilliard School's playwriting program, he was
in the first class taught by Marsha Norman and Christopher Durang.
His classmates included Stephen Belber, Kira Obolensky and Julia
Jordan, all promising playwrights. He wrote plays as well as
monologues, several of which were later published in Middlebury
College's New England Review. One of the plays was ``Skyscraper,''
a free-flowing comedy about urban architecture and couples
uncoupling in Chicago. It had a brief run Off Broadway in 1997 and
was, he said, a learning experience.
</P>
<P>
   After Juilliard he worked in book publishing and for a
documentary film company, quitting to join his wife-to-be in
London, where she was doing research for her Ph.D. Living abroad,
he began writing ``Proof,'' approaching the play in a more
realistic, less absurd style than his previous work.
</P>
<P>
   For background, he reflected on his university days in Chicago,
remembering the eccentric people in the Hyde Park section around
the university (the setting of the play). He recalled one professor
who taught chemistry all day and ``then would spend his free time
marching around his neighborhood with a broomstick chanting the
song from `The Bridge on the River Kwai' at the top of his voice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is some connection between extremely prodigious
mathematical ability and craziness,'' he said. ``I don't think that
math drives people crazy, but those with edgy or slightly
irrational personalities are drawn to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the character played by Parker was based on anyone,
perhaps his wife, he said, ``No,'' and added emphatically, ``My
wife is a very intelligent and beautiful woman. You can put that
in: intelligent and beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Again he emphasized that the family was at the center of his
play. ``I think everyone thinks about their relationship to their
parents, what they're getting from that relationship, what they're
not getting, what they will give back to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the play opened, he was upset by a line in a magazine
suggesting that it was about ``your fear of being like your
parents.'' After that appeared in print, he telephoned his parents
in Ohio to make sure they knew the fear was that of the character
and not the fear of their son. Several weeks ago, the Auburns saw
``Proof'' at a preview. ``Mom says thumbs up and Dad does too,'' he
said. ``I hope they'll be quoted in the ads.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with his gift for dialogue and characterization, he has a
strong sense of narrative. ``Proof'' has a series of dramatic
surprises, including a first-act curtain that audiences greet with
an audible sigh.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he watched the screenwriter Richard LaGravenese on
television saying he was thinking of writing a play because then he
would not have to worry about plot and ``could just have people
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just people talking!'' said Auburn in disbelief. ``I
practically threw my shoe at the television.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
