<P>
   ISRAEL-CHIPS-1STLD _ JERUSALEM _ Seated in Motorola's largest
computer chip design center, Motorola Israel President Hanan Achsaf
says Israel's
</P>
<P>
   political isolation and occasional ``short wars'' are no
deterrent for firms seeking hi-tech know-how. Amid Israel's
feverish local start-up atmosphere, several large American
companies have major operations here. They include Motorola, Intel,
Applied Materials and Texas Instruments. Chips from Motorola's
facility go into radios, cars and computers around the world,
including production in Austin's Motorola plant and development at
Starcorp in Atlanta. They come for Israel's high percentage of
English-speaking and educated workers. But, like the rest of the
world, the local supply of engineers may be nearing its limit.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-INTEL-1STLD _ JERUSALEM _ Chip giant Intel Corp. is used
to getting its way in tiny Israel. It got a $600 million government
grant to locate a chip factory here. It employs Jewish workers on
the Sabbath, technically illegal until it gets approval still
pending with the government. And, when it saw a company it liked
last year, DSP Communications, it bought it for $1.6 billion _ the
largest acquisition in the country's history. It has pumped
billions into the economy, invested heavily in improving local
schools and spawned a whole sub-economy of contractors. Israel is
grateful. But talks are under way in the company's exploration of
another giant chip factory, and Israel, now established enough on
the hi-tech scene, is not likely to be so generous this time
around. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
