<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8127 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-EXPO-2000-ART-NYT     05-28 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPO-2000-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW FACE OF GERMANY IS ON DISPLAY AT EXPO 2000 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, Germany _ Something is afoot in Hanover. This country
has built itself a 400-foot-long glass structure, called it
``Germany: Workshop of Ideas,'' and adorned it with 47 giant busts
of great Germans that include one Juergen Sparwasser, a soccer
player, but not Goethe.
</P>
<P>
   The structure in question is Germany's pavilion at Expo 2000,
the world's fair that opens on June 1. The absence of Goethe, eased
out by the likes of Marlene Dietrich, is suggestive of an insistent
national quest: to get people to think differently about Germany.
</P>
<P>
   True, the Berlin Love Parade (whose instigator, Dr. Motte, earns
a bust) and a half-century of peace have already dented German
stereotypes. But Nicholas Batten, an Expo spokesman, insisted: ``It
is very important that we keep presenting a different face. We want
to show we are not the bad Germans any more. We want to be
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictions certainly look hazardous at the 370-acre Expo site
on the southern outskirts of this modest city in the north of
Germany. With little time remaining until the opening, an air of
disorder prevails. Distinctly unGerman _ and perhaps that is the
point.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the more than 170 national pavilions seem little more
than half-finished and minor fiascos keep occurring, as when the
sand recently air-freighted to Hanover in a Jumbo jet by the United
Arab Emirates was mistaken for garbage and removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Expo grounds look chaotic at the moment,'' Wiebke Bruhns,
an Expo official, conceded. ``But I am confident that 98 percent
will be finished by the time we open. Even if that is not the case,
it will not be a catastrophe. The Germans have a reputation for
being perfectly ordered, but maybe that is not always true.''
</P>
<P>
   So, a freewheeling, free-spirited, good-luck-to-Goethe sort of
Germany is preparing to greet millions of visitors _ 40 million, it
hopes _ to the country's first World Fair since these gatherings
started in 1851. The timing is awkward: Many think the Internet has
rendered the whole idea obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   For such online debunkers of Expo, the organizers have a line:
These critics have embraced a globalizing technology at the expense
of humanity. You can't eat the Internet, they say. You can't smell
it; you can't drink it. And a world's fair should be ``a party, a
feast, a great big easygoing get-together,'' in the words of
Bruhns.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is not impressed. Indeed so underwhelmed is
the world's superpower that _ with minimal tact _ it is snubbing
the party in Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's hometown. On the site
long planned for an elaborate American ``Main Street'' exhibit, a
Romanian pavilion is being hastily erected and a Big Wheel is
planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly tried and I personally put some time into trying
to get something to happen,'' said John Kornblum, the American
ambassador to Germany. ``But in the end, globalization did us in.''
</P>
<P>
   After what was widely viewed as the debacle of the Seville Expo
in 1992, Congress passed a law saying no government money could be
used for world's fairs. So William D. Rollnick, a New York
businessman chosen as the U.S. commissioner for the Hanover fair,
spent more than two years trying to raise money in the private
sector for an American pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   His attempts ended in failure a few weeks ago _ much to the
annoyance of German officials who saw it as a further sign of the
United States turning its back on the world since the Cold War's
end.
</P>
<P>
   A major reason for the decision is that many American
corporations now see themselves as ``global players''; they do not
wish to be associated with a national pavilion. So in the age of
globalization, the country that has held world's fairs in New York,
San Francisco and Chicago, among other cities, views an American
pavilion as a waste of time, even potentially counterproductive for
global movers and shakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a short-sighted, embarrassing and deeply disappointing
attitude from the United States,'' said Friedbert Pfluger, a local
politician who lobbied hard for an American presence. ``What
message is being sent here to the rest of the world?''
</P>
<P>
   America will, however, be represented by some of its ``global
players,'' including McDonald's, IBM and Coca-Cola, corporations
that have earned the title of ``Product Partners'' by contributing
about $5 million each. The food and drinks and equipment of these
companies will be much in evidence, with advertising tied to the
Expo logo, but not under an American flag or roof.
</P>
<P>
   A brochure produced for the Expo and designed to attract
corporate support says: ``For companies, the park offers a
wonderful and credible instrument for public marketing that will
offer new ways to reach clients.''
</P>
<P>
   So is this just another theme park? It has the longest cable car
in northern Europe, the biggest mosaic in the world (6 million
pieces), the largest wooden roof over a building, and, in a partial
revenge for Goethe, promises the longest-ever performance of an
unabridged ``Faust'' I and II _ a mere 21 hours.
</P>
<P>
   But the organizers insist bigness is not all. They point to the
fact that this is the first Expo with a specific theme _
``Humankind-Nature-Technology'' _ and that the common thread is
precisely the need to find new balances between onrushing
technology and human needs, soaring consumption and dwindling
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the responses are remarkable, including Japan's pavilion
built almost entirely of recycled paper, Hungary's flower-like
structure of wood, and a Dutch pavilion that superimposes different
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Finland best catches the tensions between _ but also the
complementary nature of _ technology and nature. It has produced a
handsome ``wind-nest'' combining ecology-friendly energy sources
and a high-tech display where Nokia cell phones serve as the bodies
of birds and provide their ersatz ``birdsong.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, too, an Expo will have a series of pavilions
that are not national but dedicated to issues. Rajeev Sethi of
India is orchestrating a ``Basic Needs'' pavillion. He has
assembled a wide array of exhibits from artisans throughout the
world, as well as an intriguing creation by a British artist called
``From Muck to Gold'' that illustrates the potential uses of human
excrement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to ask questions. What is need, and what greed? What is
livelihood?'' Sethi said. ``I feel America is disconnected from
such issues. It is a land of excess. We are always crying over
whales and tigers, but basic human skills are also a dwindling
resource. Technology, yes, OK, but let's not throw out the baby
with the bathwater.''
</P>
<P>
   On such debates, at Hanover at least, the United States has
turned its back. As for Germany, well, anything goes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
