<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8129 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT &LR;      05-28 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE FRENCH OPEN, AGASSI DEALS WITH CHANGES IN HIMSELF AND
STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Sunday was, as usual, a dress rehearsal for the French
Open: a day when the matches are best-of-one and the pressure
almost none; a day when the gate receipts refreshingly go to
charity instead of to agents, money managers or the players
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But for Andre Agassi, Sunday was more a day for remembering and
reflecting the last French Open than looking forward to the next.
He returned to the center court where he had experienced the
biggest rush of his long career and heard the cheers from an
excitable French crowd that had helped lift him to last year's
title. That experience _ rallying from two sets down against Andrei
Medvedev in the final _ set in motion events that would alter more
than his ranking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I mean, how to put into words is difficult,'' said
Agassi, for whom words usually come easily. ``This was such a
marking point in so many respects. Changed my career last year, and
my life hasn't been the same on or off the court. I just hope my
life doesn't ever change this much again in a 12-month period
because it can only be not good if it changes that much.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Roland Garros last year, he had gone through a divorce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know a year later, it's like it's a lifetime ago,'' Agassi
said.
</P>
<P>
   The center court has evolved, too, although not quite so clearly
for the better. Two of the four grandstands have been demolished
and refurbished. And even though the Art Deco elements have been
carefully re-created, the stadium feels slightly different now.
Because the stands rise higher in a hurry on two sides, the court
seems more closely surrounded, the atmosphere within it more
intimate, less aloof and, in that sense, somewhat less Parisian.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even to a beautiful arena like this, Agassi said, ``it's
always a little sad to see things change a little bit,'' Agassi
said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the opponent in front of him in Sunday's charity match
was only a pleasant reminder of the past. Arnaud Clement was 2
points away from beating Agassi in the second round last year
before the American rallied to eliminate the Frenchman in five
sets. Although it didn't count this time, Agassi beat him again
Sunday before scribbling a few autographs and then facing the
press.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have lost to Clement last year, that certainly
would have changed everything, but I think the match that did
change everything for me last year was against Carlos Moya in the
Round of 16,'' he said. ``Because that's when I was really down,
and when I really started to hit out on my shots and when I
realized that if I play aggressive and bring my game to the table,
that gets it done.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been getting it done with remarkable regularity since
then, compiling a 27-1 record in the last four Grand Slam events.
Considering that the one loss came in the Wimbledon final against
its six-time champion, Pete Sampras, he should have no regrets. And
even though he has not reached another final since January and the
Australian Open _ playing sporadically in recent weeks because of
minor ailments _ he said he has no regrets about that either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Zimbabwe, played there, then Scottsdale, Palm
Springs and Key Biscayne and then kind of quickly realized that you
can't be at your best every week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can do it for a year, a year and a half, where you just
commit to giving it 150 percent every time. The results can happen
for a certain period of time, but then it quickly becomes about,
where do you want to be at your best? I just kind of made the
decision to downshift and really get myself in position for those
things that I value the most.''
</P>
<P>
   Those would be Davis Cup, the Grand Slam events and the
Olympics, in which Agassi will defend his 1996 gold-medal title in
Sydney in September. Whether he can defend his French Open title _
as always at the world's most unpredictable major tournament _ is
an open question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in some respects, having no expectations from the
public and yourself coming in here last year was certainly part of
why the story was so incredible,'' Agassi said. ``But now it's
about really me just trying to be at my best out of appreciation
and respect for so much of what this place has given to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much more prepared this year than I was last year,'' he
added. ``But I wish I wasn't prepared if it means I'm going to win
again. Things happen out there that you need to get through. Last
year I had three different matches that technically I should not
have won. It has little to do with how well you play starting a
tournament as much as with how well you play at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   On clay, with its emphasis on long, exhausting rallies, it also
has much to do with fitness, and Agassi said he took no days off
when he returned home to Las Vegas after losing to Dominik Hrbaty
in Rome 17 days ago in one of his precious few clay-court matches
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I contend that to win here, you have to be physically at your
best,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such pronouncements cannot be of much comfort to compatriot
Lindsay Davenport, second-seeded in the women's draw. Like Agassi,
she won the Australian Open and then, unlike Agassi, went on to
dominate much of the hardcourt season until a foot injury _ linked
to arthritis in her foot _ knocked her out of action for six weeks.
The good news was that her layoff allowed her to spend more time in
California with her new boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to have something else going on in your life,'' she
said. ``You look more realistically at your career. You even look
past your career.''
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as Davenport returned to tournament play at the
Italian Open earlier this month, she wrenched her back during
practice. After a week of intensive therapy in Paris with her
coach, Robert Van't Hof, she is now able to serve again and is no
longer considering a withdrawal. But she has never considered
herself the player to beat, even though she, like top-seeded
Martina Hingis, has now won all the Grand Slam events but this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels weird,'' she said. ``We always joke about it, Robert
and I: who would have thought I'd be in position to win all four?
But his whole point with me the last four months is you have to try
to enjoy this challenge being put in front of you here: `Don't take
it as pressure because at the end of the day if you don't
accomplish it, it doesn't matter.'''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Hingis, Davenport did not grow up playing on clay and
view a victory at Roland Garros as a sort of birthright.
Nonetheless, Davenport has lost to the eventual champion the last
three years in tough matches, pushing Graf in the quarterfinals
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been working on my slide, but I'm actually just
paranoid about going over on my ankles: so paranoid about it that I
can't get over that,'' Davenport said. ``But I remember talking to
Monica Seles, and she said. `I never slide and I still won the
French, so don't worry about it.' And, you know, Andre doesn't
slide either.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
