<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, May 29. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Evening Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867;
e-mail: lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   CRIME-DROP-REACT (Chicago) _ With the historic drop in violent
crime beginning to take hold in even the most blighted urban areas,
cities across the country are being transformed as neighborhoods
that had become frightening wastelands are showing glimmers of
renaissance. New homes are being built, stores are opening and, for
the first time in years, people are sitting on their front porches.
By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECTION (Lima, Peru) _ In a vote long on protests but
short on drama, President Alberto Fujimori swept to an apparent
re-election victory Sunday against an opponent who had urged his
supporters to abstain from voting as a protest to charges of fraud
and an array of campaign irregularities. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WILLS (Undated) _ Although millions of Americans have
signed living wills and power-of-attorney forms, thinking the
documents would help them avoid unwanted treatment and prolonged
deaths, in many cases those measures turn out to be useless. First
of two articles. A special report. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-OIL-FALLOUT (Midland, Texas) _ For nearly a century, the
compact between ranchers and oilmen created the huge wealth that
built modern Texas. The ranchers owned the land, the wildcatters
found the oil, and everyone got rich together. But oil is no longer
king in Texas, and the state is grappling with a less glamorous
legacy of the high-flying days. Tens of thousands of oil wells
could be leaking and threatening underground aquifers at a time
when drought has made water the state's most precious natural
resource. Now, the ranchers and the oil producers are fighting over
cleaning up the mess. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   NY-CENTRAL-PARK (New York) _ Central Park is gorgeous right now.
Especially breathtaking are the thick, deep green lawns that cost
millions of dollars to restore and now look as luxurious as
Aubaussan carpets. No wonder the number of visitors is up to 20
million this year. No wonder many of them want to treat it like a
vastly superior extension of a backyard. In other words, littering,
making noise and trampling the exquisite grass. Before, when it was
considered dangerous and rundown, it was not such a big deal that
soccer players tore up the grass with their cleats or dog owners
did not always clean up. But now, the city is getting fussy about
the park. By Barbara Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   SKIMPY-BOOKS (New York) _ In a growing number of instances
involving both trade publishers and prominent academic publishers,
bibliographies _ the traditional structural support system for an
author's work _ have been severed from books and moved to digital
outposts. There, publishers say, they are available to anyone who
wants to read them. The advantage, the publishers say, is a
smaller, cheaper, more accessible book. Some authors support the
change, while others have fiercely opposed it. By Doreen Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA-INTERNET (Hong Kong) _ Old-line Asian companies are now
devising ambitious strategies. From Taiwan to Thailand, the
region's most powerful families have started a blizzard of online
ventures. In the process, the Internet is transforming the way
business is done here and elsewhere in East Asia. Decisions, which
used to be made by the patriarch behind a veil of secrecy, are
being pushed down the ranks as Asian companies embrace Silicon
Valley-style management. By Mark Landler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
