<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 18:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8137 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-TEXAS-OIL-FALLOUT-ART     05-28 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-OIL-FALLOUT-ART-1095(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS OIL WELLS DRY UP, ATTITUDES CHANGE IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDLAND, Texas _ For nearly a century, the compact between
ranchers and oilmen created the huge wealth that built modern
Texas. The ranchers owned the land, the wildcatters found the oil,
and everyone got rich together. Oil money built universities and
football stadiums, gaudy hotels and world-class art museums.
</P>
<P>
   Even today, an estimated 1 million people in Texas receive some
sort of oil or gas royalty check.
</P>
<P>
   But oil is no longer king in Texas, and as the economy has
changed, the state is grappling with a less glamorous legacy of the
high-flying days. There are 25,000 abandoned oil wells in Texas;
another 15,000 are sitting idle, and tens of thousands of others
could be leaking and threatening underground aquifers at a time
when drought has made water the state's most precious natural
resource.
</P>
<P>
   Now the ranchers and the oil producers, the mythic figures of
modern Texas, are fighting over cleaning up the mess. A growing
number of prominent ranchers, including former Gov. Dolph Briscoe
and the caretakers of the fabled King Ranch, are organizing against
the oil industry, seeking changes in environmental and royalty laws
and portraying state regulators as toothless.
</P>
<P>
   Oil producers, on the other hand, say the landowners are just
grabbing for money as the industry is only now recovering from its
latest downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these guys are out here biting the hand that fed
them,'' said John Bell, an independent oil producer.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas of old, what was good for Big Oil was considered
good for Texas. But attitudes are gradually changing as industries
like high technology and health care lead the state's thriving
economy.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, citizens' groups in central Texas have fought
plans to reopen a 700-mile underground gas pipeline, fearing that a
leak could pollute the region's water source. In Houston, a new
generation of business leaders, alarmed by the city's smog problem,
is calling for solutions that include sharp reductions in pollution
from nearby refineries.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the harsh mesquite desert of West Texas, where the
underground sea of crude oil known as the Permian Basin once made
Midland a boom town, the bravado of the bygone era is not yet gone.
Thousands of oil pumps still bob slowly up and down in the
surrounding flat terrain, where the average summer temperatures
exceed 100 degrees. Hotels still decorate rooms with paintings of
oil wells.
</P>
<P>
   A huge white Cadillac rumbling down Big Spring Street summarized
the enduring local sentiment with a bumper sticker: ``Wake Up
America: For Our Security We Need American Oil.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside his office at the Permian Basin Petroleum Association,
the executive director, Morris Burns, brightened at the memory of
the region's past influence. ``This was what won World War II,''
Burns said, recalling that the Permian Basin produced 25 percent of
the world's oil to keep the U.S. war machine going.
</P>
<P>
   But production peaked in 1972, the oil bust came in the 1980s,
and in the 1990s oil production in Texas dropped by a third. The
recent spike in oil prices has helped producers recover from the
disastrously low prices of 1998, but the overall trend is the slow
decline of what analysts describe as a ``mature'' industry.
</P>
<P>
   For over a decade, the major oil companies have been pulling out
of West Texas, and this week Burns wearily absorbed another
defection, as ARCO announced it would close its local office of 165
employees. What would happen to the workers?
</P>
<P>
   The new-found public advocacy of the ranchers is only the latest
blow. Like so many in the oil industry, Burns says he suspects that
trial lawyers in search of a new source of fees may account for
part of it. He acknowledged that a small number of ``bad actors''
in the oil industry had behaved irresponsibly, but he said many of
them had left the business over the past decade as regulations
tightened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Producers have become much more environmentally aware in the
last 15 years,'' Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an hour's drive west of Midland, past tiny oil towns like
Goldsmith and the aptly named Notrees, the environmental legacy is
evident on the 174,000-acre Frying Pan Ranch. The property's owner,
D.K. Boyd, bought it four years ago, adding it to his five other
ranches in West Texas and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   In all, his properties contain more than 2,000 oil wells. But
when Boyd hired a San Antonio environmental consulting company to
audit his properties, it found about 1,000 contaminated sites, with
environmental damage estimated at over $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   There is heated disagreement about who is responsible for the
mess, and Boyd is tied up in fiercely contested litigation with
several of the oil producers who lease mineral rights on his
property.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless of blame, a short tour of the Frying Pan reveals
obvious examples of the problems that ranchers say exist across
Texas. A tank where crude oil is separated from salt water has
spilled into the surrounding soil. A pipeline that burst a few
weeks ago has left a brown stain across a 50-yard section. Boyd's
ranch foreman, Bill Warbois, said some oil companies did little
more than dump dirt to cover up the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's wet oil,'' Warbois said, pinching some of the brown
sand between his fingers. ``You can smell it. You can pick that
dirt up and literally squeeze the oil out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyd, who ran his own independent oil company for 20 years, said
the city of Midland had approached him about water rights in recent
weeks for an aquifer that extends more than 20,000 acres beneath
the Frying Pan. He said that he had not thoroughly tested the water
source but that a handful of test wells had shown some evidence of
contamination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is more valuable than oil and gas and becoming more so
every day,'' Boyd said.
</P>
<P>
   Vince Matthews, director for the Center for Energy and Economic
Development at the University of Texas of the Permian Basin in
Midland, said many of the wells on ranches like the Frying Pan had
been drilled by the major oil companies over 50 years ago and were
now inevitably showing signs of deterioration.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews said smaller independent oil companies eagerly bought
the properties with the exodus of the major concerns, but they did
so as federal regulation tightened and environmental awareness
started to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large oil companies saw this coming,'' Matthews said.
``They said: `We don't need this. We can go to plenty of places
around the world, find bigger reserves, and we don't have to put up
with this litigious society.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Environmental complaints have grown steadily in the past decade.
Richard Lowerre, an environmental lawyer in Austin, said lawsuits
over the contamination of ground water had become more common,
particularly in West Texas. Oil companies often settle cases with
an agreement requiring landowners not to disclose the terms,
Lowerre said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Texas Railroad Commission, which regulates the oil
industry, reported 77 cases of ground-water contamination from oil
and natural-gas activities, the majority of them in the Permian
Basin, the most drought-stricken section of the state. In 1998, the
commission received 976 complaints of oil-field pollution from
landowners.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, a number of prominent ranchers and large
landowners founded the Texas Land &AMP; Mineral Owners Association. The
approximately 500 members, who control millions of acres, include
many from the ranching families that helped found Texas, like the
Kings and the Suggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has never happened before in Texas,'' said Doug
Beveridge, who manages land and oil leases for the King Ranch in
South Texas. ``You have never had landowners come together like
this, exclusively. It should have happened 10 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Property rights are a passionate political issue in Texas, and
in broad terms, the landowners are concerned primarily with
pollution cleanup and royalties and their belief that the
regulatory and legal landscape favors the oil and natural-gas
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, unlike in many states, land ownership is severed
between the surface and the minerals below. As a result, a
landowner may or may not control the rights to any oil or natural
gas below the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The oil companies sign leases with mineral owners, which grant
them rights to drill wells and build pipelines. The mineral owners
are paid royalties on any oil or gas production, while the
landowners usually receive only a one-time payment of several
thousand dollars for the use of their land.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, including that of Boyd, landowners also hold most
of the mineral rights on their property. Usually a company will
sign a surface-damage agreement with a landowner that stipulates
cleanup responsibilities. But many landowners say there are
companies that disregard the agreements or refuse to sign them.
</P>
<P>
   The state requires that oil companies seal a well with cement
plugs once production has stopped, in order to prevent contaminants
from escaping. The cost of plugging a well usually runs as much as
$4,500. But some companies have abandoned wells without plugging
them, particularly since 1998, when low prices drove many smaller
independent companies to bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The landowners association is lobbying for new laws addressing
concerns about royalties and the legal rights of landowners in
disputes over property damage, Beveridge said. The group is also
proposing a bill to block oil and natural-gas companies from
abandoning wells.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature has sporadically addressed the problem of
abandoned wells, including a past law that imposed a fee on oil and
natural-gas production to pay for plugging abandoned wells. Last
year, the state plugged about 1,600 wells. But declining production
has meant fewer dollars coming into the cleanup fund.
</P>
<P>
   Oil companies also benefit from a state program that allows them
to pay $100 for annual extensions on plugging wells. In some cases,
companies have used these extensions to delay plugging wells for
years. Officials estimate that 15,000 wells remain idle and
unplugged because of this program.
</P>
<P>
   Public attention to the problems was heightened last September
when The San Antonio Express-News published a series of articles
detailing the full scope of the problem. The Express-News series
also explored the historically friendly relationship between the
railroad commission and the oil industry. The commission's three
members are elected and often receive large contributions from oil
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, there has been a great deal of cynicism and
people have characterized the railroad commission as a captive
agency,'' said Tony Garza, a Republican member of the commission
since 1998. ``From time to time, their concerns have been extremely
borne out.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Garza has pushed the commission to be more
aggressive in addressing abandoned wells and met with resistance.
At last month's commission meeting, Garza's proposal to curtail the
$100 program was never brought to a vote. In the coming days, the
commission's chairman, Michael Williams, is expected to make a
recommendation on the fee program based on the findings of a
special commission he appointed to address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the oil industry is declining, so are many cattle
ranches across Texas. Jan Wheelis, whose family has owned the
McFaddin Ranch in Victoria County in south Texas since 1840, said
she must find every way imaginable for her land to make money. She
is considering harvesting mesquite trees, and she has leased
hunting rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make more money off hunting than oil in this place,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wheelis still keeps 250 head of cattle but has found that the
drought makes this increasingly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   And so, she said, does the legacy of oil. Many of the 57 wells
on her land are abandoned. Last month, she filed a lawsuit against
two companies, claiming that their failure to mend broken pipelines
and other problems had created an environmental mess. In all,
Wheelis said, she had lost 40 of her 2,664 acres to contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Driving toward a lake of old cypress trees recently, Wheelis
stopped her truck and listened to a metallic sound coming from a
neighboring property.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're drilling another well,'' she said and drove away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
