<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF TALKS, ETHIOPIA PUSHES FIGHT INTO SOUTHERN ERITREA
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASMARA, Eritrea _ One of the dead young men, on a southern
Eritrean slope of shattered stones and soldiers' bodies, left
behind the start of a journal. He was born on Oct. 5, 1980. His
father died when he was young, so he moved in with an uncle. They
did not get along. His grades were good.
</P>
<P>
   He learned something about life working in a market near Nazret,
Ethiopia, where he grew up, he wrote in English, one of the
languages used in his country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many kinds of man,'' he wrote in a notebook with
a cover picture of Leonardo DiCaprio on the Titanic. ``For example,
the person who is a thief.'' Cattle traders and laborers are
better, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote nothing about the war that killed him, but then again
he only got two pages through his life. He was one of at least 24
dead Ethiopians near the town of Adi Keshi in southern Eritrea, cut
down in battle six days ago. There were said to be many more
bodies, but it was too dangerous around a jagged bend, and who had
the stomach to look anyway.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, senior officials from Ethiopia and Eritrea are to
meet in Algeria, to talk about ending a two-year war that has
killed tens of thousands of young men like this one and, here in
Eritrea, women serving as soldiers, too. After a two-week offensive
by Ethiopia, Eritrea agreed last week to pull back from the border
territory both countries claim _ paving the way, in theory, for
peace.
</P>
<P>
   But this war, which has perplexed the outside world with the
ferocity of the fight between brother nations on the Horn of
Africa, has become only more complex in recent days. Despite
Eritrea's retreat, Ethiopia shows no signs of stopping the fight,
continuing its push into southern Eritrea. Only Sunday morning, an
Ethiopian warplane reportedly bombed what officials said was a new
power plant near the Eritrean port city of Massawa, far from the
border.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopian officials say they will not end the war until a final
peace accord is signed and they themselves have verified that
Eritrea has left the last of the land that Ethiopia claims.
Ethiopia maintains that it was invaded two years ago and has made
no secret of its desire to punish Eritrea for that.
</P>
<P>
   Eritreans say they do not know what else to give up but vow to
keep fighting until Ethiopians leave the territory they have
captured in the last two weeks, indisputably Eritrea's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight to the last, and still we are fighting,'' said
Mehari Gebrehiwet, 39, a teacher in the southern Eritrean town of
Mendefera, surrounded on three sides by fighting. Still, he
despaired: ``It's a meaningless war. Meaningless loss of lives. It
diminishes the economies of both countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``War,'' he added, ``cannot be a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The likelihood of finding peace at the talks in Algeria this
week seems remote _ especially since the two nations had already
agreed on all but the fine print of a peace deal brokered by the
Organization of African Unity, but still went on with this latest
round of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be an optimist here,'' said one Western diplomat
here, who did not sound very optimistic. His conversation Sunday
was interrupted twice in several minutes with phone calls about the
Ethiopian bombing near Massawa.
</P>
<P>
   The war between Ethiopia and Eritrea began in May 1998, after
months of skirmishes along a 620-mile border that was never
officially marked off. Since then, the war has taken on
significance greater than a mere border spat. These are two proud
nations: Eritrea, born only in 1993 after a 30-year struggle
against two regimes in Ethiopia, and Ethiopia, with a strong sense
of its 3,000-year history of repelling invaders.
</P>
<P>
   Eritrea is tiny _ with 3.5 million people to Ethiopia's 63
million _ but its long struggle has defined it as a nation of
fighters. And during the two years of war, it has held its own.
</P>
<P>
   But Eritrea has had the worst of it since Ethiopia began its new
offensive on May 12, saying it wanted a quick end to the war that
has cost so much money and so many lives. First, Ethiopia captured
large areas of Eritrean territory to the west. Then on Thursday,
Eritrea pulled back from the central front, south of Asmara, and
even said it would pull out of two towns on Ethiopia's specific
request.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of what appears to be military defeat along the
border, Eritreans seem glum but say they still support their
president, Isaias Afwerki, viewed as the father of the Eritrean
nation. He has portrayed the withdrawal as a ``tactical'' retreat
that saves lives, in a nation with far fewer to spare than
Ethiopia. And some military analysts say the Eritrean Army is far
from destroyed _ though that appears to have been a prime goal of
Ethiopians in this latest offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil here, though, is tremendous.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few days, as Ethiopians have continued to push
north, towns and villages, some less than 30 miles south of the
capital here, are emptying out _ adding to the several hundred
thousand people already displaced by fighting in the west.
Roadsides are jammed with people, some carrying a bag or two of
clothes, but many empty-handed, as they flee from the towns of Adi
Keyh, Adi Quala, Mendefera, Maimine and Areza.
</P>
<P>
   Adi Quala, 44 miles by road from Asmara, is now deserted except
for perhaps two dozen people, most of them women and children. They
are living under a concrete bridge, in case of shelling. ``Where
else can we go?'' said Roma Gebrekidan, a woman in her 60s who was
scrunched under the bridge, waving away swarms of flies with a
eucalyptus branch.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two days, the Eritrean government has been moving
many refugees by bus and truck to the grounds of a secondary school
in Dbarwa, about 12 miles north on the road toward Asmara. By
Sunday, relief officials said at least 18,000 people were there,
and busloads more were still arriving in early evening. Many had
slept in the open. Latrines were dug in V-shapes in front of the
school buildings but so close to the crowds that people seemed too
embarrassed to use them.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon Embaye, an official with the Eritrean Relief and Refugee
Commission, who had to leave his own home, said that for the
moment, officials have enough cornmeal, oil and sugar to feed the
crowds who were there already. But he said the amount was ``just
enough for survival.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have shelter, blankets, clothing, utensils for
cooking,'' he said. ``It all came as a surprise that we have
thousands of displaced people. These people came from their homes
only with the clothes on their backs.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the fighting, the Eritrean army seems eager to show that
it has pulled back from the areas claimed by Ethiopia but that it
is still intact and will fight where it suits Eritrea. On Saturday,
government officials escorted reporters to Adi Keshi, just south of
Adi Quala, where the young man with the journal died, apparently to
demonstrate they can hold their own.
</P>
<P>
   For three days, ending on May 24, soldiers said they repelled an
advance of Ethiopian troops across a plain and up a steep slope _
well inside Eritrean territory. They said the combat was heavy, in
battles through the day and night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their attempt was to eat breakfast here,'' said the local
commander, Lt. Col. Tibabo Sium. ``It didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said it was possible they would continue to pull back,
deeper inside Eritrea if the Ethiopians continued to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fight on our own terms,'' he said. ``If need be, we will
pull back in some areas. But we will make sure they pay a heavy
price.''
</P>
</TEXT>
