<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-PREVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE-TIME CHAMPION COMETS ARE PRIMED TO BE THE YANKEES OF THE
WNBA 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Van Chancellor always found it difficult to root for the
Yankees. Not because he grew up in Mississippi, but because they
spoiled the fun. ``I always pulled against them because they won so
much,'' Chancellor said frankly in his Southern drawl.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chancellor can understand the trappings of such a dynasty,
the predicament of privilege. If his Houston Comets are not the
Yankees, they are the Chicago Bulls and the Dallas Cowboys of the
Women's National Basketball Association. In its three years of
existence, the WNBA has only known one champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's good for the league,'' Chancellor said. ``Comets
basketball has brought notoriety to the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston won when there were only eight teams in the league's
inaugural season. And then when there were 10. And last year, the
Comets were the best of 12.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the WNBA has expanded to 16 teams, a significant
burst that could dilute the talent pool yet by the end of the
season simply prove the theory of continuity.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's Cynthia Cooper, the league's two-time most valuable
player, the all-star forward Sheryl Swoopes and center Tina
Thompson form an unbendable triangle. Chancellor, the three-time
WNBA coach of the year, is the elixir for the team's potent, but
potentially unstable, chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those four, the Comets are once again favored to
capture the championship, a quest that begins Monday when they tip
off the WNBA season in Houston against the Liberty, the team the
Comets defeated for titles 1 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor, doing his best Joe Torre imitation, said: ``Everyone
always asks me if there is a lot of pressure. We don't think about
four-peating _ we try to give our best.''
</P>
<P>
   The other teams have no choice but to credit Houston, for now.
``I personally don't mind it _ they are setting the standard,''
said Brian Agler, the Minnesota Lynx coach and general manager, who
coached the only champion of the short-lived American Basketball
League, the Columbus Quest, to two titles. ``It makes everybody
better when we have someone to shoot for. We have to find a way to
catch up.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the WNBA's strategic burst onto the summer sports scene,
Houston has won 81 games, lost 22. The Comets are the poster
children for consistency, the best tonic for a league that, as a
result of last year's sticky labor negotiations with the players'
union, might be expanding too soon, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   In a year when four new franchises _ Portland, Seattle, Indiana
and Miami _ join the league, executives are hoping to establish
some brand recognition. For the first time, the WNBA did not coin a
new catch-phrase like ``We Got Next'' or ``Join In,'' deciding
instead to recycle ``We Got Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to build a little of equity, creating something longer
lasting than every season,'' said Val Ackerman, the WNBA president.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance last season was down slightly (by about 100 per game)
from the second season, averaging 10,704. But, as league officials
are quick to point out, attendance had far exceeded projections
(albeit deliberately set low) the first season. Success, however,
has increased expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Whereas last season the league drew a total of 1,959,733 in 32
regular-season games, Ackerman said that this season the WNBA is
hoping to draw 2.5 million fans from the 16 teams in a 32-game
season. She projects 3 million in the fifth season.
</P>
<P>
   The three networks NBC, ESPN and Lifetime are in the fourth year
of a five-year deal. And the WNBA is in the process of re-signing
major sponsors, most of whom began with three-year packages.
Television ratings held steady at NBC last season and increased
marginally on cable.
</P>
<P>
   The average minimum salaries have increased slightly, though the
average base salary for the league is still just below $36,000 for
the three-month season. ``I tell our players we look at long-term
viability,'' Ackerman said. ``With that in mind, we have tried very
hard to manage our costs.''
</P>
<P>
   The WNBA is not yet turning a profit, Ackerman insisted, but it
could be close within the next two years. ``Right now we are ahead
of schedule,'' she said, ``with the early success and the surge of
interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Lieberman-Cline, the Women's Sports Foundation president
who is also the Detroit Shock's coach and general manager, takes a
long-term view as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of the league is so bright,'' Lieberman-Cline said.
``If in 10 years we haven't had a quantum leap, I would be
surprised. Look where the men's game was 50 years ago. We should be
entitled to a growth period, not just one or two years.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a league ideal, ``We Got Game'' could simply be the
plea from the other would-be champions, a group of franchises that
is expanding, especially in the Western Conference, and gunning for
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Houston has never been strong at point guard, still coping with
the death of Kim Perot last August and then losing Sonja Henning in
the expansion draft. The center position is also a concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still the team to beat, but I think we're capable,''
said Sacramento Monarchs Coach Sonny Allen, whose team is
considered the most likely to dethrone the Comets. Sacramento,
meanwhile, has no visible weakness. The Monarchs return five core
players from a team that finished 19-12 in 1999 and which boasted
the league's most valuable player, forward Yolanda Griffith.
Griffith, a former MVP with ABL, was second in the league in
scoring last season, averaging 18 points and 11.3 rebounds.
Sacramento lost only the reserve guard Kate Starbird to the
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   The second-worst team in the inaugural season, Sacramento now
has the league's most explosive offense, as point guard Ticha
Penicheiro dazzles with no-look passes and the sharp-shooting
Olympian Ruthie Bolton-Holifield is finally healthy.
</P>
<P>
   If the Monarchs represent the run-and-gun style common in the
West, then the Liberty best characterizes the Eastern Conference.
The team is stocked with veterans like Sue Wicks and Teresa
Weatherspoon, but the Liberty is burdened by the knee injury to
Rebecca Lobo and is waiting for last year's star rookie, Tamika
Whitmore, to get in shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty was the only team to have a winning record in the
East last season, and at this point, it is clear that the Western
Conference is the stronger of the two again. The East is aging, as
well as plagued with injuries from Washington to Charlotte to
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Still, four teams from each conference will make the WNBA's
expanded playoffs this season, vying for a chance to dethrone
Houston. The regular-season opener has been moved up two weeks and
the league finishes on Aug. 9 to accommodate training for the
Sydney Olympics. The playoffs will consist of three rounds of
two-of-three-game series this season, with no byes for the top team
in each conference.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be Houston again? ``People are dying to see if they can
do it again, and if they do, it is going to be worth talking
about,'' said Washington Coach Nancy Darsch. ``If there had been
three different teams then it wouldn't have been as emotional or as
big a deal as it is to knock off the three-time champion.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
