<SLUG> BC-MEMORIAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strangers, reunited
 &HT;    Fifty-five years after responding to cries for help on the
battlefield, soldier meets man he pulled from ditch in France
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it blind luck, fate or amazing coincidence. Howard Hardrath
of Atlanta sees it as a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-six years ago, in the bloody hedgerows of Normandy a month
after D-Day, Hardrath found an unknown dogface sprawled unconscious
in a muddy, bloody drainage ditch. Hardrath pulled the wounded man
out, even though he was sure ``the guy was a goner.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, as part of his Memorial Day celebrations, on a day set
aside for the nation to remember all its war dead, Hardrath, 82,
plans to telephone that man, Jim O'Neil, 71, of Winters, Calif.,
whom ``by incredible luck'' he identified last July.
</P>
<P>
   At a veterans' reunion, he overheard a man telling war stories,
and what the old vet was saying made Hardrath ``jump out of my
skin.'' Why? His tale of how he'd been wounded and saved by a
stranger coincided exactly with Hardrath's most vivid memory of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were in the 313th Infantry Regiment, fighting near the
tiny village of Montgardon on July 5, 1944. O'Neil and two buddies
took cover in a water-filled ditch and were hit by German fire.
That evening, Hardrath heard cries for help.
</P>
<P>
   Against his better judgement, Hardrath says, about 1 a.m. on
July 6 he inched his way toward the moans and found a 6-foot deep
ditch, ``with two dead men and the third covered in blood with a
terrible wound on the top and side of his head. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd wondered always over all these years whether this bird I
got out of the ditch lived,'' Hardrath says. ``My guess was he
didn't make it. I had no name or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, this past July 24, at the 50th anniversary reunion of the
313th, Hardrath's ``miracle'' happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Fayetteville, N.C., and I'm sitting on a couch half
asleep, and about 5 feet away one of these old GIs is telling a
friend how he got hit,'' Hardrath says. ``At these meetings,
stories like this are a dime a dozen, but then he came to the part
about how he and two buddies ran and jumped in a ditch and his two
buddies both got killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked, and he had a large scar on his head, where I
remembered it had been,'' says Hardrath. ``I go and ask the guy if
there was water in the ditch, and he says `Yes.' I say, `Was there
woods on one side of the ditch and a hayfield on the other,' and he
says, `Yes.' Then I ask, ``You didn't happen to get hit on the
afternoon of July 5, 1944, did you?''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil's ears perked up.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls the moment: ``Somebody had asked me how I got my
Purple Heart, and I'd started describing what happened. Somehow
Howard overheard and realized I might be the individual he pulled
out of there. He described the physical surroundings, an American
tank that had been hit, a gunner sitting with his back toward a
hedgegrow with one of his legs missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardrath got straight to the point.
</P>
<P>
   ``I says, 'You know who came out there that night and got your
ass? I did.' He just said, 'Oh my God!' After 55 years and 19 days,
I just happened to be sitting near enough to overhear the key
information that revealed who he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The two began comparing more notes about what had come to be
known as the Battle of Bloody Hill; the terrain, the names of
nearby towns and roads; a church located near the spot O'Neil went
down. ``Everything just clicked,'' Hardrath says.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil remembered lying in the bright light of a full moon,
calling for help, and waking up where Hardrath had taken him. He
remembered that his face and head were covered with blood, just as
Hardrath recalled. And he remembered vividly that his two buddies
in the ditch _ ``Birmbaum and Bromberg'' _ had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   Both men had returned to the spot on the 50th anniversary of
D-Day, in 1994. Each had gone to the place where O'Neil remembered
he'd been hit and where Hardrath recalled saving a man, both busily
taking photographs and notes of the terrain.
</P>
<P>
   They hadn't met. But last month, when Hardrath went to
California to visit O'Neil's family, they looked at snapshots from
'94. Hardrath was in three of O'Neil's shots.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil, who was 15 when he was wounded, moved from Wisconsin to
California after the war and ran a successful business. He says he
has no doubt he owes his life to Hardrath. ``It was wonderful when
he was here, with 23 of my family members who wouldn't be around if
not for Howard,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Hardrath, who is also from Wisconsin, was a 26-year-old platoon
sergeant that July. After the war, he moved to Atlanta, his late
wife's hometown, and went into real estate. Of rescuing O'Neil, he
says: ``I was just doing what had to be done, and I'm so happy I
did. After all, the O'Neils have eight children, so I know I did
the world a good turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The 313th, recalls Hardrath, comprised some 3,500 men, so the
odds of him finding O'Neil ``must just be astronomical.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right, says Bill Bynam, a probabilities professor at
Westminster College in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is amazing,'' he says. ``Imagine these two
individuals living their lives for the next 50 years, being among a
minority of individuals attending a reunion, and happening to talk
with one another again and discovering the connection.''
</P>
<P>
   Their chance meeting is like success in a lottery, Bynum says:
``winning the big jackpot twice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of thing just doesn't happen,'' Hardrath says.
``It's a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
