<HEADLINE>
SHOWING AGE AND WEAR, LIBERTY MAY BE WATCHING THE PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LENA WILLIAMS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Liberty players say they have nothing to prove
this season. They sound sincere but not entirely persuaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty will begin the fourth season of the Women's National
Basketball Association as the defending Eastern Conference
champions. Twice in the past three years, the Liberty has been one
game short of a championship. Four of the team's veterans were
picked to play in the league's inaugural All-Star Game last season.
And the Liberty, ridiculed for lacking pizazz and stars, is
featured in the league's 2000 promotional advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   But the Liberty is not picked to finish first or second in the
East and is doubtful to make the playoffs. The favorites in the
East are the Washington Mystics, led by Chamique Holdsclaw, last
season's rookie of the year, Nikki McCray, Vicky Bullett and Tausha
Mills, this season's rookie sensation. The Charlotte Sting and
Cleveland Rockers have been deemed contenders for the second berth
in the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty _ with the league's oldest starting lineup and
uncertainty at the center position _ is given an outside shot at
finishing third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were picked fourth with Rebecca Lobo,'' Liberty
Coach Richie Adubato said. ``Any time you make a team an underdog,
that is a tremendous motivational tool for a coach to reach players
and get them to play harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobo _ who missed all but the first 42 seconds of last season
with a torn anterior cruciate ligament in her left knee _ tore the
same ligament while working out in December and will be out of the
lineup until July. Kym Hampton, the team's 37-year-old all-star
center, felt so good after arthroscopic surgery on her knee that
she came out of retirement. But the knee began swelling during
training camp and Hampton retired again Friday, disappointed that
she could not play another season.
</P>
<P>
   Adubato had hoped to rely on Tamika Whitmore, the 6-foot-2-inch
power forward who rose above expectations during her 1999 rookie
season. But Whitmore arrived in camp 42 pounds overweight and has
only shed 18 pounds in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``She probably won't be able to help us win games until after
another two or three weeks,'' Adubato said.
</P>
<P>
   Until Whitmore is able to contribute, Adubato will go with Shea
Mahoney, the 6-2 rookie forward from Western Kentucky, as his sixth
player. The coach is also looking into the possibility of the
center position ``being done by committee.''
</P>
<P>
   The three vying for the job are Olga Firsova, the 6-6 Kansas
State center who was the team's No. 1 draft pick, the 6-5
Alessandro Santo de Oliveira of Brazil and Venus Lacy, the spirited
6-3 veteran who saw limited action last season but who has
impressed Adubato with her aggressive play in camp. Sunday, the
Liberty acquired forward Tari Phillips from the Portland Fire for
guard Carolyn Young, who was not expected to play until July
because of a knee injury. Phillips, who averaged 4.1 points and 2.1
rebounds a game for the Orlando Miracle last season, was picked by
Portland in the 2000 expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   If the Liberty is to repeat as division winners, it will do so
behind veterans like the all-star guard Teresa Weatherspoon, the
team's emotional leader on and off the court, and the all-star
forward Vicky Johnson, who led the Liberty last season in minutes
per game (33) and points (13.3). Sue Wicks, coming off her best
year as a pro, and the clutch-shooting Crystal Robinson, who led
the league in 3-pointers with 76, will also be expected to step
into big roles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been told we're too old, that we needed an overhaul,''
said Weatherspoon, 35; Wicks is 34 and Johnson is 28. ``We take
that as a challenge, a motivating factor for us to walk out on the
floor and show people that we come to work every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off an 0-3 preseason, the Liberty will be tested early.
The team opens the season Monday against the defending champion
Houston Comets in Houston. Three of the Liberty's next four games
are on the road against Phoenix, Washington and Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it that way because we get to see just how tough we
really are, and just how bad we really want it,'' Weatherspoon
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a good start will matter little if the Liberty fades down
the stretch. To avoid getting run down in a season that has been
condensed to accommodate the Summer Olympic Games in Sydney,
Australia, Adubato will most likely look to Becky Hammon, the 5-6
guard who provides an instant spark off the bench, and Jessica
Bibby, the team's fourth-round pick from Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty's trademark is defense and hustle. In the end, the
key to the Liberty's success this season may well be its desire to
prove all the naysayers wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we come out every night and give it 110 percent,
people still think we can't play this game,'' Johnson said.
``During the off-season, I talked to players around the league who
said: `The Liberty. You guys aren't that good.' A lot of players in
the West said that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're the only team in the league that beat Houston three
times last year.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
