<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORONTO REALLY WINS BY A DOUGHNUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An early visitor to Canada's largest city searched in vain for
sin and extravagance and reluctantly decided Toronto was the place
where he would like to breathe his last breath.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transition between life and death would be barely
noticeable,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics said much the same thing about Seattle in the late
1920s, when Mayor Bertha Knight Landes closed up the town after
firing 100 cops who had financial investments in gin mills and
bordellos.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened since we outgrew our puritanical roots?
</P>
<P>
   Seattle built the Space Needle, but Toronto has a taller one. In
fact CN Tower is the highest free-standing structure in the world.
</P>
<P>
   They've got Lake Ontario. We have Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Both cities have sports stadiums with swinging roofs.
</P>
<P>
   We've got Pike Place. Toronto has the Kensington and St.
Lawrence markets.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's theater arts are said to be surpassed only by New York
and London, yet Seattle cannot be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent performance of the musical ``Swingstep'' in Toronto,
residents of a small Cape Breton fishing village complained of
creeping urbanization bringing with it ``crime ... traffic ... and
Starbucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Toronto has almost as many coffee shops as Seattle but
they carry the corporate logo of ``Second Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   We've got raging debates over prayer in schools. A pressure
group in Toronto claims that antisocial behavior in schools would
be reversed if a daily ``Oath of Allegiance to the Queen'' became a
ritual.
</P>
<P>
   If there are so many similarities, why was Toronto chosen over
Seattle as ``the world's most livable city'' by a U.N. panel?
During a recent visit, we tried to find out.
</P>
<P>
   We discovered Toronto has efficient and well-used subway lines,
streetcar systems and underground malls linking most of the major
downtown offices and stores. We have endless traffic jams, a
downtown bus tunnel and vague promises.
</P>
<P>
   We debate whether our city should hire hit squads to reduce bird
droppings. Toronto's most famous piece of public art consists of 60
Canadian geese flying triumphantly beneath the glass ``sky'' in
Eaton Centre.
</P>
<P>
   But it could be that Toronto was named the world's most livable
city because a resident or visitor is never more than half a block
away from a sausage stand or a doughnut shoppe. In fact, the
morning ``doughnut hour'' has been described as the defining
Canadian social event by writers for the weekly CBC comedy show
``The Royal Canadian Air Farce.''
</P>
<P>
   You can hardly get more livable than that.
</P>
<P>
   What do the eastern Canadians eat with their muffins? Seafood
stew, naturally.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Chowder
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces thick-cut bacon, in quarter-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sliced onions
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup hot water
</P>
<P>
   4 cups fish stock
</P>
<P>
   4 cups sliced potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium carrots, peeled and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon thyme
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds halibut cheeks, or other firm, white fish
</P>
<P>
   3 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup sour cream, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Chopped fresh parsley
</P>
<P>
   You can make terrific stock out of two or three fish heads, but
I know you. No way. Instead, you can substitute clam nectar or make
your stock from Knorr fish cubes, which you can buy in most
markets.
</P>
<P>
   In your chowder pot, cook the bacon slowly until it begins to
brown. Add the onions and continue cooking for about 10 minutes.
Remove from heat and stir flour into bacon grease. Cook two minutes
then remove pan from heat. Add the hot water gradually, stirring
well. With a whisk beat in the fish stock.
</P>
<P>
   Add to the pot the potatoes, carrots, herbs and seasonings. You
can let this mess sit, refrigerated, for a day or two and the
flavors will improve.
</P>
<P>
   When ready to serve, reheat the stock, add the fish in bite-size
pieces and when it begins to firm up add the milk. Simmer but do
not boil. Add more salt and pepper if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Serve in four large bowls with a scoop of sour cream, a
sprinkling of parsley and hard chowder crackers or croutons in
each. Or you could serve the chowder with:
</P>
<P>
   Mackenzie Muffins
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups flour
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup oat bran (not flakes)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   One-half teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   Three-quarters cups brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-third cups mashed banana
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   William Lyon Mackenzie was Toronto's first mayor and I believe
he liked to combine flour, bran, baking powder, baking soda, salt
and cinnamon in a large bowl. Then he made a well in the flour
mixture and set it aside.
</P>
<P>
   In another bowl dump the egg and brown sugar and beat until
smooth. Add the bananas, raisins, oil and vanilla. Beat again. Pour
into well in flour mixture, stirring just until dry ingredients are
moistened.
</P>
<P>
   Fill greased muffin cups two-thirds full with batter and bake 20
to 25 minutes in a 375-degree oven. Makes about a dozen or enough
to feed one Toronto resident until he or she reaches the next
sausage stand.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
