<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8151 &Cx1f; tta-z
u e BC-SKIMPY-BOOKS-1200(2TA     05-28 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKIMPY-BOOKS-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOKS GET SHORTER AS BIBLIOGRAPHIES ARE BANISHED TO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Cal., N.J., Md.)   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is fitting that Robert Kaplan's slim book ``The Nothing That
Is'' is a portrait of the numeral zero. The Harvard mathematician
is among a wave of mostly scholarly writers whose recent books have
left nothing in the place usually reserved for the pages upon pages
where scholars lay out the sources for their findings and opinions.
</P>
<P>
   To skim through the 78 pages of bibliography for Kaplan's
225-page book, look elsewhere _ namely on the Internet, where the
material resides on a Web site that belongs to his publisher,
Oxford University Press.
</P>
<P>
   In a growing number of instances involving both trade publishers
and prominent academic publishers, bibliographies _ the traditional
structural support system for an author's work _ have been severed
from books and moved to digital outposts. There, publishers say,
they are available to anyone who wants to read them; a note in the
printed book gives the Web address where the bibliography can be
found. The advantage, the publishers say, is a smaller, cheaper,
more accessible book.
</P>
<P>
   Some authors, perhaps surprisingly, support the change, while
others have fiercely opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly we're encouraging our authors to put as much as they
can on a Web site to try and clean up the books,'' said Larry
Cohen, editor in chief of MIT Press, which publishes scholarly and
popular trade books. ``Manuscript sizes are getting longer and
longer. We've been trying to figure out how to deal with it by
separating parts of the book that perhaps a minority of readers
would be interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's frightening,'' said Peter Lyman, a library
science professor and former head of the campus library system at
the University of California at Berkeley. ``Paper, by its nature,
is a stable medium that will last for hundreds of years if it's
acid-free and treated at a natural temperature and humidity.
Digital material is fugitive, and most Web sites disappear in about
18 months. It's more than vanity to have a bibliography. It's part
of a collaboration that stretches decades and maybe centuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 18th century, the bibliography has underpinned the
scholarship of books by organizing chaotic records of knowledge
that came before. This list of references, titles and interviews
that influence a new book is a road map for scholars and other
readers, enabling them to follow the trail of supporting evidence
for theories and controversial points.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pare down books is provoking a practical
intellectual debate among writers, publishers and archivists, and
among its most provocative aspects is whether this sort of
slice-and-dice Web publishing is an early step toward eliminating
paper versions of some books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole issue of a book is up for question,'' said
Suzanne Calpestri, a librarian at the University of California at
Berkeley who calls the division taking place grangerizing, which is
an antique term for the clipping of book engravings. ``We don't
know what kinds of issues are involved with maintaining equipment.
We don't know how to save bytes for centuries. We know that rag
paper has lasted for hundreds of years, but the digital is so
ephemeral with changing platforms and equipment. Will you even be
able to read it 15 years from now?''
</P>
<P>
   Many academic and trade publishers experimenting with these
evolving forms concede that no one really knows the answer to that
question. The Library of Congress, for example, is seeking money
for pilot programs on preserving digital material.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of an answer notwithstanding, some publishers contend
that splitting up a book is a way to sell, package and price a
title in a commercially more appealing format.
</P>
<P>
   The information from the back of the book is a natural choice
for excision, they say, because of the prevailing view that only a
small portion of readers actually pore through the material. The
word bibliography is derived from the Greek bibliographia, which
literally means the writing of books; scholars often refer to this
material as ``the academic apparatus.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, some writers feel fiercely proud of this trove
of sources because it conveys the extent of their work and gives
their theories more credibility. In March the writer Jill Watts was
asked by her publisher, Oxford University Press, to consider an
electronic split of the notes and bibliography from her
yet-to-be-published portrait of Mae West, which explores the
influence black culture had on the actress' performances.
</P>
<P>
   Watts, an associate professor of history at California State
University at San Marcos, said she was stunned by the idea and
started asking other writers and academics for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If what's on the Internet doesn't last forever, then we've
lost power,'' she said. ``If the academic apparatus disappears,
then we're moving back to an earlier period when authors weren't
citing sources and could just say whatever they wanted. We're
coming out of an industrial-oriented society that wanted everything
to be added up and quantified into a virtual society where that's
less valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement of her editor at Oxford, Watts decided to
include her bibliography and look for pages of notes and text to
trim instead.
</P>
<P>
   One reason university presses show enthusiasm for severing notes
and bibliographies is that they are often financially pressed. To
expand readership and revenue, these publishers are trying to offer
books that can find a popular market, and that means packaging that
is not too weighty or academic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're realizing that an author can put the core ideas into a
book,'' said Marlie Wasserman, the director of Rutgers University
Press and president of the Association of American University
Presses, which represents about 120 major academic publishers.
``But the kind of scholarly apparatus that went on for pages and
pages _ that we had to knock down trees for _ can be posted on a
Web site without interfering with the sales of a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers University Press is just starting to experiment with the
idea. Recently the publisher asked one of its authors, Stephen G.
Brush, to shorten a newly revised 500-page textbook, ``Physics: The
Human Adventure.'' Instead of rewriting and trimming the text,
Brush, a professor of science history at the University of
Maryland, compromised with the publisher by agreeing to post his
100-page bibliography online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen whether this will work,'' he said. ``It
hasn't even been agreed whether the author maintains the site or
the publisher does.'' He, too, regards the shift as a baby step
toward something bigger. ``What I'm worried about is the pressure
to put a book just entirely online,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who maintains the Web sites leads to even more
questions. If it's the author's responsibility, what happens in the
case of illness or death? If it's the publisher's job, what happens
if the publisher goes under?
</P>
<P>
   MIT Press encountered some of these problems recently after a
textbook author, a professor, went on sabbatical and was unable to
repair a Web site when readers complained that the bibliography
posted there had suddenly become inaccessible.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some large publishers of popular trade books, like Random House,
say they are not asking writers to divide titles into electronic
and paper sections. But several authors said that other major
publishers are beginning to raise the idea.
</P>
<P>
   One author of a forthcoming historical trade book, who asked to
remain anonymous, said her publisher had asked about splitting off
the bibliography but compromised with an agreement to put other
information, like charts and illustrations, online instead.
</P>
<P>
   Other writers, however, are pressing for such divisions. Robin
Marantz Henig said she asked her publisher, Houghton Mifflin, if
she could detach the reference section of notes and other material
from ``The Monk in the Garden,'' her new biography of the
path-breaking genetic scientist Gregor Mendel. The publisher
approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people take shortcuts and don't tell readers about
the references for the sake of not weighing down a book,'' she
said. ``This allows me to be serious about the references but not
ponderous in the book. People ask me about whether Mendel fudged
his data. This allows me to post the 1936 paper that suggested he
might have and other papers that reassessed that information.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, the author of ``The Nothing That Is'' (1999), is still
evaluating the results of his experiment with a divided book. His
electronic references have enabled him to make his bibliography
organic _ constantly growing with feedback from reviewers and
readers. And he credits the book's unexpected success to its slim
size and format.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no other option,'' Kaplan explained. ``The publisher
wanted to have the success that it wouldn't have if it was a
larger, thicker book with a more scholarly appearance. And I didn't
want my book to be published without a bibliography to back up what
are often new and controversial points. We were at loggerheads.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's editorial director at Oxford, Peter Ginna, said that
the book was one of the company's top sellers, having gone through
five new printings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are issues to be worked out. The Italian and German
translations of the book failed to make note of the existence of a
Web site. Some reviewers criticized Kaplan for the lack of a
bibliography, failing to see the reader's note that said the
material was on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   And one professor in Dublin, Ireland, simply could not download
the information from the bibliography, which includes references
ranging from ``Khandakhadyaka, an Astronomical Treatise of
Brahamagupta,'' an Indian treatise written in 1934, to ``The Man
Who Mistook His Wife for a Hat'' by Oliver Sacks, which was
published in 1985 (with a bibliography).
</P>
<P>
   In that case, there was an old-fashioned, low-tech solution.
Oxford University Press printed out copies of the bibliography and
dispatched snail mail to Ireland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
