<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AUSTRALIA-CIVIL-RIGHT     05-28 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRALIA-CIVIL-RIGHTS-485&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIANS MARCH IN SUPPORT OF ABORIGINES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ More than 200,000 people, a crowd larger
than any expected at the Olympics here in September, marched on
Sunday to support campaigns for social justice for Australia's
black minority.
</P>
<P>
   The largest civil rights gathering in Australian history clogged
Sydney, a sprawling city of 8 million people, and forced police to
close much of the city to traffic for up to eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   High above the river of people who delivered the country's
sharpest political street message since anti-Vietnam war
demonstrations in the 1970s, a sky-writer left a white vapor trail
in the sky, tracing the simple message: ``SORRY!''
</P>
<P>
   Police estimated the crowd at more than 150,000. Rally leaders
claimed the total was much higher, and a national TV network gave
an estimate of 250,000.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Clark, chairman of Australia's leading indigenous lobby
group, the Aboriginal and Torres Straits Islander Commission,
called the strong showing ``a huge success,'' while other march
organizers were swift to take the size of the gathering as a
mandate to press the government for a formal treaty on the status
and rights of Australia's 380,000 Aborigines.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Scott, chairwoman of the multiracial Reconciliation
Council that organized the march, noted that such agreements have
been negotiated for minorities in Canada, Scandinavia and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney parade _ a three-mile walk through downtown with the
air of a family outing in brisk fall weather _ was the centerpiece
of a weekend of nationwide ceremonies and rallies organized by the
council to acknowledge mistreatment of Aborigines and to press for
future equity for them.
</P>
<P>
   From early morning to mid-afternoon, a river of people flowed
across the eight-lane, mile-long Harbor Bridge on which the
Australian national flag and the black, red and yellow Aboriginal
political flag were flying. Organizers chose the route to symbolize
hopes for ending two centuries of estrangement between the white
majority and Aborigines in this country of 19 million.
</P>
<P>
   European settlement began in Australia in 1788 with a British
convict colony on Sydney Harbor. Aboriginal history here goes back
to 600 tribal groups of nomadic hunter-gatherers who roamed this
vast island continent for 40,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's marchers were overwhelmingly white, but there were also
Asians, Australia's latest immigrants. The demonstration encouraged
both black and white civil rights leaders, who concede that recent
surveys have revealed that deep national divisions still exist on
what should be done about Aboriginal grievances and aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's prime minister, John Howard, a conservative elected
in 1996, rejects the demands of Aborigines for a formal government
apology for past mistreatment and calls for a civil rights treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's march started from an intersection near his official
waterfront residence, but Howard did not join the gathering.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Reconciliation Council acknowledges that its own extensive
research shows majority support for Howard's position. The surveys
show that 58 percent oppose special rights for Aborigines to
reflect their historic position. Some 62 percent reject the idea of
an apology for previous wrongs, some fearing retroactive
compensation claims.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, 61, who is known as a close student of such polls, says
he favors what he terms ``practical reconciliation.'' On the eve of
the march he declared again that this was more likely to be
achieved by popular action than by official words and legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Howard's critics turned their backs on him and yelled
``Say sorry!'' as he spoke at a reconciliation ceremony on Saturday
to a mostly white audience of about 1,500 at the Sydney Opera House
on Bennelong Point, which is named for the chieftain who greeted
the British invaders there.
</P>
<P>
   Since that invasion, the first Australians have become the
worst-off Australians. In this generally affluent nation, their
levels of health, education, income, employment, housing, and life
expectancy are far lower than those of whites and Asians, and they
have the highest rates of imprisonment and welfare dependency.
Their plight has until recently attracted more indifference than
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Aborigines have had full civil rights since the 1960s, and in
the 1990s they made political gains. For most, these advances have
not lifted living standards much, despite welfare and other
government funding of $1.5 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The rising generation of Aboriginal leaders _ such as Sen. Aden
Ridgway, 38, the only indigenous member of the federal parliament,
and Clark, 47, who are both of mixed parentage _ say the problems
and answers are matters of self-esteem and self-determination
rather than money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
