<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NEWMUSIC-CRI-ART-2TAK     05-28 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWMUSIC-CRI-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW-MUSIC LABEL LOSES A CHAMPION
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo  NYT6  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Increasingly, as the major classical record labels
undergo seismic reorganizations, followers of new music are finding
that independent boutique labels like CRI, New World Records and
Bridge are becoming the only companies willing to record new works.
At Sony Classical, for example, film scores, crossover projects and
topical works dominate the contemporary music releases. New music
was never a priority at BMG, and it is unlikely to fare well as the
company reconsiders its classical music lines this spring. And at
Universal Classics, the Argo label, which had recorded American
composers like Aaron Kernis and Michael Daugherty, was scuttled.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Nonesuch has been notably successful with
contemporary works, which make up the majority of its releases.
Nonesuch is owned by Time Warner, which is buying EMI. If it leaves
EMI a free hand, perhaps that label's recent flirtations with new
music, by way of the young English composer Thomas Ades and others,
may continue.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last decade it is CRI, especially, that has been a
vital home for both traditionalists and listeners with eclectic
tastes, thanks to the efforts of Joseph R. Dalton, the label's
37-year-old executive director. During his decade at the venerable
label, Dalton has restored CRI to its original mission: partly to
be an alternative to the big commercial labels, which have always
kept new works at arm's length, and partly to document the major
currents and obscure tributaries of the developing American style.
</P>
<P>
   For about three decades, starting in the mid-1950s, CRI (which
stands for Composers' Recordings Inc.) was the first place
collectors turned for new works, but when Dalton arrived in 1990,
it had gained a reputation as a dusty repository of austere
academic music. By seeking out musicians that his predecessors had
ignored _ including post-Minimalists, young composers and
performers with pop music sensibilities, and Asian and Latin
American composers whose music bears the accents of their own
cultures _ Dalton has revitalized the label.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Dalton surprised much of the new-music world by
abruptly announcing his resignation. He left CRI on Friday and says
he plans to take a few months off before deciding what to do next.
CRI has moved quickly to find a successor _ some 30 candidates are
under consideration _ but its first choice has reportedly turned
down the job. There is talk of bringing the label under the
umbrella of the American Music Center, but the discussions are said
to be preliminary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised to hear that he was leaving,'' said Kernis,
whose first recording was released on CRI in 1992. ``I'm sorry for
us, sorry for the business of new music. He's given a lot of
composers and performers wonderful opportunities. It's hard to
imagine the label finding someone who will have the same kind of
openness and flexibility and who is interested in so many styles
and in exploring so many ways of seeing new music.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the extent to which CRI has been revived under Dalton's
leadership, the question of whether he was pushed is barely worth
asking. People close to him say the frustrations of working for a
nonprofit arts organization _ principally, working long hours at
comparatively low wages with a skeleton support staff _ caught up
with him. (Nonprofit tax status allows an organization to seek
subsidies and grants. Most performing arts groups are nonprofit
because the income from ticket sales does not cover costs. CRI, New
World Records and several other small, specialist labels have
nonprofit status.)
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, after a brief demurral, agreed with this analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised at the range of emotions I'm having,'' he told a
visitor to the company's offices on Spring Street in SoHo during
his final days at the label. ``People say, `How can you leave CRI?
You  &UR; are  &LR; CRI' Well, to be CRI for 10 years is a lot. It's hard. It
needed that _ someone to be a man about town, identified with the
label as I have been, to help it break out of its sleepy, dusty
academic image. But it wears on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest frustration is one that is increasingly
common in the nonprofit world: the sense that while the artists
reap the benefits that nonprofit organizations bring them, those
who keep the machinery running get few rewards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There really needs to be something prior to a lifetime
achievement award for the people who serve the arts as faithfully
as the artists,'' Dalton said. ``It's almost a vocation, getting
into this work, but there is very little nourishment. I got pats on
the head from my board. But I didn't sign on to be a starving
artist. I have an MBA. Caring for administrators, not just training
them, is something I don't think is addressed enough, and it's
crucial for the arts.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   When Dalton arrived at CRI in 1990, the label had a
distinguished history and a catalog of about 400 discs. It was
started in 1954 by the composers Otto Luening and Douglas Moore,
and Oliver Daniel, an arts executive, who included in the company's
charter the guarantee that CRI's recordings would not go out of
print so long as the company existed. Its early projects included
works by experimenters like Henry Cowell, Lou Harrison, Harry
Partch and John Cage as well as a full complement of Serialists,
neo-Romantics and composers of other mainstream and academic
persuasions. But by 1990, much of the adventure had left the label,
and it had come to be regarded as crusty and out of touch.
</P>
<P>
   Dalton, then 26, was exactly what the company needed. With a
music degree from Catholic University in Washington and an MBA from
Southern Methodist University in Texas, he had worked for a season
at the Brooklyn Academy of Music and for three years at Sony
Classical.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my first interview, I told them I came to New York because
I was attracted to the works of Laurie Anderson, Philip Glass and
Steve Reich, who were working here,'' Dalton said. ``And I saw
their backs tighten, but when I met with some of the businessmen on
the label's board, I said, `These people are on major labels, and
they sell.' It was clear to me pretty quickly why things weren't
happening at CRI.''
</P>
<P>
   An early priority was to mend fences with composers who felt
poorly treated by CRI. Another was to address CRI's reputation as a
vanity label. Originally composers had to subsidize their
recordings, usually with grants and awards, although it was never
as if anyone with the cash could buy a place in the catalog: From
the start, an adjudication committee screened submissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have guidelines on how to submit work,'' Dalton said, ``and
when I arrived, the guidelines said that if you don't have complete
funding, don't send us your music. I stopped sending that out
immediately; I thought it was appalling. My view was that an arts
organization decides what it wants to do and then finds the money
to do it. And that's how we operate now.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, CRI's projects are still subsidized by grants,
sometimes arranged by the composers, but often arranged by CRI once
a recording has been approved by its editorial committee. The
adjudication process, too, has changed during Dalton's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things that Jody and I have tried to do is keep the
committee rotating and anonymous,'' said the composer Chester
Biscardi, referring to Dalton by his nickname. Biscardi is a member
of the company's board and the chairman of its editorial committee.
``There are nine of us, and in terms of race, gender and style, it
is very diverse in its representation so that we can get a balanced
response. We get the tapes and scores, we listen to them, we have
informal discussions and we come to a consensus about what's good
for the label and whether it's possible financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Fairly quickly, Dalton was able to open CRI's gates to composers
who had previously been excluded. Beginning with a handful of
recordings inspired by the Bang on a Can Festival, he established
the Emergency Music series as a home for downtown composers who
bring together popular music influences, Minimalism and traditional
techniques in their work. Another series, Exchange: Music at the
Crossroads, has focused mostly on immigrant composers whose works
embrace their cultural roots. He reissued the label's older
recordings in an American Masters series that reminded collectors
that the catalog was full of neglected gems and important scores.
And a jazz series that he planned will have its first release this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The yardstick for success at CRI is modest. A collection of
works by gay composers was a runaway hit with sales of 7,000, a
minuscule figure by pop standards. The company's all-time best
seller, a decades-old collection of works by Harry Partch, has sold
about 25,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing one runs into at nonprofits,'' Dalton said, ``is
that there is always a board member saying, `Why are we nonprofit
anyway?' And you get board members who think they are going to come
in and give you `business sense.' I let them argue that among
themselves because, frankly, it's abusive to hear board members
telling you that `CRI is a business and has to be run like a
business' when you're spending 10 hours a day doing paperwork for
grants. They don't get it. It's not that being called nonprofit
makes us struggling and poor. It's that we're dedicated to
something that will not survive commercially.''
</P>
<P>
   CRI has, at any rate, upheld its pledge to keep its discs in
print, no matter how slowly they sell. The company has a warehouse
of LP's that collectors can still order through its Web site
(www.composersrecordings.com) and if someone wants an LP that has
not made the transition to CD and is out of stock, the company will
make a cassette dub and photocopy the liner notes. In recent
months, Dalton has been negotiating with Emusic, a company that
will allow collectors to either download works from the Internet or
order custom compilations of pieces from the CRI catalogue. He
expects that service to be available within a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What CRI does is of the utmost importance,'' said Fran
Richard, who runs the concert music department at Ascap, the
performing rights organization. ``Every composer needs recordings.
Without them, they're dead in the water, because not everyone
attends concerts, and even for those who do, it takes time to get
to know the piece. And to me, Jody was a real hero of this
business. He was a discerning impresario, with courage and vision,
and the choices he made were significant predictions of the
important works of the end of the 20th century. He produced a
legacy that has added immensely to the richness of the field, and
he's going to be missed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
