<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8175 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-CRIME-DROP-REACT-ART-     05-28 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRIME-DROP-REACT-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLIMMERS OF RENAISSANCE IN AREAS ONCE BESET BY CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: D.C., Mass., Calif., Fla., La., Ill, Texas)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ With the historic drop in violent crime beginning to
take hold in even the most blighted urban areas, cities across the
country are being transformed as neighborhoods that had become
frightening wastelands are showing glimmers of renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   From Boston to New Orleans and Los Angeles to Miami,
neighborhoods where drug gangs controlled the streets, commandeered
empty houses and terrorized residents are slowly beginning to seem
safer and more livable, according to interviews with people in nine
cities that have seen sharp drops in violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   New homes are being built, stores are opening, subway and bus
lines are adding service and banks and shopping strips are breaking
ground. There is less graffiti, and there are fewer abandoned cars
and vacant lots. And, for the first time in years, people are
sitting on their front porches and parents feel safe letting their
children walk to school.
</P>
<P>
   In the U Street neighborhood of Washington, the subway system is
operating later at night and an organic grocery store and a private
jazz club with a $2,500 annual membership fee are to open soon. In
the Oakwood section of Los Angeles, forbidding 8--foot fences are
being replaced with lower picket fences and other inviting designs.
And in Miami's Overtown and Liberty City neighborhoods, textile
plants, production studios and a food processing plant are opening.
</P>
<P>
   Especially striking is that people are beginning to move to
these neighborhoods from more stable urban areas and the suburbs,
the interviews suggest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sense that cities are safer,'' said Robert Sampson,
a professor of sociology at the University of Chicago. ``And there
is a return to the city among not just empty nesters, but people
with kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these neighborhoods are still struggling with crime and
poverty. But the improvements have taken on such momentum that they
do not appear to be slowed by increases in some violent crimes in
several cities last year, including Boston, Houston, New York, San
Antonio and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, surveys conducted by a Northwestern University
political scientist, Wesley G. Skogan, have found that in the
sections of the city where crime has declined sharply, primarily
African-American neighborhoods on the South and West sides, there
have been ``extremely large increases in the quality of life,''
Skogan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said residents in those neighborhoods had reported a
lessening of drug and gang activity, declines in public drinking,
loitering and disorder in the schools and streets that were cleaner
and had fewer abandoned buildings and cars.
</P>
<P>
   Changes like that were clear last week in one neighborhood on
the West Side of Chicago. In a city where neighborhoods are a
source of strong local pride, this section about five miles west of
the Loop did not even have a name until recently and had virtually
fallen off the map, longtime residents say. Now they say the area
has revived enough to be considered part of the Tri-Taylor
neighborhood, which is near the University of Illinois
</P>
<P>
   ``We were considered nowhere really,'' said Nancy Echevarria,
46, who has lived on Taylor Street almost all her life. ``The
neighborhood was taboo. It was like the OK Corral here. Gangs of 30
guys would position themselves right on the street selling drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Echevarria and her husband, Fidel, who are raising two children,
ages 7 and 9, and a granddaughter, age 3, used to call the police
frequently, and in retaliation, she said gang members put a bullet
through her front door a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, the rampant crime in the police
district that includes the neighborhood dropped more than in any
other section of Chicago, 36 percent from 1992 to 1998, police
figures show. Echevarria says she sees far fewer drug dealers, and
there is only one vacant house left on her block. On Taylor Street,
$350,000 condominiums are being built, and the value of three
houses owned by Echevarria has skyrocketed, to more than $150,000
each from about $15,000 some 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Her children skate and bicycle on the streets, which have new
sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other day,'' she said, ``it was so nice to come out in the
morning and just sit and hear the birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say such progress results from a number of social and
economic factors that have helped bring about the decrease in crime
and are benefiting from it. The booming economy has created so much
urban development that builders and businesses are venturing
farther away from well-established neighborhoods into ones that
were once on the edge of livability.
</P>
<P>
   Cities are using budget surpluses to offer tax incentives to
businesses that open in these areas. And in some places, like
Chicago, other major changes are under way in these communities,
including changes in schools and the dismantling of huge,
crime-plagued housing projects, like Rockwell Gardens, which is not
far from the Echevarria home.
</P>
<P>
   With less crime, there have been more jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Frank R. Nero, the president of the Beacon Council, a
private nonprofit economic development agency, said factories and
other businesses had been moving into neighborhoods like Overtown
and Liberty City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are starting to feel more comfortable,'' Nero said.
``The more investment you have in an area, the safer it is and the
safer it will become.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In addition, as things improve and as new policing strategies
concentrate on community outreach, residents have become more
willing to cooperate with the police, and that cooperation has
helped reduce crime.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Flack, who has lived in the Skyline Park neighborhood of
San Antonio for 15 years, said he saw the police on patrol much
more often and had developed more of a relationship with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know them and they know me,'' Flack said as he sat on his
porch the other day. ``If they've got a problem, they let me know,
and if I've got a problem, I know just who to call.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a shooting near his house several days ago, he said.
``The police came by and told me that a kid had shot at another
bunch of kids, and I said, `Oh, that would be so-and-so who lives
in that green house over there,''' he said. ``They had that deal
wrapped up in a couple of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   In city after city, the changes are seeping into the fabric of
neighborhood life.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, in the Uphams Corner section of the Dorchester
neighborhood, an area known for crimes like the 1992 slaying of a
man who was eating dinner with his wife at the Tasty Chicken
restaurant, drug houses have been shut down and businesses have
opened, including a children's clothing shop and a housewares
store. Youth programs have been created, a park that used to be
littered with used condoms and drug needles is being renovated and
the community has begun sponsoring a street festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see fewer bars on windows,'' said Jan Mattimoe, a middle
school teacher who helps organize a community improvement project.
``This spring I've seen more flowers in this area than I've ever
seen. There is real desire to get out there and make things look
pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington's U Street neighborhood, Cici Mukhtar, the owner
of a cafe, said she was glad to have a fancy organic supermarket
and an exclusive jazz club moving in. That is all part of what has
made the neighborhood more attractive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing, just amazing what's happening here,'' Mukhtar
said.
</P>
<P>
   Myra Power, 28, who lived in the neighborhood from 1991 until
moving to New York in 1997, was back last week, looking for work
and a place to live. She said she noticed a huge change.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I lived here, I wouldn't leave home without my Mace,''
Power said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, children stay out late at night playing basketball and
waiting in line to use the swings at the playground. Construction
crews are busy renovating old buildings and building new ones.
</P>
<P>
   Her friends, Powers said, now leave belongings out on their
porches. ``It used to be that the only thing they'd leave out was
barbed wire,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of worrying about break-ins, she said, they fret
over how to plant the most attractive garden.
</P>
<P>
   In New Orleans, the crack houses and blighted buildings that
choked the city's Irish Channel neighborhood are beginning to give
way to avant-garde galleries, clothing shops and even a designer
jewelry shop on Lower Magazine Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a grocery next door that would sell one beer
and one cigarette, and there was a pay phone there, so there was a
lot of loitering,'' said Patty Spinale, who opened her lingerie
shop, House of Lounge, on Lower Magazine Street two years ago.
``The neighborhood has really significantly cleaned up in the last
two years in terms of people investing in it. More tourists are
comfortable with venturing into the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Houston, Capt. Mark L. Curran, commander of the Eastside
Division for the Police Department, said he heard evidence of
improvement in the complaints he fielded at civic club meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the early '90s, it was rape and burglaries,'' Curran
said. ``Now it's, `I want you to take care of my neighbor's barking
dog.'''
</P>
<P>
   But as their neighborhoods have become more attractive, some
residents have found themselves pushed out, along with the
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The end of gang warfare that had terrorized the Oakwood section
of Los Angeles, just blocks from Venice Beach, meant safer streets
in an area that had been the city's only black neighborhood near
the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   It has also meant that some people who had lived there for more
than 30 years lost their leases as landlords sold property to
affluent newcomers or raised rents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up and down the street you see whites walking these days,''
said Melvyn Hayward Sr., a longtime neighborhood organizer and
director of the Vera Davis Community Center. ``In 20 years, you
would never see that. They wouldn't come down here.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes are still quite new in most of these neighborhoods,
and some residents are skeptical that the improvements will endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still crime,'' said Cynthia Harris, a case worker for
a health center, who lives in Uphams Corner in Boston. ``My son
finds needles in the driveway where he plays. And if I had an
opportunity to move, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Taylor Street neighborhood of Chicago, one developer,
Senan Nugent, hires gang members to watch his properties so that
other gang members will not steal plumbing pipes and supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nugent and others said they would not be there if they
were not convinced that it was a safe, promising place to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Dave Williams bought a new three-unit condominium on Taylor
Street for $367,000 this year, and he is renting it and three other
buildings to students at the University of Illinois and employees
at Rush Presbyterian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The renters are people who would not dare live here in the past,
Williams said. Many of the students come from the suburbs and drive
sport utility vehicles, but they have no trouble getting their
parents to co-sign their leases.
</P>
<P>
   And although he put up high wrought iron fences with electronic
security systems at the condominium, he said that only two of his
12 tenants bothered to turn on their systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were actually quite skeptical and nervous when we first
invested,'' said Williams, a emergency room physician who lives
downtown. ``But things have gotten steadily better. It's really one
of Chicago's new frontiers now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
