</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-RANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEER COMMERICAL MAKES RANT A NATIONAL PASTIME FOR JOE CANADIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Over the din of a multiscreen sports bar,
Dallas Hyde recalled the magical moment at a Calgary Flames hockey
game, when ``he'' stood up in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the crowd went nuts,'' Hyde, a 24-year-old oil
change supervisor, recalled of the moment when Jeff Douglas stepped
before a microphone to deliver ``The Rant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a lumberjack or a fur trader, I don't live in an
igloo, eat blubber or own a dogsled,'' the Nova Scotia actor said,
repeating lines from a Molson Canadian beer commercial that has
become a nationalist mantra for 30 million Canadians this spring.
Addressing an invisible American audience, ``Joe Canadian''
patiently continued his lesson: ``I have a prime minister, not a
president. I speak English and French, not American.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can proudly sew my country's flag on my backpack,'' he said,
uttering patriotic lines that are recited in bars and high school
hallways from Vancouver to Halifax. ``I believe in peacekeeping,
not policing; diversity, not assimilation.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, the television version is flashing images of maple
leaves and beavers as Joe Canadian reaches his climax, bellowing:
``Canada is the second-largest land mass, the first nation of
hockey, and the best part of North America. My name is Joe and I am
Canadian.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadian hockey teams struck out in the Stanley Cup for a
record-breaking seventh year in a row, the Canadian dollar is stuck
at two-thirds the American dollar, a southern brain drain is
cherry-picking this year's crop of college graduates, but Canadians
have found a powerful spine stiffening elixir: a nationalistic beer
commercial.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of being measured against the eternal American yardstick,
Canadians are doing something uncharacteristically Canadian:
beating their chests with patriotism. The Rant, as the 60-second
commercial is known, has won cheers in movie theaters, endless
debate on talk radio, fist-pumping ovations by fans at National
Hockey League games, and 14,000 e-mails to a special website
created by Molson, www.iam.ca.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were taken aback by how much it struck a chord with
everybody,'' said Paul Thomson, a Molson spokesman who quickly put
the Joe Canadian actor on a national tour of hockey rinks. ``There
was a lot of Canadian pride that was below the surface, exploding
the myth that young adult Canadians are not proud of their
country.''
</P>
<P>
   At Schanks Athletic Club, the sports bar here, Kim Anderson said
of the ad, ``It's kind of neat for him to yell it out,'' though
adding, ``After all, everything here is American.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in a nation with the highest level of foreign economic
ownership in the developed world _ 23 percent of companies _ the
beer-drinking patrons of Schanks were sitting in the electronic
wash of ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   From British Columbia, long a liberal bastion, Lisa McCaskill, a
sales manager, said, ``I saw it in a movie theater in Vancouver,
and people were cheering _ real patriots.''
</P>
<P>
   Glen Hunt, a 35-year-old Toronto advertising executive, wrote
the advertisement after returning to Canada last fall from a
three-year stint in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent people out on the street to see how young people felt
about being Canadian,'' said Hunt, a creative director for Bensimon
Byrne D'Arcy. ``They started pretty quiet, but once they got going,
it was a dormant volcano ready to erupt.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, this flag-waving surge has collided with two
forces that historically have deflated chest-pumping patriotism
here: English Canada's cutting humor and the nation's unity-defying
regionalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can proudly sew my country's flag on my backpack,'' Mark
Steyn, a National Post newspaper columnist, wrote recently.
``That's because, even though I am a beer-guzzling hockey fan, I
took sewing classes in Canada's non-gender-stereotyping school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted that many Canadians feel squeamish about reciting the
national oath of allegiance to Queen Elizabeth II. On one hand,
they gripe, pledging allegiance seems so American. On the other
hand, swearing allegiance to the Queen seems so British. Steyn
concluded: ``If you drink enough Molson, eventually even Canada
makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   In a country where east-west links are tenuous, comedians
quickly deconstructed The Rant into a series of regional
mini-rants.
</P>
<P>
   From this western province, an ``I am Albertan'' parody hails
John Deere for making ``the best hats,'' and then rants: ``I speak
flawless English and gripe to the store manager about French labels
on cereal boxes.''
</P>
<P>
   From Quebec, an English-language radio station aired a morning
drive-time satire that contradicted any notion of unity there. ``I
believe in language police, not equal rights,'' the announcer says
in a heavy French accent. ``I believe Club Supersex is an
appropriate place for my wife and I to celebrate our
anniversaire.''
</P>
<P>
   From Newfoundland, a regional rant concludes: ``Newfoundland is
the second island province, the first nation of drinking, and the
best party in North America! My name is Baz, and I am Newfie!''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the inability of some Canadians to take patriotism
seriously, The Rant is believed to have prompted the government of
Ontario, Canada's most populous province, to announce that,
starting next September, each student will start the day by
standing at attention, singing the national anthem, ``O Canada,''
and pledging allegiance to the queen.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Alberta, governing Conservative Party lawmakers are
considering legislation that would require schoolchildren to sing
``O Canada'' at least weekly. In Quebec, which has been run by the
separatist Parti Quebecois since 1994, Canadian symbols, such as
the national flag and anthem, are officially ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The new nationalist mood has won applause in Ottawa, the
national capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone has decided nationalism sells,'' Charles Gordon, a
columnist for The Ottawa Citizen wrote approvingly in Maclean's
magazine. ``If that's true, it's good. It means that a unique
culture, in art and music and theater and writing, can survive in
this country, survive in fact of a powerful culture pouring over
our border every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Canada's heritage minister, Sheila Copps, traveled to
Boston, where she showed the commercial to an International Press
Institute panel titled: ``American Culture _ the People's Choice or
a Form of Imperialism?''
</P>
<P>
   But unless a giddy new nationalism can really bubble out of a
beer commercial, Toronto's Globe and Mail offered this sobering cup
of expresso. A few years ago, the Charles R. Bronfman Foundation, a
private cultural group, tried to spoonfeed history to the Canadian
masses with a series titled Heritage Minutes. ``All they sparked,''
the newspaper editorialist recalled, ``was a series of parodies on
the Comedy Network called Sacrilege Moments, financed by _ wait for
it _ Molson.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
