<SLUG> BC-U.S.-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. BETTER ORGANIZED, CONGRESSIONAL REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ In a surprisingly positive report on changes at
the United Nations, the U.S. General Accounting Office has told
Congress the administration of Secretary-General Kofi Annan has
made considerable strides in improving management of the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   The report was prepared for the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, where criticisms of the United Nations have been
frequent. It lays out for Congress the complexities of the U.N.
structure and, against that background, differentiates between
reform goals that a secretary-general and the U. N. Secretariat can
meet alone, and those that depend on the decisions of 188 member
nations.
</P>
<P>
   U. N. officials said they have been trying to make this case to
impatient members of Congress for years, and some demands for
reform from Washington have been characterized as impossible in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by an investigative arm of Congress, found that
where there are serious failures or lags in making changes _ like
designing programs and their budgets more concretely, or in
monitoring results _ the shortcomings are often related to
instructions from the General Assembly that aren't clear. The U.N.
General Assembly is a parliament of nations where international
politics often block decisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our examination of General Assembly resolutions for 1997
and 1998 that required secretariat action,'' the report states,
``we judged 20 percent in each year to be too open-ended or vague
to determine what objectives the secretary-general was expected to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes: ``According to U.N. and U.S. officials,
some resolutions are vague and open-ended because members do not
agree on what outcome is desired. A vague resolution is the
compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   The congressional study includes as examples the creation of
broad assignments, like ending human rights abuses or fostering
sustainable development, without stating exactly what the Assembly
wanted the Secretariat to accomplish, or how.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. General Assembly, which often pits a majority of
developing nations against the richer industrial countries, has
also stymied the secretary-general's attempts to assign specific
time limits into U.N. programs.
</P>
<P>
   The report credits Annan's administration, which began in 1997,
with improving coordination among U.N. departments and programs, at
least at higher levels, with the creation of a cabinet-style
management team. The study also noted that the appointment of a
deputy secretary-general, for the first time in the organization's
history, has given the United Nations a chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary-General Louise Frechette, a Canadian, made the
establishment of an organization-wide code of conduct a priority,
the report stated. The code was approved by the General Assembly in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing peace and security issues, now at the center of
criticisms of the United Nations, the report again drew a
distinction between what the secretary-general can accomplish and
what problems lie beyond his capacity to solve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the senior management group and executive committee
on peace and security have helped unify policy and integrate
planning for the U.N.'s peace operations,'' the report said,
``these reform initiatives do not address the overall capacity of
the United Nations to manage, logistically support and respond to
rapid changes in the demand for and scope of peace operations
required by member states.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Accounting Office surveyors said they were told by
both U.N. officials and member nations that the organization,
constrained financially in the face of increasing demands for
services , ``does not have the capability to manage the scope and
scale of activity.''
</P>
<P>
   The report praises the U.N. mission in East Timor as an example
of a mission fielded relatively quickly and efficiently because of
good planning. In other missions, in the Mideast and Central
America, however, the study found less satisfactory coordination at
lower levels, particularly between the U. N. peacekeeping and
political departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooperation is not enough,'' the report said. ``Integration of
efforts on a daily basis from these departments is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, ``United Nations: Reform Initiatives Have
Strengthened Operations, But Overall Objectives Have Not Yet Been
Achieved,'' May 2000, is published by the U.S. General Accounting
Office and information is available on the World Wide Web at
www.gao.gov.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
