<HEADER>
A8190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      05-28 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS WILL TRY TO DOUSE KNICKS' FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers want to squeeze life from the New York Knicks
Monday in Game 4 of the Eastern Conference finals at Madison Square
Garden. If they can push a 2-1 series lead into a 3-1 advantage,
the Pacers believe the Knicks could become breathless,
introspective and numb.
</P>
<P>
   Which is how the Pacers felt after losing Game 3 at the Garden
on Saturday. A three-game lead in the best-of-7 series was there to
be swiped, the Pacers said, but they slipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of beating up on them and taking the life out of them,
we gave them life,'' Pacers forward Dale Davis said. ``And, you
know, they can take a little life and make a big thing out of it.
They have a history of performing some miracles.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers forward Austin Croshere said: ``We always seem to bounce
back when we have to. This is a game where we have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Pacers coach Larry Bird talked about how his team led Game 3 by
a point at halftime, during which he talked to his team about
taking away the Knicks' life, bounce and spirit. He said his team
could put the Knicks ``in a whole world of hurt.'' But the Knicks _
without Patrick Ewing and Marcus Camby because of injuries _
heartily inhaled and exhaled with playoff highs from Latrell
Sprewell (32 points) and Allan Houston (28 points) that helped foil
the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave them life,'' said Bird, who canceled practice Sunday
but watched film and talked strategy with his team. ``And now it's
going to be a battle, a war. I've never come to Madison Square
Garden and heard a crowd as soft as they were. And I'll never see
it again.''
</P>
<P>
   That is because Bird believes the Knicks and their fans have new
life.
</P>
<P>
   And yet both teams keep the same mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still in control of this series,'' Indiana's Jalen Rose
said. ``We win two more games, and we're in the NBA finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis added: ``Their heels are still against the wall. We're
still the same team that got the No. 1 seed in the East.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird and his players must keep that as their focus.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers enter Game 4 Monday pondering three key elements: How
to keep a hot hand going, how to negate Sprewell and Houston and
how to jolt their bench.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers center Rik Smits scored 21 points in the first half of
Game 3 but only four in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their defense was good, but I think we had a lot of guys that
wanted to get involved in things and that's our offense,'' Smits
said about his fancy start and dull finish. ``I have no idea this
time if Patrick Ewing will play, and it really doesn't matter. We
want to concentrate on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, of course it matters. The Knicks play more half-court
basketball with Ewing, who can give Smits trouble on both ends.
Without him they are more loose on the perimeter and they run more,
allowing Sprewell and Houston to slash.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get 21 points in the first half it is not a guaranteed
blueprint to get 21 in the second,'' forward Sam Perkins said of
Smits' flip-flop game. ``But you should get more touches. And when
the team starts doing things that are not working, well, you just
have to know the game, know your plan. That's what the Knicks did.
They went to things working for them _ Sprewell and Houston _ and
we didn't and couldn't stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird said: ``Rik couldn't get a 40-point game because we stopped
throwing him the ball and started moving side to side. I knew we
were in trouble at the start of the second half when there were two
loose balls on the floor and we didn't get either one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that Sprewell and Houston can light it up and we will
mix it up on them if they get going. It is a matter of showing up
and playing. Everybody talks about doubling those guys, but all I
visualize when we start talking about doubling them is Larry
Johnson wide open under the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers kept finding themselves in one-on-one situations with
Sprewell and Houston, and too often for the Pacers they lost the
matchups. Both players are exceptional at forcing switches and
sizing up defenders before slashing toward the basket or taking a
quick shot. Indiana appears to have decided, especially late in
Game 4, to double both players to take the ball out of their hands
in the final critical moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually play better every other day,'' Bird said. ``I
expect our team and especially our bench to come back and play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   With vigor. With the sole purpose of extinguishing the Knicks'
new life. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
