</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST TWO WOMEN STARTING INDY 500 HAVE AN ENTANGLED MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The historic moment was brief Sunday, only 74
laps long until the first two women to start the Indianapolis 500
left the race under their own power, their cars varying degrees of
mangled, their hopes crushed.
</P>
<P>
   They were an unlikely twosome _ 53-year-old Lyn St. James, the
oldest in the field of 33, making her seventh start, from the last
row, and the 19-year-old rookie Sarah Fisher, who had qualified
19th, in the seventh row.
</P>
<P>
   All week long, Fisher had downplayed the milestone, and tried to
separate herself from St. James, who had her beginning racing stock
cars, was not running in the Indy Racing League and did not have
the same solid open-wheel background as Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   But Fisher could not separate herself from St. James Sunday
afternoon going into Turn 1, the two entangling and subsequently
crashing into the wall. ``Of course I'm very disappointed,'' Fisher
said, then added about the two women unintentionally taking each
other out of the race: ``It's not ironic. We're just two race-car
drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   St. James, who was lapped in the 11th lap by the eventual
winner, Juan Montoya, was running two laps behind Fisher, driving
defensively with her mirrors because she had trouble handling her
car.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher, in 23rd place overall, was approaching Turn 1, coming up
on the inside of St. James. But Fisher's fellow rookie, Jaques
Lazier, tried to pass Fisher on her inside and squeezed her in a
space not built for three cars as the three drivers headed into the
turn.
</P>
<P>
   St. James, trying to avoid the wall, came down into Fisher, and
then bumped off the car right into the wall, her right-side pod
severing off and catapulting into the sky. Fisher followed next and
clipped her right side on the wall, damaging her suspension, but
not much else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a car coming behind me into Turn 1,'' said St. James,
who did not know that it was Fisher's at the time. ``I took a
defensive line but wanted to stay out of the loose stuff. Whoever
it was, I was surprised they would try to force a pass at that
point. I'm extremely disappointed it happened, but I'm even more
disappointed it happened under those circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's team owner, Derrick Walker, saw the Indy sandwich occur
differently. He cited St. James' slow speed, but put more blame on
Lazier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lynn was running really really slow, it looked like she was
running with a boat anchor hanging off the back,'' Walker said.
``Sarah was closing around her so quick she had to pass her. I
don't know who the clown on the inside was. Lazier? Well, Lazier
made two coming into the turn into three. That squeezed her. Only a
third into the race, it was a bonehead move to make two going into
three into the corner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll kill the son of a gun,'' Fisher screamed into her headset
to her team members as she came to a stop, and like St. James,
needed a tow back to the garage. Then she was upset with herself.
``She apologized for screwing up,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's anybody fault,'' Fisher said later, back in
her garage as her mechanics tried to see if they could repair the
suspension in time to get her back out on the track. They could
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was stuck in the middle,'' Fisher said. ``I was a sitting
duck in this case. When you're passing three abreast, it doesn't
happen very nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Fisher downplayed the connection with St. James, when
Fisher was 15, she attended a five-day driving camp run by St.
James, after which the participants could race go-karts, already
two levels below her. Fisher said it was it a waste of time. ``It
wasn't really helpful for me at that point in my career,'' she said
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was what happened Sunday. Officially, Fisher was 31st, St.
James, 32nd, and the pole-sitter, Greg Ray, who crashed into the
wall in Lap 66, last. Fisher had been battling engine problems on
two of her pit stops, but still controlled the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarah Fisher could have finished this 500 race and could have
benefited from that experience to come back here,'' Walker said.
``Really, she has nothing to be ashamed about. She did everything
right.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
