<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LAD     05-28 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-ROYALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PUT POWER ON HIGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Brian Cooper gave the Anaheim Angels
something they hadn't had in more than a month, but their bats did
something no Angels team had ever done, and together, it resulted
in an 8-4 victory over the Kansas City Royals on Sunday before
23,645 at Kauffman Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper became the first Angels starter since Scott Schoeneweis
on April 26 to throw eight innings. But what made Cooper a winner
was the Angels outburst in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of five hitters, the Angels hit four home runs, the
first time in club history they've hit four in an inning. Their 48
homers in May are the most in club history for any month.
</P>
<P>
   Darin Erstad, who had four hits in the game, hit the first one,
a three-run homer off Royals starter Miguel Batista. After Adam
Kennedy flied out, Mo Vaughn, Tim Salmon and Garret Anderson hit
consecutive homers, turning what had been a 2-0 deficit into a 6-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Up to then, Cooper had been a little erratic. But the runs gave
him what he needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was outstanding,'' said Cooper, who is 2-0 with a 3.21 ERA
in two starts since being called up May 22. ``We were losing 2-0,
and I hadn't found it yet. But we got those runs and that's what
started it for me. We got that lead, and I went right after them. I
got three quick outs, and it got my timing down, and I hit a groove
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   An outing like Cooper's was needed to give rest to an Angels
bullpen that's been used a lot lately. In his eight innings, Cooper
gave up three runs (one earned) and six hits with four strikeouts
and one walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``A pitching performance like that never comes at a bad time,''
Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``But the last couple of weeks
with the condition of our starters, the bullpen's just taken the
ball and really been stretched out. For him to do that, that's
huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper gave up an RBI single to Joe Randa in the second inning,
and it turned out to be the only earned run he allowed all day.
Mike Sweeney reached on third baseman Troy Glaus' throwing error in
the third inning and came around to score on a single by Jermaine
Dye. In the eighth, shortstop Keith Luuloa's throwing error led to
another unearned run.
</P>
<P>
   But when the defense was good behind him, Cooper was too.
Between Brian Johnson's one-out single in the fourth and the error
by Luuloa leading off the eighth, Cooper retired 11 consecutive
batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty much what I strive for every game, finding that
groove,'' Cooper said. ``Typically for me it doesn't start until
later in the game. But the way I consider it, once I find it, it's
game-over. I'm full of confidence. I don't feel like I'll be
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Royals still had a chance in the ninth inning
after Cooper was out of the game. The Royals have won 12 games in
their final at-bat this season and they put a scare Sunday into the
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Fyhrie and Mike Holtz combined to allow one run and four
hits when Scioscia brought in Shigetoshi Hasegawa with the bases
loaded and one out. Carlos Febles came up representing the tying
run, but Hasegawa got him to hit into a game-ending double play. It
was Hasegawa's second save of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Batista (2-3) held the Angels to four singles through four
innings, but the Angels bats erupted in the fifth. The four home
runs drove in all six runs, but the inning was started by a walk
and a perfect hit-and-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck led off with a walk and took off for second on a
pitch to Luuloa. Luuloa hit a grounder to the shortstop's spot
vacated by Luis Ordaz, who went to cover second. Walbeck went to
third on the play, then scored on Erstad's three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some guys slugging,'' said Vaughn, whose 18 homers
lead the American League. ``These guys can hurt you if you make
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad got his fourth hit of the day in the eighth, driving in
two runs with a bloop single. His 82 hits lead the majors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
