<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PACERS FADE WITH THE GARDEN CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a lazy Sunday afternoon, a few Indiana Pacers
players trickled into Madison Square Garden for a light
shoot-around Sunday. Larry Bird had called in the team to watch
film but had given them a day off from practice.
</P>
<P>
   With a crucial Game 4 with the Knicks coming up Monday, a
difficult loss in Game 3 to digest, Bird figured a day of
relaxation and contemplation in New York would serve his team well.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Davis sat in a chair on the sideline surrounded by the news
media, Rik Smits, who played an unaccustomed 40 minutes on Saturday
_ and looked it _ draped himself over a couple of chairs. Mark
Jackson filed out to the floor and held court, then Reggie Miller
sat down under a basket.
</P>
<P>
   Game 3, and the Knicks' 98-95 victory, was hashed and rehashed.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Perkins, the Pacers' 38-year-old sage, sat on a table and
lamented Saturday's loss. ``Yesterday's game was a winable game,''
Perkins said. ``We only led by one point at intermission but we
played well, we showed them that we could play well, we could beat
them here, and 3-0 sounds a lot better than 2-1. You have to finish
a team like this when you get the chance because you know how the
Knicks are.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he meant, Perkins smiled. ``Anything can happen in
this building,'' he said. ``Yesterday Spree is shooting a shot that
has no chance of going in, they call a foul on Reggie that bails
him out. Last year you had the 4-point play. And just all the other
stuff.'' Off by center court Larry Bird, the Pacers coach _ and, as
it turns out, their most consistent money player _ held court.
</P>
<P>
   In all the analysis of the game, Bird picked up on something
that only a bird truly might see. From a height and distance, with
a panoramic vantage point, he talked about an opportunity lost in a
crucial Game 3, with Indiana leading the series by 2-0. Patrick
Ewing was injured, in street clothes, Marcus Camby slipped on the
court and fell and was eventually wheeled out of the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Bird watched his team disintegrate. Poor shots, bad shots; bad
calls exaggerated by Miller's chirping at the officials. But this
was not what Bird picked up on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers missed a subtle signal on Saturday that the Knicks
were out of emotional steam. Some Pacers players were too young to
pick it up. A veteran like Smits was too old to do anything about
it, a player like Miller was too self-absorbed to notice. Bird was
not talking about a missed shot or a bad pass, a loose ball the
Pacers did not grab, Bird was referring to the Knicks crowd. The
fans. They were gone.
</P>
<P>
   At a critical point in the game, Bird felt an odd stillness fall
over the Garden. He thought back on all the games he had played in
this building as a Celtic, going back to 1979. He had never felt
this before. Not from the never-say-die Knicks. The spirit was
gone. The energy that usually leads a Knicks rally, the electricity
that shoots through the corridors and up to the rafters. Gone.
``I've never heard a Garden crowd as soft as this one was
yesterday,'' Bird said.
</P>
<P>
   For someone like Bird, a basketball artist who prided himself on
precision when he played, the choice of words was revealing.
</P>
<P>
   He did not say the Garden was flat. He did not say the crowd was
quiet. Or worried or drained of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Bird referred to the Knicks crowd as he might refer to an
opposing center he planned to attack. He said the Garden crowd was
soft. He thought the Pacers could make their comeback and get away
without having to tear through the emotional concentration of
Knicks fans in the Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a great opportunity,'' Bird said Sunday. ``It was so
important to get that game yesterday. Now we play them again and
it's going to be a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The Madison Square Garden crowd may have fallen silent with
Camby's loss, but Indiana faded along with them. ``That's been our
three-year pattern,'' Bird said. ``We play well with our backs
against the wall when things aren't going well, but when things are
going well, we can't close it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose walked out of the building Sunday afternoon when
someone asked how he felt a loss would affect the Pacers. His face
tightened. ``We're not going to lose this series,'' he said. ``I
don't care what anyone says. We're going to win this series.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach was not so sure. ``It's not about X's and O's at this
point,'' Bird said. ``It's a matter of showing up and playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird joked about the Garden crowd and said he hoped the spirit
would somehow stay away Monday. He realized the Pacers had a one
game pass and had blown it. Another missed opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never heard the Garden so soft before,'' Bird said ``I
guarantee you, I'll never hear it again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
