<HEADLINE>
BELCHER TO TRY IT AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Pitcher Tim Belcher will begin a rehab
assignment Saturday at Triple-A Edmonton, and the Anaheim Angels
hope he'll be in the starting rotation around June 13 when the club
begins a three-game series at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Belcher had offseason surgery to repair a torn muscle in his
right elbow and was expected back in early May. But he had a
setback when on a rehab assignment and had to stop throwing for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much better this time than when I went out (on a rehab
assignment) the last time,'' Belcher said. ``I thought I felt good
last time. But I thought I'd always have stiffness and soreness the
rest of my career. Now I've got nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The recovery process has been a difficult one for Belcher, who
before last season never had any elbow problems his entire career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating, tiring,'' he said. ``You have to be
real patient, which is not my strong suit, relative to baseball or
life in general. So it's been tough. One thing that's helped is
being a starting pitcher. Even when you're healthy, you're sitting
and watching 80 percent of the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding a healthy Belcher figures to help a rotation that is
inexperienced. The current rotation consists of three pitchers -
Brian Cooper, Jarrod Washburn and Seth Etherton (who began this
season in the minors), and a fourth - Scott Schoeneweis - who is in
his first big-league season as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   The other starter - Kent Bottenfield - hasn't won in his past
four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's everything he's billed to be,'' manager Mike Scioscia
said. ``He's a great competitor, he knows the game, and he knows
how to get hitters out.''
</P>
<P>
   Subpar pitching: Bottenfield was an All-Star and an 18-game
winner for the St. Louis Cardinals last season, but he has only
three wins in 11 starts this season and none in his past four
starts.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bottenfield earned the victory with 6 scoreless innings
May 5 against Seattle, he is 0-2 with a 7.33 ERA in four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not where he should be,'' Scioscia said. ``I think now
he's trying too hard and his mechanics are off. It's something he
went through last year. His rhythm is a little off, but this guy's
for real. He'll settle in, I have no worries there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
