<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TAIWAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA PROSCRIBES PRESS FROM NAMING TAIWAN'S PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In the best-selling children's series Harry Potter,
there is a character so disturbing that Harry's friends refer to
him only as ``He Who Must Not Be Named'' _ as if pronouncing the
name ``Voldemort'' would somehow solidify the demon's existence.
</P>
<P>
   President Chen Shui-bian of Taiwan is clearly China's Voldemort.
</P>
<P>
   Since his election in March, China's state-controlled press has
been filled with reporting about Taiwan and its new government. The
papers have parsed the new president's every sentence and analyzed
his administration's intentions in minute detail.
</P>
<P>
   But in this daily cascade of print, there are several words that
have practically never appeared, forbidden by government order:
``Chen Shui-bian,'' the new leader's name, and the word
``president.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, reporters and editorial writers have had to fall back
on a handful of government approved circumlocutions, all designed
to dance around the fact that the man they call, for example, ``the
new leader of the Taiwan authority'' was, after all, democratically
elected the island's president.
</P>
<P>
   ``No media outlets are allowed to use his name, at all,'' said a
Beijing journalist. ``And even though so many articles are written
about Taiwan, we can't write what we like. Papers are only allowed
to print what the central government has agreed upon.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, words in the Chinese press are carefully chosen _ or
omitted _ and carry political messages. Discussions of sensitive
subjects routinely involve a state-sanctioned vocabulary and
punctuation. And few topics are more sensitive than Taiwan, which
Beijing regards as a breakaway province that must, by force if
necessary, eventually be reunited with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   And so ``Taiwanese independence,'' for example, always appears
in quotation marks, indicating that the author recognizes the
error, even absurdity, of the phrase. The election of Chen, whose
Democratic Progressive Party has in the past supported
independence, has caused particular consternation.
</P>
<P>
   But even many Chinese journalists are perplexed at the decision
not to name Chen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see why they wouldn't want to use the term `president,'
since we don't recognize Taiwan as a country,'' said a Chinese
reporter. ``But not to use his name? Everybody here knows about
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Chinese government seems to want to eliminate any
concrete evidence of Taiwan's boisterous election and of Chen's
euphoric inauguration earlier this month. State television carried
no images of the events. And, although Chen's inauguration speech
was carefully dissected in every major Chinese newspaper, none have
actually carried the text. Within hours, however, copies were
circulating on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Chang Huei-mei, a Taiwanese pop star also known as A-mei who is
wildly popular here, followed Chen into the realm of the
unmentionable. After the singer performed at Chen's swearing-in
ceremony, China's state broadcast stations and newspapers were told
they could no longer use advertisements for Sprite soft drinks that
feature her, though they had been used the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   Chen's name has appeared in the major state-controlled news only
once since he announced his candidacy last fall. On March 18, the
day of Chen's election, the state-run New China News Agency issued
a two-sentence report: ``This evening the electoral activities for
the leadership of the Taiwan region concluded. The DPP candidate
Chen Shui-bian won 39.3 percent, the independent candidate James
Soong won 36.84 percent, and the KMT candidate Lien Chan won 23.1
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The press here refers to other Taiwan politicians directly and
frequently, including the former president, Lee Teng-hui, and
Chen's vice president, Lu Hsiu-lien _ though invariably to heap
scorn and criticism on them. The Beijing press referred to Lee
during his tenure term as the ``so-called president.''
</P>
<P>
   Lu has been as outspoken in her support of Taiwanese
independence as Chen has been circumspect on this issue. At a
recent briefing for foreign journalists, a Chinese official
explaned their policy for not naming Chen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lee Teng-hui and Lu Hsiu-lien are die-hard separatists and
incurable in this regard, so we name them,'' he said. But as for
Chen, ``We will heed his word and his acts, so we try to
distinguish him from the others.''
</P>
<P>
   A former official of the Chinese Communist Party's propaganda
department explained that the decision made a certain sense in
terms of the norms of propaganda, and keeping options open as
relations with Taiwan's new leadership evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chen is the elected leader and China must deal with him,'' he
said. ``When the government is conducting a propaganda offensive,
if it names the target, then the target has entered a `blacklist'
and it's nearly impossible to back off the condemnation. So by
keeping Chen's name out of it _ it seems silly and childish _ but
it's a way of keeping room for maneuver.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a few others, these days, who enjoy this status _
often someone whose spirit is ever-present and intensely
threatening to the government, but whose name is never mentioned in
the state press.
</P>
<P>
   A notable example is Zhao Ziyang, the former Communist Party
leader who was deposed in 1989 after he expressed sympathy for
student protesters. Still popular after a decade of house arrest,
Zhao is China's ultimate Voldemort.
</P>
<P>
   But Zhao is out of the news, and Chen at its center. So a few
tabloids have recently defied government policy and printed Chen's
name _ when it seemed too absurd not to.
</P>
<P>
   Some journalists suggest that another reason why the Chinese
authorities forbid the use of Chen's name is that they cannot
decide what honorific to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ```Mr. Chen' _ that sounds too polite,'' said one journalist.
``And of course, `President Chen' is out of the question. So what
we've arrived at for now is to just call him `the new leader of the
region of Taiwan.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
