<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Rangers received six players from the Detroit
Tigers in the Juan Gonzalez trade. There's no guarantee any of them
will play in the three-game series with the Tigers that starts
tonight at Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   The rundown:
</P>
<P>
   Frank Catalanotto, who is limited to pinch-hitter duty because
of a strained groin muscle, said he's ready to return to the field.
Manager Johnny Oates said he hasn't been told that. Either way,
Catalanotto is still a reserve behind Luis Alicea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to getting back in the lineup,''
Catalanotto said. ``But that's a decision Johnny has to make. I'm
not going to hang my head if he doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler will not play in the series. He is sidelined with a
strained hip flexor muscle, and his return is not imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm really disappointed,'' Kapler said. ``It's like an
intensity deep inside of me. It's just my competitive nature. It's
not a revenge thing or a hate thing. Most of those guys over there
I like and I'm close friends with. It's not a spiteful, negative
thing. It's like a sibling rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Reliever Francisco Cordero remains an important member of the
Rangers' bullpen, but his appearances depend on the Rangers
starters.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve catcher Bill Haselman started yesterday. Having done
that and given Ivan Rodriguez a day off, it's unlikely Haselman
will start in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Thompson is out for the season with a torn rotator cuff.
General manager Doug Melvin got another grim reminder of his
absence when he learned Thompson's 1.48 earned-run average in
interleague play over the past three years is the lowest in the
majors. The Rangers begin interleague play Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed pitcher Alan Webb is 0-4 with an 11.72 ERA for
Double-A Tulsa.  &QL; 
Greer responds
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Greer returned to the Rangers' starting lineup and went
0-4 yesterday. But he had a double as a pinch hitter in Friday's
game, and manager Johnny Oates took notice when he saw Greer
``explode ''around first base. That reassured Oates that Greer's
ankle surgery has helped restore some of the speed he has been
losing over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, he was the fastest guy in our camp until we
got \RTom\S Goodwin,'' Oates said.''I don't think it's been that
way for a while and even Rusty didn't know how bad it was. He was
all right running the bases, but when he had to round a base, or in
the outfield curve after a ball, the ankle wouldn't let him.''  &QL; 
Oliver fine
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver was examined by Minnesota Twins physician Dan Buss
during yesterday's game and was cleared to pitch in Wednesday's
game against the Detroit Tigers. Oliver complained of a dead arm in
his last start against the Twins, but Buss saw nothing wrong with
his shoulder yesterday.  &QL; 
Hitting slumps
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Palmeiro went 0-for-3 yesterday and is 2-for-22 on the
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm struggling,'' Palmeiro said. ``It's tough to go through
something like this. I'm trying to do all I can to be productive.
I'm in the middle of the lineup. For us to be successful, I have to
be successful. I need to get big hits and they're not coming.''  &QL; 
He's not alone
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Royce Clayton struck out three times yesterday and has
two hits in his past 25 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lamb has one hit in his past 17 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Jason McDonald, who struck out to end the game, is hitless in
his past 16 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Mateo has six hits in his past 35 at-bats.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Bill Haselman started for Ivan Rodriguez yesterday at catcher.
The Twins stole two bases in the first three innings and both
runners scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are 7-10 in day games.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
