<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-GONZALEZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PAY CALL ON GONZALEZ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The parting seems permanent. Juan Gonzalez has no
interest in re-signing with the Rangers and general manager Doug
Melvin remains convinced it's not wise to commit $10-15 million to
one player.
</P>
<P>
   That was the overriding reason why Melvin traded Gonzalez to the
Detroit Tigers on Nov. 2 in a nine-player trade that brought
outfielder Gabe Kapler, infielder Frank Catalanotto, catcher Bill
Haselman and pitchers Justin Thompson, Francisco Cordero and Alan
Webb to the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   In Melvin's mind, that reasoning remains valid, especially
because Gonzalez declined an eight-year, $140 million offer from
the Tigers in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see that, you feel sort of glad we made the
decision,'' Melvin said. ``It confirms what we feel. I still
haven't been sold on the fact of paying that kind of money a player
like him would command.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez and the Rangers will be reunited today, but only in
that they'll be in the same ballpark for the first time since the
trade. The Rangers open a three-game series with the Tigers tonight
at Comerica Park, and for the first time, they'll be looking at
Gonzalez in the opposite dugout. It seems destined to remain that
way for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez was terse and to the point with Detroit reporters
yesterday when asked if he thought there was a chance of re-signing
with the Rangers when he becomes a free agent at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For what?'' Gonzalez said. ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   It's highly unlikely he would be given the opportunity. Melvin
is becoming more and more convinced that teams with one player
making more than $10 million have a difficult time assembling the
complete team needed to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that a number of players making more than $10
million failed to make the playoffs last year, including Gary
Sheffield and Kevin Brown with the Dodgers, Sammy Sosa with the
Cubs, Larry Walker with the Rockies, Barry Bonds with the Giants
and Albert Belle with the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a knock on the player,'' Melvin said. ``You need
depth, you need pitching depth. That's what \RYankees general
manager\S Brian Cashman was telling me they're struggling with, now
that they're having to pay Derek Jeter, Bernie Williams and Mariano
Rivera a lot of money. They can't afford the kind of depth they
used to have.'' talked about it, paying a guy more than $10
million.'']
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his reunion with his former teammates, Gonzalez
said, ``I'll see my friends, say hello and that's about it. I don't
have any friends between the lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Ivan Rodriguez, who has known Gonzalez longer than
anybody with the Rangers, said: ``I'm sure he's going to play very
hard. He'll probably be excited to play against us for the first
time. I'm looking forward to seeing him again.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has a strained planter fascia in his left foot and will
probably be limited to designated-hitter duties during the
three-game series.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
