r s BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX     05-28 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Stars winger Jamie Langenbrunner missed the
last two games of the Western Conference Finals after spraining his
right knee early in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock sounded less convinced yesterday than
Saturday that Langenbrunner would be able to play tomorrow in Game
1 of the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really day to day,'' Hitchcock said yesterday. ``He's a
question mark to play in Game 1. If he can't feel comfortable,
there's no point in going out there. What we don't want to do is
have him go out there for one game and then be out for the rest of
the series.''
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brenden Morrow returned a week after he fractured
his right ankle in Game 1 of the Western Conference Finals, and
defenseman Richard Matvichuk played in Game 7 on Saturday after
suffering a concussion in Game 6 two nights earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars would love to see Langenbrunner back in their lineup
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to put any pressure on Jamie, but if he can get
back and play, that's a plus for our team,'' Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk said.  &QL; 
Remembering Richard
</P>
<P>
   Stars center Guy Carbonneau grew up under the influence of
Maurice ``Rocket'' Richard. So, naturally, he was mourning the
NHL's and Quebec's loss after Richard died Saturday at the age of
78.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a chance to watch him play. But I had a chance to
meet him a lot when I was in Montreal,'' Carbonneau said. ``For me,
he was an ambassador. He was one of the best hockey players in the
world. He was just living hockey every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Richard, Stars forward Kirk Muller once was the Canadiens'
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew about him before I arrived in Montreal, and once I got
there I realized that of all the great players Montreal's been
fortunate enough to have, he was the elite of them all,'' Muller
said. ``He was a super person. It will be tough for that whole
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller wore Richard's old No. 9 during the All-Star game in
Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me over afterward and said, `You're a Hab, right?' I
said yeah. He goes, `You're wearing No. 9.' I said yeah. He said,
`Don't make it a habit.' I still don't know to this day whether he
was serious about it or not.''  &QL; 
Back to Jersey
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' Stanley Cup Finals series against New Jersey is
somewhat of a homecoming for Kirk Muller, who played his first
seven NHL seasons with the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seven years is the longest time I have ever been with any one
team, and it brings back memories going back,'' Muller said. ``It
will be interesting the feelings going in there for the Stanley Cup
Finals.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Muller's friends, defenseman Ken Daneyko, still plays
with New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually grew up with Kenny,'' Muller said. ``I started my
career with him and spent seven years with him and lived with him,
and he's still plugging along. We still talk a little bit. When you
have that kind of past with a guy you want to stay in touch with
them.''  &QL; 
Ouch
</P>
<P>
   Richard Matvichuk still was feeling the effects of his
concussion Friday night as he watched Flyers forward Eric Lindros
suffer yet another concussion, on an open-ice check from New
Jersey's Scott Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was two physical teams, but you never want to see a player
get hit like that,'' Matvichuk said. ``It could be a career-ending
injury. ... It's one of those things where it's a physical game.
You've got guys that are 6 feet now that can skate like the wind
and shoot like there's no tomorrow. Of course, there are going to
be injuries. But you never want to see anybody get hit like that.''
 &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Stars winger Brenden Morrow has played in plenty of Game 7s in
his hockey career. The only problem is none of them were in the
NHL. So was he nervous? ``A little bit,'' he said. ``OK, a lot
bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were 6-for-29 on the power play in the Western
Conference Finals, including 2-for-4 in Game 7, and they held
Colorado to 3-for-30 for the series, including 0-for-3 with only
four shots in Game 7. Colorado did not score on its last 18
power-play chances.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars improved their record in Game 7s to 5-5, and Ed
Belfour improved to 4-0 in Game 7s.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
