<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE TAKES A POUNDING INSIDE FROM METS' RUSCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ No player with as many career home runs as Mark
McGwire has homered with such frequency. If you are a pitcher,
sooner or later, the St. Louis Cardinals' first baseman will get
you. He took Glendon Rusch deep two years ago, on a pitch Rusch
tried to throw inside but left in the middle of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch threw inside to McGwire again Sunday, as he did to many of
the Cardinals. It was an effective strategy, and it produced a 6-2
victory for Rusch and the Mets, who swept the first-place Cardinals
and have won eight of their last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Rusch, who had been given an average of fewer than two runs per
start this year, finally received some run support, and he didn't
waste it. The left-hander worked seven innings, allowing two runs
on five hits and walking one to improve to 2-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say the ball is juiced, but I think the hitters have
caught up to the pitchers' pattern,'' said catcher Todd Pratt. ``We
like to pitch middle-away now, and no one pitches inside
consistently anymore. If they do, they can't consistently throw
strikes inside. As hitters, we know we're going to get our pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, Glendon just kept on pounding inside and pounding
inside. When they thought he was going to go away, he came back
inside.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Zeile, Edgardo Alfonzo and Pratt had homered off Darryl
Kile to give Rusch a 4-1 lead by the time he faced McGwire with a
runner on first and no outs in the fourth. Pratt never moved his
glove as Rusch froze McGwire with an 89 mile-per-hour fastball.
McGwire moved his body as if the ball had come too far inside, but
the pitch was an obvious third strike.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went 1 for 4 Sunday and was 3 for 11 in the series, with
no home runs. Every other team that has faced McGwire three times
this year has allowed at least one home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to stay in on him and tie him up,'' Rusch said.
``He's an unbelievable hitter, as far as getting to a lot of
pitches. Fortunately, he didn't beat me today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusch said he tries to take the same aggressive approach no
matter the score. But pitching with a lead, which Rusch hadn't done
in four starts, helped make him more aggressive, he said. It is an
idea impressed on him by Mets left-hander Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   This is Rusch's fourth major league season, but he said he feels
like a rookie. ``That's good for me,'' said the 25-year-old Rusch.
``It keeps me open-minded and helps me be a sponge.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Rusch, Leiter is left-handed, but the similarities end
there. Leiter is a hard thrower who works inside to hitters; Rusch
throws softer and usually to the outside part of the plate. But
Rusch has sought out Leiter and the Mets' other veteran
left-handers for advice, and Leiter told him he can make his
outside pitches better by letting hitters know he can also come in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Act like this little bump out here is mine, and I'm going
right after you,'' Leiter said he told Rusch. ``You don't have to
throw 95 miles per hour to be intimidating.''
</P>
<P>
   Rusch gave way to John Franco in the eighth inning, and Armando
Benitez finished off the Cardinals with a five-pitch, 1-2-3 ninth.
The victory completed the Mets' second consecutive weekend sweep of
a first-place team; last week at Shea Stadium, they took three in a
row from the National League West-leading Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are 12-5 against teams that currently have a winning
record; they are 16-17 in all other games. The Mets' only losses in
their last 10 games have been one-run defeats to the San Diego
Padres, a last-place club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to make sure we don't take anything for
granted,'' said Todd Zeile, who had two homers Saturday and was 3
for 4 Sunday. ``We should have won at least one of the ball games
in San Diego. We let a couple of games get away from us when we
were flat. I don't think we were flat here at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
