u a BC-NY-CENTRAL-PARK-ART-1     05-28 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CENTRAL-PARK-ART-1060(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLASH OF CULTURES AS OFFICIALS STRIVE TO KEEP PARK LUXURIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Central Park is gorgeous right now _ moist and lush
and shimmering with health. Especially breathtaking are the thick,
deep green lawns, the dust bowls of a few years ago, that cost
millions of dollars to restore.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the anticipated number of visitors this year is up to
20 million _ an increase of at least 5 million over the last few
years. No wonder so many of them want to treat it like a vastly
superior extension of a backyard, lolling on the grass and walking
dogs. Jogging and roller-skating. Strumming guitars and beating
drums.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, messing the place up. Littering, making noise
and trampling the exquisite grass. The problem with the lovely new
Central Park is that people love it so much. Before, when it was
considered dangerous and rundown, it was not such a big deal that
musicians amplified their sound or soccer players tore up the grass
with their cleats or dog owners did not always clean up.
</P>
<P>
   But now, after spending $250 million on the park _ mostly money
raised by the Central Park Conservancy, founded in 1980 and now one
of New York's most prestigious philanthropies _ the city is getting
fussy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was a shambles, it didn't really matter what you did
on it,'' said Henry Stern, the parks and recreation commissioner.
``For a long time, the rules were ignored. But now, after 20 years
and millions of dollars, we have a safe park, a clean park, a nice
park, and keeping it like that means some restrictions.''
</P>
<P>
   And some resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I refer to it as a grass museum,'' said David Gibson, who has
two children in the West Side Soccer League, an after-school
program that had to bus children to Wards Island while Central
Park's North Meadow was restored. Marc Freedman, president of the
league, said he feared that its 3,500 children ages 5 to 15 would
not be able to return to the park, given the heavy competition for
slots on the playing fields. ``The Conservancy is not as friendly
toward kids' sports,'' he said. ``I want to have beautiful grass
for the kids to play on, but for me priority is for kids to play.
For them, the priority is nice, green grass.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's other priority seems to be enforcing long-ignored
rules.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are not new. Musicians have long been forbidden to be
too noisy or to use loudspeakers without permission. Permits have
long been required for gatherings of 20 or more people, as well as
bonds that can be revoked if the area is not properly cleaned up.
It has always been illegal to litter or to let dogs run free
outside official runs.
</P>
<P>
   But this spring, the city is clamping down. First, there were
the wars over leashing dogs. Signs announcing $100 fines for
littering are soon to go up. And this month, the city has been
ordering the park's musicians and dancers to lower the volume and
perform less often.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like the Jazz Blues Ensemble and David Ippolito, who calls
himself That Guitar Man, have been playing in the same spots for
years, acquiring loyal fans and even becoming minor tourist
attractions. Others, like the skaters who dance to amplified rock
music and the African drummers at Bethesda Fountain, provide the
kind of colorful scenes that New Yorkers and tourists _ some of
them, anyway _ say makes the city vibrant and worth visiting.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Kaufman, a Central Park Conservancy official, who was at
Bethesda Fountain on Saturday trying to disperse the drummers,
said: ``We've made the park beautiful. ``Now we want to to make it
beautiful to all the senses, including hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   But fans of the music say it raises their spirits and creates a
rare, precious urban community.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what's best about New York,'' said Lynn Walsh, a
secretary who has been gathering with about 20 other drummers at
the fountain for six years. ``This park, the outdoors, the beauty.
Most of all the feeling of love.''
</P>
<P>
   The city says there are numerous complaints about the drumming
every year. A few weeks ago, police officers ordered the drummers
to stop playing and confiscated seven African drums.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York
Civil Liberties Union, turned up at Bethesda Fountain to try to
work out a compromise that would let the drummers play. ``Usually,
we sue,'' said Siegel. ``But this time we're trying to mediate.
This is a great park and we don't need ugly scenes.'' He added that
Kaufman and other conservancy officials were not supposed to make
policy or enforce park regulations, and complained that Kaufman
appeared to be doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   The issues that are tugging at Central Park today _ noisy music
versus peace and quiet, lawn as landscape versus lawn as carpet,
orderliness vs. freedom _ were controversial from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   When Frederick Law Olmsted, the park's legendary creator,
inaugurated free band concerts in 1859, there was ``great
resistance,' '' said Witold Rybczynski, author of ``A Clearing in
the Distance,'' a biography of Olmsted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally tens of thousands of people went,'' Rybczynski said
in an interview. ``But for a long time they weren't allowed to sit
on the grass. Rich people would sit in their carriages. Everybody
else had to stand.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Central Park ``looks like nature,'' visitors often
forget they are in a fragile, artificial environment, he said.
``People think they're in the country and, within limits, are free
to do what they want. It feels wrong to have rules _ it looks so
natural, like the Garden of Eden. But the park is very delicate. If
people all start walking on grass or littering, that's it. Sound
can really carry and spoil things for other people.''
</P>
<P>
   But balancing the enforcement of park rules is equally delicate,
he said. Being too lenient can result in visitors' impinging on one
another and damaging things. Being too rigid drives people away,
potentially worsening the neglect of the park. ``Parks only exist
because people go there,'' Rybczynski said.
</P>
<P>
   Central Park began its decline during the 1960s, when people
began avoiding it for fear of being mugged. The slide was arrested
after the Central Park Conservancy raised hundreds of millions of
dollars to rehabilitate it, calling on the wealth of nearby
residents.
</P>
<P>
   Now the challenge is to keep people from loving Central Park to
death, and to persuade them to share and be considerate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Stern has asked drummers and musicians who use amplifiers to use
the band shell. But the musicians and their regular listeners
object to the formality and sterility of the concrete stage,
preferring the intimacy of the lawn or lakeside.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drums are part of my culture,'' said Rose Brito, 34, who said
she was Irish and Puerto Rican. ``To me, the noise touches my soul.
The louder it is, the more free I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Hiss, who writes about parks and open space, suggested that
a ``sound map'' be made, to find relatively enclosed areas for
music.
</P>
<P>
   But preventing hundreds of thousands of feet from stamping the
grass blades into mulch is tougher. One solution might be to spread
the wealth of visitors to other parks, like Riverside, Prospect,
Van Cortlandt and dozens of others, said Mark Caserta, an employee
of the Parks Council, an independent, nonprofit advocacy group for
the city's parks.
</P>
<P>
   The conflicts over music and silence should be worked out case
by case, Rybczynski said. ``That makes it a political hot potato,''
he said. ``But simply banning music doesn't seem right. The park
clearly requires cooperation. We've gotten very bad at compromise
in our society. But the park clearly requires compromise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
