<HEADLINE>
WORTHAM AND BOWDEN BACK HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ The Cowboys have improved their speed on both sides of
the ball this off-season.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless you count Barron Wortham behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barron is the worst driver in the United States,'' said Joe
Bowden, Wortham's best friend with the Tennessee Titans the past
six seasons, and now his teammate with the Cowboys after both
signed as free agents last month. ``You don't want to ride with
him. You kind of get impatient with a guy like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, if the speed limit is 55 mph , Barron is the only guy
I know who drives 54 or 53.''
</P>
<P>
   Both free agents signed with the Cowboys within 24 hours of each
other. Appropriately, Wortham followed Bowden. You might say
Wortham drives a slow bargain as well, since he began talking to
the Cowboys long before Bowden did.
</P>
<P>
   Wortham, a Fort Worth native who lettered in football and track
for the Everman Bulldogs, is a self-proclaimed ``slow poke'' who
takes nearly an hour to drive from South Fort Worth to Valley Ranch
each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have drivers honking at me, shaking their fist,'' said
Wortham, who started at middle linebacker for the Titans in Super
Bowl XXXIV in January. ``But I'm a cautious kind of driver. I want
to get where I'm going in one piece. Besides, the \RValley Ranch\S
facility isn't going anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to football, Wortham was described in the Titans
media guide as ``a powerful hitter whose motor is always running.''
But when it comes to competing on the highway with speeding
commuters, Wortham chooses neither to beat nor to join them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It must be that fast pace of city living ... but they're never
going to get me,'' said Wortham, who was born at John Peter Smith
Hospital just over 30 years ago and has never considered living
anywhere other than Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their athletic ability and versatility, Wortham and
Bowden can play either inside or outside linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I signed, I called Barron and said, `Get in here. This
system is made for you and me,' '' Bowden said. ``Here we
read-and-react; we don't have to do so much thinking. And we don't
have to play over the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   Wortham, Bowden and Dat Nguyen are all 5-foot-11. Pro Bowl
weakside linebacker Dexter Coakley is listed as 5-10. Only 1999
strong-side starter Darren Hambrick is over 6-foot among the
regulars at linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not putting down the system we ran in Tennessee, but the
bigger defensive tackles here allows \Rlinebackers\S to make
plays,'' Wortham said. ``This defense is suited for small, quick,
athletic linebackers.''
</P>
<P>
   Randall Godfrey, who led the Cowboys in tackles last season from
his middle linebacker position, signed as an unrestricted free
agent with the Titans. As much as the Cowboys liked Godfrey _ and
they couldn't touch Tennessee's five-year, $25 million contract
offer _ they are more than content in ``trading'' Godfrey to the
Titans for both Bowden and Wortham.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't bum a ride from Wortham, if you want to get somewhere
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``And never go out with him to eat and say, Barron, let me pick
up the check.' ``Never'' say that!'' Bowden said. ``You won't
believe how much this guy can eat. It's almost sick ....''
</P>
<P>
   But that's another story.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
