<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS STUNNED BY SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Rangers pitcher Rick Helling could be on the
American League All-Star team this year. The way Sean Bergman has
pitched this year, he could be released by the All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   Helling entered the game with a 3.22 earned-run average, fourth
best in the American League. Bergman had a 9.93 ERA, which would
have been the worst if he had enough innings to qualify. Opponents
were hitting .212 off Helling, second lowest in the league. They
were hitting .382 off Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   As Rangers designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro said, ``I felt
pretty good coming in about our chances of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers didn't win. The Minnesota Twins scored four runs in
the first three innings and somehow Bergman and three relievers
made it stand for a 4-3 victory yesterday afternoon at the
Metrodome. The victory allowed the Twins to sweep the three-game
series against the stunned Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't expect this, not when we were playing pretty
decently coming in here,'' shortstop Royce Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   Added Palmeiro, ``They obviously played better than we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Helling: ``It's tough to lose three here, but this is a
big-league team. I don't take any team for granted, and I think I
can speak for the rest of the team, nobody else does either. It
doesn't matter if it's the Minnesota Twins or the New York Yankees;
every team has a chance to win. They played well, and we didn't;
when that happens, you've got a chance to get swept.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, manager Johnny Oates had a hard time believing the
Rangers didn't do more damage to Bergman, who allowed three runs on
seven hits but saved himself by not walking a batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today was frustrating,'' Oates said. ``The game was there for
the taking, and we didn't take it. The last two nights we didn't
pitch well; today we had a shot to win and couldn't. Rick got off
to a rocky start, but after the third inning he pitched extremely
well. We had all sorts of chances to score runs and have good
at-bats, and we didn't have them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were 1-for-8 with runners in scoring position,
including 0-for-6 in the seventh and eighth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still getting people on base, but we're not getting big
base hits,'' Oates said. Bergman ``gave us some pitches to hit. If
we're patient ... we should have scored a lot of runs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, trailing 4-3, got their rally going in the seventh
with an infield single by David Segui and Ruben Mateo's single to
left. Mike Lamb advanced Segui to third with a line-drive out to
deep center, but Bergman came back to strike out Royce Clayton in
an 11-pitch at-bat and got Bill Haselman on a grounder to short to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Carrasco replaced Bergman to start the eighth and
immediately gave up a double to Luis Alicea. But he came back to
strike out Frank Catalanotto, and Eddie Guardado came in to get
Rusty Greer on a grounder to second. Palmeiro drew a walk, but
Guardado struck out Segui, once again leaving the Rangers
frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   LaTroy Hawkins, who pitched himself out of the Twins' rotation
this season, took the Rangers down in order in the ninth to earn
his first career major-league save. It was that kind of day for the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Helling started his day by giving up a leadoff home run to
Jacque Jones in the first inning. With one out, Matt Lawton singled
to left, stole second, went to third on Haselman's throwing error
and scored Ron Coomer's grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota had runners on second and third with no outs in the
second inning, but Helling kept the Twins from scoring. But, with
the game tied 2-2, he wasn't so lucky in the third. This time with
runners at second and third, Corey Koskie delivered a two-out,
two-run single to give the Twins a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Helling then proceeded to retire 13 consecutive batters. But the
Rangers could never pull even. / nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
