<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIN DELAYS THE MEMORIAL, AND PERHAPS THE INEVITABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ohio _ Instead of playing golf Sunday, Tiger Woods spent
the afternoon watching rain.
</P>
<P>
   The final round of the Memorial Tournament was suspended until
Monday after rain saturated Muirfield Village Golf Club and made it
impossible to continue. This is the second time in four years that
the Memorial's fourth round has been pushed back to a Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Play was suspended at 11:15 a.m., long before the leaders could
tee off. When play resumes Monday at 8 a.m., Woods (17-under, 199)
will hold a commanding six-stroke lead over Steve Lowery
(11-under), and a seven-stroke lead over Justin Leonard (10-under).
So while Woods wanted to finish Sunday, he did not feel he would
lose momentum after shooting a 9-under 63 on Friday and a 7-under
65 on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to lose your entire game in one day if you're
playing well,'' Woods said. ``You're not going to struggle to break
90 tomorrow. Mentally, you know you need to go out there and get
the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he did during the rain delay, Woods said, ``I ate a
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Corey Pavin and Don Pooley, who played in the first group, were
the only golfers who finished Sunday. They shot 71s. Forty of the
80 players in the field failed to complete even one hole.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who is the defending champion at the Memorial, will be
trying to become the first PGA Tour player to win four times this
year. Phil Mickelson, who is not in this field, has three victories
this year. Woods has already won the Mercedes Championships, the
AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach National Pro-Am and the Bay Hill Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Monday will probably be Woods' last round in competition before
the U.S. Open from June 15 to 18 at Pebble Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will not play this week's Kemper Open, nor is he expected
to play the Buick Classic (June 8-11) at Westchester Country Club
in Harrison, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third Monday scheduled on tour this year, and Woods
has been involved in all three. He won at Pebble Beach in February
on a memorable Monday, overcoming a seven-stroke deficit with seven
holes to play. At the Players Championship in March, Woods lost a
Monday final-hole duel with Hal Sutton, who won by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   But with Woods holding a six-stroke lead, this Monday finish may
not be as dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too often I've had a six-stroke lead,'' Woods said. ``If
it's calm and soft tomorrow, you'll have to make birdies. If the
wind blows, you won't have to go as low.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
