<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-LAPOINTE-COLUMN-N     05-28 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LAPOINTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ROBINSON, GAINEY AND THE ETERNAL CHAMPIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Late last week, Devils coach Larry Robinson praised Scott
Stevens by invoking a name: Bob Gainey. Robinson said Stevens, his
captain and star defenseman, reminded him of Gainey, a former
captain of the Montreal Canadiens. Robinson and Gainey played
together in Montreal in the mid-1970s through the 1980s, when the
franchise won six of its 24 Stanley Cup championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't speak a lot,'' Robinson said of Gainey and Stevens.
``But when they do, there is a lot of meaning there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Gainey's reputation may not be widely known throughout
the entire sports world, his name is generally understood in hockey
to stand for leadership by example, for competitive integrity and
for quiet dignity. From an ex-Canadien of that era, comparison to
Gainey is high praise.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Gainey will compete for the Stanley Cup again this
week, wearing business suits instead of sweaty uniforms. But only
one will get his name engraved in silver this spring. Robinson
coaches a Devils team that qualified for the championship round by
beating Philadelphia in seven games in the Eastern Conference
finals. Gainey is the general manager of the Dallas Stars, the
defending champions who qualified again by ousting Colorado in Game
7 of the Western finals on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still talk from time to time,'' Robinson said of Gainey.
``I respect and cherish our friendship.''
</P>
<P>
   When the series begins at Continental Arena Tuesday night,
Gainey's Stars will be favored. Not only are they the defending
champions, but they also represent a conference that has won the
trophy the last four seasons. The last time an Eastern team won was
in 1995. That team was the Devils, and they were the underdogs that
spring to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   There are not many other direct connections between the Devils
and the Stars, but one of them is Kirk Muller. Now a veteran
role-player with Dallas at age 34, Muller began his career in 1984
with the Devils, with whom he became a high-scoring power forward
before being traded to Montreal in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the team I grew up with,'' he said of the Devils.
``I've got a lot of great memories going back. It will be an
interesting feeling going in there to play the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller also has a connection to Gainey and two Dallas teammates.
Like Gainey, he is a former captain of the Canadiens. So are Guy
Carbonneau and Mike Keane. The three of them work together as a
checking line. Between games 1 and 2, Keane, Muller, Carbonneau and
Gainey are expected to travel to Montreal to honor another former
Canadiens captain. They will attend a memorial service for Maurice
Richard, who died on Saturday of cancer at age 78.
</P>
<P>
   The mourning for Richard and the championship-round presence of
Robinson and Gainey provide a Memorial Day reminder of the temporal
nature of both legendary players and sports dynasties. For much of
the 20th century, spring and the hockey playoffs used to mean an
intense focus on Montreal. But the Canadiens have won just two
championships in the last two decades, and they have missed the
playoffs the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Like Robinson and Gainey, pieces of the last great Montreal
group _ the four consecutive championship teams from 1976 through
1979 _ are scattered about the league and doing well. Ken Dryden,
the former goalie, is the president of the Toronto Maple Leafs;
Scotty Bowman, the coach, runs a good team in Detroit. Other
ex-players like Serge Savard, Rejean Houle, Jacques Lemaire, Mario
Tremblay, Doug Jarvis, Doug Risebrough and Guy Lapointe have all
tried coaching and managing with varying degrees of success. Houle
is general manager of the Canadiens; Jarvis is a Dallas assistant
coach.
</P>
<P>
   So why bring up the Canadiens again in this way when they did
not even make the playoffs again? Precisely because they are so far
from here. It has been a good tournament this spring, and it might
be a great final round. But hockey as a whole, expanding wildly to
Sunbelt states and college football cities and Nascar counties,
needs and misses the mystique of the Montreal Canadiens in the
springtime. The appearance of leaders like Robinson and Gainey are
a constant reminder, evoking mixed feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden, an occasional author who also wrote and narrated a
documentary television series, wrote of these players, that
franchise and this sport in his 1983 book, ``The Game.'' At the
time, his description of Gainey was an insightful observation about
a contemporary player on a great team. Seventeen years later, his
words seem like an amber memory from a franchise that has lost its
luster.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is such a thing as a `player's player,' it would be
Gainey,'' Dryden wrote. ``Someone who has the personal and playing
qualities that others wish they had, basic, unalterable qualities _
dependability, discipline, hard work, courage _ the roots of every
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you want a team game, where the goal is the team and
the goal is to win, you need a player with an emotional and
practical stake in a team game, a player to remind you of that
game, to bring you back to it whenever you forget it, to be the
playing conscience of the team. Like Bob Gainey.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
