<HEADLINE>
BELTRE COULD BE HEADED FOR DL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adrian Beltre's sprint down the first-base line
Saturday night could be his last for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers are expected to put the third baseman on
the disabled list unless there is a drastic improvement today in
the right hamstring he strained while running out a ground ball in
the sixth inning of Saturday's loss to Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been no moves today,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said Sunday. ``But it's pretty much a given unless there's a
difference between now and (Monday). He's not too good today.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre slowed down and grabbed his leg in apparent pain before
reaching first base in his third at-bat Saturday. He dropped to the
ground after passing the bag and had to be helped off the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in some pain,'' Johnson said. ``He had problems sleeping
(Saturday) night.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre is batting .269 with five home runs and 31 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vizcaino made the start at third base Sunday and reassured
the Dodgers by making key defensive plays such as throwing out a
runner at the plate in the third inning and running down a foul
ball for an out in the second. He also reached base twice,
including a fifth-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson did not want to think about a long-term replacement
until he knows more about Beltre's condition. For the near future,
Vizcaino and Dave Hansen are expected to split time at third.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Alex Cora would have been Johnson's first choice to
fill an open roster spot, but Cora has been bothered by a problem
with the muscles in his rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of possibilities,'' Johnson said of who would be
called up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how it goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back: Mike Fetters made his first appearance Saturday
since a sore right elbow put him on the disabled list May 4. The
right-hander, who has not allowed a run in 10 of his 12 appearances
this season, started where he left off by pitching a hitless and
scoreless eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Shawn Green took over the National League lead
for doubles when he doubled in the first inning Saturday for his
18th of the season. Green's first-inning double Sunday gave him 10
in the past 17 games, tying him with Eric Young of the Chicago Cubs
for for the major- league lead. He had four doubles last season
with Toronto. ... Reliever Allan Mills extended his
scoreless-innings streak to 8 by pitching a scoreless seventh
inning Saturday, lowering his ERA to 3.63. ... The Dodgers have
scored at least one run in the first inning in six consecutive
games, but the quick starts haven't equated to good finishes. The
Dodgers have lost four of their past five games when scoring in the
first.
</P>
</TEXT>
