<SLUG> BC-LACROSSE-PRINCETON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S ALL IN THE FAMILY AS PRINCETON GOES FOR A TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOPHIA HOLLANDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE PARK, Md. _ Coach Bill Tierney of Princeton scanned the
field uneasily Saturday and saw a strange mix of players in the
waning minutes of the men's lacrosse national semifinal against
Virginia. The coach saw untested Tigers: the freshmen Josh White
and Sean Hartofilis and the sophomore attack Brendan Tierney, his
son.
</P>
<P>
   He paused. There were two minutes remaining, and after trailing
the Cavaliers for 43 minutes, the Tigers were tied, 11-11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure you've got the people you want out there?'' he
asked his offensive coach, David Metzbower.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, we're OK,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, Brendan Tierney received a pass from White and
shoved a shot past Cavalier goalie Derek Kenney for his second goal
of the game, both in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Tierney's son Brendan, who had been maligned in discussion
groups on the Internet for being too small and too slow to play
major college lacrosse and for capitalizing on his family
connection at Princeton, had won the game. The coach's other son,
the junior goalie Trevor Tierney, had preserved the victory with 14
saves.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his sons' performances, Tierney bowed his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try so hard when coaching your sons not to be too hard or
too soft on them,'' he said in a soft voice. ``It's a hard
situation. It's hard to put into words just what this means. It's
every coach's dream, every dad's dream, and it all came together
today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tierneys and the rest of the third-seeded Tigers (12-2) will
meet No. 1 Syracuse (14-1) Monday at 10:55 a.m. in the national
title game. On April 23, the Orangemen raked the Tigers, 16-4. It
was the worst Princeton defeat in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The game took place the day after Princeton sewed up the Ivy
League championship by defeating Cornell. In that game the Tigers
lost their second-leading scorer, the sophomore attack B.J. Prager,
to injury. The reeling Tigers, unprepared and unsettled, staggered
into the Carrier Dome and got crushed.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse said it was ready for the revamped Tiger team. ``This
is a new season,'' said the Orangemen senior Tim Byrnes, citing
Princeton's 5-0 record in title games. ``Were definitely playing a
different team now.''
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse is the only team Princeton has lost to in the National
Collegiate Athletic Association tournament since 1992. Against all
other teams, the Tigers are 16-0. Against Syracuse, they are 3-3,
including a 7-5 loss last year in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 the third-seeded Tigers upset top-seeded Syracuse by
10-9 for their first NCAA title, despite not having any superstars.
The current no-name Tigers cling to that victory as proof of the
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're an unbelievable bunch of overachievers,'' Trevor Tierney
said. ``When I was a freshman, we were the team to beat. Now
everybody is counting on us to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a team that has relied on his slick saves. His 4.64
goals-against average in Ivy League games was the lowest in league
play since 1981. Over all, he has a 7.57 goals-against average and
a .643 save percentage.
</P>
<P>
   For Trevor Tierney, the decision to play for his father was an
easy one. Four years ago the coach was sitting at home when the
phone, the one he used for recruiting, rang. He was ready to talk
to a talented high school senior and roll out his best pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this Coach Tierney?`` a young voice asked politely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's this?'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trevor Tierney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to let you know that I'm coming to Princeton.''
</P>
<P>
   They laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting to get him,'' Tierney the coach said. ``We
weren't sure if we were going to.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brendan Tierney, the choice was not as easy. ``I kind of
wanted to get away for my whole life, like any normal teen-ager,''
he said. ``But it's hard to turn down such a great lacrosse program
and the best education in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   So the brothers grit their teeth when their father yells at them
on the field, biting back responses they would blare out at home.
The father forces himself through painful moments, like when he
pulled Trevor after a poor first quarter last year against North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   And they both know that when the coach screams on the sideline,
his face red, it is a field persona and nothing personal. Not
everyone knows that.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think my dad is a raving maniac all the time,'' Trevor
Tierney said. ``But he's a great dad.''
</P>
<P>
   And not a bad coach, either. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
