<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STALKING THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A specter is stalking the Internet: the specter of
the Web stalker.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a credit card issuer letting merchants of porn in on
your buying habits or confiding your travel plans or medication
purchases to private investigators. It can be a thief using your
Social Security number to steal your identity and ruin your credit.
It can even be a criminal searching the Web for your photograph, as
has happened with tragic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, says an industry busily compiling dossiers on
every American. Leave it to us to police ourselves. Someday _ after
we have your personal history going back to grades in grammar
school _ we'll get around to restraining our intrusiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after listening to false promises for five years, a
majority of the Federal Trade Commission _ Republicans dissenting _
roused itself to suggest a law providing Americans the rudiments of
privacy protection.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC report revealed that fewer than one in 10 Internet sites
that collect personal identifying data display the industry's
voluntary privacy seal. ``Self-regulation'' promised by the
mushrooming companies is a farce because they salivate at the heavy
money to be made in shadowing the users of computers, snooping into
their private lives.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pitofsky, the FTC chairman, told Senate Commerce that Web
sites should be required by law to tell users in clear language
what information they collect (often surreptitiously, through
``cookies'' implanted in computers to track your movements), and to
whom they sell or trade your personal data.
</P>
<P>
   Such disclosure is long overdue; legal gobbledygook that passes
for privacy policy conceals by confusing. Pitofsky also recommends
that netties be given the right to see what's been collected about
them, just as consumers already have the right to read and correct
inaccuracies in their credit reports.
</P>
<P>
   So far so good, although the pro-snooping lobby protests that
this is much too onerous and would slow the e-commerce boom. But
then the FTC flinched from its responsibility to consumers: It
suggested merely that Web sites be obligated to offer consumers
``the choice'' of saying no to profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds protective, but Web stalkers know that baby step to be a
sham. Marketers call it ``opt out''; it puts the burden of
protecting privacy on the consumer. Most people have neither the
time, know-how or gumption to examine closely the uses to which
their data will be put; they are unlikely to take the initiative to
direct dozens of Web sites to not shadow and share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opt out'' is the marketer's public relations trick to provide
the pretense of choice. That was the sellout that Senate Banking
chairman Phil Gramm and Treasury Secretary Larry Summers
engineered, at the banking lobby's urging, to let banks get away
with new intrusions into depositors' financial privacy. We will
have to wait until Sen. Richard Shelby, the GOP's privacy champion,
becomes Banking Committee chairman before that is changed to ``opt
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The only genuine online privacy protection is informed, written
consent. That is when the burden of getting permission to pass
around personal data falls where it belongs, on the seller, who
must explain the deal and persuade or offer inducements to the
buyer to choose to give permission.
</P>
<P>
   Real privacy depends on who is required to do the asking. An
online privacy policy that fails to conclude with ``now that you
know exactly what we will do with your information, do you give
your consent?'' is a phony privacy policy.
</P>
<P>
   At Senate Commerce last week, Democrats Jay Rockefeller and
Fritz Hollings offered a bill to require Web sites to ask such
consent. Chairman John McCain, in obeisance to evenhandedness, will
offer online hardliners further hearings next week to promise the
voluntary moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be taking on the most influential lobby in Washington
today,'' McCain tells me. He thinks the Rockefeller-Hollings
approach may be ``too encroaching'' on industry. Will he at least
move the FTC's watered-down recommendations? ``I'll introduce a
bill and we'll mark it up. But the way the Senate is being run
these days, it may never come to a floor vote. In my 14 years here,
I've never seen less done.''
</P>
<P>
   E-commercites: Until the online stalking and profiling is
stopped, go to a store and pay cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
