<SLUG> BC-NY-CRIME-DROP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXAMINING THE DIRECTION OF NEW YORK'S CRIME RATE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: With CRIME-DROP-REACT) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York preceded most cities in experiencing the
historic drop in crime that has swept across America's urban areas
and spurred an economic renaissance in many once-devastated
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But while crime in New York remains at a 30-year low, city
officials have spent considerable time and effort in the last year
trying to allay fears that the city may be headed back to the days
when more than 1,500 murders a year were not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1998, the city's murder rate had dropped to its
lowest point since 1964. But after a decline in homicides to 629 in
1998 from 2,245 in 1990, New York is beginning to record a slight
increase in murders, police records show.
</P>
<P>
   Although all other major categories of crime have continued to
decline, there have been 269 homicides this year, compared with 248
at the same point last year, police records show. And several
recent crimes _ a woman attacked by a man with a brick on a Midtown
street last fall, a spate of cabdriver killings and the murders of
five people last week at a Wendy's in Queens _ have drawn intense
media attention, suggesting that the perception, if not the
reality, of a dangerous city may be returning.
</P>
<P>
   Homicides, in fact, are down 62 percent compared with 1993,
police records show. ``When things are going well, sometimes the
shock is so large because you have told people they don't have to
worry about crime,'' said Thomas A. Repetto, chairman of the
Citizen's Crime Commission, a police watchdog group in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   While some law enforcement officials say domestic violence, gang
killings and a growth in the juvenile and young adult population
most often linked to murders are responsible for the two-year spike
in homicides, Andrew Karmen, a sociologist at John Jay College of
Criminal Justice in Manhattan, said, ``There is nothing you can
point to and say that `this is the culprit.'''
</P>
<P>
   Karmen said economic, demographic and other factors are probably
playing a role in the murder rate's increase, leading to questions
about the extent to which law enforcement has suppressed violence.
In New York, officials have credited smart and aggressive police
work for the crime rate's decline.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers agree that in many respects, the New York police
have become victims of their own success: the declining crime rate
has raised expectations and created statistical lows that will
serve to highlight any future increases.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous amount of fear,'' Repetto said,
``because you've told yourself crime is not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yolanda Jimenez, the deputy police commissioner who handles
community affairs, said city officials have been doing more to
educate people about crime trends. ``We have had a challenging four
years,'' she said. ``But in spite and despite all that, the large
crime reductions have really paved the way for people do deal with
issues like quality of life and programs for young people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0145 </DOCNO>
