u f BC-DEAL-LUCENT-NYT &LR;      05-28 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEAL-LUCENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT ANGLING FOR OPTICAL NETWORKING COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies Inc., North America's No. 1 maker of
communications equipment, is negotiating to acquire privately held
optical network technology company Chromatis Networks Inc. for as
much as $5.5 billion in stock, people close to the companies said
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   While the talks could still fall apart amid wrangling over price
and lingering interest in Chromatis from other companies, including
Nortel Networks Corp. of Brampton, Ontario, one person close to the
negotiations said the likelihood of Chromatis completing a deal
with Lucent was ``over 90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   If Lucent and Chromatis cement a deal, it will almost surely be
announced in time for the Supercomm 2000 communications equipment
trade show, which begins June 4 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Based in Herndon, Va., Chromatis makes equipment that
consolidates data and voice communication traffic from within a
large corporation or among many smaller businesses, and then
transmits that information using light waves across high-capacity
fiber optic networks within cities.
</P>
<P>
   Fiber optic networking can transmit millions of bits, or
billions of bits, of information each second along fiber optic
cables using pulses of light emitted by lasers, rather than using
pulses of electricity traveling on copper cables that have more
limited capacity. Most of the advances in optical networking in
recent years have applied to long-distance networks that transmit
information among cities or across continents. Now, a number of
start-up companies, including Chromatis, are developing products to
add capacity and flexibility to optical networks within
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has long been in optical networking, but faces increasing
competition from such companies as Nortel, a long-time rival. While
Nortel and Cisco Systems Inc., the No. 1 maker of Internet
communications equipment, have been aggressive in acquiring optical
networking companies, a deal for Chromatis would be Lucent's first
major acquisition of an optical systems company.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to Lucent and Chromatis the
negotiations are being driven by Lucent's senior executives,
including Chairman Richard A. McGinn, Patricia F. Russo, chief of
the unit that sells equipment to big communications carriers, and
Harry L. Bosco, head of the optical unit.
</P>
<P>
   But one person close to Lucent said that at least some of the
company's less-senior technology employees are lobbying against the
acquisition of Chromatis, suggesting instead Lucent acquire Astral
Point Communications, based in Chelmsford, Mass. Lucent already has
an agreement to sell Astral Point's equipment under the Lucent
brand. A Lucent spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the products from Astral Point and Chromatis are
meant to do similar things, but according to communications
equipment experts, the systems of each have particular strengths in
different areas.
</P>
<P>
   The systems created by Chromatis are thought by some experts to
be better at handling data transmitted in a format developed for
the Internet, called Internet protocol, while Astral Point's
systems considered more adept at handling data in a different
format, known as asynchronous transfer mode.
</P>
<P>
   Both formats split data into small pieces to transmit them
across networks. But while the data packets created by Internet
protocol are often different sizes, asynchronous transfer mode
breaks data into pieces of uniform size, often making data
formatted in asynchronous transfer mode easier to handle than data
formatted in Internet protocol ``packets.'' That is why
asynchronous transfer mode has become a standard format for most
telecommunications carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Data being transmitted using Internet protocol can ride on top
of data formatted in asynchronous transfer mode, meaning that an
e-mail message, formatted in Internet protocol, from Los Angeles to
New York might actually be carried across the continent on a
communications network that uses asynchronous transfer mode.
</P>
<P>
   While Astral Point's products might be more attractive to
communications carriers like regional Bell companies, the gear
developed by Chromatis might be more suitable for Internet service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent already has a strong position selling equipment to
telephone companies, but it has not been as adept at selling
equipment to Internet service providers, which may explain why
Lucent's senior management seems to be pushing the acquisition of
Chromatis.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Nortel, executives from Sycamore Networks Inc. have
expressed interest in Chromatis, according to those close to the
company, but those discussions aren't as advanced as talks with
Lucent, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
