<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8230 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DETROIT-TECHNO-NYT &LR;      05-28 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DETROIT-TECHNO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHING HARD TO MAKE `DETROIT TECHNO' ROCK ... IN DETROIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Britain, Japan, France, Germany, Canada)   By NICHOLE M. CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Carl Craig is an international music star. Every
weekend he is somewhere in the world performing before sold-out
crowds of swooning teen-agers and 20-somethings. In Belgium and
Australia, fans clamor for his autograph and a glimpse of his hazel
eyes. In London and Paris, they wait hours to tell him how his
music has changed their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But here in his hometown, the place that spawned the sound known
as Detroit techno, the 30-year-old Craig remains an unknown. For
nearly two decades, the city that set the '60s to music with the
Motown sound, has largely closed its ears to its other musical
offspring, the techno sound.
</P>
<P>
   Many people here barely regard the pulsating electronic drum
beats and synthesized rhythms that is techno as music. Few stores
stock the music, and only loyalists _ a few thousand folks in the
Detroit _ are willing to pay to see Craig, and the half-dozen
others who have made techno famous, behind their turntables,
keyboards and computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Techno music has done as much for Detroit as Motown did,''
Craig said. ``People all over the world see Detroit as this
mythological music scene; they kiss the ground when they come here
because it's where it started. They have no idea it's still a
secret here.''
</P>
<P>
   But this holiday weekend, Craig is raising techno's profile by
presiding over the Detroit Electronic Music Festival, a free
three-day outdoor dance party on the city's waterfront. Some say
that holding the festival in Detroit is a gamble, considering the
music's relative obscurity in the city. About 85 percent of the CDs
and 12-inch vinyl singles produced by the more than 25 independent
record labels here are sold overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But on Saturday, as thousands of baby-toting and droopy
jeans-wearing music lovers endured showers to listen to the first
of 70 international acts performing on four stages, it appeared
that techno might finally become a hit at home.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna Prothero and her husband, Iron, drove two days from
Denver. The couple, in their 30s, discovered the music 11 years ago
while in London. ``You couldn't find a better dance party in
America if you paid for it,'' Prothero said of the festival.
</P>
<P>
   Others came from countries like Japan, France, Germany and
Canada. Yosaku Hagiwara, 24, of Osaka, Japan, said, ``To see these
guys for free in the city where it all happened, I think is so
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The media also came. There are TV broadcasters from France,
London and Tokyo, and Canadian national radio is broadcasting
portions of the concert live.
</P>
<P>
   International journalists have not watched Detroit like this
since the 1980s when arsonists celebrated Halloween by torching
abandoned homes. That tradition, called Devil's Night, has since
been extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at it out here,'' said DJ Hannah, scanning Saturday's
crowd. Hannah, a 28-year-old disc jockey from Britain, moved here
two years ago and is married to Craig. ``This music has brought the
world to Detroit. Asian, white, black, blue. They're all here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago Kenny Larkin, who is performing this weekend,
postponed his dream of becoming a comedian to play the music he
heard rising out of dark after-hour clubs in the 1980s. Larkin, of
Detroit, says that hometown acclaim is what he has most wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so frustrating to have to get on a plane every other
weekend and fly nine, 10 hours away to get respect,'' said Larkin,
32, who owns a record label and plays regularly in Madrid, Berlin
and Dublin.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, he logged one million frequent flyer miles. Like most
techno artists, he does not discuss how much he makes from his
weekend jaunts or from record sales, which rarely exceed a few
thousand copies for any artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on MTV over there,'' Larkin. ``The record stores give as
much room to Detroit techno as they give to American pop and rock
music. It's sad we can't get people over here to see us as a
legitimate genre of music.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, Craig hopes to attract a specific market: young
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   While white teen-agers have made electronic music popular _ and
in some cases infamous because of its association with illegal rave
parties and the drug ecstasy _ black teen-agers have mostly written
it off as suburban noise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Techno is faceless,'' said Craig, who is black. ``They don't
know it's black music, that it was created by young black men in
the same way hip-hop was. We were more interested in mastering the
machines and seeing how far the music could go without being
typecast as something that came from the ghetto.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the festival succeeds or not, Craig says Detroit affords
techno artists one luxury other celebrities cannot claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jackson and people like Prince dream of going shopping
or out to dinner without someone trying to tear their clothes
off,'' he said. ``Nobody knows who we are. Yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
