<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STARS, IT'S ALL ABOUT RESPECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The Dallas Stars will never forget their
first trip to the Stanley Cup Finals, but they wouldn't have missed
this one for the respect.
</P>
<P>
   Their first Stanley Cup was for fun. This one is for a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the respect of winning a second championship that
everybody that wins two gets,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``There's a great feeling when you win two or three years or
whatever. ... You don't just want to be a flash in the pan. Nobody
likes to be a one-hit wonder.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the dance now for sure. We've given ourselves an
opportunity. We're relatively healthy, and now we're four wins away
from reaching our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the playoffs started April 12, the Stars have been
counting down the number of victories it takes to win the Stanley
Cup. They began with 16 written on a drawing board in their
dressing room at Reunion Arena. After Saturday night's 3-2 victory
against the Colorado Avalanche in Game 7 of the Western Conference
Finals, the Stars' magic number is four.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Stars have lived up to their battle cry of ``The Cup
Stays Here.'' Yesterday, the Stars left for New Jersey, where they
will play the Devils in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup Finals tomorrow
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we wanted to do at the start of the year _
reach the Stanley Cup,'' Stars captain Derian Hatcher said. ``We're
one more step closer. We're at the final stage, the final series.
It's something that we were gunning for, something we wanted to do,
and we're there now. Now, obviously, we're there to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup is overflowing with repeat winners, but since
1985, there have been only three. Edmonton won in 1987 and '88.
Pittsburgh took the Cup in 1991 and '92, and Detroit was a
back-to-back winner in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are out to leave their mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance that very few people have the ability to say
they accomplished,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``Pittsburgh
and Detroit did it in the '90s, and we fought hard and put
ourselves in this position.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, for the second consecutive year, the Stars won the
Presidents' Trophy for the NHL's best regular-season record,
posting a franchise-high 114 points. Dallas followed that with a
16-7 postseason record, including beating the Buffalo Sabres in six
games in the Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there was anything fluky about it last year. We
were the No. 1 team in the league all year long and won in the
playoffs,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``It's a relief to
get back to this point. No doubt about it; you see these teams in
the Western Conference so much all season long and to be standing
alone after it's over is a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were expected to win the Stanley Cup last year. This
year, no one was even sure they would make it through the regular
season still standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of injuries, and a lot of people didn't think
we'd make the playoffs at the beginning of the year,'' Stars
defenseman Darryl Sydor said. ``But we knew in the end we would be
a good team. A lot of what we are playing for now is respect.''
</P>
<P>
   This season was filled with turbulence. The Stars lost 395
man-games to injury, and four teams finished with more points than
Dallas' 102.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is same time, this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were on a mission,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau
said. ``There was nothing that could stop us. Every game was great
games for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I guess we just keep going from what we did in the
season _ lots of injuries, the pressure of winning the Cup last
year. We've had a lot of ups and downs. ... We didn't play our best
game every game, but we found ways to win games. That's what good
teams do.''
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Blues won the Presidents' Trophy, and the
Avalanche was the hottest team entering the playoffs with a 12-2-1
regular-season record after acquiring veteran defenseman Raymond
Bourque from Boston. Still, it was the Stars that won the Campbell
Bowl as Western Conference champions.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars disposed of the Edmonton Oilers and the San Jose
Sharks in five games each, then shook the Avs in the seventh game
Saturday night. Dallas jumped to a 3-0 lead early in the second
period, and then hung on for a one-goal victory when Bourque's shot
deflected off Adam Deadmarsh and clanked off a post and out of
harm's way with 12 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people thought we'd fold,'' Stars forward Mike Keane
said. ``This team hasn't folded up all year. With the injuries
we've had to our big guns, we still kept winning games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think a lot of people gave us any credit, so we bore
down and won the game, and now we're in the final two, and that's
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, who won the Cup in 1995, want what the Stars have.
The Stars want what the Canadians and the Islanders and others
have. In the NHL, once is not enough for a legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think that not many players in their career have an
opportunity to win back-to-back Cups, and we have an opportunity
here to do something really special as a group. That's the goal,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``Years from now, you can say we had a group of
guys here who won the Stanley Cup again.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
