<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-FARM-SUCCESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINE'S PRIVATE FARMING FINALLY TAKING ROOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Originally skedded as UKRAINE-FARMER) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT8 and NYT9 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
A map is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   POLTAVA, Ukraine _ The rolling
farmland that unfolds in all directions from here is so famous for
its rich, black soil that the Germans carted some of it home during
World War II.
<TEXT>
<P>
   This land was also the battlefield on which Russia's Peter the
Great stunned Europe's monarchs by defeating the fabled Swedish war
machine of Charles XII.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a burly agronomist with a Cossack's mustache is gaining a
reputation for doing what many Communist overlords of agriculture
repeatedly failed to do in the 20th century _ making money by
farming this land.
</P>
<P>
   Across a landscape of collapsing state farms that are the most
prominent feature of post-Soviet agriculture, a small number of
entrepreneurial private farmers, like Vasily T. Sluga, are taking
advantage of the sporadic land reforms in Ukraine to show others
the way to a more productive future.
</P>
<P>
   Their success is by no means certain in a country the size of
France where the official economy has contracted by half in a
decade, where the population is producing less food and importing
more, and where much the transition economy is impossible to
measure or predict because it occurs outside government regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Just to borrow money for seeds and diesel fuel for farm
equipment, Sluga must entice credit from local oligarchs.
</P>
<P>
   But Sluga says there are dozens, if not hundreds, of new
entrepreneurial farmers like him in central Ukraine. In the
capital, Kiev, Western officials say that anecdotal data is
trickling in to suggest that private agriculture is developing, if
not yet flourishing, on the fertile land that was once the
breadbasket of the Russian empire.
</P>
<P>
   Sluga, 43, has no special business training for the life he is
carving out for himself in the wreckage of 70 years of Soviet
collectivization of Ukrainian farming. He receives no investment
from Western tycoons, no grants from aid organizations, and no
advice from Western agriculture experts. But nearly a decade ago,
Sluga said he realized that Ukraine's state farms were doomed and
would not survive the transition from Communism, and he undertook a
plan to build a private farming business with brawn and wit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life forces us to find ways,'' Sluga said recently in an
interview in his small brick home in the village of Chutovo, about
30 miles east of here. ``Under the conditions of agriculture today,
no one is left to give orders from above and so everything depends
on the individual farmer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sluga began to run things himself in April 1993 after the first
tentative land reforms in Ukraine allocated 5 acres to each member
of the country's farm collectives swamped with debt and unable to
pay wages and pensions on time, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Today Sluga has 1,730 acres under production, with 20 employees
and a fleet of tractors, combines and a harvester, all of which he
parks in the garage of the bankrupt ``Soviet Ukraine'' collective
farm, the leaders of which have been only too happy to sell off
their equipment and buildings as Sluga needs them.
</P>
<P>
   The state farm's best foreman, Nikolai V. Ogiyko, is now Sluga's
foreman. ``People realize now that they work for themselves,'' said
Ogiyko, ``that we are on our own.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sluga bought the state farm's harvester, he also recruited
its 72-year-old driver, Ivan Nimchin, who remains an avowed
Leninist, but who now contributes his harvesting skills to Sluga's
holdings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the old system was better,'' said Nimchin, ``but it is
nice to get a paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sluga pooled his 5 acres of land with the plots from
five of his friends, and together they planted 30 acres with sugar
beets and potatoes. A second land reform decree from Ukraine
national government that year ordered state farms to make up to 10
percent of their land available for private farmers. Again pooling
his land with several friends, Sluga had more than 350 acres ready
for planting by the end of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``These lands that were given out were usually the worst lands
on the commune, on the slopes or far away from the town, but we
were lucky,'' said Sluga. ``The land we got was pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   But the fledgling private farming cooperative had no money for
seeds or equipment, and borrowed about $10,000 from a regional
farmers' organization at interest rates of more than 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The farming venture might have ended then, but for additional
assistance from a now defunct government fund to support farmers,
and deft management. With the loan, the farmers bought a harvester,
two new tractors, one second-hand tractor, fuel and seeds. They
planted winter wheat that fall, and in the spring of 1994, barley,
rye, corn, millet, sunflower seeds and sugar beets. With their
first harvest they paid off their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Sluga's business plan was relentlessly simple: eliminate
overhead costs, hire employees with multiple skills, reinvest all
profits in the business and handle negotiations and contracts
himself. The farm's office is a closet-size room in Sluga's modest
brick home. His wife raises chickens, rabbits and three pigs in a
muddy courtyard strewn with farm equipment and guarded by a
boisterous German shepherd.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife is angry at me because I have not finished my own
house yet,'' he said. ``All our money goes to the business.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sluga's first year of farming for himself, Ukraine's economy
was in free fall, with hyperinflation that reached 10,000 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was surviving in his own way,'' Sluga said, ``and
somehow we managed to stay afloat,'' by bartering crops for fuel
and seeds.
</P>
<P>
   As he had learned in agricultural school, Sluga rotated his
crops and invested his profits in herbicides and fertilizers at a
time when state farms were cutting corners, scaling back and
surrendering more and more acreage to weeds. As their yields and
output declined, Sluga's increased.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, after his first successful harvest, Sluga split with
his four partners in a disagreement about how to invest their
profits, but within two years, ``some of my former partners rented
their land to me because they could not continue on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years Sluga's farm holdings stabilized at about 300 to
400 acres, and although he was making money, his profit margins
were thin.
</P>
<P>
   But last December, President Leonid Kuchma issued the most
sweeping land reform decree to date, privatizing all state farms,
dividing the ownership of the land equally among the farm members
and withdrawing state support. A whole new opportunity opened up
for Sluga's April Farm enterprise, named for the month it was
started.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing that happened was that last winter, the Soviet
Ukraine commune made a proposition for me to become their
chairman,'' he said. ``They wanted me to take over because it was
the worst commune in the whole district and one of the worst in the
region, and they had seen that my farming business was very much in
order.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The former state farm, with 3,700 acres of land and debt of
$360,000, was headed for bankruptcy. So Sluga made a
counterproposal. The farm could fend for itself, he said, but he
would rent land from 120 members, more than 1,200 acres in all, and
he would pay rent to the owners with shares of his harvest.
</P>
<P>
   In this way, he would avoid becoming entangled in the farm's
debts, and probably get all of the farm's land and equipment within
two years.
</P>
<P>
   The farm accepted his offer, in part because no one there had
been paid for five months.
</P>
<P>
   Sluga tripled his holdings to more than 1,700 acres, and in need
of yet more capital in a cash-starved land.
</P>
<P>
   Sluga went to a newly rich oligarch and borrowed more than
$10,000 to buy seeds, fuel and additional farming equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that I am running a very big risk in taking
another loan, because if we don't receive a good harvest all that I
have is not enough to repay this debt. So we have done everything
we could and the rest depends on the weather. If we are lucky, it
will rain.''
</P>
</TEXT>
