<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CLEMENS NO LONGER IN COMMAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The celebrated pitching matchup between Pedro
Martinez and Roger Clemens took place at Yankee Stadium Sunday
night. There was reason, however, for questioning whether it should
have been so celebrated.
</P>
<P>
   The Pedro Martinez half of the matchup in the Boston Red Sox
game with the Yankees was beyond question. The doubt, then, must
have been about Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Whether they want to acknowledge it or not, Clemens has given
the Yankees reason to question his place on the Martinez plateau of
pitching. His 14-10 record and 4.60 earned run average were nothing
to celebrate last season, and the 4-4 record and 4.26 ERA he took
into Sunday night's game had not won any raves.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, his pitching in a season and a third with the Yankees
has raised more questions than it has provided satisfaction. The
Yankees still aren't certain what to think. Neither they nor anyone
else, though, was prepared to jump to any negative conclusions
about the 37-year-old right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   Asked, for example, if Clemens had lost something, Mike Stanley,
the Red Sox first baseman Sunday night, said: ``I wouldn't tell him
that. Every time somebody tells him he can't do something, he goes
out and proves them wrong. He was no longer wanted in this
organization and went out and won two Cy Youngs. He almost relishes
the fact that people think he can't do it anymore. I'm going to
give him every ounce of respect that I've ever had for him when he
was at the top of his game because he's still a presence on the
mound and still knows how to get people out.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley said he had no intention of underestimating Clemens for
this confrontation. ``You take your `A' game out against Roger,''
he said. ``You go out thinking he's going to be the five-time Cy
Young award winner that he is. You have to put just as much
concentration and effort into your at-bats.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Valentin, the Red Sox third baseman, said he had lost no
respect for the man who was his teammate in Boston for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, he's getting a little bit older now, but he is still
throwing 95, 96 miles an hour, still throwing hard,'' Valentin
said. ``I still think he is Roger Clemens. He's still one of the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   But Valentin offered an insight into why Clemens might not get
the same results now as he did in his Cy Young years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think more than anything he's having trouble with his
command,'' Valentin said. ``That's the only thing I think is
different. When he throws his off-speed pitches, sometimes he
misses and they're up in the zone, and that's when he can get hit.
He falls behind hitters and he walks hitters. He's walking more
hitters these days, I think, than he ever has in his career. I
think that's a very big factor. Why is that happening? I don't have
that answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Red Sox faced Clemens they beat up on him in
the league championship series last October. They knocked him out
one batter into the third inning. Stanley, with a single, was that
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way to beat him like we did last year in the
playoffs,'' Stanley said, ``is if he's off. If he's on his game,
then you're scratching to get a couple. He obviously wasn't on top
of his game. I'd hate to sit here and think it was all to our
credit, that he was on top of his game and we were better than he
was. That's not the way it works with a quality pitcher like
Roger.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Clemens was off his game, giving up five early
runs in the park where he had won so many games and before the fans
who had cheered so hard for him for so many seasons. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also pitched in that celebrated matchup. When he left
the game, after seven innings, he did so on his own terms. He had
allowed the Yankees only two hits and he had struck out 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give hitters a lot of credit,'' Valentin said.
``Roger's been in the league for a long, long time. When hitters
face you year after year, they get to know you a little better in
how you throw your slider, how you throw your split-finger and so
on. Pitchers have to make adjustments. Give hitters credit. They
make adjustments. He's not going to be as dominant as he was.''
</P>
<P>
   Of 50 pitchers who had made eight or more starts entering play
yesterday, Clemens ranked 17th in earned run average and was tied
with eight others for 12th in victories. The batting average his
opponents had compiled against him, .261, was nearly 100 points
higher than the league low of .167 against Martinez. Clemens had
permitted a ratio of 13.8 base runners per nine innings, Martinez
7.8. Clemens, a five-time league leader in strikeouts, including
three recent years in a row (1996-98), had struck out 57; Martinez
had struck out a league-leading 95.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup, then, appeared to be celebrated in names only,
certainly not in results. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
