<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR MONDAY, MAY 29
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NY-SENATE-RACE-NYT (moved Saturday, May 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, May 27
about the United States Senate race in New York referred
incorrectly to the views of the Republican candidate, Rick A.
Lazio, on gun control. While he opposes a proposal made by his
opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, to register new handguns and
license new gun users, he supports the Brady Bill, which requires
background checks for gun buyers, and a ban on some forms of
assault weapons. He does not oppose all forms of gun control.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-ENVIRON-BILLS-NYT (moved Wednesday, May 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 24
about two environmental measures signed into law by Gov. George E.
Pataki misspelled part of the name of the gasoline additive known
as MTBE, which one of them will ban. It is methyl tertiary butyl
ether, not esther.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BRASSAI-EXHIBIT-NYT (moved Sunday, May 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 21
about works by the photographer Brassai at the Georges Pompidou
Center in Paris misspelled the name of another French photographer,
whose work was shown with his at the Museum of Modern Art in New
York in 1951. He was Izis, not Izius.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CANNES-FILM-NYT (moved Wednesday, May 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 24
about noteworthy films at the International Film Festival omitted
the identity of one co-writer of ``Nurse Betty,'' which won the
award for best screenplay. The writer, with John C. Richards, was
James Flamberg.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-JAZZ-FESTIVALS-NYT (moved Thursday, May 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, May 25
about jazz festivals in Manhattan included an outdated reference to
a performance by John Lurie and the Lounge Lizards. Their concert
on June 18 has been canceled.
</P>
</TEXT>
