<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHING-INTERNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS GET EARLY TEACHING EXPERIENCE IN KANSAS CITY CLASSROOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In July, aspiring teacher Sarah Michael will
get her degree in education from the University of Missouri-Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   By then she will also have a line on her resume that might say
just as much about her preparation for teaching elementary school:
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience: Fifth-grade teacher, Moore Elementary, Kansas
City, Mo., School District, 1999-2000 school year.''
</P>
<P>
   In an internship program, Michael and almost 30 other college
students have taught full time in the district this year while
taking college classes. All the students are from UMKC except for
two who are from Park University.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Oliver, former dean of the UMKC School of Education,
created the program. He wanted to help solve the district's teacher
shortage and give the college students intense exposure to
classroom teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a whole yearful of experience,'' Michael said.
``You don't get this in a classroom with a professor, or in student
teaching without a whole classroom to yourself. There wasn't
anything better to get experience right now.''
</P>
<P>
   UMKC and district officials have declared the program a success.
</P>
<P>
   Had it not been for the program, the Kansas City schoolchildren
probably would have had a series of substitute teachers. Instead,
they learned from fresh, motivated college students.
</P>
<P>
   The education students lived the life of a teacher, instructing
and disciplining children, meeting with parents, grading papers and
planning lessons. They were paid $15,000 to $25,000. The higher
salaries went to interns who received specialized state
certification.
</P>
<P>
   The district will hire many of the graduates in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   UMKC and the district will continue the program, although with a
couple of changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it work? I think it worked well,'' said Alsia Cunningham,
the district's director of consolidated federal programs, who
oversaw the program. ``Did we have problems? Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Fatigue was one.
</P>
<P>
   After teaching all day, the interns had to rush to UMKC for
their classes. Then there was homework and lesson planning, which
left little or no free time or family time.
</P>
<P>
   Three participants dropped out early on. UMKC officials are
unsure whether exhaustion caused them to quit, but they say it
probably played a role.
</P>
<P>
   Trasi Pruitt said she initially worried that she would be
overwhelmed by taking classes and teaching 21 fourth-graders at
Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Oh, my gosh, this is going to be too much,' '' she
said. ``I've got to have my own classroom and jump into what I've
been going to school for, but the problem was the (UMKC) classes.
But I was loving the kids and coming to (Moore) and teaching. That
kept me motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   To avoid problems next year, the interns will take the UMKC
courses in the summer, so they can focus on teaching in the fall.
Then in the spring, when they've settled into the classroom
teaching, they will teach and take a UMKC seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating fall course work also should solve a complaint
principals had. Often the interns had to leave quickly to get to
class, so it was hard to schedule staff meetings everyone could
attend.
</P>
<P>
   Some weaknesses also emerged with the mentoring piece of the
internship program.
</P>
<P>
   Each intern worked with a mentor _ a veteran teacher _ at the
elementary school. In a few cases the mentor and intern team
taught, which allowed a lot of interaction.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, however, the mentor had an entire classroom to run, as
did the intern. The mentor was supposed to observe the intern's
teaching at times, and the intern was to watch the mentor teach,
too. They also were to discuss challenges and share ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Busy classrooms made it hard to do enough observing.
</P>
<P>
   So next year two interns will be assigned to the same mentor.
The mentor's normal class will be split in two, and each intern
will take half the class. Instead of teaching all day, the mentor
will take turns observing and planning with each intern.
</P>
<P>
   That could make the experience look more like what goes on in
the third-grade Paige Elementary classroom of mentor Linda May and
intern Anthony Butler.
</P>
<P>
   They team-teach 29 students; Butler is responsible for preparing
his lesson plans and running the classroom jointly with May.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent school day, Butler began by writing the day's
journal assignment on the chalkboard: ``If you were to come up with
a new holiday, what would it be? Why would you celebrate it?
Explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler likes to get the children thinking and writing. They did
not feel comfortable writing last September, but they do now after
writing in a journal for about 10 minutes every morning.
</P>
<P>
   He has learned that ``the only way to deal with a weakness is to
meet it head on.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael, the fifth-grade teacher at Moore, has learned from
being in the classroom that teachers cannot be rigid about what
they believe from reading books.
</P>
<P>
   While studying to be a teacher, she had thought that children
studied quietly most of the time and that giving out rewards _ such
as parties with popcorn and pop _ was bad.
</P>
<P>
   Now she knows better.
</P>
<P>
   After teaching 14 fifth-graders all day every day for a year,
she knows children are noisy. And bribes work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
