r a BC-VETERANS-SHRINE-KAN &LR;      05-28 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-SHRINE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR II VETERAN REMEMBERS NEIGHBORS WHO DIDN'T MAKE IT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 CAIT PURINTON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Six decades ago, Kansas City's neighborhoods
sent their sons to liberate Europe and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   One of those neighborhoods was the West Side. And one of its
sons was Augustine Cisneros. He returned from World War II, though
with an arm scarred by German shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   Now just months shy of 80, Cisneros reflects on those young men
from the West Side, those who attended Our Lady of Guadalupe
Church, those who went to war and those who never returned.
</P>
<P>
   On this Memorial Day, and for every day of the last couple
years, a memorial in front of Cisneros' Kansas City home pays
tribute to five men from the old neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made me put it up was that nobody was thinking of the
veterans from the West Side,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In making sure that passers-by remember, Cisneros did something
usually reserved for governments, foundations and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Vern Pall, spokesman for the Veterans of Foreign Wars, said in
16 years at the VFW, he's never heard of anyone constructing a
memorial on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of refutes what people are saying,'' Pall said. ``The
war is not being forgotten. The veterans aren't being forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros' son, Tony, helped build the memorial's brick base and
install a flag pole and lighting. A plaque attached to the front
lists the names of five ``World War II West Side Boys.''
</P>
<P>
   A ceramic angel sits above their names: Ralph Sifuentes, Ted
Orozco, Albert Valdivia, Jesse Marino and Monche Cano.
</P>
<P>
   Of the five, Cisneros was closest to Cano. They went to Army
basic training together and later shipped out for North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   While in North Africa, Cisneros, Cano and other soldiers lined
up waiting for their assignments. Cano's name was called to join
the 34th Division. Cisneros' was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they said his name, I got out of line and went to hug him
and said, `Oh, I wish I could go with the 34th Division,' &UR; ''
Cisneros said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last time they saw each other. Cano died in North
Africa in 1943, Cisneros said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros went to Italy as part of a machine gun team in the 1st
Armored Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighting the war is like going to hell,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``War,'' he said, his voice trailing off, ``it's a terrible
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   His last day in combat was Jan. 5, 1944.
</P>
<P>
   That entire day the Americans fought the Germans in Italy. As it
grew dark, Cisneros said, the Germans burned a nearby train depot
for light.
</P>
<P>
   Then the shriek of a shell sliced the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you heard them scream, you better watch out,'' Cisneros
said. ``It sounded like an alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   The shell exploded and hot shrapnel set his coat sleeve on fire
and mangled his left arm.
</P>
<P>
   Two medics put him on a stretcher to carry him out of the line
of fire. But when shells began to fall, the medics dropped him and
ran. When they came back, Cisneros asked them how long they had
been in combat. They told him it was their first day.
</P>
<P>
   Then he asked them to take him off the stretcher. The medics
hoisted him on their shoulders and Cisneros directed them to a
nearby ravine where they were safe from the cross fire.
</P>
<P>
   Later he went to a field hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``After sleeping in the foxholes,'' Cisneros said, ``I had never
felt sheets that felt so good as that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon his return to the United States, he was taken to a hospital
in Springfield, Mo. While in the hospital, he and his girlfriend,
Mary Louise Guerra, were married. Cisneros returned to Kansas City
and became a bartender.
</P>
<P>
   Today their home on Karnes Boulevard is decorated with
photographs of their children, grandchildren and
great-grandchildren. And two paintings depicting the medics
carrying Cisneros off the front lines hang in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the paintings came while the couple visited their
daughter in South Dakota. At an art show, Cisneros saw a painting
of a waterfall at night. The colors and mood reminded him of the
day he was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   He got the name of the artist, Robert Bruce, and called him.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce said he jumped at the chance to do the paintings because
he had always been interested in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros mailed Bruce pictures of himself and told Bruce his
story of his last day in combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to talking to Gus because he would add
details each time I talked to him,'' Bruce said. ``After talking to
him for a while and reading my notes, the picture just popped in my
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Tears come to Cisneros' eyes now as he sits under the paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my mother pray for me,'' he said. ``I was real
respectful to my mother. I think that's why God saved me.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the past few years that Cisneros began to talk
about his days in combat, or the day God saved his life in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cisneros talks proudly about his Purple Heart and two
Battle Stars. And he wants the World War II West Boys remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people forget about those boys who died over there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
