<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-PRISONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH THREE LOCKUPS COMING ON LINE, MISSOURI PRISONS STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 KIT WAGAR  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sidebar to KANSAS-PRISONS)
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON CITY, Mo. _ Missouri also is struggling with a growing
prison population, despite plans to open three prisons in the next
18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Corrections Department spokesman Tim Kniest said Missouri's
prison population of 27,212 is only slightly above the operational
capacity of 27,170. But that population is 150 percent of what the
prisons were designed to hold.
</P>
<P>
   To boost capacity, the state has to come up with creative ways
to house the extra inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You put beds anywhere you can,'' Kniest said. ``You have
temporary bunks in day rooms or in other secure areas that are
designed for other uses.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowding is bad enough at several prisons that they are
under court supervision. Kniest said the inmate population at
high-security prisons in Jefferson City, Moberly and Pacific and a
medium-security prison just outside Jefferson City cannot be
expanded without court approval.
</P>
<P>
   To handle new inmates, the state has three prisons under
construction that will boost capacity by nearly 20 percent. A
1,596-bed maximum-security prison is scheduled to open next month
in Licking.
</P>
<P>
   The penitentiary will relieve crowding at prisons designed to
handle the most violent offenders, but it won't solve the overall
problem, Kniest said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't help us handle the overflow at medium-security
prisons,'' he said. ``It's not a matter of just having enough beds.
It's a matter of having enough beds for each class of inmate.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other prisons _ one medium-security and one high-security _
are under construction. They will house about 3,400 inmates and are
expected to open in the fall of 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
