<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GREEN-BUILDINGS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK LEADS WAY IN REWARDING DEVELOPERS FOR `GREEN' BUILDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York state has taken the lead in making
commercial and residential buildings more efficient and more in
harmony with the environment by adopting a ``green building
credit'' against state income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The credit, which was included in the state budget signed into
law by Gov. George Pataki on May 15, is intended to encourage
building owners and developers to use advanced technologies like
fuel cells and photovoltaic panels to generate electricity and to
use materials that improve air quality inside buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge deal,'' said Robert F. Fox Jr., a partner in
Fox &AMP; Fowle Architects, which specializes in environmentally
sensitive design. ``Basically, the state is offering to pay
developers for the excess costs of doing green buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   Green buildings are generally defined as those that use energy
more efficiently than those with conventional designs and that
provide workers with well-lighted spaces furnished with an
abundance of clean air. One of the objectives of designing a green
building is to avoid using carpets, paints or other interior
materials that can release harmful chemicals after being installed.
</P>
<P>
   The credit is limited to $25 million for all projects over five
years. It was advocated by an unusual alliance, including the Real
Estate Board of New York, which represents owners, developers and
brokers, and the Natural Resources Defense Council, a major
environmental advocacy group. Similar bills are in the works in
Maryland and California, but New York's law appears to be the
first, according to the council.
</P>
<P>
   ``This collaborative effort is a prototype for other states and
eventually the federal government to follow,'' said Deborah B.
Beck, executive vice president of the Real Estate Board.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation provides a credit of 5 percent of the
capitalized cost of a project _ up to $3.75 per square foot for
interior work and $7.50 per square foot for exterior work _ to
builders who meet energy goals and use nontoxic materials in
construction. To qualify, a building must meet requirements for
energy use, indoor air quality, waste disposal and water use.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a credit equivalent to 10 percent of the cost of
new air-conditioning equipment that uses refrigerants that do not
harm the ozone layer. There are additional credits for tenants who
build their interior space to conform with the goals.
</P>
<P>
   Builders using fuel cells and photovoltaic panels, which produce
electricity without the pollution associated with conventional
power sources, are eligible for special additional credits. Both
technologies also have the potential to produce power more cheaply
than conventional methods, but they tend to be more costly because
they are less developed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point of the legislation is to jump-start industries,''
Ms. Beck said. ``We want to go from custom installations to mass
production. We want to bring more people into the marketplace and
make it more competitive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fuel cells produce electricity by consuming natural gas in a
catalytic process that does not burn the fuel. The only emissions
are carbon dioxide and water, in contrast to the mixture of
chemicals flowing from the stacks of plants burning fossil fuels.
The technology is evolving rapidly, Fox said. ``In five years, fuel
cells will be able to provide power at one-third the current
cost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Photovoltaic panels convert sunlight directly to electricity
with no emissions at all. Although individually they do not produce
much power, they can replace conventional materials in the skin of
a building, and when wired together they can produce usable amounts
of power without any expenditure for fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Durst, whose new Conde Nast building in Manhattan
incorporates both fuel cells and photovoltaic panels, welcomed the
legislation, but had some reservations. Because there is a
year-to-year limit on the total tax credits that can be claimed, he
said, there should be a way of preventing one big project from
absorbing most of one year's allotment.
</P>
<P>
   Participants in the discussions about the legislation said the
five-year limit of $25 million was inserted to demonstrate fiscal
prudence. But they said the cap might be raised or the time period
extended if the program succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   Durst also said a mechanism needs to be developed ``to help
smaller builders who do not know to apply these technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   He said his company, the Durst Organization, would continue to
incorporate green technologies despite a delay in financial
benefits that other developers found unacceptable. ``We are a
family business that is building for the next generation, so we
don't mind long paybacks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investments in advanced technology in the Conde Nast building
allow the company to operate it more economically than conventional
structures, Durst said.
</P>
<P>
   William Rudin, whose Rudin Management Co. is building a
headquarters for Reuters in Manhattan, said the building
incorporated technologies included in the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the wiring in the building could use power from
fuel cells and photovoltaic panels and that space had been
allocated to install the cells.
</P>
<P>
   The Reuters building also includes filters to improve indoor air
quality and glass that resists ultraviolet rays, reducing the
amount of power needed for cooling.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel R. Tishman, the president of Tishman Construction, which
managed the construction of both buildings, was part of a group of
business leaders and environmentalists that helped draft the tax
credit. ``Since it costs a bit more up front,'' he said, ``we
wanted to design an incentive _ like an investment tax credit _ to
encourage developers and landlords to do what's right for the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, the architect for both buildings, said the tax credits
would pay 30 percent of the cost of buying fuel cells, less federal
or state grants. And, he said, they would pay for 100 percent of
the cost of the solar power panels, minus the cost of building
materials that would have been used otherwise.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
