<HEADER>
A8268 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KANSAS-PRISONS-KAN &LR;      05-28 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-PRISONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONY RIZZO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 COUNTDOWN IS ON AS kANSAS PREPARES TO CUT PRISON POPULATION  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ Kansas prison officials are doing a lot of number
crunching these days.
</P>
<P>
   So are thousands of convicted felons, whether they're behind
bars or on probation or parole.
</P>
<P>
   All of them are counting down to Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That's the deadline for selecting the hundreds or possibly
thousands of state prisoners who will be set free as part of the
Kansas Legislature's ``corrections megabill.''
</P>
<P>
   Facing a growing prison population, the Legislature this year
approved a package of measures aimed at easing crowding without
sacrificing public safety.
</P>
<P>
   Although the moves are expected to create immediate relief for
the state's near-capacity prison system, they are likely to put an
extra burden on local jails and corrections programs. And they
don't do much to address the continuing need for cells to house the
state's most dangerous criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many who work in the Kansas criminal justice system think
the changes are better than alternatives such as cutting prison
sentences across the board or spending millions to build more
cells.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Corrections did get $6 million for an
additional 100 beds at its Ellsworth Correctional Facility, but it
says more are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this bill in its entirety as a balanced, reasonable
compromise,'' Kansas Secretary of Corrections Charles Simmons said.
</P>
<P>
   Simmons' department is determining which inmates will be set
free. It's a task he said he hopes will be completed by the end of
June.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 800 prison beds will be freed up, according to
initial estimates by the Kansas Sentencing Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners who will be freed include burglars, thieves, drug
users, bad-check writers and people who violated technical
conditions of probation or parole.
</P>
<P>
   Those who won't be released include murderers, sex offenders,
armed robbers, drug dealers and those who committed new crimes
while on probation or parole.
</P>
<P>
   An additional 1,200 to 1,500 inmates will be released from
parole, or ``post-release supervision,'' over the next six months
to a year, according to the estimates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reasonable, short-term fix,'' said Johnson County
District Attorney Paul Morrison, a member of the Kansas Sentencing
Commission, which recommended some of the changes. ``But the
reality is that as time goes on, we will need more and more prison
beds for the most dangerous inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   When the state overhauled its sentencing system in 1993, the
intent was to reserve prison space for violent repeat offenders
while offering community-based alternatives for lesser offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Legislature has beefed up the guidelines even
more, in some cases doubling or tripling the sentences for the most
serious crimes.
</P>
<P>
   That part of the guidelines is meeting its goal: Violent
offenders are being locked up longer.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the people who get chances at probation and parole who
are ending up in prison in greater numbers _ not for committing new
crimes, but for basically being irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Last fiscal year, 67 percent of admissions into the state prison
system were parole or probation violators who did not commit new
crimes, according to the Department of Corrections.
</P>
<P>
   They did things such as move without telling their probation
officers, fail to show up for drug tests or miss restitution
payments. Some of them drank alcohol or used drugs.
</P>
<P>
   It's that group of conditional violators that this year's
legislation addresses on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Among the measures adopted:
</P>
<P>
   _ Most of the conditional violators in prison are to be released
and will not be required to be on parole after they get out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probation and parole time that must be served will be cut in
half for those convicted of the lowest-level crimes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Conditional probation violators must be sent to local
community corrections programs instead of being sent to prison.
Additional violations could result in prison.
</P>
<P>
   _ Likewise, conditional parole violators first will be sent to
new day-reporting centers before being sent to prison. The
privately operated centers will be established in Kansas City,
Kan.; Topeka; and Wichita to handle a combined 220 offenders. They
will provide an intermediate sanction that is not now available.
Officials hope to have them in operation by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the legislation, officials in community
corrections programs that already are in place across the state
expect to see an increase in the number of offenders they
supervise.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County Corrections Director Michael Youngken said his
department has 565 persons in its intensive supervision program. It
also operates a 208-bed residential work-release facility.
</P>
<P>
   Although his department will have to make do without a
corresponding budget increase, Youngken said the Legislature
initially had looked at slashing local corrections money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I applaud the Legislature for the work they did in this
area,'' Youngken said. ``It wasn't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison said people who commit new crimes while on probation or
parole still will be sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   But providing an additional sanction short of prison for
conditional violators is a good way to ``hold their feet to the
fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to punish some of them is to hold them
responsible and make them go to work,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The law allows a conditional violator to be sent directly to
prison if a judge finds that placing him in community corrections
would jeopardize public safety.
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the law that is likely to have a significant
effect on local jails is the doubling of jail ``shock time'' that
judges can impose as part of probation. It will be increased from
30 days to 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one way to get an offender's attention, particularly a
young offender,'' Morrison said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
