<HEADLINE>
TASK FORCE MAKES PROGRESS IN CAPTURING VIOLENT FUGITIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Think things are piling up where you work?
</P>
<P>
   Consider what Tom Nunemaker, the FBI supervisor for the Violent
Crime//Fugitive Task Force, has to face when he goes to work every
morning: at least 6,500 active arrest warrants in the Kansas City
area.
</P>
<P>
   But Nunemaker's task force _ comprising four FBI agents and two
detectives each from the Kansas City and Kansas City, Kan., police
departments _ is making headway against that tidal wave of paper.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the task force, which was formed in January
1993, chalked up its 2,000th fugitive arrest when FBI agents
captured convicted child abuser Josie Copkney, 26, in a Gladstone,
Mo., apartment building. Copkney quickly was returned to court,
where she was sentenced to 20 years in prison for abusing her
9-week-old daughter in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we got a pretty dangerous individual off the street,''
Nunemaker said.
</P>
<P>
   The task force focuses only on the most violent local fugitives,
those for whom warrants already have been issued for crimes such as
murder, rape, robbery and burglary. Larry McCormick, the FBI agent
in charge of the Kansas City office, said the key to the squad's
success is the remarkable cooperation it has forged on all levels
of law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a partnership designed to make the city a safer place,''
McCormick said. ``The task force has been a tremendous success in
getting violent criminals off the street. The program targets the
most likely to commit additional crime, so it's preventive
maintenance on the criminal element.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police Detective Al DeValkenaere, a member of the
task force, said the diversity of experience on the squad and the
ability to bring both federal and local resources to bear on a
problem accounts for much of the team's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody brings something to the table,'' DeValkenaere said.
``The FBI has unbelievable resources nationwide. It works because
we have places to go with the information. We can call people in
others cities who do the same kind of work, and because of the
serious nature of the crimes, the information doesn't just sit
around.''
</P>
<P>
   DeValkenaere said the cooperation of fugitives' friends and
family, as well as community resources such as the TIPS Hotline,
also are important to the squad. Assuring relatives that task-force
members just want to bring the fugitive in safely can generate
worthwhile leads and result in significant arrests, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes for a very satisfying line of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just putting the bad guy in jail,'' DeValkenaere said.
``It's what police work should be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
