</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECTION-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES(1020)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUJIMORI THE VICTOR IN RUNOFF ELECTION; PROTESTERS TAKE TO THE
STREETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: SUBS lede with Fujimori winning, updates estimate of
demonstrators in 4th graf, inserts 6th graf to add percentages with
virtually all of vote counted; minor changes elsewhere; subs
overline.) 
By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ In a runoff vote long on protest but short on
suspense, President Alberto Fujimori swept to victory Sunday
against an opponent who had urged his supporters to abstain because
of what he called vote fraud and an array of campaign
irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori had hoped for a third landslide victory that would
venerate his successes defeating two terrorist groups and
hyperinflation and making peace with Ecuador after decades of
border tensions. Instead, the 61-year-old leader won a hollow
victory leaving the country badly polarized and facing possible
economic sanctions just as it tries to emerge from recession.
</P>
<P>
   The balloting capped a campaign full of dirty tricks, violent
demonstrations and condemnations from Fujimori's opponent,
Alejandro Toledo, who withdrew on May 18 _ too late to pull his
name off the ballot. The Clinton administration, France, Britain,
Canada, Argentina and Costa Rica echoed Toledo's criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   Even before voting drew to a close, demonstrations grew more
intense and downtown Lima was filled with the pungent smell of tear
gas. Government helicopters buzzed overhead as a crowd of some tens
of thousands of demonstrators assembled Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   In Chimbote, a northern port and Toledo's hometown, armored
vehicles rolled through the streets as police broke up
anti-Fujimori demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   With virtually all of the vote count- ed, Fujimori had 50.8
percent while Toledo had 16.7 percent, with the rest of the ballots
left blank or nullified.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization of American States released a report last week
saying, ``the Peruvian electoral process is far from one that could
be considered free and fair,'' noting that government funding was
used in the Fujimori campaign, media access was dominated by the
president, and that there was not enough time to inspect new
computer vote tabulation software to assure a fair count.
</P>
<P>
   Before a single vote was cast, election observers from the
Organization of American States and the Carter Center, based in
Atlanta, had withdrawn in disgust after they failed to persuade the
government to postpone the election. Toledo, the only challenger on
the ballot, did not vote and told reporters the election was as
``fraudulent as a soccer game in which the field is tilted and one
side chooses the referees and the reporters who cover the
contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's bid for a third term has stirred opposition here ever
since Congress fired three judges more than two years ago for
ruling that a constitutional ban on a third presidential term
prohibited the president from running. Fujimori argued that he
could run since the constitution was written after his first term,
meaning the ban would only apply if he ran for a fourth term.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters appeared to be going through the motion of voting in
an election that lacked drama after Toledo pulled out 10 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no institution in this country that is free
anymore,'' said Enrique Fernandez, a 48-year-old folk music
promoter, before voting in the working-class neighborhood of Rimac
in order to avoid a $35 fine for not voting or problems with the
police. ``The Justice Ministry and election authorities are totally
controlled and this is all a fraud.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a 54-year-old business professor who was educated in the
United States, insisted that Sunday's uncontested election would
hurl Peru into uncharted, turbulent political currents. Once
re-elected to a third term, he said, Fujimori ``will be a permanent
source of political instability that will have permanent economic
consequences. I can assure you he will not last very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Toledo predicted that protests around the country will
gather momentum. There have already been strikes and road blockades
in the cities of Iquitos, Cuzco and Chiclayo in recent days, as
well as several violent incidents in Lima, including rock and
firebomb attacks by university students on the presidential palace
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The tainted Peruvian election will dominate a meeting of foreign
ministers of the countries belonging to the Organization of
American States scheduled to meet in Canada this week. The
ministers could ultimately decide on sanctions, although in the
past severe action has been taken only in cases of coup d'etats or
other overt interruptions of democratic process.
</P>
<P>
   It is more likely sanctions will come from the United States,
where Congress has already passed a joint resolution calling for a
review of all political, economic and military relations with Peru.
Still, it remains doubtful Washington will cut deeply into
assistance that goes toward Peru's efforts at combating terrorism
and narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration pushed hard for Fujimori to hold a
second-round vote during a questionable slow count in the days
following the first-round of balloting on April 9. But in recent
weeks Washington has softened its criticism of Peru and allowed the
Organization of American States, a usually cautious regional
organization, to take the lead in pushing for democratic reform
here.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, President Clinton had strong words for Peru on
Friday, the day after election authorities had already decided to
go ahead with vote. ``Free, fair and open elections are the
foundation of a democratic society,'' he said. ``Without them, our
relationship with Peru inevitably will be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori is counting on the United States to go easy on him,
rather than jeopardize the cooperation of the two countries in
economic, anti-terrorism and especially anti-drug programs that
have halved this country's coca plant production in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be terrible if our anti-narcotics collaboration was
upset and we will continue to welcome U.S. investment,'' Fujimori
said. ``These are elements in our relations that will supersede
whatever tensions arise from the election.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori used an assortment of sweet carrots and rather sharp
sticks on his way to a third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   In a wave of populism, he raised the minimum wage and handed out
land titles to 150,000 peasants during the campaign. But Fujimori
was also besieged by criticism from international election
observers for a range of campaign irregularities. Poor mothers
dependent on government milk and food handouts were pressured to
attend Fujimori rallies, for example, and intelligence agents
followed and harassed opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Many tabloid newspapers that have connections to Fujimori's
intelligence service and all television networks save for one cable
television station either did not cover the Toledo campaign or
tilted their coverage toward salacious and unproved allegations of
financial fraud, sexual innuendo and claims that he had an
illegitimate daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, a journalist who said he had videotapes showing
Fujimori's intelligence chief meeting with election officials was
assaulted by three unidentified men. From a hospital bed, he said
the assailants cut his wrist to the bone with a saw as they
demanded he disclose his sources inside the intelligence agency.
</P>
<P>
   In the hours following the April 9 vote, cries of fraud arose
when ballots and tally sheets disappeared for several hours.
Election authorities only announced that Fujimori did not receive
the required majority to avert a second round after three days of
heavy international pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo ran a strong race in the April first round, promising to
give the poor jobs and to disentangle the courts and congress from
the tight grip of presidential control.
</P>
<P>
   But he appeared to fumble badly when he suddenly sought to drop
out of the race 10 days ago, claiming that he was not willing to
lead his supporters into a fraudulent vote unless the election date
was postponed several weeks to give international observers an
opportunity to audit computer software designed to count ballots.
</P>
<P>
   He slid in a variety of opinion polls, as voters either
expressed disappointment in his apparent surrender or dismay that
he was willing to incite unrest and damage the image of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   A poll conducted by Datum Internacional between May 19 and 22,
which only the week before had shown a virtual tie between the two
candidates, showed that 55 percent of voters disapproved of
Toledo's decision to drop out of the race. The poll also showed
Fujimori leading Toledo by a 54-46 percent margin, suggesting that
Fujimori could win a clean, free election anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo's argument that he was a victim of fraud was also hurt by
public criticism levied at him by the head of the observation team
from the Organization American States, who said Toledo's
oscillating position on conditions for competing in the runoff made
it more difficult to negotiate a delay in the election date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
