r a BC-RIVER-DRUGS-KAN &LR;      05-28 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVER-DRUGS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINUTE QUANTITIES OF EVERYDAY MEDICINES APPEAR IN WORLD'S WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 MICHAEL MANSUR and JOHN MARTELLARO  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In the rivers of America, from which most of
us draw water to drink, something new and seemingly unusual is
being detected _ drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The stuff of your medicine cabinets _ antibiotics, pain
relievers, birth control pills and beta blockers _ is becoming a
common contaminant in the waters of the modern world, passed from
humans to sewage treatment plants, and then discharged into streams
and rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Whether these drugs pose a threat to humans is not yet known,
federal officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Kansas City water department say they have run
new, sophisticated tests on drinking water to see whether it has
been contaminated by these pharmaceuticals and by chemicals from
personal-care products, such as shampoos or suntan oils.
</P>
<P>
   So far, they say, they have not found a trace. But the
Environmental Protection Agency also is looking at the levels of
the contaminants in drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of concern. This is the current hot topic,''
said Connie Hull, who oversees the Kansas City water department's
laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide studies are under way to determine how many of these
``emerging contaminants'' are in rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest effect will probably be on fish and other aquatic
species that must live today with a little bit of caffeine,
synthetic hormones from birth control pills and other
pharmaceuticals, said Christian Daughton, an EPA researcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``What little that is known serves to show that rather low
concentrations at least have the potential to exert substantive
effects on aquatic life,'' Daughton wrote in a recent critical
review of research on these new pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, certain anti-depressants can alter the spawning
behavior of shellfish.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, studies have shown that sewage discharges containing
synthetic or natural sex hormones may be changing the reproductive
organs in fish.
</P>
<P>
   A 1996 study examined Mississippi River carp below sewage
treatment discharge pipes in the St. Paul, Minn., area and found
that their blood hormone levels were altered, especially compared
with fish in a pristine stream.
</P>
<P>
   In U.S. households, pharmaceuticals, perfumes and shampoos are
as common as peanut butter but probably occupy a lot more shelf
space.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, is not all flowing out of our households.
High levels of chemotherapy and other drugs have been found
downstream of hospitals. And below the giant new hog farms of the
Midwest, researchers are detecting animal hormones and antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists worry that the increased use of antibiotics may lead
to contamination of the waters, increasing the potential to create
more bacteria strains that are resistant to the drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Don Wilkison, who works in the U.S. Geological Survey's office
in Independence, routinely finds a wide assortment of
pharmaceuticals and personal-care products in the waters of Brush
Creek and the Blue River:
</P>
<P>
   Acetaminophen. Ibuprofen. Heart medicine. And, of course,
caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   The levels are barely detectable. Even so, they raise a concern.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkison cannot say whether those chemicals, at such minute
levels, pose problems for the creatures that live in the Blue River
or Brush Creek. He noted, however, that a lot of chemicals _
including pesticides and synthetic fertilizers _ already are in the
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Mix it all together, Wilkison said, and ``we really don't know
what's happening in the ecosystem.''
</P>
<P>
   The human body breaks down some medicines, but other drugs, once
taken, can stay potent after they leave your body. Others are
rendered inert after human consumption but reactivate when mixed
with chemicals during sewage treatment or in the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment plants settle out and remove most contaminants, but
not all. Plant managers generally focus on pollutants for which
they must meet federal standards. Pharmaceuticals and chemicals
from personal-care products are not regulated under laws for sewage
or drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The pharmaceuticals also might be dumped into streams and rivers
in areas, such as Kansas City, that have combined pipes for storm
water and sewage, designed to overflow during heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   Only in recent years have scientists begun to look for traces of
pharmaceuticals. It is only recently that laboratory analysis
became sophisticated enough to detect such tiny amounts of the
pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators say much more research will be required to
determine whether they should limit the amount of these pollutants
in sewage discharges.
</P>
<P>
   The first concerns about these contaminants were raised in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 a study found traces of pharmaceuticals below the Big
Blue Sewage Treatment Plant. At the time, that plant treated
three-fourths of Kansas City's sewage.
</P>
<P>
   The study found drugs and the products of their breakdown in the
city's sewage effluent. When it tested drinking water in Kansas
City and St. Charles, it did not find the pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be well to consider further evaluation of public
drinking water supplies for the presence of drugs consumed in large
quantities,'' were the study's final words.
</P>
<P>
   For years little follow-up appeared.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, however, researchers in Europe were
documenting the same phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Swiss chemists were searching for the levels of an
herbicide in lake water when they found a chemical they could not
identify at first. It turned out to be clofibric acid, a
cholesterol drug in common use there. It was also the same drug
identified in the Kansas City study in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   When the scientists tested other lakes and rivers in Europe,
they found the drug in almost all cases. They could find no
industrial spill to explain such contamination. Their only
explanation: It must come from human wastes.
</P>
<P>
   More recently German scientists expanded the search, finding 30
to 60 drugs in the typical water sample, although at extremely low
levels.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, researchers in northern Europe have continued to
find traces of pharmaceuticals in rivers, lakes and the North Sea.
</P>
<P>
   It is only in the former East Berlin, said Daughton of the EPA,
that traces of pharmaceuticals have been found in public drinking
water supplies. That is probably because treatment plants there are
fairly primitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal opinion is that if there's going to be a problem,
I don't think drinking water is where it'll be,'' Daughton said
last week. ``It'll be in the aquatic realm.''
</P>
<P>
   But researchers have many more questions to answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just starting in this country with the research,''
Daughton said. ``Almost all the research for the last 10 or 15
years has been done in Europe, primarily in Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug companies are required to test new drugs to determine the
toxicity to creatures in the environment. Daughton wonders whether
those tests are adequate to detect the subtle changes that might be
produced by low concentrations of these chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   And no one has assessed what happens chemically when these
compounds mix, Daughton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For decades all we've been looking at has been pesticides and
industrial pollutants,'' Daughton said. ``But there's a whole world
of other compounds that get into the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, with so much left to be done before the extent of the
problem can be known, Daughton likes to keep the focus on
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really not the pharmaceutical companies' issue,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's you and I who consume these things. So it's you and I who
are potentially causing the pollution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-URBAN-RENEWAL-NYT &LR;      05-28 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-URBAN-RENEWAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PART OF NEW YORK, THE BOOM REMAINS A BUST 
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It has been over three decades since Sen. Robert F.
Kennedy cast a spotlight on the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of
Brooklyn by making it the focus of a bold new economic development
program. The uniting of ``the best of community action with the
best of the private enterprise system,'' he said, could make a
model urban neighborhood rise from the ashes of ``physical decay
and human despair.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, the plan worked. Its most visible achievement was
the conversion of an abandoned milk-bottling plant in the heart of
the neighborhood into a shopping plaza and cultural center.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more: Hundreds of homes were rehabilitated,
thousands of jobs were created, the neighborhood got its first
large supermarket in years, and IBM brought in a computer-cable
production factory that once employed 450 people.
</P>
<P>
   A generation later, however, the predominantly black New York
neighborhood that is reaping the benefits of a robust economy is
Harlem, not Bedford-Stuyvesant.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being central to current political and economic plans
for reviving neglected areas, Bedford-Stuyvesant has receded into
the shadows, community leaders say. Some blame the perception of
rampant crime, even though crime is down. Others say Harlem has
more political clout in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But many people both inside and outside Bedford-Stuyvesant also
say that the organization that was intended to help bring
prosperity to central Brooklyn _ Bedford-Stuyvesant Restoration
Corp. _ has served as an impediment to progress, an entrenched and
sluggish bureaucracy instead of a spark plug for local
entrepreneurs and nationally known merchants.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning rod for some of the criticism is Roderick B.
Mitchell, the president and chief executive of Restoration for the
last 12 years. His detractors call him prickly and arrogant,
incapable of working cooperatively with other community leaders.
Some local business owners say he has opposed efforts to bring new
jobs to the area.
</P>
<P>
   But Mitchell cited several new businesses in Restoration Plaza
and the organization's continuing support of several longstanding
cultural programs, including an art gallery and two theaters. He
also pointed to a $9.8 million project, which is nearing
completion, to make the fortresslike Restoration Plaza more
inviting.
</P>
<P>
   Restoration, a nonprofit corporation, oversees 11 subsidiaries.
In its early years, Mitchell said, an estimated 80 percent of the
company's revenue came from government sources, but in more recent
years, it has received most of its money from rent and other
earnings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's glory days seem to have ended. Once a model
for about 2,000 community development corporations across the
United States, Restoration is now running large deficits ($990,000
this past fiscal year, and $1.6 million the year before).
Restoration-sponsored construction has ceased, and the organization
has managed to attract only a few new businesses to the
neighborhood in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   When IBM moved out in 1993, the company was replaced by an
employee-owned computer-repair business, where only 30 people now
work. During the last fiscal year, Restoration reported that it
spent $2.6 million on its programs, only $130,000 of which was used
for economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Bedford-Stuyvesant's problems are apparent on Fulton
Street, the bustling main commercial thoroughfare. It has street
vendors, 99-cent stores, beauty and nail salons, jewelry and liquor
stores, but few essential services like dry cleaners and sit-down
restaurants. There are no movie theaters, bookstores or record
stores.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, many other explanations for the slow pace
of commercial development in Bedford-Stuyvesant, a community of
about 140,000 people. Central Brooklyn, home to about 300,000
people, has no politician to match Charles Rangel, the Harlem
congressman who was instrumental in obtaining hundreds of millions
of federal, state and city dollars for his district. Nor does it
have the high density that many retailers seek.
</P>
<P>
   To out-of-town retail executives (and even many New Yorkers),
Bedford-Stuyvesant is a still a scary place, and even some local
merchants remain fearful.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood could support some of the amenities that are
cropping up in Fort Greene, a predominantly black middle-class area
of Brooklyn _ coffee bars, art galleries and other urban ``eye
candy,'' said Colvin W. Grannum, the chief executive of Bridge
Street Development Corp., a church-affiliated group that has worked
closely with the New York City Housing Partnership to develop
affordable housing.
</P>
<P>
   But first the community has to advertise its strengths, he said.
``Forty percent of the people are poor, and business people look at
that and say, `There is no way this is going to work,''' Grannum
said. ``But the other 60 percent is solid, working-class families,
and there is even some affluence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
