</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WENDYS-MURDERS-515&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO CHARGED IN WENDY'S KILLINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two men facing an avalanche of evidence in a
notorious case that could lead to the death penalty were arraigned
in a Queens court Sunday on murder and robbery charges in last
week's execution-style massacre at a Wendy's restaurant that left
five workers slain and two others shot and left for dead.
</P>
<P>
   As the suspects, John B. Taylor, 36, and Craig Godineaux, 30,
stood silently in a packed courtroom, a prosecutor described in
gripping detail how the victims were bound, gagged and blindfolded
with duct tape, their heads were covered with plastic bags, and
they were shot one by one as they knelt in a freezer room.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were marched single file into a big freezer box,'' the
prosecutor, Gregory L. Lasak, told Judge Michael Aloise of Criminal
Court in a voice trembling with emotion. ``They were told to get on
their knees, and they were each shot by the defendants once in the
head.''
</P>
<P>
   Lasak, the executive assistant in charge of major cases in the
office of the Queens district attorney, said each of the
defendants, who were arrested on Friday less than 48 hours after
the killings, had made a videotaped confession implicating himself
and his accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   The admissions, he said, included a ``calculated plan'' to rob
the Wendy's in Flushing, where Taylor had worked last fall, and to
kill the workers to eliminate witnesses. And they included numerous
details about how the executions were carried out and how $2,400 in
cash was stolen.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the confessions, Lasak said, three witnesses, including
one of the surviving victims, have identified the defendants as the
assailants. And the police found in Taylor's possession the gun
used in the crimes and a videotape from Wendy's surveillance camera
showing both suspects, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Lasak described the victims as ``seven hard-working people, and
added: ``The evidence we have to tie these defendants to the case
is overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   The defendants were each charged with 25 counts _ five of
first-degree murder for intentionally killing multiple victims,
five of first-degree murder for the intentional killing of people
during a robbery, 10 of second-degree murder not necessarily
involving intent to kill, two counts of attempted murder, robbery
in the first degree and weapons possession in the second and third
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Conviction of first-degree murder carries a possible death
sentence or life in prison. Under the law, the Queens district
attorney, Richard A. Brown, has 120 days to decide whether to seek
the death penalty. He noted Sunday that he had not yet decided, and
would consider many factors, including the wishes of the victims'
families and what he called the ``callousness, ruthlessness,
character, criminal record and motivation'' of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a decision that I do not take lightly,'' Brown said at a
news conference, at which he spoke with somber confidence about the
strength of the case, calling the evidence ``overwhelming,'' and
saying he expected a grand jury next month to return indictments on
first-degree murder and other charges.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Taylor has worked at fast-food restaurants in New York in recent
years and, the authorities say, tried to rob five fast-food outlets
last year. He has been a fugitive since November for jumping bail.
Godineaux, who has worked recently as a security guard in a
clothing store, has served three prison terms for robbery and drug
offenses in the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects did not enter pleas during the arraignment; that is
customary in hearings when a grand jury has not yet returned an
indictment, especially in potential death-penalty cases. Standing
with their lawyers _ John Youngblood of the state's Capital
Defender Office for Taylor, and Heidi Segal of the Legal Aid
Society's capital defense unit for Godineaux _ they said nothing
during a 20-minute hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, short and heavy-set in a black denim suit, stared
straight ahead, while Godineaux, a tall, rangy man in a black
T-shirt and blue jeans, gazed at the floor. Neither was handcuffed,
but security in the court was tight, with 10 police and court
officers, many of them wearing bulletproof vests, standing by. The
wood-paneled courtroom was crowded mostly with reporters, although
Aloise excluded cameras.
</P>
<P>
   There was little discussion of bail. ``There is no greater risk
of flight than someone who would have this hanging over their
heads,'' Lasak said when the subject came up. Youngblood and Segal
did not pursue it, reserving their bail requests, and Aloise
remanded the suspects for a hearing on June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, officials said, will be held in maximum-security cells
at either Rikers Island, the city's sprawling East River prison
complex, or the Brooklyn House of Detention. At Youngblood's
behest, the judge ordered a suicide watch placed on Taylor, who, in
his confession, said that in the hours before his capture he had
thought about killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   While there appeared to be no friends or relatives of Taylor in
the courtroom, there was a handful of supporters of Godineaux, and
as the suspects were being led away after the hearing, a woman
wearing a red sweater over her head shouted: ``I love you Craig''
and broke out in sobs, crying, ``Oh, God!''
</P>
<P>
   Someone else shouted, ``Burn in hell!''
</P>
<P>
   Unable to get into the small courtroom, which could hold only
about 75 spectators, more than a dozen friends and relatives of the
victims waited outside in a hallway, many of them with eyes red
from crying and with the toll of grief and anger etched on their
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``They deserve what they got coming,'' said Louis Bossler, a
friend of the Wendy's night manager, Jean Dumel Auguste, 27, of
Brooklyn, who had fired Taylor last October and, investigators
said, was the only one of the victims that Taylor acknowledged
shooting with a Bryco .380-caliber semiautomatic pistol that he
bought for $250 earlier this year on a street in Queens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
