<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
4 HURT AS ISRAELIS FIRE AT TAUNTING CIVILIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to rewrite lede and 7th grafs for greater accuracy. Inserts
new 8th graf on official response of Israeli army.)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ Israeli soldiers Sunday fired on Lebanese and
Palestinian civilians who were throwing stones and trying to push
across the border from what was until last week the
Israeli-controlled buffer zone between the two countries. Four
people were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Also in southern Lebanon, a Hezbollah fighter killed a Christian
man, and two Lebanese children were killed and seven people wounded
when their car drove over a land mine on a road.
</P>
<P>
   The events underlined the potentially deadly confusion and
tension that still reign in much of southern Lebanon, four days
after Israel abruptly withdrew its forces from the nine-mile-wide
area it occupied for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Although a parade of Lebanese government officials have visited
the area and claimed victory over Israel, the Lebanese army has
stayed away, leaving to the Hezbollah militia the work of policing
towns and villages and rounding up abandoned Israeli weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah, which waged a long war against Israel and its
Lebanese allies in the south, has deployed hundreds of its fighters
in the area to prevent looting, police villages and pursue members
of the South Lebanon army who worked for Israel during the
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The Muslim guerrillas have sought in recent days to present
themselves as mere custodians of southern Lebanon, acting as a
temporary force of law and order until the government takes over.
But its ability to act as a civil guard, rather than a militia, has
been sorely tested, as the increasingly unruly scenes at the border
fences between Lebanon and Israel have shown.
</P>
<P>
   At Kafr Kila, where the shooting by Israeli soldiers occurred,
barely 15 yards separate Israeli guards and the throngs of Lebanese
and Palestinians who have come to gawk, shout insults and sometimes
throw stones over the border since the pullout. A Hezbollah
official did not make an appearance until late in the day, hours
after Israeli soldiers had lobbed smoke bombs over the fence and
fired on Lebanese and Palestinian protesters. Once there, he urged
the demonstrators to stop throwing stones and trying to push across
the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israeli force at the scene called repeatedly on the
civilians to leave the area,'' the Israeli army said in a
statement, according to Reuters. ``When they did not obey, the
force responded with a stun grenade and then with shots aimed at
the lower body.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary-general of the militia, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah,
has said it is to be expected that, after so many years of
occupation and conflict, Lebanese would express anger and hostility
toward the first Israelis many of them have seen.
</P>
<P>
   But Nasrallah also has sought to reassure the Christians who
live in the former security zone, including those who may have had
family members in the South Lebanon army or who may have found work
in Israel during the isolated years of occupation, that Hezbollah
intends to protect all Lebanese.
</P>
<P>
   In the south Lebanese village of Qlaia, two of Nasrallah's
deputies, Sheik Naim Qassem and Muhammad Raed, made a point of
publicly reassuring the Maronite Christian residents after their
priest canceled Sunday Mass at his St. George Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``He who attacks the residents of Qlaia attacks Hezbollah, and
he who violates the people of the south violates the resistance,''
Raed told villagers outside the church.
</P>
<P>
   The priest, after meeting with the two Hezbollah representatives
in private, later celebrated Mass.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what led to the killing of a Christian man in
the village of Rmeiche earlier in the day. Some villagers told
reporters that the killer was a Hezbollah fighter who wanted
revenge on the dead man's family, which included members of the
South Lebanon army. Others said the killer had opened fire on a
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese police, who have a few hundred men in the south,
called the shooting an ``individual incident,'' and Hezbollah
denied that it had any involvement.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 members of the South Lebanon army and their
families fled to Israel during the withdrawal, although the United
Nations brought several busloads of them back to Lebanon Sunday so
they could surrender to the government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, about 1,500 former militia fighters had given
themselves up to Hezbollah, which has turned them over to the
Lebanese army for trial.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese now also face the problem of clearing Israeli mines
in the former buffer strip. The U.N. officials who are working
along the border to certify Israel's withdrawal have said mines
threaten their safety and have called on Israel to turn over maps
of the mined areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
