<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAINTY CLOUDS FUTURE OF MOTORPLEX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Texas _ Texas Motorplex general manager Elon Werner said
he has heard the rumors about the track losing one of its dates for
2001. He also admitted he does not know what the future of the
Castrol Nationals is, but he has yet to hear anything official from
the National Hot Rod Association about next year's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   And that lack of communication is a concern, Werner said.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been much communication between Texas Motorplex
officials and the NHRA over the past few months, Werner said,
adding he has not seen a tentative schedule for next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had tried to have a number of conversations with the NHRA,
\Rpresident\S Tom Compton and the NHRA hierarchy,'' Werner said.
``We just have gotten nowhere with that. This has not been a
problem that has arisen in the last few weeks. But the realization
is setting in that we have been trying to communicate with \Rthe
NHRA\S and our sponsors have been trying to communicate with \Rthe
NHRA\S, and there has just not been any kind of reciprocal interest
of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorplex president and owner Billy Meyer said Friday that he
would sell the Motorplex if the track did not have two dates next
year. And Werner said Meyer is serious about selling.
</P>
<P>
   Some consider the Motorplex the standard by which all other
drag-racing facilities are judged, with one of the first to have a
wrap-around tower and luxury suites. It cost Meyer around $6
million to build the facility in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a realization of Billy that `I don't want to
fight this anymore,' '' Werner said. ``When Billy says, `Hey,
people are not returning my phone calls and I am trying to get
answers, and no one is getting me answers.' That's a problem. He's
been in this sport for 30 years, and he's seen its low times and
helped it grow.''  &QL; 
One upset, one loss
</P>
<P>
   Reher-Morrison Pro Stock driver Bruce Allen was defeated in the
second round of yesterday's final eliminations by Greg Anderson,
but the Arlington resident said it was a good weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And his first-round victory over No. 1 qualifier Kurt Johnson
may have helped that. Allen, who qualified No. 16, won the race on
the ``hole shot,'' or quicker reaction time at the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's reaction time was 0.408 seconds, while Johnson had a
0.489. Johnson had the quicker ET and speed, but Allen won on the
starting line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our car was a lot faster than 16th, and that was because we
did not make a good run in qualifying this weekend,'' Allen said.
``We made a good run and had a good \Rreaction time\S. \RJohnson\S
made a good run but didn't have a good \Rreaction time\S.''  &QL; 
Tough test
</P>
<P>
   It might have been the toughest test of the all-concrete
quarter-mile Texas Motorplex racing surface since 1986. But after
the final round was over, most praised the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hot and sometimes humid weather this weekend, the
track produced the quickest Funny Car field in NHRA history, and
Gary Scelzi's No. 1 Top Fuel qualifying run was the fastest under
the new 90 percent Nitromethane rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy Meyer had intelligence enough to build an all-concrete
racetrack that holds up in this hot weather,'' said Austin Coil,
who is the co-crew chief for nine-time Funny Car champion John
Force. ``The asphalt just does not hold up in this kind of weather.
 &QL; 
Fiery win
</P>
<P>
   Scotty Cannon's first-round upset of Whit Bazemore produced some
fireworks, literally. Cannon won the matchup after Bazemore's Funny
Car suffered a parts failure, but at the finish line Cannon's
Oakley Camaro Z28 caught fire.
</P>
<P>
   Cannon escaped the fire, but the car was severely damaged. His
crew fixed the car for the second round against Frank Pedregon, but
Cannon did not leave the starting line after his engine shut down.
/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
