<SLUG> BC-RAC-LONESTAR-MILLION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODAY'S FIELD WORTH MUCH MORE THAN A MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ It doesn't take long for jockey Marlon
St. Julien to figure out the event he likes best when he visits
Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the All-Star Jockey Championship because it gives you a
chance to compete against the best riders in the country, a chance
to see how you measure up,'' St. Julien said. ``But this \RLone
Star\S Million Day looks like a pretty good deal.'' In its second
year, Lone Star Million Day appears to placing itself on the banner
of big events at the track. Today's 11-race card features seven
stakes races with purses totaling $1 million. The highlight is the
$300,000 Lone Star Park Handicap, which was regarded well enough by
the North American Graded Stakes Committee that it received a Grade
III status this year. Lone Star officials don't worry that Million
Day will take any of the spotlight from the National Thoroughbred
Racing Association All-Star Jockey Championship, the track's
signature event that will be presented for the fourth year on June
23.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two different objectives with each event,'' Lone
Star general manager Steve Sexton said. ``With Million Day, we're
trying to get the best horses here for people to bet on. The
objective with the Jockey Championship is to put the riders in the
spotlight and not as much as the horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say this, and we don't always want to be walking around
patting ourselves on the back: This is one of the best if not the
best day of racing in terms of quality racing ever in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's Million Day has attracted 61 horses with total
earnings of $15.5 million. Last year, the horses involved had $9.9
million in earnings, so it's an increase of 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Dallas Keen, who has been racing in Texas since the
Class I tracks opened, has graded-stakes winner Allen's Oop in the
Lone Star Park Handicap, and he thinks this is a better group of
horses than the time Skip Away raced in the 1997 Texas Mile the
year before his Horse of the Year campaign and when Real Quiet
raced in the '99 Texas Mile the year after his victory in the
Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lone Star's always done a good job of getting really good
horses here, at least for the big events,'' Keen said. ``And for
them to have 13 horses in the \RLone Star Park\S Handicap, you
don't see that in a Grade III stakes race.''
</P>
<P>
   The field for the Lone Star 'Cap includes millionaire Classic
Cat trained by Bob Baffert, who also brought Grade III winner
Purely Cozzene for the $200,000 USA Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Luftikus is stabled on the West Coast for trainer Vladimir
Cerin, but he's making a return trip for the Lone Star 'Cap after
racing third in the Texas Mile last month. Luftikus is owned by
Stronach Stable, which also owns Preakness Stakes winner Red
Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton says a return trip by high-profile stables such as
Baffert's and Stronach's is a key toward one day landing a
Breeders' Cup championship at Lone Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting horsemen who operate on the national scale to
come in here,'' Sexton said. ``If we can get them here, we think
they'll return.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's helpful for our chance to get a Breeders' Cup one day.
No horseman on the national scale is going to be comfortable going
to the Breeders' Cup at a track that's foreign to them.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
