   (NYT9) POLTAVA, Ukraine -- May 28, 2000 --
UKRAINE-FARM-SUCCESS-2 -- Across a landscape of collapsing state
farms that are the most prominent feature of post-Soviet
agriculture, a small number of entrepreneurial private farmers in
the Ukraine, like Vasily T. Sluga, left, 43, are taking advantage
of the sporadic land reforms in Ukraine to show others the way to a
more productive future. ``Under the conditions of agriculture
today, no one is left to give orders from above and so everything
depends on the individual farmer,'' says Sluga. Nikolai V. Ogiyko,
right, is Sluga's foreman. ``People realize now that they work for
themselves,'' says Ogiyko, ``that we are on our own.'' (Patrick E.
Tyler/The New York Times)
