   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 28, 2000 --NEWMUSIC-CRI -- Joseph R.
Dalton, 37, former executive director of CRI, an independent label
that has recorded major and obscure representatives of the
developing American style. During his decade at the venerable
label, Dalton has restored CRI to its original mission: partly to
be an alternative to the big commercial labels, which have always
kept new works at arm's length, and partly to document the major
currents and obscure tributaries of the developing American style.
(Andrea Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 28, 2000 -- AUBURN-THEATER-INTERVIEW-1 --
David Auburn's ``Proof'' at the Manhattan Theater Club is a family
play of ideas. With intricate twists and turns, it takes a dramatic
and comic ride through the lives of a brilliant, deranged
mathematician and his two daughters, one of whom has devoted
herself to taking care of her father. ``I think everyone thinks
about their relationship to their parents, what they're getting
from that relationship, what they're not getting, what they will
give back to them,'' says Auburn, 30. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 28, 2000 -- ENTREPRENEUR-PROFILE --
Robert L. Johnson, chief executiver officer of Black Entertainment
Television at BET headquarters in Northeast Washington. Johnson,
54, is one of the country's most successful black entrepreneurs,
indeed one of the most successful business executives of any race.
In the last 20 years he has used his business savvy and his ability
to attract white investors with deep pockets to build Black
Entertainment Television, and later BET Holdings, into a
entertainment giant worth, he says, more than $2.5 billion.
(Susanna Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 28, 2000 -- NY-CENTRAL-PARK -- New York's
Central Park is gorgeous right now, moist and lush and shimmering
with health. Especially breathtaking are the thick, deep green
lawns, the dust bowls of a few years ago, that cost millions of
dollars to restore. In an effort to keep the park from reverting
back to it's dismal days, the city's main priority is currently
enforcing long-ignored rules, much to the dismay of many park
regulars. However, the issues that are tugging at Central Park
today, noisy music versus peace and quiet, lawn as landscape versus
lawn as carpet, orderliness vs. freedom, were controversial from
the beginning. (Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NORTH PARK, Fla. -- May 28, 2000 -- LIVING-WILLS --
Although millions of Americans have signed living wills and
power-of-attorney forms, thinking the documents would help them
avoid unwanted treatment and prolonged deaths, in many cases those
measures turn out to be useless. At the age of 91, Bertha Hyman,
center, now deceased, had a clear mind and a firm resolve. When her
life neared its end, she wanted no heroic measures and no
resuscitation. However, when Hyman had trouble breathing a few days
after surgery for a broken hip in 1998, her nieces, Rosalind Keyes,
left, and Sabena Wilensky, were horrified to find that she had been
put on a respirator. (Photo Courtesy of Sabena Wilensky/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- May 28, 2000 -- MODERN-DANCE-ESSAY -- Like
Eliot or Louis Armstrong, Graham invented a language that molded,
some would even say branded, generations of artists. Over the years
some of her dancers left to choreograph and form their own
companies. The best known, Merce Cunningham and Paul Taylor, had to
throw off her technique to find their own. Members of the Martha
Graham Dance Company participating in their last class, Sunday. The
company, founded by Graham in 1929, suspended operations due to
financial problems. (Nancy Siesel/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
