u s BC-CAR-INDY-NYT &LR;      05-28 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTOYA DOMINATES INDY AND DRINKS HIS MILK 
</HEADLINE>
   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Storm clouds were about to burst again, but red
rose petals showered first, embracing Juan Montoya in victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled his milk mustache for 400,000 fans, appreciating the
tradition, including the swig of milk, that was the Indianapolis
500, but even more so, he was savoring the moment for what it was:
a dominating victory, regardless of location, regardless of racing
league affiliation, just a Sunday afternoon drive spent looking in
the rear-view mirror and the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya came to the Indianapolis Motor Speedway this year for
the first time, an outsider, from another country, Colombia, but
more significant, from another racing series.
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old Montoya is the reigning Championship Auto Racing
Teams winner, from the Chip Ganassi team that had won the past four
CART titles but had not competed here since 1996 because of a
political roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   With a mixture of brilliance and assurance, Montoya led the 84th
Indy 500 for an astounding 167 of 200 laps when it finally started
after a 3-hour-9-minute rain delay, and easily finished 7.184
seconds in front of Buddy Lazier. Montoya, who averaged 167.677
miles an hour, won $1,235,690 of the $9,476,505 purse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will take time to realize what I just won,'' he
said. ``I wanted to win here like any other race.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazier, the 1996 Indy champion, said: ``When you win this race,
you earn it. He ran a real good race. They've dominated in the
other series. They've won what, 60 percent or something of those
races?''
</P>
<P>
   This year Ganassi decided he would be the first CART team since
1996 to come to Indy, shrugging off the boycott by his league that
began when Tony George, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway president,
formed the rival Indy Racing League and required different engine
specifications and chassis from CART's.
</P>
<P>
   With the reigning IRL champion, Greg Ray, taking the pole away
from Montoya, race day was already billed as a duel between the
fledgling league and the one with the better-known stars.
</P>
<P>
   John Menard, one of the original IRL team owners, saw Montoya's
overwhelming victory as proof that the newer open-wheel series is
not yet a match for CART.
</P>
<P>
   ``They raised the level of competition to a whole new level,''
said Menard, who fielded cars Sunday for Ray and Robby Gordon.
``It's certainly going to raise some questions about the ability of
the IRL teams to compete with CART. But they were the best of the
best; a very powerful team, a very organized team.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of the IRL drivers saw the race as a duel between the
series, nor did they try to block Montoya and his Ganassi teammate,
Jimmy Vasser. Rather, it was the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was very good sportsmanship,'' Lazier said. ``I was
hoping the IRL guys would stay with each other. But I got hammered
and boxed, and they were all IRL drivers. I wish they didn't have
that good of sportsmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, some fans stood and cheered, and a handful of fans
were chanting, ``IRL, IRL'' when Montoya went to victory lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were here like any IRL teams, we weren't here with a CART
flag,'' Montoya said. ``I look at myself and I'm just like any
other driver out there.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the Indy 500 is not just another race, neither is Montoya
just another driver. He won seven poles and seven races last season
in CART. This was his first victory this season, and it came a day
after the Ganassi team had flown to Nazareth, Pa., to run a
225-mile race that was rescheduled from April because of snow.
</P>
<P>
   Although Montoya had the fastest car, he got caught up in
traffic and accident debris and finished seventh on Saturday.
Sunday, he maneuvered through every situation with ease. He started
in second position, and early in the race, when lapping Lyn St.
James, he had to avoid her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lyn St. James nearly put me in the grass, that was the closest
call in the race,'' Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   On the 74th lap, St. James and the 19-year-old rookie Sarah
Fisher crashed coming up on Turn 1, cutting short the historical
aspect of having two women starting the race for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya was by that point building his lead. He passed Ray on
Lap 26. Ray crashed on Lap 66, and the two-time Indy winner Al
Unser, Jr. got caught in the debris, which punctured his radiator
and forced an early exit.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya would not be challenged significantly again until Lap
161, following a restart from an accident. Lazier was coming up on
him, sensing an opening and smelling fumes 0.127 seconds behind
Montoya's G Force-Aurora.
</P>
<P>
   By Lap 163, though, Lazier was 0.137 seconds behind. Two laps
later, Montoya edged away again, to a lead of 0.199 seconds. By Lap
171, Montoya led by 2.506 seconds. His teammate, Vasser, was in
second until Lap 195, when he had to make a pit stop for gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to stretch the fuel as far as we could,'' Vasser
said. ``It just didn't work out. I'm really happy for Juan. It's
great, the best team won.''
</P>
<P>
   Montoya became the first rookie to win at Indy since 1966, when
Graham Hill _ another veteran driver but a first-timer in
Indianapolis _ won the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was always interested in political part of things,
but I was not into that,'' Ganassi said. ``This is a big race. I
don't care what car you are in, the outside envelope is that and he
pushed it today.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
