u s BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZE     05-28 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-TRAILBLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERYTHING COMES UP ROSES FOR THE LAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TOM SPOUSTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ They strode off the court with wide grins and
wacky statistics, believing that no matter what happened in the
first half, they would prevail against the doomed Portland Trail
Blazers. After cruising to a 103-91 victory Sunday, the Los Angeles
Lakers also believed they had just stolen the Western Conference
finals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not even the Lakers figured on beating the Trail Blazers twice
at the Rose Garden, where the Trail Blazers were 5-0 in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Such thinking was as seemingly absurd as Shaquille O'Neal's
making every free-throw attempt, or guard Ron Harper's becoming an
inside force with 18 points and seven rebounds, or Glen Rice's
scorching the Blazers for 21 points, including nine in a row to
start the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But these are once again the ultraconfident Lakers, who toyed
with the Trail Blazers in Game 4 and turned a rugged, evenly
matched series into a lead of three games to one in this best-of-7
series.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers fell behind by 11 points early, cut the deficit to
five by halftime, outscored Portland by 34-19 in the third quarter
and could wrap up the series at home on Tuesday night in Game 5 at
the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gained a lot of confidence coming in here and winning two
games on the road in a pressure situation,'' said Kobe Bryant of
the Lakers, who finished with 18 points after a slow start. ``We
just came out in the third quarter, executed and put it on them.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal led the Lakers with 25 points and 11 rebounds, and he
foiled the Trail Blazers' strategy of fouling him as often as
possible, which began with 5 minutes 53 seconds remaining and the
Lakers ahead by 89-77.
</P>
<P>
   A 52 percent shooter from the line this season, O'Neal made six
consecutive free throws and finished 9 of 9 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me, excuse me,'' O'Neal said as he cleared a path
through a crowd of reporters in the Lakers' locker room. ``The big
Maravich coming through,'' he said, referring to Pete Maravich, a
career 82 percent free-throw shooter .
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal added: ``I was talking to my 3-year-old daughter before
the game, and all she said was, `Good luck, Daddy, and bend your
knees.' The first one fell, the second one fell, and I just got in
a rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's mood was as infectious as the Lakers' free-throw
shooting. They made 31 of 34 attempts, including 12 straight late
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   After O'Neal made his six free throws in a row, the Trail
Blazers also tried to foul Harper, but the veteran also knocked
down six straight.
</P>
<P>
   With his backup Brian Shaw suspended for Sunday's game for
leaving the bench during an altercation in Game 3, Harper was
forced to play 34 minutes. He hit 6 of 12 shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably still won't start guarding me,'' Harper said.
``They probably still think I'm not out there. But my teammates
know I can hit shots, and they got me the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing worked for Portland in the second half. Rasheed Wallace,
who finished with a career playoff-high 34 points, scored 13
straight during the fourth quarter, but all that did was prevent
further embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   The Trail Blazers shot 29.4 percent (5 of 17) in the third
quarter while the Lakers shot 70 percent (14 of 20).
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we have to draw on is that we have the
ability,'' Portland Coach Mike Dunleavy said. ``It's not uncharted
territory for us. That's the main thing right now. Our focus has to
be playing one game right now. You don't look at the whole series
unless you're a New Jersey Devils fan. We just have to get one game
and bring the series back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Smith scored 20 points for Portland. Scottie Pippen, who
was held to 11 points, managed only four in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They broke us down in the second half and we didn't have a
chance to make adjustments on defense,'' Smith said. ``We weren't
that bad in the second half, it's just that they had guys get
hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, celebrating his 33rd birthday, started the sudden momentum
swing in the Lakers' favor, sinking his first four shots in the
third quarter. At halftime, the Lakers decided to set more screens
to free Rice for more shots and he responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my mind made up I was going to come out and take more
shots and give us a spark,'' Rice said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-00 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000528.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-28 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-ASIA-INTERNET-1STLD-W     05-28 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-INTERNET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA'S TYCOONS JOIN THE INTERNET RUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to change age in 2nd graf from 43 to 46.)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In this densely packed city, where property is the
coin of the realm, Raymond Kwok is as close as one gets to royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Kwok's 46th-floor office looks out on a forest of skyscrapers,
dozens of them built by his family. Across the harbor in Kowloon
are sawtooth rows of apartment houses, also built by the family.
The Kwoks' real estate empire is one of the largest in Asia, making
Raymond, 46, and his two brothers fabulously wealthy, even by Hong
Kong's baroque standards.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, Kwok is worried about something that has
little to do with concrete, glass and steel. ``We always follow
closely what is happening in the U.S.,'' he said. ``In America, we
see how technology is changing business, how technology is creating
a lot of new businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Internet sweeps across the Pacific, Kwok believes
technology will unleash the same frenzy of sudden wealth and
disorienting change in Asia. If his family wants to keep its place
among Hong Kong's commercial elite, he says, it must join the
revolution. So Kwok, a Harvard MBA, has devised one of the most
ambitious Internet strategies of any old-line Asian company,
creating a diverse portfolio of Internet start-ups related to his
family's business.
</P>
<P>
   The Kwoks are one of several families of Asian tycoons who are
determined not to be left behind. From Taiwan to Thailand, the
region's most powerful families have started a blizzard of online
ventures. Whether their core businesses are in property,
telecommunications or banking, Asia's tycoons are seizing on the
Internet in hopes of expanding their reach and making even more
money.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the Internet is transforming the way business is
done here and elsewhere in East Asia. With its emphasis on speed,
openness and collaboration, the Net is challenging traditional
Asian values of prudence and family control. Decisions, which used
to be made by the patriarch behind a veil of secrecy, are being
pushed down the ranks as Asian companies embrace Silicon
Valley-style management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The classic Asian family dynasty probably isn't the best
suited to succeed on the Internet,'' said Peter Yip, the chief
executive of Chinadotcom, one of Asia's first publicly traded
Internet companies. ``But I've been amazed by how quickly they've
learned the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is so sanguine. Despite their chameleonlike
adaptability, Asia's tycoons may have trouble making the leap into
cyberspace, critics say. For the last quarter-century, the tycoons
rode a wave of double-digit growth. In countries like Indonesia,
Thailand and Malaysia, cozy ties with governments sheltered them
from market forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys think the Internet will bring them prosperity for
the next 25 years,'' said Jimmy Lai, a Hong Kong publisher who is
putting his media properties online and starting an Internet
shop-from-home service. ``But to unlearn the lessons of the last 25
years is impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, Lai (pronounced lie) predicts, the culture of the
Internet will erode the dominance of family dynasties in Asian
commerce. By making information widely available, the Web will
gradually devalue the networks of personal contacts _ known in
Chinese as guanxi _ amassed over decades.
</P>
<P>
   Kwok, though, thinks he can ride the technology tidal wave. He
spent much of 1999 in the United States, roaming around conferences
and quizzing entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered some online businesses that play to the strengths
of property owners. One is providing specially outfitted office
space to house computer servers. Another is creating Internet
sites, including chat rooms and bulletin boards, for the residents
of the apartment complexes owned by the Kwok family's company, Sun
Hung Kai Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Kwok packaged his collection of start-ups into a holding
company, Sunevision, which went public on the Hong Kong Stock
Exchange. While Kwok is the chairman, he has recruited an outside
executive to run it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind-set of a technology company is very different from a
property company,'' Kwok said. ``We needed to remove a lot of
baggage.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jeffrey Koo Jr., the challenge was persuading his elders
that the Internet was more than a fad. Koo, 35, is a
fourth-generation member of a family that controls a vast empire in
banking, telecommunications, cement and cable television.
</P>
<P>
   In talking with classmates from the Wharton School in 1997, Koo
became convinced that his family had to lash its future to the
Internet. As president of the family's Chinatrust Commercial Bank,
Koo began taking baby steps online. But his father turned down his
first request for $10 million to finance an Internet service
provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father and his brothers were against me doing this because
they thought of it as a form of gambling,'' Koo said. ``When I
would talk excitedly about a new venture, they would look at me
blankly.''
</P>
<P>
   In Koo's case, the elders came around when Microsoft bought a 10
percent stake in his start-up, Gigamedia, a broadband entertainment
and information service. Earlier this year, Gigamedia became the
first Taiwan Internet company to go public on the Nasdaq exchange.
Although it was caught in Nasdaq's downdraft, it is still worth
well over $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Koo is developing online banking and a regional e-commerce
service to complement the family's 75 percent stake in Gigamedia.
Less than two years after his father gave the Internet the cold
shoulder, Jeffrey Jr. said, he now talks constantly about the
cyberworld.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To some students of Asian business, this is merely a new chapter
in an old story. Ethnic Chinese families have traditionally
prospered by adapting to new circumstances. Kwok Tak-seng, the
patriarch of the Kwok family, started as a trader in southern
China. By the 1950s, he had migrated to Hong Kong and become the
local agent for the YKK zipper company of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing more opportunity in property than zippers, Kwok began
building apartment houses. By the 1980s, he was a leading real
estate developer. Kwok died in 1990, but under his three sons, Sun
Hung Kai grew into a conglomerate with interests in toll roads,
cargo handling and mobile telephones.
</P>
<P>
   ``One good thing about old-economy companies is that they have
profits and cash flow,'' said Raymond's older brother, Thomas, who
oversees Sun Hung Kai's real estate business. ``But old-economy
companies need new-economy ideas to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   For all their rock-solid stature, however, Asia's tycoons face
challenges from a host of upstarts. Lai, the publisher and a
self-styled maverick, offers himself as an example. Last year, he
started a venture that lets customers order groceries and other
goods by phone or over the Internet. The company, adMart, delivers
from its warehouses, cutting out the middleman.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, the middleman for many of these goods is Li
Ka-shing, a billionaire who owns one of the two local supermarket
chains. When Lai's delivery business began to pinch Li's stores, he
canceled his company's advertising in Apple Daily and Next
magazine, the outspoken newspaper and weekly magazine at the heart
of Lai's company.
</P>
<P>
   For Lai, the lost revenue has hurt. But after years of tweaking
Hong Kong's establishment in his newspaper, Lai relishes mounting a
frontal assault on its most powerful local businessman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never take on Li Ka-shing before,'' Lai said. ``But if
I'm riding on the back of a huge market force like the Internet,
then even he can't stop me.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the Internet is the second revolution to rumble
through Asia recently. In 1997 and 1998, the regional financial
crisis brought many family empires to the brink of ruin. Even in
Hong Kong, property prices plunged by more than half, and are only
now recovering.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, many Asian governments took steps to clean up
their banks, tighten commercial regulations and force companies to
improve their disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the crisis, Asian firms regarded financial disclosure
and minority shareholders as a necessary irritant,'' said Peter
Churchouse, the co-head of research at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
in Hong Kong. ``Now they know they can't get away with that.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Asia's tycoons were humbled, the crisis did not dull
their entrepreneurial instincts. Watching start-ups like Amazon.com
and Ebay become sensations in America, the tycoons saw a chance to
make a quick score. Virtually every conglomerate rushed out an
Internet unit.
</P>
<P>
   Li Ka-shing started e-commerce ventures through his two
companies, Hutchison Whampoa and Cheung Kong Holdings. He also
backed a Chinese-language portal, Tom.com, which prompted a
near-riot among investors when it went public last February.
Tom.com tumbled in the global sell-off of technology stocks. But
thanks to Li's gold-plated reputation, it still trades above its
offering price.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to hand it to the conglomerates, they've maintained
their position in a radically different economy,'' said Mark Duff,
the founder and chief executive of Boom.com, an online
stock-trading company here.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Duff and other independent entrepreneurs fear that the
tycoons are colonizing Asia's cyberspace. They say that the family
companies can soak up money and talent that could have gone to more
daring ideas.
</P>
<P>
   It is true that the tycoon-backed ventures are often
unimaginative. Sunevision's concept of providing warehouses for Web
servers was pioneered in the United States by Exodus. Tom.com
promoted itself as a mega-portal for Chinese audiences around the
world. When it went public, its Web site consisted of a home page
and links that went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the initiatives in Asia are extremely shallow,'' Duff
said. ``But the brand names of the families are so strong that it
doesn't matter. They get funded.''
</P>
<P>
   A few executives are trying to force deeper changes in Asian
culture. Richard Li, the son of Li Ka-shing, is building an office
park here. The 64-acre complex, known as Cyberport, is supposed to
offer tenants like Microsoft, IBM and Softbank a campus-like
environment where ideas can be swapped and new businesses hatched.
</P>
<P>
   Just 33 years old, Li is the brashest Internet entrepreneur in
Hong Kong and a symbol of Asia's headlong flight into cyberspace.
His two-year-old company, Pacific Century Cyberworks, recently won
a $36 billion takeover battle for Hong Kong's main telephone
company. Li is also building a satellite-delivered Internet
service.
</P>
<P>
   Li epitomizes the contradiction in Asia's version of the
Internet. A scion of the Li dynasty, he has created a cyber-age
company crackling with the energy of employees hoping to strike it
rich on stock options. The company's latest conquest has been
likened to America Online's acquisition of Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Li would never have triumphed unless the Bank of China
arranged a $12 billion syndicated loan to finance the deal. And
analysts agree that Li would never have landed such a loan without
his father's connections.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise with the Cyberport. It may plant the seed for a fertile
technology culture in Hong Kong. Yet rivals of the Li family have
criticized the project because it was awarded to Pacific Century by
the Hong Kong government in a back-room deal.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the tycoons stop short of extolling Asian values,
but they make no apologies for their privileges. ``There's a blend
of Western and Asian elements here,'' said Alex Arena, Li's top
lieutenant. ``It's not a question of being like the U.S. It's a
question of cherry-picking from the U.S.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
