<HEADLINE>
FRANCE TELECOM REPORTED SET TO ACQUIRE ORANGE FROM VODAFONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to move `$183 billion' from 3rd graf to end of 12th graf,
where it is qualified.)  
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   France Telecom is planning to announce Tuesday that it has
agreed to acquire Orange PLC, Britain's third-largest wireless
phone operator, from Vodafone AirTouch for more than $37 billion,
executives close to the negotiations said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale would conclude one of the most highly anticipated deals
in Europe, which was supposed to attract bidders from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its acquisition of Mannesmann AG, the German
industrial and telecommunications conglomerate, in early February,
Vodafone was required to sell Orange to appease regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies in Europe and even some in the
United States seeking to establish a foothold in Britain's
lucrative wireless market expressed interest in Orange, but the
expected auction never came.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, France Telecom, which had been talking to Vodafone even
before its acquisition of Mannesmann was completed, fired the
first, final and only shot for Orange before its rivals could get
to the table with an offer.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives close to the talks, France Telecom will
pay about 40 billion euros in cash and stock, or $37.4 billion. It
will also assume about 10 billion euros, or $9.4 billion, in debt.
Vodafone, which will announce its 1999 earnings Sunday, will hold
about a 10 percent stake of nonvoting shares in the French company,
though it may eventually have to dispose of its new stake to
placate regulators.
</P>
<P>
   For France Telecom, the acquisition of Orange vaults it into the
upper echelon of European telecommunications competitors, giving it
substantial reach beyond its own borders. Orange has 6 million
customers in Britain plus alliances and other licensing
arrangements across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With the purchase of Orange, France Telecom would obtain a
``universal mobile telecommunications system'' license to offer
fast Internet access on cellular phones. In April, a British
subsidiary of NTL of New York, backed by France Telecom, withdrew
from the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The deal would put France Telecom in direct competition in
Britain with Vodafone, the largest wireless operator in the world;
British Telecommunications, which operates BT Cellnet; Deutsche
Telekom, which owns One2One; and TIW UMTS Ltd., which is owned in
part by the Hong Kong conglomerate Hutchison Whampoa, another
recent winner of a so-called third-generation wireless license.
Hutchison Whampoa had owned a majority stake in Orange before it
was acquired by Mannesmann in October, which set off this entire
series of acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   France Telecom plans to merge Orange with its own wireless unit,
which includes Itineris, the largest wireless company in France,
with more than 10 million subscribers and operations in Denmark,
Belgium, the Netherlands, Italy, Austria and Switzerland. It will
then spin off the combined company within a year, executives close
to the negotiations said, adding that Hans Snook, chief executive
of Orange, would run the new company. Snook had initially been
opposed to selling the company directly to a competitor but has
since become amenable to the deal, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone's sale of Orange directly to a rival is a reversal of
its original plan to spin off Orange and sell shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the sale comes as a result of the recent spate of
high-revenue auctions across Europe for the third-generation
wireless licenses _ for mobile phones that may include Web browsing
and video conferences. Vodafone recently paid $9.42 billion for a
license in Britain and is competing for similar licenses across the
Continent. The higher-than-expected license fees have forced
Vodafone to try to raise cash. And amid plunging telecommunications
share prices generally, the company's stock has sharply fallen
since its acquisition of Mannesmann, a deal valued at the time
around $183 billion. On Friday, Vodafone shares closed here at
2.8125 pounds, down from 3.855 pounds in February.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Vodafone said it would sell its entire stake in
Cegetel, a French phone company, to its partner Vivendi. Vodafone
had earlier said it would sell 7.5 percent of Mannesmann's stake in
Cegetel, but it decided to sell the whole stake _ 15 percent _ to
raise more cash. Vodafone also sold Mannesmann's engineering and
automotive unit, Atecs, for 9.6 billion euros to the German
companies Siemens and Robert Bosch in April.
</P>
<P>
   To support its acquisition of Orange, France Telecom is also
going on a selling spree to raise cash. It said on Friday that it
would sell most of its stake in Telefonos de Mexico to raise $1.9
billion. Telmex said it planned to buy the remaining stake for $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   Vodafone is being advised on the deal by Goldman, Sachs;
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette; Dresdner Kleinwort Benson, and UBS
Warburg. France Telecom is being advised by Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, Credit Suisse First Boston and N.M. Rothschild.
</P>
<P>
   In part, the sale comes as a result of the recent spate of
high-revenue auctions across Europe for the third-generation
wireless licenses _ franchises for mobile phones that may include
Web browsing and video conferences. Vodafone recently paid $9.42
billion for a license in Britain and is competing for similar
licenses across the Continent. The higher-than-expected license
fees have forced Vodafone to try to raise cash. And amid plunging
telecommunications share prices generally, the company's stock has
sharply fallen since its acquisition of Mannesmann,
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
