<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLAZERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALF BAD NOT GOOD FOR BLAZERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ The Portland Trail Blazers are convinced they
have it half right.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the other half is killing them. Humbling them before
the home folks, pushing them toward an unexpectedly early stay at
the summer retreat.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in as many home playoff games against the
Los Angeles Lakers, the Trail Blazers saw spirited and crisp play
in the first half dissolve into Paul Allen's worst nightmare this
side of a tech market crash come the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Once again the Blazers had a near meltdown in the third quarter
and could never recover, this time falling 103-91 in Game 4 at the
Rose Garden on Sunday to trail the Lakers 3-1 in the best-of-seven
Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have outscored the Blazers 61-35 in the third
quarters of the two games in Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just haven't played the same way for two halves the last
couple of games,'' Blazers guard Damon Stoudamire said. ``And
that's been the tale of this homestand for us. We haven't been able
to sustain.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers are uncertain how much to blame themselves for their
second-half troubles, and how much to give the Lakers credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we had played well, if it would have helped
us, as well as they played,'' Blazers forward Scottie Pippen said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Lakers stepped up their defense in the third
quarter, holding the Blazers to just 5-of-17 shooting (.294
percent). At the same time, they started converting, hitting 14 of
20 (70.0) to outscore Portland 34-19.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers also turned up the rest of the game, scoring well
in the hustle categories - outrebounding the Blazers 11-5, passing
out 11 assists to their five and blocking three shots to none for
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They stepped it up,'' Blazers forward Brian Grant said. ``I
don't want to say we got complacent, but we just didn't step it up
in both halves, and they made us pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took a 76-66 lead into the fourth quarter and then
saw the Blazers offense reduced to Rasheed Wallace and four guys in
Portland uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace scored Portland's first 13 points in the period. Another
Blazer didn't score a field goal until Arvydas Sabonis dunked with
2:13 remaining, by then the Lakers were up 101-82.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers had started a third-quarter spiral there would be no
escaping.
</P>
<P>
   ``The third quarter has been our Achilles' heel,'' Grant said.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers love to run, but are finding it difficult to get
into a transition game when the Lakers convert.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming in (at the half) and adjusting,'' Portland
guard Steve Smith said. ``We're missing some shots and they're
making some, where we can't get into transition.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stoudamire: ``When the ball goes through the hole, that's
going to make it hard for anybody to create anything because then
you have a defense that's set. I think that's what happened in the
third quarter. It was hard for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't figure to get any easier now. Only six teams in NBA
history have come back from a 3-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, we just have to believe in ourselves and know
that we can beat this team,'' Grant said. ``If we don't believe
that, we shouldn't even play on Tuesday. I know the kind of pride
everybody on this team has. We're going to go down to L.A., work
hard on Monday, then go out there on Tuesday and let it all hang
out.''
</P>
<P>
   And they hope, that won't be the half of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
