<SLUG> BC-BKW-WNBA-PREVIEW-CAPSULES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WNBA EXPANDING INTO THE NEW CENTURY
</HEADLINE>
  By LIZ ROBBINS  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (A team-by-team look at the now 16-team Women's National
Basketball Association which tips off Monday with the Liberty
playing the Comets, the defending champions. Records and finishes
are for last season.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK LIBERTY (18-12, first in East)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Richie Adubato.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Teresa Weatherspoon, 5-8 G; Vickie Johnson, 5-9 G;
Sue Wicks, 6-3 F; Venus Lacey, 6-5 C.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Last season the Liberty took Houston to three games in
the finals. The center Kym Hampton retired and Rebecca Lobo may not
be available until July, but the reserve center Lacey has been the
biggest surprise of training camp. Crystal Robinson led the league
in 3-pointers last season, and with reliable veterans in
Weatherspoon and Wicks, the Liberty could win a weak conference.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON MYSTICS (12-20, fifth)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Nancy Darsch.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Chamique Holdsclaw, 6-2 F; Nikki McCray, 5-11 G;
Vicky Bullett, 6-3 F.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: This could be the most improved team in the East with
Holdsclaw, the rookie of the year, and McCray, an all-star, joining
Bullett. But they are battling injuries and Bullett is still
playing in Brazil.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ORLANDO MIRACLE (15-17, tied for third)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Carolyn Peck.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Shannon Johnson, 5-7 G; Nykesha Sales, 6-0 G; Taj
McWilliams, 6-3 C.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: This team has one of the best backcourts in the
conference, with the all-star Johnson and an improved Sales.
McWilliams, who had eight double-doubles last season, brings
leadership. The first-round pick Cintia Dos Santos, a 6-4 center
from Brazil, needs experience but could solidify the frontcourt.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE STING (15-17, tied for second)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: T.R. Dunn, first year.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Dawn Staley 5-6 G; Tracy Reid 6-0 F; Andrea Stinson
(N.C. State '91) 5-10 G.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Charlotte returns most of its core, after trading Vicky
Bullett to Washington, but that core has also been prone to
injuries. The Olympic point guard Staley is recovering from knee
surgery. Reid, the 1998 rookie of the year, is also injury prone
and the lack of height could limit the team.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND ROCKERS (7-25, last)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Dan Hughes, first year.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Eva Nemcova, 6-3 F; Merlakia Jones, 5-9 G; Ann
Wauters 6-3 C; Suzie McConnell Serio, 5-6 G.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Wauters is a 19-year-old who can dunk, but she is
slight and inexperienced. Nemcova is one of the sharpest shooters
and most athletic players in the league, and Jones is a creative
guard. Even though the Rockers might struggle at the point,
Cleveland will be improved.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT SHOCK (15-17, tied for second)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Nancy Lieberman-Cline.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Dominique Canty, 5-9 G; Wendy Palmer, 6-2 F; Edwina
Brown, 5-9 G.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Brown, the first player selected in the draft, is a
versatile addition to a team that lost three Australian players,
who chose to train for their Olympic team instead. But Canty and
Tamicha Jackson, the speedy rookie point guard, will make games
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA FEVER (Expansion team)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Anne Donovan (interim).
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Kara Wolters, 6-7 C; Stephanie McCarty, 5-9 G;
Gordana Grubin, 5-11 G.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Wolters had a strong preseason and will develop with
tutoring from Donovan, the interim coach until the Olympic coach
Nell Fortner arrives next season. McCarty, who won the 1999 NCAA
title with Purdue, will be a draw for fans. But on a down note,
Grubin, one of the best guards in the league last year at Los
Angeles, injured her ankle in the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI SOL (Expansion team)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Ron Rothstein. KEY PLAYERS: Marlies Askamp, 6-5 C; Debbie
Black 5-2 G; Sharon Manning 6-3 F.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Askamp, acquired from Minnesota, brings much-needed
help in the paint. Black, the scrappy point guard acquired from
Utah, is recovering from back surgery. The two best players Miami
acquired will not be in uniform: center Elena Baranova blew out her
knee before training camp and Sandy Brodello is training with the
Australian national team.
</P>
<P>
   WESTERN CONFERENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON COMETS (26-6, WNBA champion)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Van Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Cynthia Cooper, 5-10 G; Sheryl Swoopes, 6-0 F, Tina
Thompson, 6-3 F.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Once again, it is the Comets' championship to lose.
Point guard is a small concern, with the former Connecticut star
Jennifer Rizzotti set to split time with the Brazilian Janeth
Arcain.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO MONARCHS (19-13, third).
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Sonny Allen.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Yolanda Griffith, 6-3 F; Ticha Penicheiro, 5-10 G;
Ruthie Bolton-Holifield.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: On paper, the deepest, most talented team in the
league. Griffith is the league's reigning MVP and defensive player
of the year. Adding the former Olympian Katy Steding to an already
explosive offense, the Monarchs have the best shot of dethroning
the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   PHOENIX MERCURY (15-17, tied for fourth)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Cheryl Miller.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Jennifer Gillom, 6-3 C; Tonya Edwards, 5-10 G;
Brandy Reed, 6-1 F
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: The Mercury has been a dominating team in the West
since the league began, and this year should be no different.
Edwards and Reed, coming in a trade with Minnesota as the Lynx's
leading scorers last year, have stepped right in, adding exciting
offense to an already deep team with Gillom and the returning
forward Michelle Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES SPARKS (20-12, second)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Michael Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Lisa Leslie, 6-5 C; DeLisha Milton, 6-1 F; Tamecka
Dixon, 5-9 G.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: An underachieving team that finally broke through last
season, the Sparks could be just as good this year. But four
head-coaching changes in four years have underlined instability in
management. Leslie and Milton are proven leaders in the paint, but
the team might be shaky at point guard.
</P>
<P>
   UTAH STARZZ (15-17, tied for fourth)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Fred Williams.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Natalie Williams, 6-2 F; Korie Hlede, 5-9 G; Margo
Dydek, 7-2 C.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: The Starzz are dangerous and capable of finishing as
high as second in the conference, even with point guard Jen Azzi
sidelined until July with a broken hand. With a lot of pure scorers
on this team, Utah could have its first winning season.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA LYNX (15-17, tied for fourth)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Brian Agler.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Katie Smith, 5-11 F; Kristin Folkl, 6-2 F; Andrea
Lloyd-Curry, 6-2 F.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: Agler traded veterans to receive eight draft picks. In
the meantime, Smith, Lloyd-Curry and a fast improving Folkl are all
healthy and will help Minnesota win enough games to stay
competitive in the tough conference.
</P>
<P>
   PORTLAND FIRE (Expansion team)
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Linda Hargrove. KEY PLAYERS: Sophia Witherspoon, 5-10 G;
Lynn Pride, 6-2 F; Tari Phillips, 6-1 F
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: The Liberty lost Witherspoon in the expansion draft,
and now she anchors a surprisingly deep team of other WNBA castoffs
and young, versatile players like Pride. Played well in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE STORM (Expansion team) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COACH: Lin Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   KEY PLAYERS: Edna Campell, 5-8 G; Kamila Vodichova 6-4 F; Sonja
Henning 5-7 G.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK: This is probably the weakest of the four new
franchises, but Dunn, a veteran coach, should coax some victories
out of her limited talent. Vodichova, from the Czech Republic,
could be the steal of the draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
