<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL IS QUESTIONABLE WITH INJURED LEFT FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ They are reputed to be the kings of adversity,
the team that grows incredibly strong and resilient when its roster
and room for error are chopped short. Whether overcoming the loss
of its star center, making a huge halftime deficit disappear or
ignoring a pronounced height disadvantage to block a jump shot, the
Knicks seem to morph into basketball's version of the little engine
that could whenever necessary.
</P>
<P>
   At Madison Square Garden on Monday, the Knicks will again try to
snuff out long odds in Game 4 of their Eastern Conference
championship series with the Indiana Pacers. With the availability
of the hobbled big men Patrick Ewing and Marcus Camby already in
question, the Knicks received more disheartening news Sunday when a
magnetic resonance imaging test revealed that Latrell Sprewell had
an incomplete fracture of the fifth metatarsal in his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   It will be decided just before the 5:30 p.m. tip-off whether
Sprewell, who did not practice Sunday, will be able to play. The
availability of Ewing, who missed Game 3 after spraining a tendon
in his right foot on Thursday, and Camby, who sprained the medial
capsule in his right knee on Saturday, will also be game-time
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy, his team down, two games to one, is
preparing as if all three players will miss the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting any one of them to play,'' he said after
being forced to take the floor so his depleted team could simulate
a five-on-five set at practice. ``I'm watching those guys, and they
have legitimate injuries. I want them to play if they can be
effective. If they can't be effective, then they're going to have
to sit there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell, who recorded 32 points and eight rebounds to lead the
Knicks to a 98-95 victory in Game 3 on Saturday, said he injured
himself while diving for a loose ball late in the fourth quarter.
He acknowledged that he could hardly walk Sunday, but disputed Van
Gundy's prognosis and said he planned to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, it didn't feel like much,'' Sprewell said of his
injury. ``Really, it didn't feel like much after the game either.
But this morning it was pretty swollen and pretty stiff. It's
pretty sore. I really can't walk on it good. But I think I'll be
able to play. I'm planning on playing regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who is suffering from acute peroneal tendinitis, said on
Saturday that he would definitely play in either Game 4 or Game 5,
but he was unable to practice Sunday. Before Game 3, he slid into
his warm-ups, got his ankles taped and attempted to jog onto the
floor, but his test run was cut short by the intense pain. He will
go through the same steps Monday and hope for a different result.
</P>
<P>
   Camby, who injured his knee while driving to the basket early in
the second quarter, did not attempt to run or jump on Sunday
either. But he said that if he were a betting man, he would bet on
himself to play Monday. He added that he would force himself to
play if both Sprewell and Ewing were unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to be ready to run on it,'' Camby said. ``If I can
run on it and push off, then I'm going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby, who missed 19 games this season because of assorted
right-knee injuries, complained before Game 3 that his subpar play
throughout the playoffs was because of his banged-up body. But he
said there would be no such excuse if he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to go out there and lay an egg,'' Camby said.
``I think I can be somewhat effective. I'm going to get something
accomplished if I'm able to go, so it just remains to be seen. I
feel confident. I've been playing with a banged-up knee all season
long, and nothing I think is going to set me back from a confidence
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Knicks have thrived in the face of injury the past two
postseasons, winning four of five games against Indiana without
Ewing, it seems virtually impossible for them to beat the Pacers
with Sprewell, Ewing and Camby on the sidelines. They proved on
Saturday that they could overcome the losses of Ewing and Camby,
who played only five minutes before being injured, but eliminating
Sprewell from the mix may be too much.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the Knicks with just two legitimate scorers in
Allan Houston and Larry Johnson, and Johnson is much less than 100
percent. Halfway through Sunday's practice, Van Gundy pulled him
out because of tightness in his back. Both he and Johnson said he
would play Monday, though.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy said he was considering three starting lineups if
Ewing, Sprewell and Camby don't play. He could start Kurt Thomas at
power forward and move Johnson to small forward, start Chris Childs
at shooting guard and move Houston to small forward, or start the
little-used John Wallace at small forward. As he did in Game 3,
Chris Dudley will start if Ewing is absent.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Van Gundy shared a bit of what will certainly
become his pre-game motivational speech with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just got to find a way to get even tomorrow,'' he said.
``It doesn't matter how it happens or who plays. The nine that are
left got to be ready to play. You can make all the excuses for
yourself and for your team, and they do absolutely no good. In the
end, no one cares. Instead of making excuses for why they can't,
give them reasons why they can. And I think we have more than
enough reasons why we can, and that's what we've got to focus in
on.'' History is one reason. The others are not so clear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
