<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS AND STARS TAKE COMMON APPROACH TO CUP FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils consider themselves very
similar to the Dallas Stars, their opponent in the Stanley Cup
finals that begin here Tuesday night. Both teams have proven
goaltenders, solid defenses and explosive forwards. But the Stars
are the defending champions and have more experienced veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas also defeated the Devils the two times they met in the
regular season, but the playoffs are different. Just ask the St.
Louis Blues, who finished the regular season with the best record
in the league and took the first exit in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regular season doesn't mean a thing,'' said Alexander
Mogilny, who scored three goals against the Stars as a member of
the Vancouver Canucks before joining the Devils hours before the
trading deadline in March. ``I don't even remember who I scored
against,'' Mogilny said when asked whether he scored against the
Stars' Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great goaltending, mobile defense and guys who can
score,'' Mogilny said. ``I think we have all those things, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils finished the regular season with 103 points to 102
for the Stars. They both have playoff records of 12-5. The Devils
eliminated Florida, Toronto and Philadelphia, while the Stars
eliminated Edmonton, San Jose and Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Because they finished with one point more than than the Stars in
the regular season, the Devils have the home advantage, but they
have a better record on the road (7-2) than at home (5-3) in these
playoffs. The Stars are 9-1 at home and 3-4 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur's and Belfour's playoff statistics are very
similar. Both have played every minute in goal for their teams in
the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur has allowed 30 goals to 31 for Belfour, who has the edge
in save percentage, .931 to .923.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour has played 125 games in the playoffs and has a record of
73-47.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie is an excellent goalie with a lot of success in his
career,'' Brodeur said. ``He gives his team a chance to win every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are the precise words that others use about Brodeur, who
has played 78 games in the playoffs with a record of 46-32. Each
has won the Stanley Cup once, Belfour last year and Brodeur in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   One slight edge the Devils may have against the Stars is an
extra day's rest. The Devils completed their physical seven-game
series against the Flyers on Friday after rallying from a 3-1
deficit, while the Stars edged Colorado in Game 7 Saturday night in
Dallas. The Stars flew to New Jersey Sunday, while the Devils
practiced for an hour Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Devils said they preferred Dallas as an opponent
because of the high altitude they would have had to deal with in
Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have trouble breathing in Colorado,'' John Madden
said. ``From that standpoint, Dallas is probably better. For us, it
doesn't matter. We have to play our game. We cannot count on Marty
to hold up from beginning to end.''
</P>
<P>
   When coach Larry Robinson was asked about his Devils' chances
against the Stars, he said, ``Fifty-fifty.'' Most of his players
echoed his sentiment, but some went a little further.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry told us that if we put our minds to it we can do it,''
Sergei Brylin said. ``We did it with Philly and we believe we can
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils' advancement to the finals has been credited in part
to Robinson's tirade after a loss in Game 4 against the Flyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This speech has been blown out of proportion, and I want to
put an end to it,'' Robinson said. ``It's not me who has done
anything here, it's the players on the ice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
