<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MEDICAID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK GOP POLITICKING REVIVES MEDICAID PLAN FOR STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ What a difference a candidate makes.
</P>
<P>
   In state budget talks in April, the New York Legislature was
prepared to have the state join a new program to let thousands of
disabled people stay on Medicaid, the federal health insurance plan
for the poor, even after getting jobs. But Gov. George Pataki's
office balked at the cost, and the plan was dropped, apparently
dead for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it is very much alive again, and state officials and
lobbyists say it stands a good chance of approval. Why? Because its
primary author is U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, the Republicans' new
candidate for the U. S. Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
Lazio was chief sponsor of the bill in Congress that created the
program and set aside $250 million to help states pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican state legislators have said they're aware of the
political value in participating in a bill-signing at which they
would join Lazio, Republican governor and Medicaid beneficiaries,
an opportunity that could prove helpful for campaigning. That
notion, they said, has been enough to sway the governor, a prime
sponsor of Lazio's candidacy, into reconsidering the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the governor's office confirmed that the program
was once again under consideration, but would not say why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides the merits _ and we supported it all along _ this
thing is golden politically,'' a Republican state senator said.
``We see that, and the governor sees it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Republicans, who hold a majority in the state
Senate, may be vulnerable this year and have said they see the U.S.
Senate race as being crucial to their chances in November. George
W. Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, is not
expected to carry New York, so state Republican lawmakers want a
strong U.S. Senate candidate.
</P>
<P>
   That candidate was New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, but he
dropped out after learning that he had prostate cancer. Lazio is
expected to be nominated by the state GOP to run for the U.S.
Senate at his party's state convention in Buffalo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   While the New York state Senate Republicans assert that Lazio is
just as strong a standard-bearer as Giuliani, they have been eager
to bolster his name recognition among voters.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicaid effort benefiting people with disabilities seems
made to order, the kind of program more commonly identified with
Democrats. And it contrasts with the image that Clinton is trying
to impose on Lazio _ that of a far-right, ideological conservative.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign has noted that she, too, favored the Medicaid
program , emphasizing that it was her husband, the president, who
signed it into law.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kink, a lobbyist for Housing Works, an advocacy
organization for people with AIDS, said, ``It's pretty clear that
Lazio's entry into the race reignited interest in this.''
</P>
<P>
   In state Legislature conference committees last month, the
Assembly, led by Democrats, and the state Senate agreed to have the
state join the new Medicaid program. But Pataki's budget office
said it would cost the state $24 million a year, twice as much as
estimated by both houses of the Legislature and advocates for the
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   In budget talks, the governor's office insisted that if the
program were to be included in the budget, the Legislature would
have to give up $24 million worth of its pet projects to keep
within the overall spending caps the lawmakers had agreed to. Faced
with that, the Legislature dropped the idea, and the $77.5 billion
budget was approved in early May without the Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past week, as Lazio emerged as his party's
uncontested U.S. Senate candidate, several Republican state
senators _ including two influential Long Island representatives,
Kemp Hannon, the Health Committee chairman, and Dean G. Skelos, the
deputy majority leader _ pushed to resurrect the idea. Officials
say both houses of the Legislature are still willing to approve it,
though that would break the spending cap. The question remains
whether Pataki will go along.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, people lose Medicaid benefits if they get full-time
jobs. Advocates for the poor have urged changing this, so that the
poor do not have to choose between employment and health care,
which they say impedes efforts to move people off welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The new program would allow people with disabilities to keep
Medicaid coverage after finding work if they do not earn more than
$45,000 a year. But each state must decide whether to participate
in the program and share in its cost. A disabled person earning
more than about $17,000 a year would have to pay a monthly premium
to stay in Medicaid. The premium would vary depending on income,
ranging from $25 to $333.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
