<SLUG> BC-INVESTING-DOMASH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE INVESTING: WHERE TO FIND GUIDELINES FOR CHOOSING AN
ONLINE  BROKER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By HARRY DOMASH 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More and more investors are doing their stock
and mutual fund investing online these days.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why. It's often faster and more convenient, and
it's usually considerably less expensive than calling a broker.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100 stockbrokers offering online trading, how do
you pick the broker that best suits your needs?
</P>
<P>
   The choice depends on your investing style. For instance,
lightning-fast trading speed and rock-bottom commissions are the
most important criteria for active traders.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual fund investors couldn't care less about those factors.
They look for brokers offering a wide selection of funds with
little or no transaction fees.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile long-term stock investors often seek out brokers
offering the best research reports.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG PICTURE: The first step in picking an online broker is
getting up to speed on who's out there. The best place to do that
is Gomez ( &LR; www.gomez.com &LR; ). Gomez is in the business of rating
online services of all sorts: airlines, banks, car buying sites,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   Click on Brokers under Personal Finance on Gomez' home page to
access their online broker ratings. Gomez ranks brokers both by
categories and by profiles. The six categories include Overall
Score and Ease of Use.
</P>
<P>
   Profiles refer to investing styles and are more useful than the
category ratings. The profiles include:
</P>
<P>
   Hyperactive Trader: Fast trades, low costs and simple operation
are the main criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Serious Investor: Gives most weight to analysis and research
tools.
</P>
<P>
   Life Goal Planner: Most emphasis on mutual fund selection and
retirement planning tools.
</P>
<P>
   One-Stop Shopper: Looks for breadth of offerings and ease of
use.
</P>
<P>
   Start by clicking on the Overall Score category see a list of
Gomez's 20 top-ranked brokers to get an overview of the major
players. When I did, the top five brokers were E-Trade, Charles
Schwab, Fidelity Investments, DLJ Direct and TD Waterhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Then click on the each of the profiles to see how Gomez ranks
the brokers according to different investing styles.
</P>
<P>
   From the rankings, click on a broker name for a review of each
broker's offerings, including Gomez's take on their important
benefits and shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   From there you can click on Broker Performance Monitor to see
how fast that broker's site is responding currently and the average
response for the last 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez includes active message boards for each broker. Click on
``Read what consumers are saying'' to access the message board for
that broker.
</P>
<P>
   The site's ratings are useful for the big picture, but they
aren't the final answer. For one thing, their ratings are too
broad. For instance, their Overall Cost rating combines costs of
stock trades, expenses associated with buying stock on margin and
mutual fund trading charges into a single rating.
</P>
<P>
   I doubt if many mutual fund investors are concerned about margin
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Another downside of relying solely on Gomez's ratings is the
potential for conflict of interest. Gomez sells advertising and
other services to the same brokers it rates.
</P>
<P>
   DETAILED COMPARISON: Take your list of broker candidates to
Xolia.com ( &LR; www.xolia.com &LR; ) for a detailed comparison of broker
features.
</P>
<P>
   Xolia, pronounced ``zoh-LEE-uh'' means ``to choose wisely,''
according to information on the site. Xolia.com allows you to
simultaneously compare more than 80 features of three different
brokers. The site lists just about everything: trading hours,
minimum account balance requirements, stock trading commissions,
options commissions _ you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Find the broker comparison by selecting Broker Decision Center
on their home page, and then click on Comparison Tool. The most
important factors depend on your particulars. Here are some I've
found important.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-In Offices: There are times when conducting business in
person is easier and faster than via the Web or by mail.
</P>
<P>
   Cash Minimum: The minimum amount required to open an account
varies widely among brokers. For instance, DLJ specifies no minimum
while Charles Schwab requires $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   IRA Fees: Look for brokers with no annual fees if you plan to
open an IRA account.
</P>
<P>
   Stock Trading Commissions: Some brokers charge different fees
for stocks depending on the exchange where a stock is traded or
whether you place a market or limit (you specify the price) order.
Look for brokers with the lowest ``limit order'' fees if you plan
to be an active trader.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual Funds: Mutual fund investors should look for brokers with
the largest selection of funds ( Total Funds). Brokers allow you to
buy and sell a selected group of no-load funds with no commission
(no-fee funds). They charge commissions when you trade other
no-load funds. Give preference to brokers with the largest number
of no-fee funds ( No-Fee Funds) and to brokers with the lowest
commissions for no-load funds with trading commissions (OL No-Load
Commission).
</P>
<P>
   IN THE TRENCHES: Don't even think of opening an account with an
online broker before checking OnLine Investment Services
( &LR; www.sonic.net/donaldj &LR; ) run by Donald Johnson, a retired history
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lists fees and such for each broker, but the most
important information is Johnson's summaries of experiences related
to him by investors actually using the broker's sites. The
information is gritty, down to earth and very relevant to what
you'll experience.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's site isn't elegant and can be confusing to navigate.
The home page starts with a summary of problem brokers and then
lists links to rankings based on several criteria. Select
``Discount Brokers Ranked,'' and then click on ``For an
alphabetical listing ...'' to look up specific brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Go back to the home page and then click on ``Help in Choosing a
Discount Stock Broker'' for Johnson's ranking of brokers in
categories such as best for experienced investors, best for less
experienced, best for low commissions and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   The information on Johnson's site is updated frequently and is
more current than broker information I've seen elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Internet trading isn't for everyone. It's only suitable for
investors who do their own research and make their own decisions.
You don't get the kind of professional advice that you'll receive
in person from a full service broker.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Domash publishes the Winning Investing newsletter. You can
read his columns at  &LR; www.winninginvesting.com &LR;  or contact him at
 &LR; hdomash(AT)winninginvesting.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
