<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH 21: WEB GIVES LESSONS IN CIVIC DUTY  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Judging by the Internet ads on TV _ or, for that
matter, the press releases that flood tech reporters' in boxes _
you could be forgiven for concluding that the Internet is all about
e-commerce and not much else.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, that's not the whole story. It's also, among other
things, a tool for citizenship: It gives us all unprecedented
opportunities to inform ourselves about public issues, not only
from the thousands of online news and opinion sites, but also
directly from original sources such as government documents and
legal filings.
</P>
<P>
   This week, I want to point out several online documents that
provide interesting background on technology-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   First, the Microsoft antitrust case. As you've undoubtedly read,
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson gave clear signals at a hearing last
week that he intends to order the breakup of Microsoft. You may
also have heard that he commended a document submitted by a pair of
computer trade organizations, proposing a three-way split rather
than the two-company solution proposed by the Justice Department,
as ``an excellent brief, excellent brief.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, thanks to the Net you can go read that brief for yourself,
at least if you have Microsoft Word or an Adobe Acrobat reader. As
with most Web adventures, it took a little hunting and a few error
messages, but I finally found a copy that downloaded pretty quickly
at  &LR; www.ccianet.org &LR; , the site of one of the organizations that
submitted the brief, the Computer and Communications Industry
Association.
</P>
<P>
   As an official  &LR; amici curiae  &LR; brief, it contains a fair bit of
legal mumbo jumbo. But it also lays out pretty clearly the
arguments for giving Internet Explorer to a third new company
rather than, as in the Justice Department plan, to the proposed
applications company.
</P>
<P>
   It also does, in my layman's opinion, a better job than the
Justice Department's six submissions in relating the remedies it
proposes to the facts of the case and the legal precedents.
</P>
<P>
   One passage that caught my attention: In refuting Microsoft's
contention that its abuses cause no harm to consumers, the brief
argues that ``Consumers feel this injury every time another hour is
lost from a crash caused by an operating system that is under no
competitive pressure to improve stability.''
</P>
<P>
   While you're at it, take a peek at another friend-of-the-court
brief posted at  &LR; www.brook.edu/views/papers/litan/20000428.pdf.
 &LR; Submitted by Robert Litan, an economist and lawyer who formerly
served as deputy assistant attorney general in charge of the
Justice Department's antitrust division and distinguished
economists from Stanford, Harvard and Yale, this brief makes the
case for a solution that would create three competing
operating-system companies in addition to an applications company.
</P>
<P>
   I'm by no means convinced this would be a better world if we had
three times as many versions of Windows. But the economists make
some interesting arguments, such as the observation that
Microsoft's 88 percent rate of return on its capital and R&AMP;D
investments in 1999 exceeded the average rate of return at other
major corporations by a factor of more than 13.
</P>
<P>
   One red flag: Noting that in many antitrust cases the ``relief''
phase has been treated as an afterthought, the authors urge the
judge to undertake extensive fact-finding and hearings on possible
remedies. Jackson, however, made it clear last week that he has no
intention of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   I understand his impatience, but I'm afraid that in his rush to
remedy, he may miss important considerations and give Microsoft
additional grounds for appeal and obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY ONLINE: If you have any more stomach for legal
documents, I'd also recommend at least skimming through Privacy
Online, a report submitted to Congress last week by the Federal
Trade Commission, which you can find in Acrobat format at
 &LR; www.ftc.gov/os/2000/05/index.htm22. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The report is based on a study of 335 Web sites plus 91 of the
100 busiest sites. Its basic argument is that self-regulation, the
approach to privacy protection the high-tech world has advocated
for years, has fallen far short of the industry's promises. In
response, it recommends that Congress enact legislation setting out
basic standards for online information collection and creating a
mechanism to enforce those standards.
</P>
<P>
   True, the FTC found, the percentage of sites that post privacy
policies and various seals of approval from self-styled watchdogs
has grown substantially.
</P>
<P>
   But when the researchers analyzed the content of these posted
policies, the picture looks very different: Only 20 percent of the
busiest sites, for example, have policies that address all four of
the basic principles of privacy the commission recommends.
</P>
<P>
   The principles in question are hardly radical notions. On the
contrary: They're simple ideas _ telling us clearly what
information you're going to collect, how you're going to do so, and
what you're going to do with the data you accumulate, and giving us
some choice about how the information can be used, plus a chance to
correct inaccuracies.
</P>
<P>
   A concrete example: 57 percent of the sites in the random sample
and 78 percent of those in the busiest-sites group allow the
placement of cookies by third parties, typically network
advertising companies, such as the infamous DoubleClick, that use
these bits of software to engage in online profiling. And a large
majority of these sites don't tell their users anything about these
third-party cookies.
</P>
<P>
   I have never considered posted privacy policies an effective
solution _ who reads them anyway, and what guarantee is there that
they reflect what the site actually does? What I want to see are
some simple, straightforward rules _ with the force of law behind
them. It's an approach that seems to work in Europe. Why not here?
</P>
<P>
   After years of supporting industry self-regulation, the FTC has
now come to the same conclusion. Unfortunately, to judge by press
reports, its proposal is going nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, ever eager to promote individual rights unless
corporate profits and campaign contributions are at stake, promptly
denounced the report. And the Clinton administration, as usual,
scuttled right along behind, hastily trying to distance itself from
the recommendations of its own appointees.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Republican FTC commissioners filed a vigorous
dissenting opinion to accompany the majority's report. I didn't
think much of his arguments, but I had to chuckle over his name:
Orson Swindle.
</P>
<P>
   NOW WE'RE GETTING SOMEWHERE: One heartening tech trend during
the past year has been the emergence of ``subscription computing''
_ plans that let small businesses contract with an outside vendor
for a complete package, including hardware, software, local-area
network, high-speed Internet access, tech support and nightly
backup, all for a flat fee per user per month.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, pioneered by Bay Area startups like CenterBeam
( &LR; www.centerbeam.com) &LR;  and Everdream ( &LR; www.everdream.com &LR; ), just
makes all kinds of sense. Few businesspeople would attempt to do
their own plumbing or air conditioning _ why should they waste
their time and talent configuring PCs, tracking down patches and
battling bugs?
</P>
<P>
   The malicious viruses that have wrought havoc in recent months
only strengthen the case for this kind of service, at least for the
vast majority of companies that can't justify the cost of a
dedicated staff to watch for new attacks and make sure everyone's
backed up.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Everdream is announcing a new and welcome addition to its
package: It's putting a series of guarantees behind its promises.
If customers encounter a hardware problem that the company's
technicians can't fix remotely, they promise to FedEx replacement
equipment, with your last data backup already loaded.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a software issue, they pledge never to send you
somewhere else for a solution. And if you're not satisfied with
their response, they say they'll pick up the next month's charge.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, they also promise a month's free service if you're
kept on hold for more than 90 seconds, or they don't reply to
e-mail within four hours. And if you lose a backed-up file and they
can't restore it, you'll be entitled to two months of service
without charge.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, big corporations have exacted such pledges, known
as ``service level agreements,'' from their technology providers.
It's great to see small business at last getting a chance to enjoy
similar benefits.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
