u p BC-NJ-GORMLEY-SENATE-2TA     05-28 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-GORMLEY-SENATE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-MARINE GORMLEY WORKS UP A SWEAT IN CROWDED BUT OBSCURE SENATE
FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ It wasn't much of a spider, but the
pinhead-size critter evidently chose the wrong fist to climb
across.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. William Gormley _ former Marine captain, Villanova
rugby star and jogger before dawn _ was gesticulating over a plate
of fried eggs as he tried to differentiate himself from the three
other Republicans running in New Jersey for the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The spider was not helping Gormley make his case. Squish. The
spider was no longer a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   With the June 6 primary nearing, an unwieldy pack of Republican
candidates is struggling against obscurity. More than 50 percent of
potential voters surveyed say they do not even know the Republicans
vying for the seat that Sen. Frank Lautenberg, a Democrat, is
trading for retirement.
</P>
<P>
   But few homeowners in Chatham who answered a knock on their door
two weekends ago are likely to forget the sight of a sweat-soaked
Gormley bouncing on their thresholds. In his effort to meet as many
voters as possible, Gormley, wearing shorts and sneakers, was
running _ literally _ door to door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this kind of campaigning makes an impression on the
voters,'' he said with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   A powerful Atlantic City lawmaker who heads the judiciary
committee in the state Senate, Gormley, 54, is known in Trenton for
his fiery temperament, intense exchanges and ability to strategize
like a military field commander under siege.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill doesn't bumble or fumble,'' said Sen. Gerald Cardinale, a
Bergen County Republican who is a Gormley supporter. ``When he
focuses on something he wants to get done, it gets done.'' Gormley
has another trait that sets him apart from his primary rivals: a
knack for raising money. So far he has collected $2.4 million; Rep.
Robert Franks of Union County, who is considered the other
front-runner, has raised just under $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a race that features three moderates _ Gormley, Franks and
James Treffinger, the Essex County executive _ and a former
Libertarian, Murray Sabrin, Gormley's stockpile of cash will buy
the kind of commercials that makes all the difference in a state
that gets its network television from New York and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   As the gatekeeper of legislation affecting Atlantic City,
Gormley has benefited from casino industry largess, prompting some
to question his fund-raising ethics. Over the years he paved the
way for 24-hour gambling and championed another measure allowing
patrons to buy chips with credit cards. He pushed through
legislation that funnels a tax on gambling revenue into casino
expansion, and through his efforts, the state is constructing a
$330 million tunnel that will bring patrons to the doorstep of a
planned casino.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley insists he has never let contributions from gambling
executives influence his legislative work. ``Every vote I've ever
made concerning casinos has been for my constituents,'' he said.
``That's the standard. Period.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of his colleagues in the legislature, both Republican
and Democrat, were critical of his style, no one suggested that
Gormley was under the spell of the gambling industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen, if Boeing is the largest employer in your town, are
you going to be for them or against them?'' asked Richard Codey,
the Senate minority leader. ``But on the other hand, if he doesn't
agree with the casino people, he'll say so.''
</P>
<P>
   After 23 years in the State House, Gormley is eager to move on.
Not that he has not tried in the past. A 1989 run for governor went
badly (he finished fourth out of four), and in 1994 he lost a
vicious congressional fight against Frank LoBiondo, a conservative
Republican who tried to link him to Gov. Jim Florio and his
unpopular tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley was better financed and better known than his rival, but
in the end he was overwhelmed by conservatives and gun advocates,
who were infuriated by his vote against assault weapons. (In 1991,
a year after that well-publicized vote, Gormley nearly lost his
Senate seat to an unknown Republican whose candidacy was largely
financed by the gun lobby.)
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Gormley has turned his stand on gun control
into a purple heart. At nearly every public appearance, he reminds
people that he was the only Republican to vote for the ban on
assault weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the Marine Corps, I fired an M-16, and I've seen
the damage they can do,'' he said. ``I don't think we need these
weapons in New Jersey.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gormley has been around guns and law enforcement officials all
his life. His father was the sheriff of Atlantic County for two
decades, and the family spent most of the year in an apartment
attached to the jailhouse, which is still known as Gormley's Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Local judges would stop by for lunch, and prisoners would
sometimes baby-sit for the Gormley children. For a change of
scenery, the Gormleys would summer at the seaside funeral parlor
where Sheriff Gormley was undertaker.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from law school, Gormley enlisted in the Marine
Corps, where he learned some valuable lessons about the commonweal.
When his commander spotted a package of chocolate chip cookies sent
by his mother, he chastised Gormley for not sharing and forced him
to consume the entire two-pound box as his unit looked on. In
telling the story, Gormley made it clear he was not knocking the
corps. ``I loved being in the Marines,'' he said wistfully, chin
cocked high.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for him to pick up the political baton from
his father, who was also the local Republican ward leader. In 1975,
a week after Gormley's honorable discharge from the military, he
was nominated county freeholder. It was an easy win, and the
Gormley name, he said, did not hurt. ``People down there thought
the world of my father,'' he said. Two years later Gormley was
elected to the General Assembly, and in 1982, he was elected to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   As chairman of the Judiciary Committee, Gormley controls all
appointments by the governor and judicial nominations. It is a
powerful post, and colleagues from both parties described Gormley
as fair, someone who rarely holds up appointments for the sake of
politics.
</P>
<P>
   But fans and foes agree that Gormley can as graceful as a drill
sergeant. Animated and loud, he has a tendency to bring his face
within six inches of an opponent's in an argument. Often one hand
will grab the other person's arm while his other hand jabs the air
for emphasis. He is the kind of guy who delivers unkind words
through a game-show host smile.
</P>
<P>
   Others say his behavior can be disturbing and self-defeating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill has a short temper and a long memory,'' said Steve
Salmore, a Republican consultant who worked on LoBiondo's
congressional race against Gormley. ``He's very bright, but he's
very pugnacious and has a tendency to polarize people.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters call his ferocity an asset. ``He's an ex-Marine, what
can I say?'' said his campaign consultant, David Murray. ``He's a
passionate and intense guy. You want a laid-back nice guy who
equivocates, you can have Bobby Franks. But if you want a
risk-taker, someone with courage and character, Bill Gormley's your
guy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
