<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BLOCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD BLOCH, 78, COMPUTER PIONEER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass.)   By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard M. Bloch, a pioneer in the development and design of
digital computers, died of cancer on May 22 in Framingham, Mass. He
was 78 and lived in Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As chief operations officer at Harvard University's Computation
Laboratory in the early 1940s, Bloch helped design and program the
first automatic digital computer, dubbed the Mark 1.
</P>
<P>
   He also invented the procedure for automatic error detection
known as parity check, which is used in almost all computers today.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Rochester, N.Y. on June 18, 1921, Richard Milton Bloch
was the son of Harry and Tillie Bloch, who operated a small
printing business. He attended Harvard on a scholarship, graduating
in 1943 and serving in the Navy in World War II. He then returned
to Harvard as a research associate in the university's engineering
division.
</P>
<P>
   Over the succeeding years, Bloch worked in a number of
administrative positions in the rapidly growing computer industry,
including general manager of the computer division of Raytheon,
vice president for technical operations at Honeywell, vice
president for corporate development at the Auerbach Corp. and vice
president of the advanced systems division of General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   He was also chairman and chief executive of the Artificial
Intelligence Corp. and the Meiko Scientific Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Bloch is survived by his wife, Ruth, and seven children: Susan
Bloch-Nevitte of Toronto, Charlote Johnson Zembko of Bolton, Mass.,
Lawrence of Belmont, Emily Martin of Bolton, Mass., Debra
Ellingwood of Framingham, Mass., Katheryn Swarts of Houston, and
Richard, of Huntington Beach, Calif. He is also survived by eight
grandchildren. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
